<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SUMMER-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: a lot of story.'' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But there were plenty of other successes. The summer will set a
record with as many as a dozen movies topping $100 million,
obliterating the previous mark of nine in each of the past three
summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really interesting that we saw 10 different films at No.
1 in 10 weeks because it showed an extremely competitive market,''
Dergarabedian said. ``We're seeing huge competition in holdover
films and that shows the audience is expanding. It's not a finite
pie; the slices are a little bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of pie, ``American Pie'' would have been the summer's
biggest surprise if not for ``Blair Witch.'' Made for a
bargain-basement $11 million with no stars, the R-rated comedy was
the most successful at aiming for a specific audience - teen-age
boys - and will propel raunchy projects for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Disney also scored surprisingly well with ``Tarzan'' with a
much-admired marketing campaign that broadened the audience
considerably beyond children and into the teen-age crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Hollywood hit a home run this summer with teen-agers'
apparently insatiable desire for horror films.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sony bombed in late May with ``The Thirteenth Floor,''
the audience remained primed in mid-July when ``Lake Placid,'' with
no major stars, took in a better-than-expected $10 million on its
opening weekend. ``The Haunting,'' ``Deep Blue Sea,'' ``Sixth
Sense'' and ``Blair Witch'' dominated the box office for the next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Except for horror films, studios managed to avoid direct
confrontations for the most part. ``I think studios did a pretty
good job of spacing out the films,'' Devlin said, noting that the
two Julia Roberts films - ``Notting Hill'' and ``Runaway Bride'' -
opened with more than two months between them.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a perfect summer by any means. Warner Bros., after
reviving itself during the winter and spring, began to stumble
again with underperformers in ``Wild Wild West,'' ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' and ``Iron Giant.'' ``Eyes,'' Stanley Kubrick's final film,
was particularly disappointing for many moviegoers who often left
the theater feeling a combination of anger and boredom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's movies like `Eyes Wide Shut' that make people stop going
to the movies,'' said Rick Manly, an Altadena resident and frequent
moviegoer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, many trackers believe the tone for the summer was set
12 days before ``Phantom Menace'' opened when ``The Mummy''
debuted. For exhibitors, it was a godsend to have another hot film
to play during the ``Phantom Menace'' frenzy and answered their
most frequent complaint to Hollywood - give us your best movies all
year, not just around summer and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The `Mummy' was such a nice surprise,'' said Devlin. ``It
was perfect popcorn entertainment and set the tone for a lot of
sort of review-proof movies.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
