<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BOX OFFICE FIGURES WILL EASILY SURPASS LAST YEAR'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood studios, wielding a finely tuned
hype-and-buzz machine, have confounded the skeptics this summer
with an astounding string of successes at the nation's box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big surprise has been how well the overall business held
up every single weekend,'' said Drew Devlin, president of Clark
Film Buying in Bozeman, Mont. ``I'm a firm believer in the notion
that going to the movies is a habit and once you get people going
to good movies, they keep on going.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood will easily smash last summer's Memorial Day-Labor Day
record of $2.58 billion by at least 20 percent, or better than $500
million. That's not just because of a certain movie about Jedi
Knights and lightsabers; it reflects the industry's ability to walk
the fine line of - on the one hand - delivering mass-entertainment
films that - on the other - somehow offer something that's never
been seen before.
</P>
<P>
   The summer season's real power emerged after ``Star Wars:
Episode 1 - The Phantom Menace'' had been open for three weeks,
when ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' opened with a
stunning $54 million weekend total.
</P>
<P>
   That triggered a run that has made Hollywood history - 10
different films have led the box office for 10 consecutive weeks,
including this weekend's expected winner, ``Bowfinger.'' The
previous record had been seven consecutive weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diversity of films shows the studios have spread out their
best films well with a lot of doubles and triples,'' Devlin said.
``All in all, the exhibitors have been pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' was a huge help to its rivals, analysts
contend, as moviegoers ignored critical carping over Jar Jar Binks
and the inevitable comparison with the original ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like `Titanic' lifted the rest of the box office,
`Phantom Menace' did the same thing,'' said Robert Bucksbaum,
president of the Reel Source forecasting service.
</P>
<P>
   ``When `Phantom Menace' sold out in the first weeks, people went
to see other films,'' he added. ``A good film gets everyone in the
mood to go to the movies and enables other films to be hits.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the No. 1 films that have driven this summer's
box office. The season will probably be best remembered for a
bizarre film about three novice moviemakers disappearing into the
Maryland wilderness in search of a 200-year-old witch. At a time
when the average film costs over $50 million to produce, ``The
Blair Witch Project'' was done for less than one-thousandth of
that.
</P>
<P>
   Though it never finished first, ``Blair Witch'' ignited
midsummer moviegoing as it crossed over from the art-house circuit
to shopping-mall multiplexes. It also redefined how to create the
pre-opening sizzle among the most lucrative moviegoing sector -
teen-agers and young adults - by offering up a completely unique
film that somehow had the feel of ``this really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even three weeks ago, people would have laughed at the idea of
`Blair Witch' grossing over $100 million,'' Bucksbaum said. ``It's
going to lead to a huge wave of change. Just like `Titanic'
convinced people that they could spend $200 million and still be
successful, studio executives are going to be looking for this kind
of movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The marketing for ``Blair Witch'' - consisting of a disturbing
trailer and an Internet site that offered clues and background on
the fictional 1994 incident - cost Artisan Entertainment less than
$10 million. The studio has been taking out advertisements in Daily
Variety bragging not about its gross - which should be around $110
million by the end of this weekend - but the number of hits at
www.blairwitch.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the success of `Blair Witch' is its cleverness,''
said Joseph Butt Jr., an analyst with Forrester Research. ``It
worked brilliantly because it used the Internet effectively as a
multichannel marketing campaign. It demonstrated that it can be a
very effective medium and filled in a lot of story.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</P>
</TEXT>
