<HEADLINE>
RATTLERS GO DOWN IN FLAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It took a half for the smoke to clear Saturday at
Pepsi Arena. By then, the Rattlers' season was in ashes.
</P>
<P>
   With Eddie Brown showing why he's got the nickname
``Touchdown,'' and haunted by so many past semifinal failures, the
Albany Firebirds rolled into the ArenaBowl for the first time with
a 73-47 rout before 10,043 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went their way,'' defensive specialist Cedric
Walker said. ``We couldn't put a foot in front of them to slow them
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Overzealous pyrotechnics weren't needed to fire up the Firebirds
(13-3) with enough pre-game fireworks to light up (cough, cough)
the New York night. Albany had been here enough, losing four
semifinal games in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed five minutes for some of the smoke to
dissipate so the Rattlers could find the ball when it was kicked
off the net. The half was played in a haze, which, it seemed, was
where the Rattlers' heads were throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never put any pressure on them, and, when you don't put any
pressure on them, they can pretty much do whatever they want,''
said quarterback Sherdrick Bonner, who made his first appearance of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he spent the night tossing and turning. After
Saturday, he'll be in defensive specialist Cecil Doggette's
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who had a 41-game touchdown streak snapped in last week's
first-round victory over Grand Rapids, scored four touchdowns,
setting an Arena Football League playoff record with 239 receiving
yards. He caught 13 passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so riled up, I had so much adrenaline, I just couldn't
sleep,'' Brown said. ``But that's not unusual before a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially a game as big as this.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of Doggette, he played the game with a sore left
hamstring that caused him to miss the last three regular-season
games. He aggravated it in practice early in the week and was held
out until Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was more physical or mental, wondering in
the back of my mind if I was going to pull it again,'' Doggette
said.
</P>
<P>
   The only chance the Rattlers had was to put pressure on
quarterback Mike Pawlawski, and that didn't happen enough.
Pawlawski knows every step Brown is going to make. He also was
eager to meet up with these guys after missing a meeting here in
May, in which backup Jeff Loots riddled the Rattlers in a 59-54
victory, as Pawlawski spent the game in a hospital with a bleeding
ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   Pawlawski passed for 303 yards, completing 22 of 32. He was not
intercepted. The Firebirds didn't fumble either.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner, who rejoined the Rattlers on Tuesday after getting cut
by the Atlanta Falcons on Monday, said, ``This was more
disappointing than what happened to me earlier in the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner nearly matched Pawlawski's yardage (298) and had six
touchdowns passes, but he was picked off once and lost two snaps.
</P>
<P>
   Add Van Johnson's 56-yard kickoff return, the Firebirds scored
28 points after Rattlers turnovers and a special-teams breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Danny White used a different math, calculating what would
have happened if the Rattlers had scored instead of turned the ball
over: ``That's 42 points, right there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to overcome that, unless you're playing a team that
is making mistakes and giving it back to you, and they never did,''
White said. ``They weren't very good hosts.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Firebirds scored on every possession, being held out
of the end zone only twice, as Don Silvestri kicked field goals of
42 and 23 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to hand it to Albany,'' White said. ``They
played a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pawlawski and Brown have such a great rapport.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said if he had to carry the Firebirds on his shoulders,
he'd do it. But all he was looking to do, he said, was not bust an
assignment and do the ``little'' things to help get them to a place
they've never been.
</P>
<P>
   Albany will stay home to play the eighth-seeded Orlando
Predators next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (11-5), playing musical quarterbacks in the last month,
lost three of its last four games, but, for the first time in four
games, scored more than 35 points.
</P>
<P>
   Despite six touchdown passes from Bonner, who had only three
days to reacquaint himself with his former team and the 50-yard
game, this was a collective loss.
</P>
<P>
   Defense, special teams, and the offense broke down too many
times to beat an average team. Against the league's highest-scoring
offense, it was no contest. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
