<HEADLINE>
CO-LEADER HAS OFTEN FELT LEFT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, ILL. - The young man who is tied for the lead at the
PGA Championship is a minority. Growing up, he often felt
self-conscious, different from most other kids. All his life he has
experienced the sting of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Question is, can he beat Tiger Woods?
</P>
<P>
   His name is Mike Weir.
</P>
<P>
   Mike is left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a right-handed world. Every day the 12 percent or so
of people who were born left-handed face inconveniences and
challenges the rest of us don't.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handers must shake hands using their right hands. Since we
write from left to right, a left-handed person risks getting ink
stains on his hand. Using scissors can be a hardship. For a
left-handed child, most school desks are unusable.
</P>
<P>
   Know the French word for left? It's ``gauche,'' which also means
clumsy or socially inept. When you receive a left-handed
compliment, how does it make you feel?
</P>
<P>
   Left-handers happily point out that if the right side of the
brain controls the left side of the body, then only left-handed
people are in their right minds.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo da Vinci was a lefty. So was Aristotle. Picasso.
Michelangelo. Beethoven. Einstein. Babe Ruth. So is Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But how many accomplished left-handed golfers can you name _
other than Phil Mickelson? Bob Charles is the only lefty ever to
win a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   So good luck to Mike Weir. I'm pulling for him. Today _ two days
after International Left-Handers Day _ the 5-foot-9, 150-pound
Canadian, who has never won a PGA Tour event, lost his tour card
last year, and is ranked 103rd in the world, has the opportunity to
win the last of golf's four majors.
</P>
<P>
   All he has to do is beat Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   In a head-to-head duel.
</P>
<P>
   With the crowd cheering wildly for the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't that be a story.
</P>
<P>
   Weir's daunting task brings to mind the scene in the movie
``Dumb and'' ``Dumber'' where Jim Carrey asks a beautiful young
woman what the chances are of her becoming romantically interested
in him. One in a hundred? Be honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``One in a ``million'','' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're telling me,'' Carrey's thick-headed character says
excitedly, ``there's a ``chance''!''
</P>
<P>
   The odds, of course, heavily favor Tiger Woods Inc. Woods won
the last seven tournaments in which he held the lead going into the
final round. While he only shares the lead with Weir, the general
feeling is that Woods should win his first major since his
record-setting victory at the 1997 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is on his game. He sounds confident. The other day he was
asked if the length of the Medinah Country Club course (7,401
yards) is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for me,'' Woods said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Weir understands and accepts his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind being the underdog,'' he said, not that he has a
choice. The 29-year-old was paired with Woods in the final round of
the recent Western Open. Woods' victory was cause for celebration
in the Chicago area, where Woods is only slightly less popular than
Ernie Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Weir is viewed as something of a curiosity. Canada hasn't
produced many great golfers. The fact that he hits the ball from
the ``wrong'' side is seen by many (mostly right-handers) as
another reason to bet against him.
</P>
<P>
   It can be difficult being left-handed. When Weir was 13, he
wrote a letter to Jack Nicklaus. The boy wanted to know, if he
decided to pursue golf, whether he should switch to right-handed.
To Weir's surprise, Nicklaus wrote him back. He told the boy not to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the greatest player of all times told me to stick to it,''
Weir said, smiling, ``I was going to stick to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now here he is with a chance to do something no southpaw has
done since Charles won the British Open in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me at the beginning of the year I was going to be
in this situation, I would say there was no way,'' Weir said with
refreshing candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been gaining confidence. Gaining momentum. I don't
have anything to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, except the PGA Championship. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
