<HEADLINE>
TIGER LEADS YOUNG LIONS AT MEDINAH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY JOHN DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ The 81st PGA Championship has been thrown to the
young lions. Make that three lions and one Tiger, who knows how to
pounce when the scent of victory is in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who has won seven straight tournaments when leading
after three rounds, moved into a tie for the lead with Mike Weir on
Friday at Medinah Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 23, and Weir, 29, were at 11-under 205, 2 shots ahead of
19-year-old Sergio Garcia and 26-year-old Stewart Cink. That
foursome, which averages just over 24 years old, moved to the front
Saturday when the likes of 45-year-old Jay Haas and 54-year-old
Hale Irwin failed to keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players these days are getting very good, very fast,'' Cink
said in explaining the youth movement. ``Guys are learning how to
play earlier, they're playing more, they're stronger and they have
better equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at his young age, Woods has the edge in experience among
the leaders, especially when it comes to winning PGA Tour events.
He has 14 victories, with four this year, including one major _ the
1997 Masters. The other three have one victory combined, by Cink in
the 1997 Greater Hartford Open.
</P>
<P>
   When he breezed to that Masters win in record-shattering
fashion, it seemed to many that Woods would be in the hunt for
every major event for years to come, but that hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came out, I won in '97 by 12 shots and everyone
thought you can do that every time you tee it up,'' he said.
``Well, golf's not really like that. It's very difficult to win
major championships. You've got to have some lucky breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That week, everything went my way, and I understand that
people are basing their expectation level on that week. Whether
that's realistic or not, I don't know. But it is very difficult to
win major championships, and to win them the way I did and win them
frequently. Just to win one is an accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Just being here is an accomplishment for Weir, who will be
paired with Woods today.
</P>
<P>
   He's trying to become the first Canadian and the only
left-hander besides Bob Charles to win a major. That, and playing
with Woods, might seem like too much pressure to handle, but Weir
doesn't think so after the road he's traveled to play on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   After college, he tried qualifying school for five years,
playing the Australian Tour when he failed, then finally earned his
tour card last year, but didn't earn enough to keep it. He went
back to tour school this year and nearly shot himself out of the
qualifying tournament with a 75 in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember many times that I was missing cuts on the
Australian Tour,'' he said. ``Then you're by yourself, you don't
have any money and your're out there practicing until you can't see
a shot 5 feet in front of you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things I'll always have in my memory bank. Those are
the tough times and if anything contributes to my determination now
it's because I know how hard it was to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   That determination has paid off as Weir has earned nearly
$600,000 this season and three times has been paired in the final
group of a PGA event.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was with Woods, July 4 at the Motorola Western Open
in nearby Lemont, Ill. He also was in the final pairing with David
Duval in the BellSouth Classic in April and with Tommy Tolles and
Barry Cheesman in the Touchstone Energy Tucson Open.
</P>
<P>
   While he failed to win any of them, Weir has improved each time,
shooting 73 in Tucson, 72 in the BellSouth and 70 in the Western in
his final rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind being the underdog,'' he said. ``Tiger's the best
player in the world and I didn't even have my card a few months
ago, but I'm making strides in my game. If you had told me at the
beginning of this year I was going to be here, I would have said,
`No way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Weir got here by shooting a round of 69 Saturday, highlighted by
an eagle at the par-5 14th hole, where he hit a pitch shot from 35
yards away over a bunker and into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Woods shot 68, carding five birdies and one bogey, including a
chip-in from 50 feet on the par-4 sixth hole. Cink and Garcia also
shot 68 on a day when Medinah No. 3 played much tougher than it had
the first two days because of swirling winds.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who is considered the European version of Woods, had
four birdies during his bogey-free round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about playing (today) with Tiger,'' the young
Spaniard said. ``I was doing my best but I couldn't catch him. It
was almost impossible. It looked like if I made a birdie, he went
behind me and made one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he keeps playing like he did today, maybe we have to look
for second place, but I'm going to do my best to try to catch
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Haas, the second-round leader, slumped to a 75, putting him 5
shots off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Joining him at 6-under 210 were Nick Price, Jim Furyk and Skip
Kendall. Furyk, the University of Arizona product, played the first
five holes in 4 under par, with an eagle at the par-4 fourth hole.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, the Senior Tour player from Paradise Valley who started
the day four shots behind Haas, failed to keep pace, carding seven
bogeys in a round of 68 to fall 12 strokes behind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
