<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-STING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY HAS PAYBACK IN MIND FOR STING'S LAUGHTER IN ROMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Mercury and Charlotte Sting arrived at Sky Harbor
Airport at the same time on Saturday, coming from different
locations and going in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   When their paths intersect for a game at 7 tonight, the slight
difference in their records is not reflected in the standings. The
Sting (15-14) has all but clinched a third consecutive WNBA playoff
berth, while the Mercury (13-15), playing in the vastly superior
Western Conference, has no chance of continuing its playoff string
with four games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But there are reasons for Phoenix to still play hard: the chance
for fourth place in the West and a winning record, possibly better
than that of all but one team in the East; to extend to franchise
record nine-game win streak at America West Arena; and perhaps most
of all for payback, which it owes Charlotte in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Including a pair of preseason games this season, the Sting has
five straight decisions over the Mercury. And it won so easily on
June 24, 88-72, after leading by as much as 23 points, that it took
to making fun of its slow-footed opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most embarrassing thing was they were laughing at us,''
forward Jennifer Gillom said at the time. ``That's the second time
that's happened. It's a matter of pride now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Phoenix was only 2-4 after losing that game. It sank all the
way to 3-10 before beginning a recovery that diminishes even what
Charlotte has accomplished since firing Coach/General Manager
Marynell Meadors on July 11 and promoting assistant Dan Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 12, the Sting (5-7 under Meadors) is 10-7 under
Hughes, an assistant men's then women's coach at the University of
Toledo from 1991-97, while the Mercury is 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing (difference) has been the rebounding,''
Hughes said. ``The team has taken a lot of the effort and focus
that they wanted to improve with and put it into rebounding. It's
really impacted our defensive play.''
</P>
<P>
   But in its past five games, four of them losses to West teams,
Charlotte has been outrebounded by a combined 172-120.
</P>
<P>
   The Sting is coming off a 78-64 loss at Sacramento on Friday
that leaves it still one win shy of the playoffs. It also fell
Monday to Utah, 67-65, which defeated the Mercury, 67-64, on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's old, but we're not just playing for ourselves,
we're playing for Phoenix now and pride,'' said Mercury point guard
Michele Timms. ``And it would be nice to finish the season with a
few wins against teams that are going to be in the finals
(playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice to sit back and say we had a bit of a bad patch
at the start that really hurt us, but we beat those teams at the
end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix also plays West playoff qualifiers Sacramento and
Houston in a Tuesday-Wednesday back-to-back before closing the
season against Utah on Friday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
