<HEADLINE>
LATE-INNING LOSS SPOILS GOOD DEEDS FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Juan Gonzalez was back in the lineup and going deep,
Ivan Rodriguez recorded his historic 20th stolen base and Rafael
Palmeiro reached 30 home runs and 100 runs batted in for the fifth
consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   But through the thick gloom of the Rangers postgame clubhouse,
nobody was interested in talking about individual accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask me tomorrow,'' Rodriguez said after becoming the first
major-league catcher to hit 20 homers and steal 20 bases in a
season. ``Not tonight; 20-20 is better when we win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't win last night. Instead they saw two-out
ninth-inning home runs by Palmeiro and Todd Zeile go to waste when
the White Sox rallied in the bottom of the inning for a
sloppy-but-exciting, 8-7, victory at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile should have been one of the heroes after his game-tying
home run. Instead, he was among the most frustrated afterward.
Zeile slipped while trying to field a ninth-inning bunt, a pivotal
play in leading to the White Sox's game-winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly one of those days that will test the old
fortitude,'' Zeile said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to win ballgames,'' said Gonzalez, who had a two-run
home run and a run-scoring double in his first game back since
straining his left hamstring on Tuesday. ``I felt all right, but
the thing is to win the ballgame. Oakland is playing great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, after their fourth consecutive loss, need to pay a
little more attention to the Oakland Athletics. The second-place
Athletics defeated the Toronto Blue Jays, 13-5, yesterday and trail
the Rangers by 41/2 games in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks, ten days ago we were the best thing since sliced
bread,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``We will be again. All those
things were once going in our favor, and they will again. You watch
the worm; it will turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to have it turn, you have to catch the ball and make good
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't last night when it counted most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frustrating,'' losing pitcher Jeff Zimmerman (9-2) said.
``Nothing else describes it. We haven't been playing good baseball.
We're losing games we should be winning, and it's got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers thought they had it stopped. They led 5-2 into the
sixth, but the White Sox rallied for four runs that inning against
starter Mike Morgan and reliever Tim Crabtree. The Rangers then
erased the White Sox's 7-5 lead with two out in the ninth when
Palmeiro and Zeile hit back-to-back home runs off White Sox closer
Bob Howry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our chances of winning right there were great,''
Palmeiro said. ``We just needed to get back in and hit, but we
didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ray Durham led off the ninth with a single. Mike Caruso
followed with a sacrifice bunt up the third base line, but Zeile
slipped as he went to field it and kicked the ball into foul
territory. Durham raced to third on the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went to field it ... thick grass, and it's damp that time
of night,'' Zeile said. ``I went to stop, and my body would, but my
feet wouldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas was walked intentionally to load the bases, and the
Rangers brought Mark McLemore in from right field as a fifth
infielder. But it didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman did get Magglio Ordonez on a short pop to right, but
Paul Konerko hit his fly ball a little deeper, and Roberto Kelly
had no shot at getting the speedy Durham at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only positive about this game is we had life in the ninth
inning,'' Palmeiro said. ``That and having Juan back in the lineup.
You can see what happens when he plays. Everything else you can
throw out.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
