<HEADLINE>
HALL TO JOIN PAN PACIFIC TEAM  
 EARNS BERTH WITH DRAMATIC FREESTYLE WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Five months ago, Gary Hall Jr. thought he might quit.
Today, there are probably some rivals who wish that he had.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, of Phoenix Swim Club, re-established himself as a major
threat for medals at the 2000 Olympics with a dramatic victory in
the 50-meter freestyle at the national championships at Minneapolis
five days ago.
</P>
<P>
   With his comeback win, Hall earned an invitation to compete for
the U.S. team in Sydney at the Pan Pacific Championships, which is
considered a major steppingstone to the 2000 Olymic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, a silver and gold medalist at the 1996 Olympics, plans to
travel on Tuesday to Sydney where he will join the U.S. team, which
departed Friday. The team, also includes Misty Hyman, a Phoenix
native who is about begin her junior year at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Pursley of U.S. Swimming said Hall was given permission
to arrive late because he needed to regain weight and adjust levels
of insulin he has been taking since he was diagnosed with diabetes
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Hall was suffering from the flu five days before the nationals
last week when the 24-year sprinter won the 50 at 22.13, fifth
fastest in history. The performance would have tied him with
Alexander Popov for the 1996 gold medalist Atlanta, where he went
22.26.
</P>
<P>
   It also has put him within striking distance of the world record
of 21.81, which was set by Tom Jager in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to really expect,'' Hall said after his
victory in Minneapolis. ``There's just been so much I've had to
overcome. It's been so long since I've raced that it was like a new
sensation for me. I could tell that I hadn't done it in such a long
time. I was really nervous, and I'm not usually that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall has fought the International Olympic Committee over a
three-month suspension it handed down for a positive marijuana
test. He also has had repeated battles with the bureaucracy that
runs U.S. swimming.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pan Pacs, he also is eligible to swim the 100-meter
freestyle and legs on the 4x100 medley and 4x100 freestyle relays,
according to Pursley, the national team director and one of the
officials who has often been at odds with the Phoenix swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Klete Keller of Phoenix Swim Club and Brophy Prep won the
5,000 meter title last week in Minnesota and qualified for the Pan
Pacs.
</P>
<P>
   His younger sister, Kalyn, won a Bronze medal in the 200
Butterfly for the U.S. this summer at the Pan Am Games in Canada. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
