<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGACHAMPIONSHIP-TEX </SLUG>
 
TIGER TIED FOR LEAD AT PGA (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ If it's crunch time in suburban Chicago, Tiger
Woods and Mike Weir must be in control of the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in a month, they are.
</P>
<P>
   The final pairing in today's closing round of the PGA
Championship at Medinah Country Club is identical to the one that
tromped across the crosstown fairways at Cog Hill Golf &AMP; Country
Club to decide the Western Open on July 4. That day, Woods
prevailed over Weir by three shots.
</P>
<P>
   PGA pursuers indicated they would be surprised if a similar
scenario does not unfold at Medinah, where Woods and Weir will
begin the final round tied, at 11-under par. Stewart Cink and
Sergio Garcia remain two strokes back, at 9-under, but no one else
is closer than five shots.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, for one, sounded ready to concede the Wanamaker Trophy
to Woods at the end of the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tiger keeps playing like he played \Ryesterday\S, maybe we
have to look for the second place,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, added Fred Couples, Woods is once again in the driver's
seat in the Windy City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be tough for anyone else in the field to beat him,
regardless of who he's paired with,'' Couples said. ``Tiger's just
a better player. He's the best player in the world right now.
There's more pressure on Weir than Tiger, because \RWeir\S will
have to play his absolute best to beat him. Tiger doesn't have to
do that to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If Woods isn't at the top of his game, he's showing Medinah
galleries a reasonable facsimile. Woods breezed through a
five-birdie, one-bogey 68 yesterday, matching the lowest score of
the third round. He had a 50-foot chip-in for one birdie and
tap-ins for two others. In backing a second-round 67 with a
third-round 68, Woods has posted the two lowest scores in his past
19 rounds at major championships on consecutive days at Medinah.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt primed to pick up his second major
championship, Woods said: ``I am ready, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Weir, a Canadian who was the medalist at the 1998 PGA Tour
qualifying tournament, understands the challenge he faces today. He
is just glad he will begin the final round on even footing, rather
than with a four-shot deficit, as he did at the Western Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes it a little different scenario. Still, I am
obviously the underdog,'' said Weir, who picked up three strokes on
the final five holes by chipping in for eagle at No. 14 and
draining a 20-foot birdie putt at No. 17. ``I realize the crowds
are going to be pulling for him hard, but I can't pay attention to
all that stuff. I don't think this is Tiger's tournament to lose.
Anybody could have a hot day and win.''
</P>
<P>
   If the frontrunners stumble, two-time PGA champ Nick Price and
Jim Furyk headline a four-player group at 6-under, five strokes off
the pace. Brandt Jobe, a Southlake resident who competes on the
Japanese Tour, sits in ninth place, at 4-under, after yesterday's
69.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks, the 1996 PGA champ, recorded a
hole-in-one during a round of 70 and moved into 14th place, at
3-under for the tournament. Brooks has not finished better than
38th (1999 Masters) at any major since his victory at the 1996 PGA.
</P>
<P>
   At eight strokes off the pace, Brooks said he's a long shot to
win but is glad to be making noise again at a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing fine. I just want to keep it going for another
round,'' Brooks said. ``I don't have any expectations for
\Rtoday\S. I can't control what the other guys shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, however, finds himself in control of his destiny after 54
holes at a major championship for the first time since the 1997
Masters. There, he won by a record-setting 12 shots. He's won the
past seven tournaments where he has held a 54-hole lead.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that others view him as the man to beat this afternoon
at Medinah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to win one major championship,'' Woods
said. ``I need to take care of business before I can start worrying
about kicking in the door and winning my second. But I do feel
comfortable in this position. I enjoy being in a position where
everybody's trying to beat me. That usually brings out my best.
Hopefully, that will be good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, Woods will leave the Windy City with his first Wanamaker
Trophy. Not to mention a 2-0 lead in final-round duels with Mike
Weir. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
