<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STRAWPOLL-AFTERMATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SETS HIS CAMPAIGN'S SIGHTS ON IOWA CAUCUSES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush
failed to net any bass while fishing Saturday morning, but he
landed a big one at night with a victory at the Iowa Republican
Party presidential straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know that I know this is just the beginning.
I've got a lot of work to do,'' Bush told a pompom-waving crowd of
about 250 supporters in a circus-style tent after the vote. ``But
this victory today in Iowa put me on the road to winning the
nomination of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said pundits contended he had little to gain and much to
lose two months ago when he announced that he would participate in
the straw poll despite a late start campaigning in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to you, we gained a lot,'' Bush said. ``We have more
than accomplished what we set out to do. We jump-started our
grass-roots organization for the main event, the Iowa caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The caucuses next January are the first major test of the
presidential candidates in a contest that actually begins the
process of selecting delegates to the national nominating
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush finished first in the straw poll balloting at about 31
percent, followed by Steve Forbes at 21 percent. Elizabeth Dole was
third with 14 percent. They were the only candidates to finish in
double-digits.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking to his supporters, Bush told the Houston
Chronicle he does not believe that his nomination is now
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all ... You can never take anything for granted in the
political process,'' Bush said. ``I've got to get my organization
in place in other states. This is just the beginning in Iowa.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush congratulated his opponents, but also said some might want
to ``reassess'' whether their campaigns are still competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had entered the straw poll confidently, saying he was
``laying the groundwork'' for the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll ``is an interesting test of our organization.
Where we're strong, we'll bolster our strengths. Where we find
weakness in our organization, we'll change,'' Bush said hours
before the votes were in.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign had set a spending limit of $750,000 on the
straw poll for exhibit space, phone banks, direct mail,
entertainment, tickets to vote at the event and buses to bring
supporters from across Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're judicious in our budget, run no TV ads,'' Bush said.
``Our organization worked late into the night to get our votes
turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's victory, a poll released Saturday indicated there
is still softness to Bush's strength in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 400 Iowa Republicans found Bush leading his next
closest opponent by 17 percentage points. But the poll by The
Polling Co. of Washington, D.C., also found 55 percent said they do
not know where Bush stands on issues important to them, and 45
percent were unable to name any of Bush's accomplishments as Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth of those polled said the first words that came to mind
when they heard Bush's name were ``his father'' or ``his family
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush started his public events Saturday with a bass fishing
demonstration with professional Johnny Morris at a small lake owned
by the Izaak Walton League, a hunting and fishing conservation
organization. Bush, flipping a yellow-tailed spinner, came off a
pier fishless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't trying to catch fish, and it worked,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the straw poll audience in the Hilton Coliseum
on the campus of Iowa State University, Bush promised that as
president he would push for tax cuts and improve schools. He said
he also will end an era of negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country is hungry for a new style of campaign: positive,
hopeful and optimistic,'' Bush said, ``a campaign that appeals to
our better angels, not our darker impulses.''
</P>
<P>
   Long lines of Bush supporters waited at the Texas governor's
tent for barbecue. Tracy Bird and Emilio Navaira provided
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, more than 350 motorcyclists led by U.S. Sen. Ben
Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., and Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson
roared onto the straw poll grounds as Bikers for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush briefly posed for photographers on a motorcycle after
telling the motorcyclists: ``We're all Republicans here because we
believe in individual freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, appearing on CNN's ``Evans, Novak Hunt &AMP; Shields'' show,
defended the National Rifle Association, from which his father
resigned in 1995 after the group's director called federal officers
``jack-booted thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view them as a great demon,'' Bush said of the NRA,
noting, however, that he is not a member. ``If I agree with them, I
will do so. If I don't agree with them, I will be bold enough to
say so.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he favors instant background checks for gun
purchases, but he said he believes it is more important to enforce
the nation's gun laws than to pass new laws restricting gun
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
