<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE EAGER FOR RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sure, Todd Stottlemyre wanted the sleepless nights of
worrying about his career, the guilt of not giving the return on a
four-year, $32 million contract and the shoulder pain to end.
</P>
<P>
   But when Stottlemyre was throwing poorly Saturday before his
last rehabilitation start in Tucson, he turned to pitching
coordinator Gil Patterson and said, ``I gotta get it to another
level. I can't take these 9:30 (a.m.) games anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   His next notch produced a seven-inning Rookie League complete
game, yielding six hits and one run with no walks and 10 strikeouts
on 81 pitches. Stoked about the longest outing of his comeback, he
sped up Interstate 10 to even beat some teammates to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-month battle to be part of Arizona's pennant
chase, Stottlemyre will start Friday at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   He elected to pass on the common option of surgery to repair his
mostly torn rotator cuff in May and said he had players and coaches
asking, ``Are you crazy? How are you going to pitch without
surgery?''
</P>
<P>
   Just fine, so far, with a new grip suggested by pitching coach
Mark Connor to ease the shoulder strain and put the sink back in
his sinker.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has felt progressively better since that discouraging
first day of throwing six weeks ago. Team physician David Zeman
already had told him he was ``a miracle'' at that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had made up my mind I'd pitch again this year,'' Stottlemyre
said. ``This is the neatest group of guys I've ever been around my
whole career and I wanted to be a part of it. To get back and pitch
for this club again meant everything to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre spent five weeks lifting weights without picking up
a ball before two simulated starts and three Rookie League outings.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling as though he is entering a new season, Stottlemyre said
he will change his work habits between starts to strengthen his
legs for a new tighter motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my stuff was normal,'' he said of Saturday's
victory. ``The big thing was getting up and down seven times and
not having problems getting loose each inning. ``It's hard for me
to believe that my MRIs look as bad as they do and I feel as good
as I do. I'll take each start as another new gift.'' &QL; 
Kim throws again &QL; 
To close the doubleheader Stottlemyre started, Byung-Hyun Kim made
his first game appearance of his neck strain rehabilitation with
two shutout innings. Kim will throw this week for one of Arizona's
minor league affiliates. &QL; 
Lee in the outfield &QL; 
Manager Buck Showalter said slumping first baseman Travis Lee's
recent outfield practice was mainly to give the team flexibility
rather than call up a player in light of Steve Finley (back) and
Tony Womack (leg) missing recent games with injuries. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
