<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR'S PROFANE TIRADE DESERVED DISCIPLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apparently not happy that their thunder in Southern California
was being taken away by the Anaheim Angels, the Los Angeles Dodgers
reclaimed their status as the preimminent baseball franchise in the
Los Angeles area last week.
</P>
<P>
   But just like their brethren in Orange County, the Dodgers
gathered attention for all the wrong reasons. Right fielder  &UR; Raul
Mondesi's profanity-filled tirade against Manager  &UR; Davey Johnson
and General Manager  &UR; Kevin Malone has left the Dodgers in a serious
spin-control mode.
</P>
<P>
   But is it a battle that can be won? Mondesi laced into his two
immediate superiors in a way that would have anyone in the real
world tossed out on his backside within seconds. This being the
world of professional sports, though, the Dodgers, to date, have
done nothing to seriously discipline Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, knowing full well whom he was talking to, told Dodgers
beat writers in Montreal last week that he was no longer willing to
play for ``(expletive) Davey and (expletive) Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of all this,'' said Mondesi, 28. ``I told my agent
to get me the (expletive) out of here as soon as possible. I can't
take this anymore. I've had to deal with this all year. I told them
to trade me because I don't want to (expletive) be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Expletive) Davey and (expletive) Malone, they try to put all
of our problems on me. They're trying to say that all this
(expletive) is my fault. That's the way they feel, fine. Just get
me out of here. (Expletive) Davey. (Expletive) Malone. (Expletive)
both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, a suspension for conduct detrimental to the
organization would have been warranted and most likely received in
a positive manner from frustrated Dodgers fans, who believe the new
Fox administration is taking everything the Dodgers have stood for
and turning it upside down.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost impossible to believe the  &UR; Peter O'Malley-owned
Dodgers would have allowed such comments to be passed along without
serious consequences. It would be foolish for the Dodgers to make a
snap judgement and simply trade Mondesi (although that would not be
a simple process considering he has $20 million owed over the final
two years of his four-year, $36 million contract, which also
includes a pair of club-owned options in 2002 and 2003 worth $12
million each).
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, the 1994 National League Rookie of the Year and the
first Brooklyn or Los Angeles Dodger ever to hit 30 home runs and
steal 30 bases in the same season, is an immensely talented player
who is capable of becoming a Most Valuable Player at any time.
</P>
<P>
   He possesses all five tools that scouts so tirelessly search for
in players. Mondesi may feel singled out for the Dodgers' abysmal
season, but that's simply not the case. This is a club that has
suffered a total collapse and is showing what little character it
has within its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers divulged last week that Mondesi has privately been
fined regularly this season. It's obvious that shielding Mondesi
from criticism has not worked so far. Maybe it's time to take this
mess more public and make a stand, one O'Malley certainly would
have taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't acceptable, and we're taking the appropriate steps
internally,'' said Malone, a good man of strong convictions who
must have become sick upon learning of the outburst. ``We're going
to handle the situation as we feel is best, but we're going to keep
that within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as far as what we're going to do long term, I'm not going
to comment on that. We're going to keep all of our options open and
we're going to continue to support Raul and help him in any way we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, a native of the Domini can Republic, will never be a
vocal leader and that's OK. He cannot, though, become what he
showed last week, a childish boor ready to pack it in just because
things aren't going his way.
</P>
<P>
   He's better than that and he knows it. At the very least, he
should know it. He's not a child anymore and should be held
accountable for his actions. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
Third baseman  &UR; Wade Boggs took the mound for Tampa Bay last week
during a 17-1 drubbing at the hands of the Baltimore Orioles. It
was only the second time in major league history that a player with
3,000 hits pitched for his club. Can you name the other? &QL; 
Another disgruntled soul &QL; 
 &UR; Frank Thomas, the identity of the Chicago White Sox, is another
player unhappy with his role and ballclub. Breaking the
smile-everyday-image he has maintained all season, Thomas let it be
known that he simply does not want to play first base again, a
point that seemed to be driven home after he botched a play that
led to a five-run outburst by Oakland last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I booted it, that's why I'm a designated hitter,'' he told
White Sox writers in an expletive-filled tirade. ``I'm not a first
baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day brought no reversal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a DH all last year, and I'm a DH this year,'' he said.
``I've had my time in the field. I know the position I should be
playing, and that's DH. I feel good DH'ing, more comfortable. I've
got to hit. I've got to adjust to that role.''
</P>
<P>
   Most amazing is that Thomas recently turned 31. He's young and
extremely athletic (he also played football in college at Auburn)
and, at one time, was an adequate first baseman. When folks argue
about the designated hitter, this is the worst-case scenario for
those in favor of watching the greats (such as a  &UR; Harold Baines or
a  &UR; Paul Molitor) still playing into their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Frank is that he convinces himself that he
can't play somewhere or do something, so he doesn't,'' Manager
 &UR; Jerry Manuel said. ``He takes a strong asset and makes it an
enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are on Manuel's side. Thomas is hitting .345 as a
first baseman with eight home runs and a .553 slugging percentage
compared with .287 with seven home runs and a .450 slugging
percentage as a DH.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Manuel seems to be unwilling to change his
thinking. ``He'll be back out there,'' he said. &QL; 
Opposite end of the spectrum &QL; 
Then there's Cincinnati first baseman  &UR; Sean Casey, as solid and
grounded a human being as there is in the game today. Though Casey
has seen his average drop from .371 at the All-Star break to .346
entering the weekend series, his priorities remain on being an
upstanding citizen first and foremost.
</P>
<P>
   Casey recently befriended a Dayton man about his age who
regularly attends Reds games. The two struck up a friendship and
the man,  &UR; Shane
 &UR; Whiteman, began walking Casey to his car after home games.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteman seemed sad one day last week, and when Casey asked if
anything was wrong, Whiteman told him of his father's sudden death
from a heart attack and how the family could not afford a funeral
or a burial. Casey said, ``I'll pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whiteman refused to accept Casey's offer. But Casey agreed to
appear at a Dayton autograph show last Thursday with all proceeds
going to the father's funeral. Now that's giving back to the
community. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
In a 1925 game, while playing in his next-to-last season for the
Detroit Tigers,  &UR; Ty Cobb pitched one perfect inning in a similar
mop-up situation. Cobb also pitched four relief innings in 1918 for
the Tigers, allowing two runs on six hits. He was still more than
500 hits shy of reaching 3,000 at that time. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The AL Comedy Central Division is alive and well: Cleveland may
have gone 13-13 before its weekend series, but in the same span the
Indians managed to widen their division lead from 13{ to 17{ games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Suddenly Suppan: Kansas City starter  &UR; Jeff Suppan, who couldn't
cut it during his time with the Diamondbacks, is finding the
American League much more to his liking. Suppan pitched his second
straight complete game last week and was 7-6 with a 3.74 ERA before
his Saturday start.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Steve Renko.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Leaving an impression (literally): New York Yankees boss
 &UR; George Steinbrenner sent former Yankees third baseman  &UR; Wade Boggs
an original  &UR; LeRoy Neiman painting of  &UR; Joe DiMaggio after Boggs'
3,000th hit. The painting was signed by Neiman and DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Timing is everything: Boggs took the occasion of his 3,000th
hit to make a public pitch to the Devil Rays to pick up his 2000
option. Since Boggs is set to receive somewhere in the $750,000
range, it seems likely Tampa Bay will pick up the option. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida's  &UR; Alex Fernandez, still feeling the ill effects of a
surgically repaired shoulder, is about to give way to Boston's
 &UR; Pedro
 &UR; Martinez as baseball's winningest pitcher yet to reach his 30th
birthday. Fernandez is 102-82. Martinez is 101-49 after getting his
17th win of the season Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite blowing his last two save opportunities, Boston
knuckleballer  &UR; Tim Wakefield has been successful in converting 14
of 17 save situations entering the weekend since taking over for
injured closer  &UR; Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta starter  &UR; John Smoltz, unable to throw breaking balls
because of elbow discomfort, is experimenting with a three-quarters
delivery curveball of sorts that had Houston's hitters confounded
last week.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego pitcher  &UR; Brian Boehringer doesn't use a bat with his
own name on it. He also doesn't use a teammate's bat. Boehringer
uses a  &UR; Jackie Robinson model, one he bought at a garage sale
several years ago. It even has the thick handle that many bats from
that era had.
</P>
<P>
   Texas did everything it could during the off-season to trade
away pitcher  &UR; Esteban Loaiza. Now it seems like Loaiza, who is 3-0
with a 3.81 ERA in his five starts since the All-Star break, would
be in the Rangers' rotation if the playoffs began today.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado believed it had received minor league outfielder
 &UR; Thomas Johnson along with  &UR; Brian McRae and  &UR; Rigo Beltran from the
Mets two weeks ago when the Rockies sent  &UR; Darryl Hamilton and
 &UR; Chuck
 &UR; McElroy to New York. It turns out Johnson has decided to retire, a
decision he was contemplating before the trade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eddie Murray will take a serious step toward becoming a major
league manager when he takes over the managerial duties of the
Scottsdale Scorpions in the Arizona Fall League this year. Murray,
Baltimore's hitting coach, badly wants to manage and is taking the
same route  &UR; Dusty Baker took seven years ago. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Texas has any inkling of trading  &UR; Juan Gonzalez, count
Detroit as a very interested party. The Tigers made an inquiry into
Gonzalez's availability last month and are open to the idea of
trading away whatever it takes to secure the two-time MVP, who is
eligible for free agency after next year.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati GM  &UR; Jim Bowden is suddenly talking about wanting to
re-sign left fielder  &UR; Greg Vaughn to a contract extension. ``He is
great in the clubhouse and is a positive influence on our young
players,'' Bowden said. ``We wouldn't be where we are without
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay returns to play at Tropicana Field next Friday.
Designated hitter  &UR; Jose Canseco, out since the middle of July after
back surgery, expects to be back in the Devil Rays lineup for the
game against Kansas City. Tampa Bay entered Saturday's game 9-20
since Canseco went down.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal Manager  &UR; Felipe Alou is seriously kicking around the
idea of moving  &UR; Wilton Guerrero from second base to outfield over
the winter. The Expos are seeking a winter ball spot for Guerrero
and may put him in the outfield for all or most of September. Alou
envisions Guerrero taking on a roll similar to that of  &UR; Tony
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   No one has said anything publicly, but Detroit Manager  &UR; Larry
Parrish last week said he would understand if he weren't asked to
return. The Tigers, who have the worst record in the majors, might
be interested in Atlanta hitting coach  &UR; Don Baylor or  &UR; Phil Garner,
fired by Milwaukee last week.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but it appears the Montreal Expos will probably
remain in Quebec, at least for the 2000 season. Major league
officials are intent to keep their 28-year stretch of no franchise
moves intact, and the Expos appear close to possibly securing a
downtown stadium proposal. It's all iffy, though. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. NY YankeesFinished a 6-1 trip to Seattle and Oakland, places the
Yanks usually have trouble.  &QL; 
2. ClevelandCould have five players on its rosterwith 25 home runs
each.  &QL; 
3. AtlantaDon't ever count the Braves out of anything. They still
have gobs of talent.  &QL; 
4. NY MetsEntered the weekend 43-18 since the coaches bloodletting,
er, firings.  &QL; 
5. TexasToronto taking three out of four showed how vulnerable
Rangers are to LH batters.  &QL; 
6. HoustonHad their hats handed to them by a still-impressive
Atlanta club.  &QL; 
7. CincinnatiJust when it seems the Reds are ready to fade, they
jump back in.  &QL; 
8. ArizonaIf you're a D-Backs pitcher, take the body armor out to
the mound.  &QL; 
9. BostonWith rookie  &UR; Brian Daubach doing damage, Sox believe they
are one to beat. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. DetroitDon't look now, but the worst record in the game is
here.  &QL; 
29. AnaheimEntered the weekend series 5-21 since the All-Star Game.
 &QL; 
28. MontrealThat faint heartbeat is another Expos stadium proposal
on the horizon.  &QL; 
27. Tampa BayIf  &UR; Jose Canseco returns, there may be reason to watch
this club again.  &QL; 
26. FloridaRose up and showed the Giants they are not to be taken
lightly.  &QL; 
25. Kansas CityYuck! The bullpen is up to 25 blown saves, and
counting.  &QL; 
24. ColoradoAnother  &UR; Clemente ( &UR; Roberto's nephew  &UR; Edgard) is
getting a shot in CF.  &QL; 
23. Chicago CubsThings are only going to get worse on the north
side these days.  &QL; 
22. BaltimoreWith nothing to play for, O's fans look for
 &UR; Cal &UR; Ripken  &UR; Jr.'s return. ON THE RISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oakland Athletics: They're no longer the East Bay's running
joke. Clubs take the A's seriously these days and for legitimate
reasons. Oakland has run off the best home record (41-19) in all of
baseball. With just a $22 million payroll, the A's are making a
serious run at the American League wild-card spot. While they have
the worst average in the AL, A's hitters have already hit more home
runs than last year's total of 149. The pitching, even with the
dumping of moody
 &UR; Kenny Rogers, has been very good. The addition of  &UR; Kevin Appier and
 &UR; Jason Isringhausen, a potential closer, can only help. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; San Francisco Giants: Meanwhile, on the other side of the San
Francisco Bay, things have not looked very good since the All-Star
Game. The Giants, who led at the break, fell 7{ games back as the
weekend series began. Closer  &UR; Robb Nen, one of the most dominating
at his position for years, was 0-4 with three blown saves and a
6.55 ERA since the break entering this weekend's series. ``Ever
heard the saying, `buzzard's luck?' ''  &UR; Ellis Burks asked. ``That's
how our luck is going right now. It's buzzard's luck.'' &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Palmer, the Seattle Mariners director of Safeco Field
planning and development, has been doing some serious spinning,
trying to get Mariners hitters to accept the lesser home
run-friendly park the club moved into last month. Palmer went this
far in explaining the recent complaining: ``I think it's probably a
recessive gene. But I think how superstitious baseball players are,
how they talk themselves into a mind-set, if they just can relax
and let it go (they'd be better off).'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's no secret anymore. Pittsburgh rookie second baseman
 &UR; Warren Morris is showing all the makings of being the real thing.
Acquired from Texas last season in exchange for  &UR; Esteban Loaiza,
Morris has made the most of his change of scenery. His .306 average
and .379 on-base percentage lead all National League rookies. He
also ranks in the top five among NL rookies in nearly every
offensive category. In short, the Pirates feel like they made a
steal in prying Morris, a minor leaguer at the time, away from the
Rangers last season. &QL;
</P>
