r s BC-FBC-ASU-FLOWERS-AZR &LR;      08-15 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-FLOWERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWERS GROWS INTO LEADERSHIP  
 DEFENSIVE END DRIVEN BY DESIRE TO COMPETE, WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP TONTOZONA _ Competitive? You want competitive?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're walking down the hallway, he'll bump you so he can
have the most space,'' said Arizona State safety Willie Daniel of
his roommate, Erik Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ever hear me say, `It's just a game,' I'm either
talking to a kid, or I'm lying,'' the defensive end said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's his Earl Anthony-like tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I saw this dude bowl a 300 game and I thought, `I can
do that,' '' Flowers said. ``Next thing I know, I'm buying a ball,
bag and shoes, and I'm bowling every day.''
</P>
<P>
   It is war when he plays video games. Defensive tackle Junior
Ioane's recent string of victories over Flowers in a boxing game
called ``Knockout King'' still eats at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how bad I hate to lose,'' he said. ``When
Junior was beating me, it made me upset. I'd tell him I don't care
as he'd walk by me saying, `I got the belt. I got the belt.' But I
hated it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can take laid-back.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for ASU, which has turned to Flowers to be its
defensive leader. The promise he showed in 1998, and his commitment
in the off-season, made him a natural choice.
</P>
<P>
   Leadership was not one of the Sun Devils' strengths last season.
Flowers is not a scream-on-the-field type _ linebacker Eric Fields
has that mastered _ but he's a leader by example, from his work
ethic to his passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like the throwback of a gym rat,'' defensive line coach
Kevin Wolthausen said. ``He's in the offices all the time. He's
early for meetings. He always wants to talk football.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not one of those guys that's good at something and does
it because he's good at it. He's passionate. Sometimes's he'll come
in, sit down, not say a word and just hang out. Then he'll watch
some tape and start talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers was a good player last season, and the Sun Devils
believe he can become a great one. After taking time to adjust to
ASU's system, the junior-college transfer showed significant
progress, finishing with 33 total tackles and three sacks.
</P>
<P>
   He has become someone the Sun Devils like to hold up as a
representative of their program. He is charismatic and
civic-minded, and was one of the seniors at the forefront of a
project to help refurbish a center for the homeless in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He is diligent in his off-season training, a product of his fear
of failure and of a lesson he learned when he was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cutting the grass and did a terrible job. It was still
about an inch high,'' he said. ``My grandfather made me cut it
again, and after he spanked me, he sat me down and said, `There's
no point in doing something at all if you don't do it right the
first time.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kind of said, `All right, all right,' but it really set
in. After that, almost everything I did, especially in football,
I'd do it until I got it right.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few places the message didn't set in was high school.
He began skipping classes as a junior in Texas and eventually
stopped going. The subsequent 0.0 grade-point average impacted him
academically in such a way that only two small junior colleges
would take him despite a standout senior season on the football
field.
</P>
<P>
   It was to the benefit of Trinity Valley Community College in San
Antonio, which is where he was when ASU found him. His and Ioane's
potential have made it easier for some to swallow the team's
decision to bring in 14 junior-college players this season.
</P>
<P>
   There are no more signs of his lack of focus, on or off the
football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's easy to deal with,'' equipment manager Mark Zimmer said,
``but he definitely knows what he wants. He wants things a certain
way.''
</P>
<P>
   His friends say he is equal parts intense and fun-loving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a 21-year-old kid,'' Daniel said. ``He's playful and has
so much energy. He's smiling all the time, loves to wrestle and
tries to beat us up.''
</P>
<P>
   ````Tries,'''' said safety Al Williams, another roommate, who
practices martial arts. ``We have to work him, beat him up now and
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Flowers, ``Al provokes me. I'm like a dog minding my own
business and he comes and takes away my bone.''
</P>
<P>
   He's often looking for a video-game or bowling partner. He and
fullback Jake Each recently took on tight end Todd Heap and
linebacker Mason Unck at a local bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were talking noise, they had never seen me play,''
Flowers said. ``We beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   His energy level is always turned on high and, unlike many of
his teammates, he won't nap between Tontozona two-a-days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'd have to restart,'' he said. ``I can't restart.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers hopes all his energy will help him record more sacks
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to the quarterback is like eating peach cobbler every
Sunday,'' Flowers said. ``It's not going to always happen, but when
it does, you just want to _ ``grrrr'' _ bite into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers is one dose of confidence away from being a great
player. Wolthausen has seen his growth in just one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times a guy wants to do the right thing, but he's
unsure and hesitant,'' Wolthausen said. ``That's the thing that
really kept Erik last year from making big plays. He'd have an
opportunity but he'd think, `Is that what I'm supposed to do?'
</P>
<P>
   ``From knowledge and experience comes the ability to see and
react without really having to think about it. And that's been the
whole development of his game: having the confidence in his ability
and his reactions so he doesn't have to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers feels more confident about himself and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 10th week of last season, we were making formation
calls and guys were still messing up,'' Flowers said. ``Here we are
the third day (of camp) and everyone's coming together. Granted,
there's still some mistakes, but everyone seems ready for the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenge? That's Flowers' kind of team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
