<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ARIZONA-WADE-AZR &LR;      08-15 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-WADE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADE TAKES STEP FORWARD  
 THRIVES ON SWITCH TO RECEIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLAS, Ariz.- In one of those textbook-like scouting reports,
Bobby Wade's first step probably has been dissected in painstaking
detail.
</P>
<P>
   But forget tiny fractions of time on an electronic stopwatch.
Wade already is beating a clock that usually defines and limits
freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Wade has taken his first step.
</P>
<P>
   The highly recruited prospect from Desert Vista High School
asked Arizona coaches to move him from running back to receiver on
the day the Wildcats opened camp at Cochise College.
</P>
<P>
   Wade got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   One step and nine days later, he's several steps ahead of even
the most optimistic expectations Arizona had for this 18-year-old.
He's been running consistently with the first and second teams as a
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going better than I thought,'' said Wade, the 1998
Arizona Player of the Year, who still is listed as a tailback on
the Wildcats' roster. ``I didn't anticipate playing in camp as much
as I have so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as repetitions and time, it more than I expected. But
I'm still learning. I just hope to contribute and maybe make the
traveling squad.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has guaranteed Wade a seat on the plane for Arizona's
opener Aug. 28 at Penn State in a game between two teams ranked
among the nation's top five. But, at this point, it would be a
surprise if he's not on board.
</P>
<P>
   Even Arizona coach Dick Tomey, who is always cautious about
first-year college students, is talking as though he will include
Wade as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to play,'' said Tomey, whose club was No. 4
Saturday in the Associated Press' preseason poll. ``So far, he's
been working between the first and second groups. He wanted to see
if he could contribute at wide receiver, and so far, he's shown he
can be effective in that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an electrifying kind of athlete. Of all our freshmen, he
appears to have a real chance this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade's potential emergence as a sudden factor in Arizona's
promising season is a mix of good and bad news.
</P>
<P>
   First, the bad. There's some uncertainty about Arizona's
receiving corps. Dennis Northcutt is No. 1, but he has been
troubled by a slightly knee sprain. Brad Brennan is listed at No.
2, but he has been sidelined through much of camp with a hamstring
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona already had been searching for a third receiver because
of Jeremy McDaniel's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Before camp opened, Marvin Brown, a 5-foot-11 transfer from
Chabot Junior College (Hayward, Calif.), was considered a
possibility. At times, Brown's diving, sideline catches have
displayed skills that might make him a competent option for
quarterbacks Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   But the range of possibilities grew by a big step when Wade took
the initiative and asked for the switch.
</P>
<P>
   With his request, there's good news. Although still untested,
Wade has shown a lot of versatility. Why let his evident talent go
untapped in a season full of the highest hopes?
</P>
<P>
   Wade was recruited as a running back, but barring injury,
there's little chance of him getting much time at a position that
belong to last year's Pacific-10 Conference rushing champion, Trung
Canidate, the senior from Central High. The backup to Canidate
figures to be the highly-touted Leo Mills, a redshirt freshman who
is recovering from a separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Wade saw an opportunity. So did the Arizona coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played that kind of position before,'' said Wade, 5-11,
180 pounds, who will attend his first college class later this
month. ``It's something I'm comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona already is planning to use him on kickoff and punt
returns along with Northcutt. Both can catch and run. It's easy to
imagine the two combining on effective reverses, just as McDaniel
and Northcutt often did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wade's potential was summed up in one sequence Saturday in a
scrimmage. On a sweep, it looked as though he might slip in the
backfield. But, in an acrobatic 360-degree twist, he regained his
balance and was gone for a big gain.
</P>
<P>
   It was two for one.
</P>
<P>
   Two first steps in one run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
