<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASS FISHING BEST AT NIGHT OR DAWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Fishing for bass in Arizona's desert lakes has fallen
into a consistent pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The best fishing is at night when temperatures drop, or early in
the morning and late evening when the bass still are active.
</P>
<P>
   It's just too hot during the day. Last week, when temperatures
remained cooler than normal, and the humidity dropped, was an
exception.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the humidity dropped because I could use my evaporative
cooler again and not sweat all day.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kile, a bass pro who lives in Tonto Basin, said the pattern
should remain until late September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nights should cool off a lot,'' he said Saturday. ``The
shad will move nearer the surface, and fishing patterns will
change.''
</P>
<P>
   The top-water bite in early morning and late evening has been
best on lures such as the Zara Puppy or Spook. Soft jerk baits,
such as the Slug-Go, also have been good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here (at Roosevelt Lake), the buzzbait has become really
effective,'' Kile said. It should be at other lakes, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Night and day fishing should be best, he said, on red and purple
Westy Worms in the daytime and black ones with a yellow streak at
night. Carolina-rigged lizards in a watermelon color also are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Roosevelt, the right depth is 10 to 15 feet in the Salt
River arm and 15 to 25 feet in the Tonto Creek arm,'' Kile said.
``The Salt River arm has muddier water. That's why you have to fish
shallower.''
</P>
<P>
   Kile said the same patterns also should apply at other desert
lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll probably have to fish even deeper at really clear lakes
such at Pleasant,'' Kile said. ``At more turbid lakes, like San
Carlos and Alamo, the bass should be shallower.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of September, bass should be hitting shad on the
surface all day. The shad should be shallow enough that bass can
herd them to the surface and slash them.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of top-water fishing, one of the best pieces of gear
you can carry is a pair of binoculars. At first light, when the
bass start boiling on the surface as they chase shad, binoculars
allow the angler to see those boils from a long distance.
</P>
<P>
   If fish are boiling in an area, they're likely to keep boiling
periodically. Get near the boils and shut off the outboard so you
won't spook them. Wait until they begin slashing the surface and
cast to those boils. Even if they're not boiling, the bass are
there. Just keep casting.
</P>
<P>
   Waning San Carlos Lake, which was at 4 percent of capacity, is
beginning to get needed help from monsoon rains in the White
Mountains. Runoffs from the Alpine area into the Gila River and
some from New Mexico have caused the lake to rise to 5 percent of
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   As of late last week, flow into the lake from the Gila was at
2,700 cubic feet per second, a vast improvement over the dribble it
was getting.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt, at only 31 percent of capacity, is still by far the
largest inland lake in the state at 10,631 surface acres. Pleasant,
which is at 70 percent of capacity, is the second largest with
7,886 surface acres. Alamo is third with 3,252 surface acres.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Church, who owns Bartlett Lake Marina, believes that there
are more suitable ways to judge a lake than listing its percentage
of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are constantly being asked what is the percentage of
Bartlett Lake,'' he wrote. ``In our opinion, this question does not
really give them the answer they're looking for. In fact, it can be
somewhat misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't realize that when Bartlett is at 39 percent
(of capacity), it still covers nearly 1,500 (surface) acres. As you
know, this is several hundred acres larger than Saguaro and Canyon
(lakes, which are at at 1,184 and 724 acres, respectively, and
about 90 percent full).
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that if the surface acres were provided in the paper
rather than the percentage, it would give the recreation users a
more accurate understanding of the size of all the lakes.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an important suggestion. What do you anglers think about
it? Let me know. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
