<HEADER>
A7808 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-COCACOLA-`GATESGATE'-     08-15 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCACOLA-`GATESGATE'-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE JOINS MICROSOFT ON ANTITRUST COP'S `MOST WANTED' LIST  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 14 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Gates quaffs Diet Coke like James Bond sips dry martinis.
But Microsoft, the world's most valuable company, and Coca-Cola,
the most valuable global consumer brand, have more in common than
the planet's most valuable bladder.
</P>
<P>
   Both have fallen foul of a new wave of antitrust activism. A
verdict is awaited in the lengthy court battle between Microsoft
and America's Department of Justice (and various states).
</P>
<P>
   As for Coca-Cola, antitrust objections in Europe, Australia and
Mexico recently prompted the Atlanta-based fizz-maker to scale down
by half its acquisition of assorted brands from Cadbury-Schweppes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, the European Commission has said it is
investigating Coca-Cola and the firms that bottle and distribute
its brands, for allegedly abusing a dominant position in Germany,
Denmark and Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Now, an unpublished report by Italy's competition authority
concludes that Coca-Cola has committed a ``grave violation'' of
antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both Microsoft and Coca-Cola protest their innocence.
Windows is the operating system used in most of the world's
personal computers. Coca-Cola's various brands (the ``real thing,''
plus Fanta, Sprite and a few others) account for 51 percent of
global carbonated soft-drink sales.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the two firms claim to operate in fiercely competitive
markets. Microsoft says it faces intense competition from other
operating systems (actual and potential), older versions of Windows
already in use, and piracy. It has less than 10 percent of world
software revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Coca-Cola says it has a paltry 2 percent share of the
liquids poured down people's throats. That puts it well behind
rivals such as water, tea and fruit juice.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, both Microsoft and Coca-Cola grew into big,
profitable corporations largely because they were better at
competing than their rivals were. That sort of competition brings
welcome energy and innovation.
</P>
<P>
   But how should the two firms behave towards competitors now that
they are successful? The answer, it turns out, involves more art
than science.
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable economists can usually disagree on the proper way to
define the relevant market in which to assess the degree of power
exercised by a firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, to prove market power usually requires evidence that
it would be hard for a more efficient rival to capture market
share; and evidence, too, that the incumbent has the ability to
raise prices significantly _ say by 5 percent _ and keep them there
for a longish period of time, say a year.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's and Coca-Cola's broad definition of their markets is
clearly self-serving, but cannot be dismissed out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   In Pepsi, Coca-Cola faces a big, aggressive competitor.
Microsoft operates in a rapidly changing business, where past
innovation has undermined apparently dominant firms. Even so,
analysis presented in the Microsoft trial, and to the Italian
investigation of Coca-Cola, suggest that both do enjoy a degree of
market power.
</P>
<P>
   Because the evidence is finely balanced, the authorities are
right to focus on the most egregious aspects of the way the two
firms treat their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to stop Coca-Cola battling Pepsi. The Department of
Justice has not tried to stop Microsoft pitting its Internet
Explorer browser against Netscape's Navigator. It merely wants
Microsoft to include Netscape Navigator alongside Explorer on its
Windows system.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates has compared this to ``telling Coca-Cola to include
three cans of Pepsi in every six-pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, to do that would be absurd. However, the analogy is
misleading. A better parallel would be a requirement that consumers
be given ready access to Pepsi as well as to Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Is that so absurd? Strikingly, in most of the countries in which
Coca-Cola and its bottlers are under investigation, it is accused
of trying to stop retailers (and wholesalers) making Pepsi
available.
</P>
<P>
   It is allegedly doing this through a mixture of financial
incentives and bullying _ possible because in these countries Coke
has a much higher market share than it does in America where Coke
and Pepsi are fairly evenly matched.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Microsoft nor Coca-Cola has offered any compelling
economic arguments for depriving consumers of the chance to choose
easily between their product and its main rival. That is why, on
balance, both deserve to lose. After all, the burden of proof in
such cases should lie on those who wish to be allowed to deprive
consumers of reasonable choices.
</P>
<P>
   If the Microsoft and Coke cases establish that as a principle,
celebrate by cracking open the fizzy stuff. And no, that need not
mean Diet Coke &QL; 
