<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HOTSUMMER     08-15 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HOTSUMMER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets seek relief from discomforts of offseason
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JONATHAN FEIGEN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Winter was nice. Not too cool, not too hot. Scottie Pippen used
to laugh about the temperature in Chicago as he reveled in his
Houston honeymoon and the endless kindness and appreciation showed
by his new franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were magazine cover darlings then, having romanced
and won the biggest-name free agent. They were instant contenders
for another NBA championship. The lockout was over, and every seat
was again filled. NBA players were moving to Houston suburbs like
New Yorkers retiring to Florida. Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich was
anointed the U.S. Olympics coach. The Rockets were hot again.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's just hot. The championship hopes were replaced by a
second consecutive first-round flameout. And summer has brought a
merciless run of bad news as unrelenting as the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Rockets' season ended four games into the postseason,
the franchise was rocked from a backlash of trade talks involving
center Hakeem Olajuwon. Tomjanovich later checked himself into a
hospital suffering from exhaustion and forced himself to skip his
summer USA Basketball coaching duties.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime assistant coach Bill Berry recently defected to the
Chicago Bulls, and Robert Barr, the team's 42-year-old senior
executive vice president of basketball affairs, retired, citing the
demands of his job or perhaps the length of his job title. And
Pippen, just a few months removed from exchanging vows with the
Rockets, has asked to go back to his ex.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever temptation there might be to assume a crack in the
team's foundation, Rockets officials insist none exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coincidence of timing,'' said Carroll Dawson, Rockets
vice president of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Added Tomjanovich: ``It's part of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a sports team, it's not like a normal business,''
Rockets owner Leslie Alexander said of the summer tumult. ``It's
very volatile. We've been very serene here compared to other teams,
except we've done big things. We brought Clyde (Drexler) in. We
brought Charles (Barkley) in. We brought Scottie in. But aside from
that, this has been a relatively serene business. But sports teams
change. Businesses might have the same 12 people for five, eight,
10 years. This business, every year you have new players. It's just
a different sort of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the summer developments do or do not indicate, Rockets
officials face other pressing matters that are likely _ in some
cases certain _ to have long-range impact on the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is in the middle of negotiations for a new arena,
talks that he described as vital and ``not close.'' But even after
reaching an agreement with the Harris County-Houston Sports
Authority on an arena plan, there is still a referendum to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson is working to retool a roster with no salary-cap space
and little room to maneuver player salaries.
</P>
<P>
   And Tomjanovich is looking to adjust his offense to fit a team
with young, athletic talent in the backcourt, an aging frontcourt
and a superstar brought in to bridge the two suddenly seeking a
return to his past.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is confident something will be worked out on the arena
front. He often has described a new arena as vital to the success
of the franchise, citing the revenue streams other new arenas bring
as ways to help keep up with player salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Pending the result of other referendum votes, if the Rockets do
not have a new arena by the time their Compaq Center lease ends in
2003, only they and the Orlando Magic will not play in either a new
or redesigned arena or have one on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people in this city want the Rockets to succeed and be
competitive and want the city to grow and be strong, and all those
things would happen with the new arena in town,'' Alexander said.
``It would be a great place to be. A lot of people in this town
have never been to one of the great new arenas in this country. Our
arena is like a high school gym compared to the great arenas. They
want the best, and that's what they would get with the new arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, it's no new taxes. It's not like we're coming to them
with a sales tax. They would get a great new place and great
experience. Why wouldn't they do that? But we have to make a deal
first, and we're not even close to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said the team's recent obstacles would not affect the
momentum for a referendum. But he said Pippen's interest in
leaving, even if limited to rejoining former coach Phil Jackson, is
disappointing. Alexander was instrumental in acquiring Pippen and
said Pippen's request of a trade to the Lakers ``hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's upsetting,'' Alexander said. ``But Scottie is a
professional. He always keeps himself in great shape. If Scottie is
with the team _ and that is a big `if' _ he will be ready and will
play to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts. We made a commitment to him. I thought he made a
commitment to us. I'd like him to keep his end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander insists the team is not due for an overhaul, and
he believes in retooling while remaining competitive. The Rockets
were 31-19 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to do what we think is the best thing to do to
win championships,'' Alexander said. ``That's our goal here. If
that time comes (to rebuild), if we think that is what should
happen, we'll do that. But right now, we don't feel that time has
come. And maybe we can stay on top and rebuild at the same time, be
a playoff team and a contender and rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've rebuilt the backcourt with young players. We have young
players on this team. We love our first-round pick, Kenny Thomas.
We have Othella (Harrington, going into his fourth season) in the
frontcourt. This team is aging, but it's not completely old. I
don't think we're at a crossroads.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen and Barkley have been public in their belief the
Rockets need help to contend. Many of the Western Conference
playoff teams have made moves; the Rockets have yet to sign a free
agent, and their options are dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I know it doesn't
fit anyone else's timetable. Everybody's timetable would be, `Let's
get it done now.' It doesn't always work that way in the world.
Sometimes you sign a free agent on the opening day of training
camp. It takes two to tango.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets' dance card is close to full. The addition of
Pippen's contract pushed the Rockets way over the salary cap,
leaving them with only the salary-cap exceptions of $2 million and
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   With Olajuwon and Pippen occupying more than $29 million of the
$34 million salary cap, the Rockets' other signed players all make
roughly $2 million or less, severely limiting the Rockets' options
in trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying,'' Dawson said. ``We still have our two
exceptions. As long as there is someone out there you think would
have a chance to help your team and might accept one of those two
exceptions, you keep looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not impossible to make deals. It's more difficult. If
you're over the cap, there's a limited number of things you can do.
I said last year, after this deal (to sign Pippen), we're over the
cap. We have two exceptions. There's the draft and in certain
instances, we can make trades. But the free agents would be coming
in on exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent developments have not made anything easier. Rockets
officials insist they indicate nothing about the franchise or its
future, and that the developments are isolated in every way but
their timing. But that is enough to have made it a long, hot summer
with camp seven weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very unusual year,'' Alexander said. ``The
Hakeem (trade) reaction. Rudy had physical problems. But we always
want to have a team people care about, not just another pro
basketball team, but something in their hearts they love, that
gives them great enjoyment and they associate with. This is their
team. They like how it's run, who we're involved with and they feel
proud they can support. The only thing I don't want to have happen
is for that to change, and I don't think it has because of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
