<HEADER>
A7816 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SCARY-KIDS-TODAY-ECON     08-15 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCARY-KIDS-TODAY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN GOTHIC: THE HORROR OF OUR `BLAIR WITCH' KIDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent provocative ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 14 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few things are more subject to historical revisionism than
cultural change. Everybody likes to celebrate torches being passed,
though only when he is part of the generation that is doing the
receiving.
</P>
<P>
   It is an item of faith for Hollywood's ruling caste of
baby-boomers that a glorious revolution took place in the 1970s. It
was a time when Jack had more hair, Clint rode tall and Warren's
fingertips were the things that Woody most wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   A brash young group of directors with names like Coppola,
Scorsese and Lucas reinvigorated Tinseltown.
</P>
<P>
   Truthful historians might record a few protests from the
preceding generation about a sudden increase in violence (the
horse's head in the bed; that rather unpleasant taxi driver). But
that was simply the noise of an old scene which did not ``get it''
quietly disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Now it seems that a similar ``youthquake'' is under way in
America's dominant medium.
</P>
<P>
   A trend which began with movies like ``Scream'' and ``I Know
What You Did Last Summer,'' and television shows such as ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer,'' now seems unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   While Stanley Kubrick's final oeuvre, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' was
crawling its way to $60 million at the box office, teen flicks made
for a fraction of the cost have sprinted past that number.
</P>
<P>
   The old guard at Warner Bros. has resigned; middle-aged TV
actors are being shown the door to make way for twenty-somethings
or teenagers. Rather than slyly adding years to their age on their
CVs to bestow gravitas, screenwriters now subtract a decade to
appear young.
</P>
<P>
   And now America has ``The Blair Witch Project,'' a horror
mockumentary made for $35,000, which has captured the all-important
``13-25 demographic,'' soared to the top of the box office, made
the covers of Time and Newsweek _ and could end up being the most
profitable film ever produced (in terms of return on capital).
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair Witch'' (which, alas, has nothing to do with Britain's
prime minister) is mostly shot with a handheld camera and rose to
fame via Internet chat rooms. It is the brainchild of a couple of
young directors who boast about their contempt for all that ``movie
s--- (crap).''
</P>
<P>
   If American parents wince when they hear that phrase, it will be
because it seems symptomatic not only of youth culture but of youth
in general.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Blair Witch haunts the eponymous movie, the homes of
baby-boomers are now possessed by an equally pathological figure _
``our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   When politicians talk about ``our kids,'' they either mean a
lonely alienated boy bent over a computer screen, or a teenage girl
who begins each sentence with ``like'' and is planning her first
cosmetic operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids,'' goes the conventional wisdom, are the reason why
``American Pie,'' a film where the title became a temporary love
interest, was a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Our kids recorded that racist, sexist rap over our old Joni
Mitchell tape. Our kids vote less and smoke more than their
predecessors; they are worse at maths than Czech kids.
</P>
<P>
   And, as every documentary about ``our kids'' reminds you, they
were the killers in the classroom in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Is this fair? Worrying about children is nothing new. But the
current bout of hysteria seems particularly open to correction. The
problems begin with definition.
</P>
<P>
   When people talk about ``kids'' they now seem to mean anybody
between toddlers and early middle age; and, by infantilizing
teenagers, adults make their behavior even worse than it sometimes
is.
</P>
<P>
   As Jonathan Rauch recently argued in the National Journal, the
fuss about ``children killing children'' in the wake of Littleton
was absurd: the two killers were 18 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   Put it another way: the older ``child,'' Eric Harris, was old
enough to drive a car, vote, join the Army and (in most states) get
married _ though not old enough to buy a drink.
</P>
<P>
   Some consistent distinction needs to be made, not just in the
law but also in political debate, between genuine children and
young adults.
</P>
<P>
   Next, it is not clear from the statistics that our kids, however
you define them, are indeed getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the latest figures show that adolescent sex is
decreasing. Many of the worthiest nonpolitical groups report a
surge in young membership. And in culture at least there is the
suspicion that they are getting a bad rap.
</P>
<P>
   As James Wolcott argues in the current issue of Vanity Fair, the
present bout of virgin-seducing and slasher movies seems to be the
work of an older group of producers who have made teens this year's
``designated sinners, camera fodder for jaded appetites and
projected desires.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, he points out, something distinctly odd about Brett
Easton Ellis, the author of ``American Psycho,'' one of the most
gratuitously violent novels ever, complaining about ``teens running
roughshod over this country _ murdering, raping, gambling away the
nation's future _ and we have the bills for counselling and prison
to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, from some angles the argument that American youth is
less responsible than its self-obsessed and self-indulgent boomer
parents seems downright laughable.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has gone on about the problems with ``our kids'' more
than the Clintons; yet their daughter Chelsea is by some way the
most dignified member of their family.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, the creation that most people bring up in the
context of kids, has so far proved for the most part a miracle of
youthful inventiveness. Even ``Blair Witch'' is not just another
slasher movie, but something recognizably different from its
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one gory moment in the whole film, which uses
psychology rather than special effects to terrify you. True, the
dialogue is a little lame: ``This is so not cool'' is hardly
Shakespearian. On the other hand, ``Goodfellas'' is not exactly
Proust.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the longer you look at ``our kids,'' the more you can
trace back the problems and any possible solutions to the
baby-boomers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, America's schools are worse than they should be, but that
is because the boomers have refused to reform them (witness the
resistance even now to the idea of mild experimentation with
vouchers).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, children do not vote, but that is because the boomers have
turned politics into a moneyed husk.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they do shoot each other, but that is because the boomers,
once so moralistic about nonviolence, have allowed gun ownership to
soar.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than worrying about ``our kids,'' the real horror movie
still seems to be ``Mom and Dad.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,125-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
