<HEADLINE>
NEPAL'S OLD SOLDIERS APPEAL TO BRITAIN FOR A BETTER DEAL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note Sept. 18 Gurkhas protest, Kathmandu _ 21st graf)   (This heads-up 775-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 14 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATHMANDU _ The recruitment of Gurkhas by the British army has
long provided a tough but lucrative job for some people in the
hills of Nepal with unproductive land and no other source of
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Harka Gurung, a former government minister in Nepal, recalls
that his father could educate four of his children on his pension
of 75 rupees (less than Pounds1 these days) that he received for
his 21 years of service in the British army. His father retired in
1926.
</P>
<P>
   There are many like Gurung who could not have attended school,
let along entered the professions, without their father's pension.
But what seemed a fair deal in the old days may not seem so fair
now.
</P>
<P>
   The service of Gurkhas in the British army dates back to 1817.
Their bravery in numerous battles has brought fame to themselves
and to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   When the British left the Indian subcontinent in 1947, they
continued to employ Gurkhas. Britain created a special status for
them in its army, which protected them from being regarded as
mercenaries, a sensitive matter for Gurkhas.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, a number of retired Gurkhas sought to draw
attention to the fact that Gurkha pay had fallen behind that of
other soldiers in the British army. But in the days of Nepal's
absolute monarchy nothing was done to further their claims. Those
who protested were often jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the establishment of multi-party democracy in Nepal in
1990, the campaign has been revived. At its head are two groups,
the Nepal Ex-Servicemen's Association and the more radical Gurkha
Ex-Servicemen's Organization (GESO).
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has had some success. In 1997, the British
government raised the Gurkhas' pay to that of other soldiers. But
their pension remains far lower than a British soldier's.
</P>
<P>
   GESO wants Gurkhas who have served in the British army to get
pension rights equal to other British soldiers. It also seeks
employment opportunities for Gurkhas' children in Britain, and for
Gurkha ex-soldiers to be allowed to work there.
</P>
<P>
   The British say that the formula used for working out the Gurkha
pension was laid down in the treaty it signed with Nepal and India
in 1947, which was based on Indian army rates. That treaty is still
in existence, and Britain seems disinclined to update it.
</P>
<P>
   The British also observe that living costs in Nepal are low
compared with those in Britain and other rich countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``But things are different now,'' says Harka Gurung. The 1947
agreement was drawn in haste, he believes, and was only temporary
in nature. The agreement should be scrapped or renegotiated, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The death in June of two Gurkha officers who were defusing bombs
in Kosovo, the first NATO casualties of its peacekeeping operation,
has added strength to their campaign for better pensions.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of one of the officers has been much interviewed by
British newspapers. It has been pointed out that, had her husband
been a British soldier, she would have received a lump sum of more
than Pounds64,000 ($103,000) and an annual pension of about
Pounds15,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Nepali widow has received Pounds19,000 and a pension of
Pounds940, which under present rules will be reduced after five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Gurkhas blame the Nepali government even more than the
British for not pressing their claim. But government in Nepal has
been in a wobbly state for years.
</P>
<P>
   Both the ruling Congress party and members of the opposition
have in fact spoken in support of the Gurkhas' case. Backing the
Gurkhas, who are well regarded in Nepal, wins votes. But perhaps
their voices have not carried weight in London.
</P>
<P>
   Militant-minded Gurkhas point out that there are some 30,000
former Gurkha soldiers in Nepal. What would happen if they took up
arms against the government, as have the Maoist guerrillas who have
fought in the border country for years?
</P>
<P>
   A more rational suggestion being canvassed by former Gurkhas is
that they should bypass their own government, and file a legal
claim for better pensions against the British government in London.
</P>
<P>
   The Gurkhas, however, first plan to parade and thunder through
the streets of Kathmandu in September, hoping to catch the
attention of the world.
</P>
<P>
   They are organizing an international conference in Kathmandu
starting on Sept. 18, which they say will highlight their unfair
treatment by the British government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the biggest ever gathering of the Gurkhas,'' says
GESO's president, Padam Bahadur Gurung, who is under attack in his
movement for its lack of success. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
