<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS BACKS UP TALK, BEATS HINGIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ All week, Serena Williams seemed bent
on hyperbole. First, she said if she played more tournaments, she'd
be No. 1 in the world. Then, she boasted that she didn't care who
her opponents were, even if the list included Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Those exaggerations didn't look off base Saturday night.
Williams beat Martina Hingis 6-3, 7-5 in 1 hour, 9 minutes in the
Acura Classic semifinals at Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Williams never lost serve and broke Hingis twice. She looked on
top of her game against the No. 1 player in the world. She had 38
winners to Hingis' eight. Williams was asked if anyone could have
beaten her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anyone,'' she said. ``Nope. Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will face Julie Halard-Decugis in the final.
Halard-Decugis upset top seed Lindsay Davenport 6-3, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, Williams broke Hingis' serve to take a 6-5
lead. Hingis placed balls well, repeatedly making the No. 6 seed
sprint across court. But Hingis finally hit wide on match point.
What could Hingis have done to get a winner?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few people who could get the ball by me,''
Williams said. ``You should ask them what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first set, Williams broke Hingis in the fourth game with
a winner down the line. Hingis had two break points in the seventh
game. But Williams delivered two of her seven aces to ward off
Hingis, who despite the loss, said Serena's older sister, Venus, is
the more consistent player.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't play like this every day, otherwise she'd be the
better one,'' Hingis said. ``Serena was all pumped up in this
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis beat Venus Williams, ranked fourth in the world, last
week in the finals of the TIG Classic in San Diego. Serena
Williams, ranked 11th, got revenge for the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never beat both of them in a row,'' Hingis said. ``It's
always that I'd lose to the other the next time. It's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   What really might have helped Williams was not playing singles
since the French Open. Her legs and demeanor appeared rejuvenated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible for a player to win two straight, or
three in a row,'' said Hingis. ``There are always other players who
are there that are fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 17, showed more poise than when she lost in the
quarterfinals of the Acura Classic the past two years. Williams,
who is 2-3 against Hingis, did have 22 unforced errors, but her
winners made up for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A younger Serena would have lost her serve in the final game,
lost control and maybe even thrown her racket,'' Williams said.
``I've eradicated that Serena and she's out of here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
