</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PEEWEE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEE WEE REESE DIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pee Wee Reese, captain of the Brooklyn Dodgers'
fabled ``Boys of Summer,'' never played with Don Sutton. But when
the Hall of Fame right-hander was to have his number retired at
Dodger Stadium last August, Reese was the first person he asked to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   To Sutton and several generations of fans, Reese embodied the
tradition of the National League's most storied franchise, a Hall
of Fame shortstop who died Saturday in Louisville, Ky. at the age
of 81 _ one year to the day after he came to honor Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a cornerstone of this organization and to everyone who
ever put on the Dodger uniform,'' Sutton said. ``There are a lot of
us who will be forgotten as the years pass, but there are three
names that will always be remembered: Sandy Koufax, Jackie Robinson
and Pee Wee Reese.''
</P>
<P>
   Born Harold Henry Reese, he played just one season in Los
Angeles, ending (in 1958) an 18-year career that included nine
All-Star games, seven pennants and Brooklyn's only World Series
title in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   But Reese left a lasting memory in 1959 when he wheeled Roy
Campanella to home plate in front of 93,103 emotional fans at the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, Reese's respect and appreciation for his old
teammates was remembered throughout the game. He was hailed as a
champion during baseball's difficult integration in the late 1940s,
when he put aside Southern stereotypes and befriended rookie
second-baseman Jackie Robinson as he was breaking baseball's color
barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Reese set an example for acceptance by putting his arm around
Robinson during a game that was getting ugly at Cincinnati's
Crosley Field, a quiet gesture that resonated throughout the league
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Don Newcombe, who later won a Cy Young Award, remembered that
Reese's compassion was equal to his competitive fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad, sad day,'' said Newcombe, now a member of the
Dodgers community relations department. ``I miss him as much as I
miss Jackie Robinson or Roy Campanella, because he was such a good
and sincere man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pee Wee was one of the guys on the Dodgers who we, I mean the
black guys, could look to for leadership. Jackie would tell us who
the nice guys were and who wasn't. And Pee Wee was surely one of
the nice guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese, inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1984, was busy after
his baseball career, working for Louisville Slugger and
broadcasting with CBS, NBC and the Cincinnati Reds. He was a
frequent visitor to the Dodgers spring training camp in Vero Beach,
Fla., including the 40th anniversary celebration in 1995 of
Brooklyn's only championship.
</P>
<P>
   Reese had battled illness in recent years, overcoming prostate
and lung cancer. During his bout with lung cancer in 1977 he
underwent radiation treatment after doctors removed a malignant
tumor. He also was recovering from a broken hip at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult time for all of us,'' Newcombe said. ``But
Pee Wee was in a lot of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese is survived by his wife since 1942, Dorothy, and son Mark.
</P>
<P>
   Flags at Dodger Stadium in Los Angeles were flown at half-staff
for Saturday night's game against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Although Robinson, Campanella and Don Drysdale are gone, there
are a number of players from that 1955 team who are alive: Koufax,
Newcombe, pitchers Carl Erskine, Clem Labine Billy Loes, Joe Black,
Ed Roebuck and Johnny Podres; infielder Don Zimmer, center fielder
Duke Snider and an unknown left-hander named Tom Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the captain and he'll always be the captain,'' said
Lasorda, who went on to manage the Dodgers for 20 years and reach
the Hall of Fame. ``He was a great leader. We loved him very, very
much. Pee Wee was a Hall of Famer as a ballplayer, but more
importantly he was a Hall of Famer as a person. There isn't anyone
who played for the Dodgers who didn't love Pee Wee Reese.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese's short stature (5-foot-10, 160 pounds) and
self-deprecating nature belied his fierce competitiveness. But a
man who served a three-year stint in the Navy during World War II
became a perfect symbol for the Brooklyn Dodgers, who despite seven
trips to the World Series, were always viewed as underdogs to the
crosstown New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Six times they lost to the Yankees, which resulted in the
rallying cry, ``Wait Till Next Year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers were an immensely talented team that included
six future Hall of Famers, nine if you count manager Walter Alston
and broadcasters Vin Scully and Red Barber. But Reese, who came up
in 1940, was the unqualified leader, guiding the Dodgers to the
pennant in 1941, their first since 1920.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met him, I was so much in awe,'' Scully said.
``He was the heart and soul of the `Boys of Summer.' If a players
needed to be consoled, Pee Wee would console him. If a player
needed to be kicked in the fanny, Pee Wee would do that, too. If a
player really needed a friend, Pee Wee was there for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese was the National League's premier shortstop, playing in
New York, the center of the baseball universe that also had the
Yankees' Phil Rizzuto and the Giants' Alvin Dark.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the Dodgers leadoff hitter, leading the league in
walks (104) in 1947, runs scored (132) in 1949 and stolen bases
(30) in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Reese compiled a .269 lifetime batting average and is first
among Dodgers in walks (1,210) and runs (1,338).
</P>
<P>
   He was at his best in the World Series. In 1955, the Dodgers
went to a seventh game against the mighty Yankees and Reese
provided the spark. Reese fielded a ground ball for the final out
of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began to think we could never beat the Yankees,'' Newcombe
said. ``Then on that day in the clubhouse, Pee Wee said. `It looks
like we can beat these guys and show them that we can do it. Today
is the day we can do it.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
