<HEADER>
A7839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-HAAS-BOS &LR;      08-15 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-HAAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDIE-FREE DAY PUTS HAAS BACK WITH PACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Had they told him a few days ago that he would
be 6 under par through three rounds of this PGA Championship, Jay
Haas would have been very happy.
</P>
<P>
   So here he is, 6 under through 54 holes and Haas is anything but
happy. Quite the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed I didn't do better,'' said Haas. ``I had a
lot of chances, but my irons weren't very good. I just hit some bad
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first two days of this tournament, Haas quietly went
about his job, a tough task given the commotion that was going on
around him all week. But Haas is used to the background; he has
never screamed for the spotlight, never been flashy, and never hit
it a mile. All he has done is effectively put up a 22-year career
that includes nine wins and some serious runs at the Masters and
this championship.
</P>
<P>
   And with six birdies in an opening round of 68, and six more for
a 67 Friday, Haas was the surprise leader by one shot at 9 under
through 36 holes. A surprise to observers _ and to himself. ``I
haven't really been playing that well,'' he said. ``So it was nice
to get into this position.''
</P>
<P>
   At 45, Haas knows how to calm the nerves, so no worries as he
went off in the last group with lefthander Mike Weir. Surely, the
veteran would handle the moving day experience better than an
unproven youngster from Canada. Guess again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very cool. Hit a lot of nice shots and putted very
well,'' said Haas of his playing partner who would post a 69 to get
to 11 under, which will keep him in the final group Sunday _ this
time with Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Haas? He'll play a few groups in front, because his round of 75
dropped him to 6-under. It was a round without a birdie. It was
also a round that showed bad signs early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a great drive on the first hole and only had a 9-iron
left,'' said Haas, ``and I left it 40 feet short and right.'' He
settled for par on a hole he had birdied the first two days.
</P>
<P>
   Haas hit a bad shot on the par-3 second, and though he got it
up-and-down, it is hard to get deeper into red numbers when you are
scrambling for par. Particularly when those chasing you are making
birdies, like Weir did at the second to pull into a tie.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the last time all day Haas would have a piece of the
top spot. He made another bad approach to the par-4 third, made
bogey, and was one behind. At the sixth, he drove it perfectly and
thought he'd have a good chance to knock it close. ``But it landed
in a divot and I was lucky to gouge a 9-iron out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   When he made the turn in 39, Haas had fallen to 6 under. Tiger
Woods, playing ahead of Haas, was 10 under, Wier was at 9, Stewart
Cink and Jim Furyk were both at 7.
</P>
<P>
   Though he came home with nine straight pars, that isn't going to
gain you anything _ unless you're at a US Open or perhaps crazy
enough to return to Carnoustie. No, an even-par 36 knocked Haas
even further off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was 6:15 and Haas virtually had the whole right side of the
practice area to himself, with only Sweden's Gabriel Hjerstedt in
close view. Haas took some swings, then put on his coach's hat. His
son by the same name took his turn and began drilling shots into
the picture-perfect blue skies. Jay Haas Jr. is caddieing for his
father and in a few days he'll be heading to Augusta State College.
</P>
<P>
   As Team Haas hit balls, at the far end of the range, Woods was
about to end his practice session. So at the urging of fans, Woods
started his now-famous routine _ bouncing a ball off the face of
his wedge, keeping it going as he moved the club between his legs,
then back around. The fans loved it, but when Woods tried to finish
by whacking the ball down the range, he fanned.
</P>
<P>
   Loud groans, so Woods did it again. This time he succeeded, and
the fans roared.
</P>
<P>
   Woods moved rapidly from the range, as if he right then and
there wanted to tee it up in search of what very well could be his
second major title in his 12th chance as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   Haas barely noticed. He had a few more swings to make. He was
now five shots off the lead in his 67th start in a major
championship. Most likely it will end the same as the previous 66 _
without a win _ but it will be played the same way, too. With a
determined effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
