<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-15 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, CANADA! THERE'S A SURPRISE ATOP LEADERBOARD 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ We'll give them Larry Walker, but what is this
nonsense about a Canadian tying Tiger Woods for the third-round
lead in the PGA Championship?
</P>
<P>
   Golf, Canada. Canada, Golf. Does this have any kind of a ring?
</P>
<P>
   Sure it does. Kind of like, Baseball, Afghanistan. Afghanistan,
Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Larry Walker out of this, what does a good Canadian lad
do? He skates. He skates, he shoots, and, hopefully, he scores! Or
maybe he makes a skate save. He can play golf in his spare time. We
all know every NHL player worth his dentures loves golf. That
doesn't mean he's very good at it.
</P>
<P>
   This one is.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Mike Weir identifies himself as a hockey player. ``I
played some left wing as a kid,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Weir. Mike Who? Even the Canadians don't know from Mike
Weir, but he has shot 68-68-69_205 in the first three rounds of the
PGA and that's the same score as Tiger Woods. It's also two shots
better than Sergio Garcia's 207 (also Stewart Cink, who can
certainly play but needs to see a judge about a new name).
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the co-leaders far transcend the obvious
ones, like skin tone, place of birth, and bank accounts. Mike Weir
is lefthanded; how about that? Mike Weir was never on television
swinging a golf club at age 2. Mike Weir did not enter the PGA Tour
as an anointed prince, complete with endorsement deals. Mike Weir
came into the luxurious PGA the hard way, via Australia and the
dreaded Qualifying School.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger was raised to be a champion. Mike Weir was just another
sports-hungry kid in Sarnia, Ontario. He did not grow up
worshipping George Knudson or Al Balding, the only two Canadian
golfers anyone can name. He is from the same home town as Dino
Ciccarelli, Tony McKegney, Pat Verbeek, and all those damnable
Hunter Brothers (Dale, mostly). Lotta high sticks, there.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 10 or so the family moved across the street from the
Huron Oaks Country Club, and that's where young Michael was
introduced to golf. He wrote Jack Nicklaus a letter when he was 13
asking the great man if he should convert to playing righthanded.
Amazingly, Nicklaus wrote back, telling him to stay right where he
was, so to speak. So that was cleared up. Mike Weir could think
about becoming the next Bob Charles (this was pre-Phil Mickelson).
But so what? This was Canada, remember? The golf season is what,
two hours long?
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's a throwaway line. ``The season starts in late March.
It's still damp until then,'' reports Weir.
</P>
<P>
   He got good enough to earn a golf scholarship to BYU, although
it's not like he was Mr. Big, or anything. He turned pro in 1992
and got onto the Canadian Tour in 1993, but, no offense, no one
makes any money on the Canadian Tour. The goal is to get on the PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   His travels took him to Australia, and that wasn't what you call
a euphoric experience, either. ``I was in Australia, missing cut
after cut, with no money,'' he recalls. ``I remember battling out
there on the range, until it was so dark you couldn't see 5 feet in
front of you. I always keep those thoughts in the memory bank.''
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, that Draconian Q-School. He failed to get out of it the
first four tries. The fifth time, he started out with what he
called a ``good 75,'' after which he settled down and shot 27 under
par in the next five rounds to win medal honors. Hallelujah! Free
at last! And PGA-certified, too.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers often undergo dramatic technical transformations, and
Mike Weir is no exception. You think you know what you're doing
even when you really don't. Weir's epiphany came when he found
himself on a practice range one day in 1995 next to Nick Price,
then master of all he surveyed in the golfing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was coming off his club like little bullets, and I
thought, `There is no way I can do that with my swing,' '' says
Weir. ``I had to reconstruct everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to 1999. He missed the cut three of the first five
times out, but then got into a little groove. He was fifth at the
BellSouth Classic and played really well at the Motorola Western,
where he found himself paired with Himself in the final round.
Tiger already had a four-shot lead, so winning wasn't much of an
option. But Weir shot a respectable 70 and walked off with a
second-place finish and $270,000 paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   You probably missed that. Most Americans and Canadians did. The
first time most people heard of Mike Weir was Thursday, when he
shot that opening-round 68. Well, OK, a lot of unknowns and
quasi-knowns score well on Thursday. Most of them are home by
Saturday. Not Mike Weir. He has been abusing Medinah, and now a
whole lot of people will be tuning in Sunday to see Tiger battle
Sergio and asking themselves, ``Where did this little (5 feet 9
inches) lefty come from, and why is he saying `aboot?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm the underdog,'' he says. ``Tiger's the best player
in the world, and I'm a guy who once had no tour card.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and let's not forget Sergio, who, truth be told, definitely
forgot about him when he had the microphone. ``He's 19,'' says
Weir. ``Amazing. When I was 19, I couldn't even beat my buddies on
the BYU team, let alone the best players in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppose Weir wins. Will those madcap Canadians riot in the
streets? ``That's a good question,'' he says. ``They may get
excited. Or no one might care at all. I just hope I get to find
out, one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   A lefthanded Canadian refugee from the Q-School might win a
major. I've told you before and I'll tell you again. I'll take
truth, plus the points, over fiction any time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
