<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-MAGGERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGGERT'S ON CUP CUSP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ It is a most painful walk that golfers make,
those steps from the 18th green to the scorer's trailer after 18
holes that did not go particularly well.
</P>
<P>
   With reporters waiting, it becomes a bare-footed walk on
white-hot coals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, each of them stopped, void of excuses. Graciousness is
still present and accounted for out here.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Maggert was perhaps the most disappointed, though there is
still reason to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give my eye teeth to play,'' he said late Friday of his
desire for a Ryder Cup berth, ``but it is out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't when he arrived at Medinah, however, for he was 10th
in the Ryder Cup standings and could have secured his spot with a
good performance. Maggert failed. He shot 73-76 and missed the cut
at 5 over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mentally worn out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he remains 10th in the standings, several of those behind
him _ most notably Tom Lehman at No. 11 _ could push him out of
automatic-pick territory. No, he said with a smile, he wouldn't be
doing any voodoo as he watches the weekend action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Tom Lehman all the best. I'd like to see him play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   There was irony to the proceedings, said Maggert, recalling that
in both 1995 and 1997 he played his way onto the team with red-hot
PGA Championship finishes at Riviera and Winged Foot, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's my turn to get bounced out,'' he said. ``I can't
control that, though. I'm not going to go home and root against
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he embraces optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I finish 11th, I think I'm a strong contender (for a
captain's pick),'' he said. ``Certainly, I think my game fits The
Country Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Stricker and John Huston did not hold out such hope. They
entered this PGA Championship 12th and 13th in the standings and
knew it was simple: Play your way on. Both came up woefully short,
a fact so disheartening they talked of a season that is virtually
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ryder Cup was very important, no doubt I wanted to be on
that team,'' said Stricker, who shot 72-76 to miss the cut. It
included a back-nine 40 in the second round that had him shaking
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I double-bogeyed 15, bogeyed 16, and bogeyed 17, it was
hard to play 18. I don't expect to be picked. I wouldn't want to be
a part of the team the way I've been hitting it the last couple of
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker said he would go home and spend time putting the
disappointment behind him. No plans for any more tournaments, at
least not yet, said Stricker, and certainly no way he'll wait for
an invitation to the Sept. 24-26 matches in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Huston is another who doesn't expect any phone calls from US
captain Ben Crenshaw. His PGA Championship came to an end with a
second-day 80, an ugly effort lowlighted by a triple-bogey 6 at the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just playing horribly,'' said Huston. ``Mentally, I need some
time off. I'll play in Akron (the NEC Invitational, a World Golf
Championship event), then maybe not again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The push for a Ryder Cup spot, said Huston, had worn him down at
a time when his game was struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Janzen was another who had Ryder Cup hopes when he arrived
at Medinah, though admittedly his chance was more of a long shot.
He may be a two-time US Open champion and two-time Ryder Cup
member, but Janzen was 23d in the standings and probably needed to
win this event.
</P>
<P>
   He never came close, shooting 73-75 to miss the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Was he, too, disappointed? Just as he had been in 1995 when
captain Lanny Wadkins bypassed him with one of his two captain's
picks?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to catch a plane,'' said Janzen, waving off
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   We'll take that as yes, he's disappointed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
