<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JOHNSTON-MANFREDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSTON RETAINS WBC BELT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET PEQUOT RESERVATION _ There was a rare occurence in
a boxing ring Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at the Grand Pequot Ballroom at
Foxwoods Casino: Two guys who really knew how to fight were
actually fighting each other.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 rounds, World Boxing Council lightweight champion Stevie
Johnston and challenger Angel Manfredy put on a clinic on the manly
art of self-defense. This was no wild-eyed brawl, no lopsided
mismatch, no battle of clinches. This was boxing the way it used to
be, two technically proficient fighters working at close quarters
most of the night, slipping, feinting, landing some hard punches
and avoiding a lot more of them.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night when no one had to look to find the other because
it would have been difficult to slip a fax between them as they
fired away, each pressing the other and refusing to have their
wills broken even after one (Manfredy) had broken his right hand
and the other (Johnston) injured his left and bled from a cut that
needed many stitches to close.
</P>
<P>
   That neither carried the megatonnage to take out the other was
of little importance. This was boxing the way it's supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Johnston retained his title by unanimous decision as
judges Terry Smith and Tom Kaczmarek saw him a 116-112 winner,
while Bob Logist scored it 118-111 for the champion. The Globe card
also had Johnston winning, 116-112.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth round was typical as the two battled at close
quarters with Johnston strafing Manfredy from off the ropes with
some crushing right hands and Manfredy answering whenever his chin
wasn't being bombed. At the end of the round, you thought Johnston
had the edge but it wouldn't take the Lincoln-Douglas debates to
argue the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's only upset came earlier when Arturo Gatti didn't
have to go to a plasma center after his comeback win over
overmatched Reyes Munoz.
</P>
<P>
   The oft-lanced former junior lightweight champion made a quick
comeback after three straight losses when he stopped the factory
worker from Erie, Pa., at the end of the first round, dropping him
with a right behind the head and a short following left.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz got up staggering as referee Eddie Cotton approached but
before he could touch Munoz the fighter stumbled away, slumping
into the ropes and then turning from Cotton and bending over like a
man feeling sick to his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   When he continued to reel around blindly, Cotton stopped the
fight after finally lassoing him as the bell sounded to end the
opening round. Several minutes later, Munoz was flat on his back on
a stretcher and taken from the ring wearing a neck brace and an
oxygen mask as his mother and wife both stood crying and in shock
at ringside.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dr. Anthony Alessi said it was a precautionary measure
and later said Munoz was stable, it was a hard end to a hard road
Munoz had been walking throughout his boxing career. Munoz came
into this bout having trained two hours a day while not missing a
single one of his $12-an-hour shifts at an Erie factory that makes
concrete barriers, a disadvantage nearly as serious as the clear
talent difference between himself and the hard-punching Gatti.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 25 prize fights, Munoz had never had the opportunity to
be a professional fighter in the true sense and he quickly paid for
it Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. Although he fights for money, Munoz (21-4)
never made enough for a living, as Gatti (30-4, 25 KOs) had done
all his career.
</P>
<P>
   The $20,000 he earned Saturday &UR;  &LR; night didn't come easily either
during the fight or before it. It meant so much to his family that
his wife thanked HBO executive Lou DiBella for having given her
husband the opportunity. Just getting here on time cost Munoz three
vacation days.
</P>
<P>
   The vacation clearly stopped not long after he entered the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-champion, who was coming off an eight-month layoff and
three straight losses that had thrown his boxing future into doubt,
watched silently as Munoz was loaded on the stretcher and sent to
Backus Hospital in Norwich. When he was gone, a man who had often
left boxing rings bloody and battered could only say, ``I didn't
really know what this kid had. It was my comeback fight after three
losses but Munoz's condition puts a damper on everything. I'm very
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   So was a family to whom $20,000 seemed like a lot less money
when Reyes Munoz was leaving the arena than when he came into it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
