<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW SURPRISES FOR SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The loudest sound in the Seattle clubhouse came from a
single air conditioning vent. Only the persistent rattle saved the
room from absolute silence. But despite the best efforts of the
noisy machinery, a mustiness enveloped the area where players
quickly dressed and tersely commented on Saturday's events.
</P>
<P>
   When just a handful of players and coaches remained, a video of
the Mariners' 13-2 loss to the Red Sox was replayed on a television
in the corner. The visitors cued the tape to the top of the fifth
inning. Lefthanded pitcher Rheal Cormier readied himself on the
mound for one final out. Then, the camera cut to a grinning Pedro
Martinez in the bullpen. The Red Sox ace turned temporary reliever
chewed his gum and blew pink bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the action on the field, Cormier delivered his
final pitch and Seattle catcher Tom Lampkin singled to right. Butch
Huskey fielded the ball and threw home, attempting to prevent David
Bell from scoring. The plate umpire called the Mariner out. Manager
Lou Piniella and third base coach Steve Smith earned ejections for
arguing the play. From all angles on the tape, Bell appeared safe.
</P>
<P>
   In 30 seconds of muted video, Seattle's disappointing afternoon
played out a second time. Between the controversial call at the
plate that robbed the visitors of a second run in the fifth and the
smiling bullpen visage of a tardy Martinez, the Mariners had a
catalog of bizarre distractions to choose from. But none of the
game's oddities could take the focus of a second loss at Fenway
that dropped Seattle farther out of the playoff picture in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised,'' said Alex Rodriquez about seeing
Martinez in a relief role, ``but he wants to get his work in. It
doesn't mean anything. The game was out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox held a 7-1 lead when the ace relieved Cormier. And
Rodriguez's home run in the sixth and double in the eighth did
little to improve matters.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle pitcher Jeff Fassero, who played with Martinez in
Montreal, chatted with the scheduled starter over the bullpen wall.
The two former teammates touched briefly on Martinez's late
arrival. The Boston pitcher did not elaborate on his tardiness,
adding only that because he was late manager Jimy Williams decided
not to start him. Instead, Martinez and Fassero talked about old
times with the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their business, not ours,'' said Fassero, when asked
about Martinez's lack of punctuality.
</P>
<P>
   The only player on the Seattle side investing any significance
in a relief appearance by the Dominican was Edgar Martinez. The
Mariners' designated hitter collected his 1,500th career hit with a
single in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro is one of the best pitchers in baseball,'' said Edgar
Martinez. ``It means more when you can get it off of somebody like
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the corner of the clubhouse opposite the video machinery,
Bell sat and calmly tried to explain the controversial play.
Piniella was not available for comment. The second baseman said he
didn't feel a tag, but could not tell how much the swipe by Boston
catcher Jason Varitek missed his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game can be kind of unpredictable at times,'' said Bell.
``But the bottom line is that we lost and that's all we're thinking
about right now. (Pedro and the controvesial call) are the kind of
things that you have to kind of deal with and be ready to handle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7844 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      08-15 1940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS FIASCO IS RICH 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ It was the week pro golf turned into major
league baseball. Or was it the NBA? No matter. It became everything
you detest about professional sports. Instead of Dave Pelz
infomercials, The Golf Channel probably went in search of Judge
Wapner or Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen holes worth of thoughts, observations, and wonderment:
</P>
<P>
   1) Phil Mickelson demanded to know, ``Who negotiated that
deal?'' when advised that The Country Club was being paid millions
to host the Ryder Cup. To which he should have been told: ``None of
your business. Now put down the briefcase, take off the Rolex, and
pick up your clubs. Go find the range and work on that swing so it
holds up when the pressure is on.''
</P>
<P>
   2) David Duval told us that he never used the word ``boycott.''
What he said was: ``It would take players not playing'' to change
things. Funny, sounds like the definition of boycott.
</P>
<P>
   3) Duval said he perhaps should not have called the Ryder Cup
``an exhibition,'' a term that enraged captain Ben Crenshaw. ``How
can David say that,'' said Crenshaw, ``when he hasn't even played
in one?'' But Duval only recanted halfway. ``But it seems like a
large corporate outing, doesn't it?'' he said. Sure it does. Just
like every other sporting event that goes on in this country.
Wonder if Duval had a problem with that corporate outing at TPC
Sawgrass in March? Or was the $900,000 check enough of a pacifier?
</P>
<P>
   4) We were told time and again ``everyone was on the same
page.'' To his credit, Duval told us he did not want to receive any
compensation in any form. Next in the press room, Tiger Woods said,
``I would like to see us receive whatever the amount is, whether it
is $200,000, $300,000, $400,000, $500,000 . . . whatever it is. And
I think we should be able to keep the money and do whatever we see
fit. For me, personally, I would donate all of it to charity. But I
think it's up to the other person's discretion of what they want to
do with it.'' Maybe they are on the same page. But it sounds like
they are reading different books.
</P>
<P>
   5) Nick Faldo, probably the most confused golfer on the planet,
stood on the putting green in front of Medinah Country Club's
massive clubhouse, wearing a sly grin as two dozen reporters chased
after players who had just left a closed-door meeting. ``And they
wonder why they can't win this team event,'' is what the look on
his face said.
</P>
<P>
   6) Duval was asked if this was all about having money given to
him so that he could dish it to charity and receive a big tax
break. Stunned, Duval shook his head. ``Man, I'm just a golfer,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   7) Let me understand: The PGA of America (a nonprofit
organization) opens its books, shows where it funnels money from
the Ryder Cup, and the players say there is no problem with where
it goes. It's just that a few private-jet golfers would like
control, a voice, some accountability.
</P>
<P>
   8) Which makes me wonder: When Larry Rinker, Danny Edwards, and
a few of the second- and third-tier players wanted the PGA Tour (a
for-huge-profit organization) to open its books and explain a few
financial matters, all they were talking about was having control,
a voice, some accountability. The private-jet golfers screamed,
``No way. All is well.''
</P>
<P>
   9) Mark O'Meara claimed Crenshaw had not singled him out. Yes he
did, O'Meara was told. No he didn't, said O'Meara. Yes he did,
O'Meara was told. Finally, O'Meara realized that Crenshaw had, in
fact, named him. He walked away muttering, ``I still can't believe
he singled me out.'' Mark, have you been living on the moon
recently?
</P>
<P>
   10) Mark James: ``We're not going into the Ryder Cup for money.
Never have been. Even in Europe the guys who are making the team
are making 350,000-400,000 pounds prize money. And you want a bit
more for playing in the Ryder Cup? When half the Tour would
actually pay to play in it? We're losing touch with reality, some
people, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   11) Crenshaw: ``I'm personally disappointed in a couple of
people in that meeting. I mean that. And they know who they are.
And whether some players like it or not, there are some people who
came before them that mean a hell of a lot to this game. And it
burns the hell out of me to listen to some of their viewpoints.'' A
round of applause, please.
</P>
<P>
   12) What did Jay Haas think of Crenshaw's statements? ``It's
about time,'' said Haas.
</P>
<P>
   13) Sitting in the audience listening to Crenshaw speak was club
pro Bruce Zabriski. He got so fired up that he told some reporters
he was ready to run through walls for the captain. If you ever saw
Zabriski, you would have no doubt that he could run through a wall.
</P>
<P>
   14) Remember Woods vs. Duval Aug. 2? Made-for-TV excitement? How
about another one, say Woods-O'Meara vs. Duval-Mickelson? Let's say
they schedule it for Sept. 25, a Saturday night. It conflicts with
the Ryder Cup, so it is perfect. They get an exhibition that
shouldn't be taken seriously, and they get the all-important
dollar. Crenshaw gets to pick Tom Lehman, Fred Couples, Corey
Pavin, Paul Azinger, Hale Irwin, and Zabriski to round out his
12-man team. The US wins, 17-11. Woods-O'Meara vs. Duval-Mickelson
pulls in a 6.2 rating. Everybody is happy.
</P>
<P>
   15) The PGA of America is not totally without blame. It knew
about this mess. Tom Kite has been quoted as saying he warned the
organization after the 1997 debacle in Valderrama that the issue
had to be addressed. The PGA of America let it go too far.
</P>
<P>
   16) Davis Love. His passion for the game is genuine. He
rightfully felt the issue should have been settled behind closed
doors. It wasn't, not because of the media, but because
self-centered players like Woods and Duval sadly have aligned
themselves with the ultimate boor, O'Meara, instead of a class act
such as Love.
</P>
<P>
   17) In all of this mess, hardly any mention was made of the club
pros. They are the heart and soul of the organization and I would
be willing to bet that nearly every PGA Tour pro owes something to
a club pro somewhere down the line. With all the talk of spreading
out the proceeds, not enough people have said that the club pros
deserve a bigger piece of the pie. They do.
</P>
<P>
   18) Somehow, we managed to have all this chaos without John Daly
in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two best stories of 1999 in golf? Give me Jerry Higginbottom
and Colin Cann. They were the well-respected caddies for O'Meara
and Annika Sorenstam, respectively, until those relationships came
to an end. Surely, their many friends felt for them, since toting
bags for such high-profile and successful golfers is rewarding and
from all accounts, neither Higginbottom nor Cann was guilty of
anything other than being in a high-risk trade. But before anyone
could feel too sorry for them, Higginbottom and Cann landed quite
nicely _ the former with Sergio Garcia, the latter with Grace Park.
Garcia, you know about. Park, you soon will, for it says here she
will be the dominating LPGA Tour player starting in 2000. Park,
last summer's US Women's Amateur champion, turned pro after the US
Women's Open in early June, and is proof positive that sometimes
father does know best. Her father, an extremely wealthy and
influential businessman in Korea, insisted on a long-term
investment, not a short-term fling of sponsor's exemptions to LPGA
Tour events. Thus, Park has toiled far from the spotlight, playing
the hard-to-find Futures Tour. With four wins in eight starts, she
is the leading money-winner, a status that would be rewarded with
her Tour card for next year. No qualifying school for this young
lady, whose power, finesse, and composure will take the sport by
storm next year . . . So how did a kid from Madison, Wis., end up
at the University of Hartford? It was the only college where he
would be able to play golf and hockey, said Jerry Kelly. Then, he
said, ``They dropped hockey when I got there. I was awfully
disappointed, but in retrospect it was the best thing that ever
happened to me.'' Kelly is in his fourth year on the PGA Tour and
made the cut in the PGA Championship after getting in as first
alternate. Last year, Kelly withdrew from the championship to be
with his wife on the birth of their son, Cooper. Two of Kelly's
best friends are NHLers from his hometown _ Kevin Dean, now with
the Atlanta Thrashers, and Barry Richter . . . Ironic twist to this
pay-for-play nonsense: The PGA of America announced that it has
gotten involved with an important renovation project at Clearview
Golf Club in East Canton, Ohio. It is the first and only golf
course in the US designed, built, and managed by an
African-American, William J. Powell. His daughter, Renee, a former
LPGA Tour player, is the head pro and son Lawrence is the course
superintendent. Architects Michael Hurdzan and Pete Dye have been
enlisted by the PGA of America to help with renovations, which
should be completed by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a short but very sweet PGA Championship experience for
Mike Baker, the club pro out of Bangor, Maine. ``For the first
eight holes I felt like I belonged out here,'' said Baker, who went
to the second stage of Tour qualifying last year and may give it
another shot this fall, ``but then I played the last 10 like a
dunce.'' He shot 36-44 for an opening 80, and followed it up with a
75 to post an 11-over total. ``I gave the folks back home something
to get excited about early,'' said Baker. Still, the trip was
everything Baker had thought it would be. ``Actually more so,'' he
said. ``It was kind of neat signing autographs, even though nobody
knew who I was. I wasn't that nervous on my first drive. I was more
nervous when I got it under par.'' Baker's caddie was Tom Caron,
who works for the Bangor Daily News. If possible, he had a more
enjoyable trip than Baker, though this was a ``one-time job.''
Caron filed daily accounts for his newspaper and said lugging a
pro's golf bag is a heavier burden than he had imagined. ``But he
would have to have paid to have the club provide a caddie,'' said
Caron, laughing. ``I was doing it for free. I saved him big
bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What has been a tough stretch of golf took a good turn at a most
opportune time for James Driscoll of Chestnut Hill. The
senior-to-be at the University of Virginia won the prestigious
North-South Amateur at Pinehurst No. 2 Friday, thrashing John Pitt,
9 and 7, in the 36-hole final.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad way to head to Pebble Beach, where Driscoll will begin
play in the US Amateur Sunday. The two-time Massachusetts Amateur
champion was coming off a disappointing collegiate career, as well
as an earlier-than-expected exit from the State Am at Kittansett.
</P>
<P>
   At Pinehurst Friday, Driscoll made just three birdies, but the
key to his victory was a bushel of pars. In fact, he told Golfweek,
``I was lucky that I caught a lot of good players on their off
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Pitt, Driscoll stormed to a 5-up lead through 10 holes,
and did not relinquish honors at the tee until the 16th. Pitt won
holes 15-17 to reduce Driscoll's lead to 3 up, much to delight of
the hometown fans (Pitt hails from Wilmington, N.C.).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little worried at the end of the morning round,'' said
Driscoll. ``He had the momentum from his gallery and I told myself
to forget the morning round, to treat the afternoon as a separate
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to win the afternoon match.''
</P>
<P>
   He followed his game plan to the letter, jumping out quickly to
get back up by five holes and cruising to the impressive win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
