<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7845 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     08-15 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD FEELINGS FOR WILLIAMS TO MOP UP 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ These should be glory days at Fenway Park. The Sox are
rolling, Brian Daubach (5 for 5 Saturday, 11 RBIs in two days) is
suddenly a direct descendant of Walt Dropo and Fred Lynn, every
game is a sellout, and Boston again leads the wild-card bakeoff.
</P>
<P>
   So why was there old-timey turmoil at Fenway Saturday? Why did
$75 million ace Pedro Martinez rip into manager Jimy Williams after
getting credit for his 17th win with four innings of mop-up duty?
</P>
<P>
   Because Williams spanked Martinez for being too late to prepare
for his start. Williams opted for the immortal Bryce Florie, then
summoned Pedro for garbage-time punishment with the Sox leading,
7-1, in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who said he was late because he was at home working
with a personal therapist, was furious with his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on time to start,'' said the ace. ``I excused myself
with my teammates, but Jimy didn't let me do it . . . Jimy wanted
to be stubborn. I told him that there's no reason to do that. It
could have stayed in the clubhouse, but instead he had to make a
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, Martinez added, ``He didn't have any reason to
embarrass me out there. If I'm a bad influence on the team, they'd
better get me out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's door was closed after Pedro delivered his postgame
blast. But before the ace was interviewed, the manager said, ``He
was late. We had to make a decision and start another pitcher. He
wasn't here yet. I didn't know where he was. He got here after the
decision was made to start another pitcher. You don't just come in
and throw your clothes on and run out to the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The club rule is that starting pitchers must be at the park one
hour before game time. According to Williams, Martinez was still
absent about a half-hour before the game. Martinez admitted being
late, but insisted he was prepared to start. After engaging in a
heated exchange with Williams, he went out to the bullpen. By that
time Florie, who had yet to start throwing, was stretching in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Jimy doesn't trust my way of being out there every
five days,'' said Martinez. ``He knows I told him the truth. I
guess you're better off lying. If I had told him a family member
passed away, it probably would have been OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager would not make any comment on disciplinary action,
saying, ``We keep everything in-house.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Martinez claimed the manager did not do.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we're still wondering why in the name of Denny
Galehouse Williams would bring Martinez out of the bullpen to start
the sixth inning of a game the Sox were leading, 7-1 _ a game
Boston went on to win, 13-2? Williams would appear to have
forfeited one of Pedro's starts in the name of principle.
</P>
<P>
   How is this good for the team? It was a maneuver of Daddy Butch
Hobson dimensions. With Saturday's game in hand and Pedro still on
ice, would it not have made sense to pitch the ace Sunday, then
bring him back on Friday? Mark Portugal gets bumped. Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   When this question was put to Joe Kerrigan, the pitching coach
said nothing except, ``You're asking the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought him in because we needed another reliever,'' said
Williams. ``I'm trying to win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Punishment?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, just trying to help the team win a game,'' said the
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Why not pitch Pedro Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   ``A moot point. You can answer that yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Why bring him into a game that's over?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you look at baseball different than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess so. Virtual Rheal Cormier (who relieved Florie and pitched
to one batter) could have stayed in the game. Rich Garces and Mark
Guthrie were available. And if the Sox can't trust their
(admittedly depleted) bullpen with a 7-1 lead in the sixth, what
chance do they have in the race anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The bizarro day got off to a funny start for members of Red Sox
Nation who came to see Pedro and got Florie. It was the baseball
equivalent of buying your ticket to see Dustin Hoffman in ``Death
of a Salesman,'' then watching the curtain go up and looking at
Matt LeBlanc as Willy Loman.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox fans lined up for standing room early Saturday. They
poured into Fenway toting K-cards and Dominican flags. Nobody
thought to bring the state flag of South Carolina, the home of
Florie.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be one of those World Cup-Comes-To-Fenway
Saturday afternoon specials. But Pedro was late for work and the
Sox opted for the immortal Florie as a stand-in starter.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro is hardly the first Sox starter to have trouble getting to
the park on time. When Oil Can Boyd worked here, Sox management was
in constant crisis, waiting around the clubhouse wondering if the
Can would show _ much like Boston Garden rock fans of the 1970s,
hoping the Rolling Stones would get out of a Rhode Island jail in
time to start a concert before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Florie's 4 2/3-inning stint was impressive, but a far cry from
the best in Sox history. Most of you no doubt remember Ernie
Shore's effort against the Washington Senators in 1917. In the
first game of a doubleheader, Babe Ruth walked leadoff hitter Ray
Morgan, then got tossed after beefing with umpire Brick Owen.
Without any warmup, Shore came on and retired 26 consecutive
batters after Morgan was caught stealing.
</P>
<P>
   Cormier came in to get the last out in the fifth Saturday, and
could have been awarded the easy victory, but official scorer
Charles Scoggins opted to give the win to the $75 million mop-up
man.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez surrendered a solo homer to Alex Rodriguez, but not
much more. The first K-Card went up when he picked up his 200th
strikeout (Jay Buhner) of the season. He finished with six
punchouts in four three-hit innings as the game lurched toward its
inevitable conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Then he blasted his manager.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
