<SLUG> BC-WONDERLAND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PA'S BELLA FASTER THAN `EDDIE' 
</HEADLINE>
 DERBY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVERE, Mass. _ The 65th running of the Wonderland Derby was
billed as a one-dog race, but, in truth, there were two top
greyhounds in the event, and 5-1 ($12.80 to win) second choice Pa's
Bella beat 2-5 favorite NR's Fast Eddie out of the box Saturday
night and was never headed as she romped to a 6-length victory.
</P>
<P>
   Based at Raynham Park, Pa's Bella was the second point-getter in
qualifying for the Derby, winning three straight before running
fourth in her final prelim. But NR's Fast Eddie had won all four
and run a blazing fast 37.92, second fastest in history for the
2,045 feet of the Revere Course. As a result, NR's Fast Eddie got
all the publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Pa's Bella, a 29-month-old daughter of P's Rasing Cain-Pacific
Episode, broke from No. 8 and simply was quicker to the turn than
NR's Fast Eddie, who started from No. 1. NR's Fast Eddie chased
bravely but to no avail, and Pa's Bella earned the $60,000 winner's
share for owner George Benjamin, who owns Benjamin's restaurant in
Taunton. The final time was 38.15, the third fastest in stakes
history, over a track turned wet by heavy rains that began about an
hour before post time of the Derby. TM's Show Buzz was along in
time to be third at 10-1 from box No. 2, another 4 1/2 lengths
behind, while Melleray was fourth, 2 more lengths in arrears, at
14-1 from box No. 3. The 8-1-2-3 superfecta returned $670.20.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she sprinted at Raynham, she had a great run,'' said
Benjamin, who has 80 dogs in his kennel at Raynham. ``The 8 hole is
her best hole in sprints. Once she gets running room, she's tough
to beat. She has some punch at the end. We tried her three times
going long at Raynham. The first time she took the lead and got
caught late, then she won the next two. She took to this track, as
you could see. I knew she had the right hole, it was just a matter
of the break.''
</P>
<P>
   Pa's Bella has a record of 37-20-6-4-5 at Raynham, and she
zipped through the first three qualifiers at Wonderland with clear
sailing. However, in the last prelim, she came up against NR's Fast
Eddie and could do no better than fourth, which accounted, in part,
for the disparity in the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got trapped inside and never got a chance to run in that
final qualifier,'' said trainer Glenn Atkinson. ``NR's Fast Eddie
had never been contested. I wanted to see what would happen if he
was challenged for the lead. Whichever dog went to the front was
going to win because, even though it rained, the track stayed fast.
NR's Fast Eddie is a nice greyhound and I wouldn't want to have to
run against him 10 times in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Being from Taunton, Benjamin grew up around dog racing there,
when the Taunton track was open, and at Raynham, which eventually
added Taunton's dates. ``I always enjoyed dog racing,'' he said.
``I love the sport. I tied in with Glenn 15 years ago and we've had
our good times and our bad times. We had a dog, Dicky Valle, who
won the Greyhound Race of Champions. It's no longer run, but it had
a purse of $200,000, and we got $100,000 for that. This one is
sweet, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pa's Bella has two full sisters, Pa's She Cat and Pa's Reale,
who are almost as good, although they don't have the strong finish
she has, and are more suited to a sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pa's Bella is great in the kennel,'' said Atkinson. ``She's
happy-go-lucky. She's a great dog, with a great personality. Her
two sisters are very good, but she's the best of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Next for Pa's Bella will be the American Derby at Lincoln Sept.
11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
