<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Aug. 16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MILITARY (Tokyo) _ Driven in part by the perceived growing
threat of a missile attack from North Korea, from the rising sense
of insecurity in East Asia, and from a general weariness with war
guilt, 45 years after World War II ended, the Japanese government
has broken out of its usual reticence on the topic of the country's
military past, just as it has begun pushing to build up its feeble
defenses. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-DRUGWAR (Palmapampa, Peru) _ After recent gains against
drug smuggling that had made coca growing unprofitable, prices are
now back up and authorities in Peru and the United States are once
again deepening their involvement in a cyclical drug war. By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-MEMORIAL (Omagh, Northern Ireland) _ How the maimed and
bereaved of this town in Northern Ireland are doing on the first
anniversary of the deadliest bomb attack in 30 years of sectarian
warfare. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
on Sunday defused a crisis with a key Orthodox party that had
threatened to leave his governing coalition because part of a huge
turbine was allowed to be transported on the Sabbath in
contravention of religious law. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A military analysis of the fighting in
the Caucasus republic of Dagestan. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MEDIA (Prague, Czech Republic) _ How the media covering
Kosovo are faring now that the war is over. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Daily developments and a
look at what it is like for the Russian peacekeepers in Kosovo. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   DONATED-DRUGS-STUDY _ Public health officials have long
suspected that many drugs donated to aid groups to be sent overseas
do not meet local medical needs or are likely to expire before they
can be used. A new study by the Harvard School of Public Health
concludes that concerns over the quality of donated drugs are
well-founded. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-HOTEL-FIGHT (Cannes, France) _ In Cannes, a grandson is
fighting over a hotel, a family name and its heritage. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTONS-HOUSEHUNTING _ The Clintons _ Bill, Hillary, Chelsea
and Grandmother Rodham _ are looking at houses in Westchester. By
Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   LA-SHOOTING-GUNS _ The violent saga of Buford O. Furrow Jr., the
white supremacist who wounded five last week at a Jewish day center
and admitted that he killed a letter carrier in Los Angeles,
highlights another aspect of the nation's guns laws: that members
of hate groups can legally buy firearms or become licensed firearms
dealers. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN-CONGRESS (Lafayette, La.) _ Thousands of Acadian
descendants from 81 families with names like LeBlanc, Broussard and
Thibodeaux have convened in towns throughout the 22-parish region
of Louisiana officially called Acadiana. They have traveled from
all over the United States, and from Canada and France, to join the
second bilingual cultural celebration called Congres Mondial
Acadien. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   MO-LIVESTOCK-LAWSUIT (Unionville, Mo.) _ As states are starting
to monitor livestock production as they would a smokestack
industry, Missouri sued a giant pork producer for violating the
state Clean Water Act. The company has agreed to a settlement of
about $25 million, largest civil settlement with any livestock
operation in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DALAI-LAMA (New York) _ The Dalai Lama holds a service in
Central Park. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-STRAWPOLL-ASSESS (Ames, Iowa) _ An assessment, following up
on the results of the Iowa straw poll here on Saturday. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON-NOVEL (Washington) _ Long forgotten in the civilian
world, the 1968 novel ``Once An Eagle'' has reached cult status in
the Army, Marines and the upper echelons of the Pentagon. It is the
basis for countless seminars, classes and is required reading for
every Marine officer. A look at how and why this novel has become
the favorite metaphor for the military. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIOTECH-CROPS (Washington) _ A scientist directing a key
study on genetically engineered crops at the prestigious National
Academy of Sciences left last month for a job with the
biotechnology industry, angering environmental scientists who say
they fear the final report will now be biased toward the industry's
points of view. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   MILLS-PROFILE (Washington) _ A profile of Cheryl Mills, the
Clinton defense lawyer who vaulted to fame with her impassioned
defense in the impeachment trial and who has since turned down the
job of chief White House counsel. By Robin Toner. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Anthony Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: William Safire is on vacation.
</P>
