   CULTURE (Moving in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POETRY-SLAM (Chicago) _ The National Poetry Slam is back in
Chicago for its 10th anniversary. By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERTS (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook on the
patterns in Bruce Springsteen's local concert series. By Neil
Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   BACH-MANUSCRIPTS (Undated) _ The story of the search for the
Bach archive, discovered by scholars last month in a huge cache of
German musical scores hidden in Ukraine's Central State
Archive-Museum of Literature and Art, is straight out of a Cold War
novel. The collection, including hundreds of unpublished
manuscripts by Johann Sebastian Bach's sons and forebears, was long
feared to be lost or destroyed. It has been in Ukraine ever since
the Red Army took it from Germany as a trophy after World War II.
By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIMENT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Neil Gordon reviews ``The
Experiment,'' by John Darnton.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ D.J.R. Bruckner reviews
``They've Got Death Bound Up,'' a lyrical and colorful show that
the Puerto Rican Traveling Theater and Pregones Theater is
presenting in their annual series that this year runs in parks in
all five boroughs of New York and several New Jersey sites through
Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL (Moving in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-SPORTS (Vancouver, British Colombia) _ Electronic Arts'
digital studio here, where sports stars have their movements
recorded for digital rendering in computer and video games, is
helping propel best-selling titles like the hit ``FIFA Soccer.'' By
John Markoff. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-BANKS (Frankfurt) _ More on the French takeover battle
involving Banque Nationale de Paris, Paribas and Societe Generale.
By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-BUYING (Undated) _ What the latest book-sales data from the
book industry say about what kind of books are selling _ and by
what means. Among other findings, mail order is clearly giving way
to online sales. By Doreen Carvajal. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ACCESS (Undated) _ By now, with AOL attracting all the
beginners, and with giants like Microsoft and AT&AMP;T mopping up
around the edges, the Internet access market was supposed to be out
of reach of small local and regional players. But many a
mom-and-pop ISP is thriving, charging as little as $5 a month to
put people on the Net. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Short news items about computer and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Traditional retailers have spent
the last two years watching the Internet play havoc with their
businesses. To divine the secrets of the new medium, they have been
forced to study their virtual counterparts for clues on how to
compete in this radically different arena. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ As the market for technology stocks
continues its lurching slide, some of us with memories that predate
Internet Time are thinking about infinite loops. The Digital
Commerce column. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   OGILVY-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ A division of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
Worldwide in New York is seeking to raise its profile by doing the
same for its parent. The division is the Brand Integration Group,
which works on assignments in areas like design, corporate identity
and packaging for clients including American Express, IBM, Mattel
and Sears, Roebuck. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   GPS-PROBLEMS (Undated) _ For unwary users of a government
satellite system that guides ships and airplanes, keeps cellular
networks humming and helps surveyors lay out property lines, next
weekend could be marred by a disorienting flashback. The system is
about to run out of the allotted digital space for timekeeping that
keeps it running properly. By Barnaby J. Feder. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIR-CUTBACKS (London) _ British Airways is not only planning
to cut jobs, it is also planning a pan-European legal battle to
force some of its biggest competitors to drop incentives paid to
travel agents. It contends that these incentives are the same as
the ones the European Commission forced it to abandon. By Andrew
Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   ALUM-MERGER-TALKS (Undated) _ The board of Reynolds Metals is
expected to have a Sunday board meeting to discuss competing bids.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-COLUMN (Undated) _ A look at joint operating agreements,
in light of the Hearst-Chronicle deal in San Francisco. Has the era
of the JOA passed? By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ Short news items about the media
business.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
