<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DALAILAMA16-COX     08-15 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALAILAMA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dalai Lama begins 11-day visit to Indiana
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Donna Denman was raised a Presbyterian, but four
times a week she sits cross-legged on the floor of the Dharma
Center in Yellow Springs, chanting and meditating and focused on a
statue of the Buddha.
</P>
<P>
   Denman, 65, retired director of the Greene County Housing
Authority, has practiced Zen Buddhism for the past 11 years. ``My
life goal has always been to serve others,'' she says, then laughs,
because she knows how Pollyanna-ish that sounds. ``I had a desire
to be unselfish, but no way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major themes in Buddhism is our interdependence.
What we think affects how we act, which affects other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practicing Buddhism, the self begins to disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Transcendence from selfish concerns: By its very nature,
Buddhism seems incompatible with America's consumer society, fueled
by manufactured needs from tanning salons to sports utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But like the grains of sand in a mandala, particles of Buddhism
have sifted through to American popular culture: meditation and
yoga, the Beatles and Richard Gere.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred years older than Christianity, conceived in India
and exported throughout most of Asia, Buddhism increasingly appeals
to the intellectual curiosity and spiritual hunger of contemporary
Westerners, too.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic, then, that the Dalai Lama comes to Indiana this
week, not so much as an ambassador for Buddhism, but to deliver a
message that is most startling to hear from a religious leader:
That is, religion doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, Ethics for the New Millennium, the spiritual
and political leader of Tibet writes that ``... I have come to the
conclusion that whether or not a person is a religious believer or
not does not matter much. Far more important is that they be a good
human being.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama, speaks today at Market Square Arena in
Indianapolis on the subject of ``Transforming the Millennium.'' He
then travels to Bloomington, home of his older brother, a retired
Indiana University professor. At Bloomington's Tibetan Cultural
Center, the Dalai Lama will lead the eight-day ``Kalachakra
Initiation for World Peace,'' considered the most sacred of
Buddhist rituals.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony of teachings, prayers, meditations, dances and the
making and dismantling of a mandala _ a colored sand diagram used
as a meditational aid _ will be translated from Tibetan into
English and other languages. About 4,000 people are expected to
attend, paying $50 a day for a seat in the white, air-conditioned
tent.
</P>
<P>
   The public is invited, although there are posted prohibitions:
``While you are on the premises, observe the rules for lay
Buddhists living in pure conduct: i.e. no killing, stealing, lying,
sex, drugs or alcohol. Please respect the environment. Do not
litter.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his 11-day visit to Indiana, the Dalai Lama is
expected to hit hard on the theme of inter-religious harmony and
the need to forge a universally accepted code of ethical conduct _
work that has traditionally been done within the boundaries of the
world's religions, but doesn't necessarily have to begin there.
</P>
<P>
   How to do so? It's not an original idea, he writes in his book,
``but ordinary common sense ... we take as our starting point the
observation that we all desire happiness and not to suffer ... each
individual has a right to pursue happiness and avoid suffering ...
one of the things which determines whether an act is ethical or not
is its effect on anothers' ... experience or expectation of
happiness. An act that harms or does violence to this is
potentially an unethical act.''
</P>
<P>
   This 14th Dalai Lama, said to be reincarnated from his
predecessor in order to serve the people, has charmed much of the
world with his compassion, wit and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very dignified, quiet and humble,'' says Yuan Tsing, a
retired professor of Asian history at Wright State University, who
met the Dalai Lama in Bloomington about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of average build, wearing glasses and speaking English with a
heavy accent, the Dalai Lama repeatedly describes himself as a
``simple monk _ no more and no less.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1960, when the Communist Chinese invaded Tibet, the Dalai
Lama has carried out his duties from exile in India. His efforts to
seek autonomy for Tibet without the use of violence earned him the
1989 Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Among Buddhists, the Dalai Lama has as much respect as the pope
does among Catholics, Pryor says. But the Dalai Lama doesn't have
the organizational power. Buddhism isn't hierarchical; part of its
appeal to the estimated 2 to 5 million Americans who call
themselves Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very psychologically focused tradition, which fits well
with contemporary thought,'' says Robert Pryor, who teaches
``Buddhism in America'' at Antioch University. ``It resonates so
well with how Americans are feeling today, when you look at all the
phenomenal change in modern life. (Buddhism's) fundamental
challenge is accepting change and dealing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 60 paying members of the Dharma Center in Yellow
Springs, a nonprofit corporation created to provide information and
access to all forms of Buddhism: Zen, Tibetan, Vipassana and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Although Buddha was an historical figure, Buddhism doesn't
recognize a prime mover or creator, Pryor says. The focus is on
``the present, not how we got here. You just figure out how to live
your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans have found that they can appropriate bits and pieces
of Buddhism while still holding on to their other religious
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   That practicality is one of its attractions for Leisa Schaim, a
22-year-old Antioch student. Although she still feels connected to
her Jewish heritage, Judaism for her ``is centered so much on
prayers that somone else wrote. It is not personally connected to
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddhism seems to me a more concrete way of learning how to
live well and deal with life's circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many Americans, she came to Buddhism through the practice
of meditation, something she felt she needed to deal with the
stress in her life. Now, she says, she's leaning toward Buddhism
because ``I like the silence. That helps me more than parables.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll attend one day of the Kalachakra this week with a few
other Antioch students. Does she believe that a room full of people
chanting, praying and meditating can help bring about world peace?
She smiles. ``I don't know. I'm such a skeptic.'' She's taking her
time as she becomes comfortable with Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   And from skepticism, faith may flower.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
