<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EXPERIMENT-BOOK-REVIE     08-15 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPERIMENT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE EXPERIMENT': A WORLD OF UNCANNY COINCIDENCES AND DEAD RINGERS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Neil Gordon is the New Fiction Forum editor at The Boston
Review and author, most recently, of ``The Gun Runner's Daughter,''
a novel; publication notes at end.) 
(nk) 
 By NEIL GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The opening pages of John Darnton's second thriller are a
catalog of the impossible, incredible and entirely inexplicable. As
the plot develops, it's propelled by a series of ever more blatant
coincidences. If the suspense genre demands the illusion of an
inevitable unfolding of events toward a revelation that, no matter
how implausible, is impossible to disbelieve, ``The Experiment''
violates every tenet of the form.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it is wholly engaging, for Darnton has found a world
where fiction pales before the unbelievable truth.
</P>
<P>
   Jude Harley, a 30-year-old reporter for a New York tabloid and
part-time novelist, is assigned to cover a brutal murder. Although
the victim has been disfigured, DNA tests identify him as a New
York state judge. But Jude discovers that the judge is alive and
well. Further testing proves that the victim was, although
genetically identical to the judge, five years younger. What can it
mean?
</P>
<P>
   Jude is not allowed to find out: With suspicious alacrity and
outrageously convenient timing, his editor has transferred him to
write an article on identical twins who were separated at birth.
The research leads him to Dr. Elizabeth Tierney, Tizzie, a twins
researcher at the Rockefeller Institute with whom Jude quickly
falls in love.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on a remote island off the coast of Georgia, a colony
of young adults is being reared in a laboratory setting, and two
mavericks, Skyler and Julia, have begun to suspect that all is not
well in their little utopia. When Julia is killed and eviscerated,
as several others on the island have been, Skyler is forced to
escape the island for the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Unschooled, unused to the world, he is shunted back and forth
among the homeless until he happens to pick up a copy of USA Today
and sees a photograph of a New York novelist who looks exactly like
him, although somewhat older. The novelist? Jude Harley. Nor is
that all, for when Skyler arrives in New York to confront his
doppelganger, he finds that Tizzie is identical to his childhood
love from the laboratory, Julia.
</P>
<P>
   This run of coincidence is astonishing, but even more so is its
explanation. For this is a novel set in a world of artificially
created identical twins and, as Tizzie tells Jude during the course
of his research, the uncanny and mysterious coincidences that haunt
the lives of twins separated at birth are well documented. Such
twins are found not only to share genetic traits but to have
identical accidents and life experiences as well: They marry
similar partners, favor the same brands of toothpaste and share the
same politics.
</P>
<P>
   Darnton is at his best when synthesizing and dramatizing
extensive research, as in his best-selling first novel,
``Neanderthal.'' This has its dangers: When journalists turn to
fiction, the first hurdle is that of abandoning the reporter's
reliance on fact in favor of the authenticity of the imagination.
But Darnton, the cultural news editor of The New York Times, neatly
slips out of his research and into a densely imagined universe,
telling his story with abandon and infectious pleasure, so that the
mysteries of his tale are far more pressing than the enigmas of his
research.
</P>
<P>
   How are Jude and Skyler, identical to each other but separated
by a few years in age, related? Or Tizzie and Julia? How are they
all connected to the bizarre and brutal series of murders that
surround them? Who are the laboratory ``orderlies'' (three violent,
massive and identical psychopaths) who are pursuing them? And why
will the FBI not help? To answer any of these questions is to give
away twists and turns that Jude, Skyler and Tizzie must navigate
until the horror of the experiment that rules their lives is
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   When a thriller succeeds as a novel rather than as merely a
diversion, it is invariably due to the author's skills of
characterization more than the ingenuity of the plotting. ``The
Experiment'' succeeds only so far as its characters engage us. In
the first part of the book, Jude, with his wry reflections on
newspaper reporters and _ particularly funny _ on newspaper
editors, is, if not the equal of Philip Marlowe or Tom Ripley,
certainly as compelling as Robert B. Parker's Spenser or Patricia
Cornwell's Kay Scarpetta. He's complex and original enough even to
draw us into the absorbing question of high vs. low art, which
cannot fail to occur to the reader when a Pulitzer Prize- and
George Polk Award-winning journalist (Darnton has won both) sets
out to write a mass-market thriller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that kind of a writer,'' Jude explains to a reader who
has criticized his grammar. ``What kind are you?'' she asks, to
which he replies: ``A people's writer. Nongrammatical. Idiomatic.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the story reaches its end, pure plot tends occasionally
to overshadow the characters. Jude and his comrades become slightly
generic: Jude loses his cynical humor, Tizzie gives no sense
whatsoever of being a doctor. Other disturbing problems detract
from the book's momentum: props (a cellular telephone, a notebook
computer) appear conveniently out of nowhere; and a much too long
and winding pursuit brings us to a much too predictable close.
</P>
<P>
   These are, however, small faults of performance rather than the
more damning literary failures of misplaced ambition or integrity.
This is a book that, at its best, seems to aim for the American
ideal of Dashiell Hammett and Patricia Highsmith, maverick writers
who saw in commercial fiction the chance to tell both meaningful
and accessible stories. It demonstrates that to make a thriller a
work of complex fiction does not mean, as Jude seems to imply,
filling it with grammatical niceties or literary prose. It means
infusing the form with as much meaning _ moral, political,
emotional _ as the characters have depth to experience and the
author has the heart to explore.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Experiment''
</P>
<P>
   By John Darnton
</P>
<P>
   421 pages. Dutton. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
