<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-ACCESS-ART-9     08-15 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ACCESS-ART-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE REMAINS NO. 1 BUT GROWTH SLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online is the undisputed king of Internet service
providers, having added 5.1 million members in the last year alone,
for a total of more than 17 million subscribers. But its growth
rate masks a remarkable trend: The company's share of the Internet
access market is no longer growing as it once was; it may in fact
be declining.
</P>
<P>
   The market for Internet service providers, or ISPs, rather than
consolidating around America Online, Microsoft and telephone
companies like AT&AMP;T as many industry observers had predicted,
remains a diverse industry with wide-open possibilities for
competitors, including mom-and-pop operations.
</P>
<P>
   America Online's monthly subscription plan, meanwhile, is now
just one of many business models for Internet access, and new
models seem to pop up weekly. Free access, often supported by
advertising, has taken root in Europe and is spreading to the
United States. And hardware manufacturers are teaming up with ISPs
to offer a range of discounted plans.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that America Online remains the leader of the
pack. The nearest competitors, Worldnet from AT&AMP;T and MSN from
Microsoft, have fewer than 2 million members each. But research
firms generally agree that America Online's market share is not
growing the way it has in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the wide-open nature of the Internet access market
is the beleaguered state of MSN. Its membership numbers are flat
and Microsoft admits that it is losing market share, although it
declined to release exact numbers. The company plans to beef up its
marketing budget and make a run at big growth later this summer,
said William Diefenbach, group product manager for MSN Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   The persistent _ and, in some circles, unexpected _ growth of
small local ISPs continues to make for a complex market.
</P>
<P>
   Boardwatch Magazine, a widely circulated trade journal, reports
that its directory of ISPs in Canada, the United States and the
Caribbean grew 36 percent between last October and July, to 6,511
from 4,800. Greg Tally, editor of the directory, said the increase
was partly the result of existing service providers' registering
with the directory for the first time, but he added that many were
new.
</P>
<P>
   ``There still are plenty of up-and-coming ISPs,'' he said.
``It's still exploding.''
</P>
<P>
   Most service providers are relatively small, serving several
hundred dial-up customers, Tally said. Boardwatch reports that of
the ISPs in its directory today, fully 5,895 offer local access
numbers in fewer than 25 area codes, whereas only 616 are available
in more than 25 area codes, meaning they are accessible to users on
a regional or national basis.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers may be misleading, because some small service
providers primarily serve local businesses rather than dial-up
customers like the average Web surfer. But both Tally and MSN's
Diefenbach said the small ISPs remained a powerful force in the
dial-up market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen, in aggregate, the smaller and local and regional
ISPs gaining share,'' Diefenbach said.
</P>
<P>
   Access Internet Communications Inc., a small service provider
with several thousand customers in Cupertino, Calif., says it has
seen its dial-up subscriber base grow by 25 percent a year. James
Thomatos, the company's vice president of sales and marketing, said
the demand for access was so great that there were plenty of new
customers to be shared among ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   But he said small service providers were also attracting
customers because they offered more personalized service than the
big services. ``When you call here, someone answers the phone,'' he
said. ``Have you ever tried to do business with the phone company?
It's not the easiest thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the market are efforts to offer free
Internet access, a concept already popular in Europe and making its
first major wave in the United States with a company called Netzero
Inc. In the last six months, Netzero, based in West Lake Village,
Calif., has grown faster than any other service provider in the
country, with the exception of America Online. Last October it had
100,000 subscribers. It now claims 1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We add one every 13 seconds,'' said Mark Goldston, the
company's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Netzero plans to make money by showing targeted advertisements
in a box that is always present on its subscribers' screens.
Netzero filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission on July
14 for an initial public offering of stock, which is likely to take
place before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Alta Vista, a search engine and portal owned by Compaq Computer,
last Thursday began offering free, ad-supported Internet service.
The company will use the service to drive traffic to its Web sites,
increasing advertising income. Even Microsoft has recently talked
about offering cheap or free access, but it has not disclosed solid
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts, some of whom have expressed skepticism about
the idea of free access in the past, say the idea's time may have
come. ``The price is going toward zero,'' said Drew Ianni, an
analyst for Jupiter Communications, a New York-based market
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of businesses are offering free computers as an
enticement to sign subscribers up for Internet service, but this
model is unproven. In a variation on this theme, Microworkz.com
Corp. is selling a computer for $299 with a year of free Internet
access included. After its partnership with Earthlink Network Inc.
fell apart amid an exchange of lawsuits earlier this month,
Microworkz teamed up with AT&AMP;T to provide the Internet-access part
of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ianni says that consolidation is imminent and that AT&AMP;T, America
Online or MSN will begin to snap up large ISPs like Earthlink and
Mindspring Enterprises Inc. ``We're in the lull before a firestorm
of acquisitions,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Market research firms cannot agree on whether the market share
of industry leaders is dipping, rising slightly or holding steady.
One firm, Cahners In-Stat Group, reported this month that America
Online's market share dipped over the last year to 21.5 percent
from 24.3 percent. It estimated the total number of Internet
accounts in the United States at 66 million.
</P>
<P>
   IDC, another market research firm, estimates that America
Online's market share has dropped to 39.3 percent from 42.1 percent
in the last year, and that MSN dropped to 4 percent from 5.9
percent. It puts the size of the Internet access market at just 37
million accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Schuler, president of America Online's interactive
services group, said its ``market share has been steady.'' He
argued that it was a testimony to the online service's strength
that no other major ISP had broken out of the pack to claim even a
strong second place.
</P>
<P>
   Schuler added that America Online, which charges $22 a month for
unlimited access, does not feel threatened by the free services. He
said he did not believe they could attract enough advertising to
make the business profitable. ``It's not a business model,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
