<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AIR THREATENS SUIT AGAINST RIVALS AND PLANS CUTBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Airways PLC confirmed Sunday that it was
considering bringing lawsuits against several of its European
competitors over incentives to travel agents and that it would cut
some jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the airline, Europe's largest, was fined 4.4 million
pounds, or about $7 million, by the European Commission for abusing
its dominant market position by paying higher commissions to travel
agents in return for promoting British Airways over other airlines.
Many of the carrier's rivals have similar programs, and British
Airways said it had been singled out unfairly and planned to go
after its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very seriously considering lawsuits,'' a spokeswoman,
Louise Evans, said, confirming a report in The Sunday Times of
London.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways maintains that it wants to level the playing
field now that it is prohibited from offering incentive programs to
travel agents. If the airline proceeds with the lawsuits, it would
sue big European carriers like KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, Lufthansa,
Air France and Alitalia in their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, British Airways said it would eliminate jobs as it
tries to lower costs by $360 million. The company confirmed reports
in The Sunday Times and The Observer that it will lay off workers,
but declined to specify how many.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, British Airways reported its worst fiscal quarter in
seven years as profits fell 84 percent. It cited discount fares and
a decline in the number of first- and business-class passengers.
The company said it would reduce capacity by 12 percent to lower
costs and move from using larger planes to smaller ones to improve
the percentage of seats filled on flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
