<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OGILVY-AD-COLUMN-NYT     08-15 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OGILVY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: OGILVY MAKING FOUNDER'S SIGNATURE ITS BRAND
NAME
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A division of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide in New York
is seeking to raise its profile by doing the same for its parent.
</P>
<P>
   The division is the Brand Integration Group, which works on
assignments in areas like design, corporate identity and packaging
for clients including American Express, IBM, Mattel and Sears,
Roebuck. Such tasks are becoming increasingly important as
marketers look for campaigns that offer significant elements beyond
the trappings of traditional advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about commercials anymore,'' said Brian Collins,
senior partner and creative director for design and brand identity
at the division. ``Everything the agency does must be part of every
place where the consumer comes into contact with the brand, moving
away from being an advertising agency to being a branding
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Tuesday, the Brand Integration Group is introducing
the results of a project undertaken for the agency: the remaking of
the corporate identity of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather. The signature of the
founder, David Ogilvy, is becoming the signature of the agency as
the Ogilvy name, in his own handwriting, is adopted as its logo.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy &AMP; Mather executives are also asking that the agency be
referred to colloquially as Ogilvy, a moniker that is already in
use along with the initials O&AMP;M The formal, official name will
continue to be Ogilvy &AMP; Mather.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about `brand stewardship' and we don't have it,'' said
Rick Boyko, co-president at the Ogilvy New York office and chief
creative officer at Ogilvy North America. Boyko's reference was to
the philosophy the agency espouses, centered on a comprehensive
approach to selling brands to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inherent in this is the idea of going back to who we are,'' he
added, ``having an identity that sparks a rejuvenation of David and
everything that goes with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, during a commemoration of the 50th anniversary of
Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, ``we came back to much of what David said and
wrote,'' Boyko said. ``There's a sort of reassessment when you're
50, a `Who am I? What have I done?'''
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion was that ``there's a great equity here,'' he
added, ``from David's driving force, his great legacy. So let's
bring it to the forefront.''
</P>
<P>
   David Ogilvy, who founded Ogilvy &AMP; Mather in 1948, died on July
21 at 88. It is coincidental that the project, in development for
more than a year, is getting under way so soon after David Ogilvy's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, now owned by WPP Group PLC, is the second giant
agency to tinker recently with its informal name. D'Arcy Masius
Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications in New York, the flagship of
MacManus Group, is asking to be called D'Arcy rather than DMB&AMP;B
Another big agency has actually changed its name: DDB Worldwide in
New York, part of Omnicom Group, which had been known as DDB
Needham.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy &AMP; Mather's decision to go by only the Ogilvy name ``is
great,'' said Richard B. Fizdale, chairman and chief executive at
the Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago, another huge agency that venerates
its founder through an elaborate corporate identity program.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett paid homage to David Ogilvy last week with an
advertisement in the trade publications Advertising Age and Adweek.
The first line of the ad, which was the brainchild of a Burnett art
director, Frank Scotti, read ``David Ogilvy 1911- ,'' implying he
was still alive. Under that was the sentence ``Great brands live
forever'' and the Burnett logo, the signature of Leo Burnett, who
was for many years a friendly competitor of David Ogilvy's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've embraced the truth about the brand known as Ogilvy:
humor, uniqueness, boldness, individuality,'' said Judd Harner,
senior partner and managing director for brand strategy and client
services at the Brand Integration Group. The new logo will appear
on everything from stationery to visitors' passes to business
cards, he added.
</P>
<P>
   That echoes the work the Brand Integration Group has produced
for paying clients like Jaguar, the luxury car line owned by the
Ford Motor Co. A brand identity program carrying the theme ``A
Jaguar is a copy of nothing'' extends from brochures for consumers
to posters for dealer showroom walls to trade show exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   There are even pocket-sized cards issued to all Jaguar
employees, describing what is said to compose ``the Jaguar
essence.'' Printed on the cards are words like ``elegant,''
``sensuous,'' ``original,'' ``refined'' and ``power.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Or are those the words to be listed on the pocket-sized
cards that will someday be issued to all Ogilvy employees
describing ``the David Ogilvy essence''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
