<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Rain will be scarce in much of the nation as sinking air in a
ridge of high pressure from the southern Plains to the Northeast
states suppresses clouds and showers. Very hot conditions will
persist in the southern Plains while most of the northern states
have seasonable warmth.
</P>
<P>
   After a cool dawn in interior sections, ample sunshine will
boost temperatures near or above seasonal levels in most of the
Northeast states. A few puffy clouds will form near the
Appalachians during the afternoon. Humidity will be comfortable in
most areas, but sultry air will linger along southern parts of the
Middle Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will have plenty of sunshine, but a few isolated
thunderstorms will develop near the Gulf of Mexico and the Georgia
and South Carolina coastlines. Humidity will begin to rise across
the Tennessee Valley as a wind flow from the south increases.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow band of thunderstorms will develop from the central
Plains to the western Great Lakes as a weakening cool front lifts
humid air. Otherwise, ample sunshine will prevail from the central
Plains to the southern Great Lakes. In the wake of the front, less
humid air will surge across the Dakotas into Minnesota on breezes
from the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, a few afternoon thunderstorms will develop over the
central and southern Rockies. Otherwise, sunny and very warm
conditions will prevail. A warming trend will begin in the
Northwest, although cool air and low clouds will linger near the
Washington coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HAWAIIAN HURRICANES
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Hawaiians were keeping a wary eye on two storms
swirling within 1000 miles of the island chain. A tropical
depression was weakening 700 miles south of Kauai. Meanwhile,
Hurricane Dora was moving west 500 miles southeast of Hilo. Strong
hurricanes are infrequent visitors to Hawaii, although Hurricane
Iniki slammed into Kauai in 1992. The ocean near the islands is
several degrees cooler than the 80-to-90-degree water where
hurricanes form. Deprived of energy from the warmth of the eastern
Pacific, hurricanes usually weaken as they approach Hawaii.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
