<HEADLINE>
MEDIA COLUMN: NEWSPAPER DEAL IN SAN FRANCISCO REVIVES DEBATE ABOUT
REGULATION
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the 1970s? When sideburns, bell-bottoms and government
regulation were in fashion? When 62 million copies of the country's
1,748 daily newspapers circulated every day? When Congress, saying
it wanted to insure a diversity of editorial viewpoints, passed a
law making it easier for some financially troubled newspapers to
stay afloat?
</P>
<P>
   The Newspaper Preservation Act of 1970 fits the media world of
1999 about as well as a pair of 1970 bell-bottoms fits its original
owner. And recently many of the original rationales for the law
were stood on their heads by the proposed $660-million sale of The
San Francisco Chronicle to the Hearst Corp., owner of its
archrival, The San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's joint operating agreement was one of 25 or more
that came and went over the years, first without federal sanction
(the prototype agreement was signed in Albuquerque, N.M., in 1933)
and, after 1970, with the government's provisional blessing.
</P>
<P>
   The structures varied, but the basic principle was the same.
Competing newspapers would share certain costs _ like printing and
distribution _ and split certain revenues, like advertising and
circulation dollars. Newsrooms and editorial pages remained
separate, ideally providing diverse viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the San Francisco agreement leaves 12 joint
operating agreements from York, Pa., to Honolulu. Agreements, and
newspapers, have died in places like St. Louis. For some years,
many of those who study the industry _on Wall Street and in
universities _ have asked out loud if the agreements served their
stated purpose of insuring multiple editorial voices. Longtime
opponents, like Bruce B. Brugmann, the publisher of a weekly
newspaper, The San Francisco Bay Guardian, argue that the JOA's, as
they are known in the business, never insured anything but
publishers' profits. Brugmann called the Chronicle sale the
``assassination of a newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   But Donna Patterson, a deputy assistant attorney general in the
Justice Department's antitrust division, tends to think the 1970
law did some service. ``I guess historically it's been a success,''
she said, ``because it's preserved voices longer than they would
otherwise have been preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst officials refused to comment. But another publisher,
Dennis Hetzel of The York Daily Record (circulation 43,000 every
morning), which is in a joint operating agreement with the York
Dispatch (circulation 40,000 every afternoon and 93,000 on Sunday),
said the newspapers' nine-year-old joint operating agreement freed
him to invest more in the newsroom, which competes fiercely with
the newsroom of The Dispatch. ``Both newspapers are better,''
thanks to the business cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Brugmann, argue that the agreements make tame,
hand-fed creatures out of businesses that had been aggressive
business competitors. ``The publishers just don't want to
compete,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Did the law lengthen the life of some troubled newspapers? ``No
one can say for sure,'' said Stephen Barnett, a law professor at
the University of California at Berkeley. But JOAs, he said, ``have
clearly had the effect of crippling the weaker paper.'' When the
agreements end, those weaker papers tend to end with them.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Lacy, a professor of journalism at Michigan State
University, sees today's situation as the outcome of economic
forces, not misguided regulation. ``The inevitable is happening,''
he said. ``The forces that create the one-paper town were not
overcome by the Newspaper Preservation Act.'' Instead, he said, the
act just prolonged the dying of the weaker newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, the end of the joint operating agreement is
widely expected to leave the town with one daily. Who will to buy
an afternoon newspaper with a circulation one-quarter that of its
morning rival, without having the printing and distribution
capacity, or being willing to spend millions to develop it?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Veronis, Suhler &AMP; Associates, a New York investment
bank, will find a buyer for The Examiner _ maybe a small local
publisher. If it does, there will be no joint operating agreement
to shelter the new owner from the rigors of competition, as The
Chronicle and The Examiner have been sheltered since 1965. (Their
joint operating agreement was established before Congress shielded
most such arrangements from antitrust action.)
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the San Francisco agreement also made it likely
that, once The Chronicle's owners decided to sell, Hearst _ the
company with the most incentive to eliminate one newspaper _ would
be the most likely buyer. It had the right of first refusal,
according to one person who has seen the agreement, and its $660
million bid came four days before other companies' bids were
formally due, pre-empting potential rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors aiding Hearst had nothing to do with well-meaning
economic regulation. As a privately held company, Hearst has no
stockholders to answer to, while most other potential bidders did.
And Wall Street, in recent years, has frowned on newspaper
companies that make expensive acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   But in the world of 1999, does the loss of a newspaper matter as
much as it did in 1970, when the scores of cable channels and
hundreds of Web sites did not exist?
</P>
<P>
   The new media landscape and the growing competition for
advertising dollars, make it harder for a weak newspaper to
survive, and make its survival less urgent, Lacy believes. ``I'm
not sure I'd call the Newspaper Preservation Act a failure,'' he
said. ``Just a non-success. People back then did not realize that
this would not make a difference in the long run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
