<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT     08-15 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE REPORT: CONVENTIONAL RETAILERS USE WEB TO IMPROVE
SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traditional retailers have spent the last two years watching the
Internet play havoc with their businesses. To divine the secrets of
the new medium, they have been forced to study their virtual
counterparts for clues on how to compete in this radically
different arena. Many have sought the counsel of Internet
consultants, while others have felt compelled to wade through
stacks of dot-com and E-business books _ bought, no doubt, at
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Now that some of the faster readers have finished studying, they
seem poised to turn the tables on their Internet brethren.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers of the so-called bricks-and-mortar variety are
plotting their revenge not simply by creating Web sites of their
own, but by integrating their Internet operations into their
physical stores. Executives say that by mingling the virtual and
physical retail environments, they can better serve customers in
both. There is, of course, a newly minted buzz phrase associated
with this trend _ ``clicks and mortar'' _ but those in the industry
say the transformation has been brewing for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been dealing with a lot of companies almost paralyzed
with fear about the Internet,'' said Melissa Bane, an E-commerce
analyst with the Yankee Group, an Internet consulting firm. ``Some
of the smarter ones are starting to realize that it's their game to
lose. They already have the customers, and now they can use the
Internet in their stores as a tool to expand their share of
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Activmedia Inc., an Internet research firm, 54
percent of companies with online and off-line sales operations now
report substantial two-way interaction between the two divisions.
Analysts and executives say most of that interaction focuses on
such things as marketing campaigns, but the strategy is starting to
move beyond simply printing the address of the company's Web site
on its receipts and shopping bags.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Recreational Equipment Inc., an outdoor goods
retailer, has placed Internet kiosks in 52 of its 53 stores and has
integrated Web access into its cash registers, said Matt Hyde, vice
president for online sales. The kiosks allow shoppers to look up
detailed information on every product that Recreational Equipment
carries, regardless of whether that particular item is available in
the store. Blocking software bars users from going to sites other
than the retailer's (www.rei.com) and its outlet site
(www.rei-outlet.com). Meanwhile, cashiers can look up items on line
through the Web-enabled registers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a quantum leap in terms of customer service,'' Hyde
said. ``Say I'm in our Wisconsin store, and I'm looking for a haul
bag for a rock-climbing trip to Yosemite. I'm not going to find
that in that store. Before, I'd stand in line at customer service,
a rep would look it up, and I'd have to know exactly what I wanted
for them to be able to help me because chances are they wouldn't be
familiar with haul bags. Now, I can look that up with or without a
salesperson, I can see pictures with all the product info, and I
can buy it at the checkout counter and have it delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Anecdotal evidence suggests that Recreational Equipment was the
first major retailer to put kiosks into its stores, starting in
Seattle, in 1996. Such kiosks are quickly becoming standard fare,
however. Companies like Sears, Gap, Compaq Computer and Borders
Books, among others, have begun major efforts to give customers a
virtual shopping option even as they browse the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure that 10 years from now, every major retail company
will have an Internet-enabled device in the store,'' said Rick
Vanzura, president of Borders Online, who began the bookseller's
campaign to install Internet kiosks in each of the company's 270
superstores.
</P>
<P>
   Vanzura, who recently left Borders to join a start-up company,
said the Internet effort would cost Borders ``in the eight
figures,'' given the technology infrastructure it requires. In the
coming months, he said, the store kiosks will allow customers to
order not only any of the 700,000 titles in the Borders warehouses,
but also out-of-print books, which will be printed and shipped to
the customer's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly an expensive proposition,'' Vanzura said. ``But
I'm confident we'll see a return on that investment _ and it won't
take decades.''
</P>
<P>
   David S. Pottruck, co-chief executive of Charles Schwab, said
the cost of integrating his company's Internet strategy with its
off-line strategy had gone far beyond the price of Internet kiosks.
Pottruck, who said he coined the phrase clicks and mortar in a
recent speech, noted that when the company merged its on- and
off-line divisions last year and lowered the charge for off-line
clients from roughly $65 a trade to $30 (to match the online fee),
it cost the company between $125 million and $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he said, Schwab had to integrate online trading
kiosks more fully into its 300 offices, train its advisers to serve
customers both on line and off and bolster the company's customer
service systems.
</P>
<P>
   But the move has clearly paid off, he said, given the company's
leading position in the online trading category and its customer
growth this year. And more changes will be in order, as customers
become technically savvier, he predicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't need people to provide some of what's needed today,
but it will open the door for people to provide new services that
we don't have today,'' Pottruck said. ``You might click on an icon
on your computer and have someone appear immediately to help you.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the realm of finance, he said, ``traditional stores
will need to use the Internet to create a richer shopping
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Supermarkets will have to provide a range of experiences _
cooking tips, recipes you can get at a kiosk _ instead of simply
being places to pick up merchandise,'' he said. ``Those days are
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bane, of the Yankee Group, said that once companies
integrated the Internet into their point-of-sale systems, cashiers
could conceivably access a customer's previous buying history
during checkout and suggest other items to buy. Or, once shoppers
returned home, they might find a coupon in their e-mail from a
store they recently visited. The store's knowledge of the
customer's on- and off-line purchasing history is potent marketing
material, she said, adding, ``They can leverage the technology
investments they've already made.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gap, for one, has no immediate plans for such a
comprehensive integration of its on- and off-line stores, Rebecca
Weill, a company spokeswoman, said. But the company has created
``Web lounges'' at eight of its flagship stores, featuring black
leather couches, chairs and computers framed with brushed metal
casings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're always crowded,'' Ms. Weill said of the lounges.
``Sometimes people even buy items from the kiosk instead of going
through the store for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
