<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: FRINGE FESTIVAL OPENS; PHILADELPHIA ORCHESTRA AT
TANGLEWOOD; MAYAN MASTERPIECES ON DISPLAY; ROOTS OF AMERICAN
MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 175 productions from emerging theater
companies, dance groups and performing artists from 15 countries
and nearly 30 U.S. cities are on tap beginning on Wednesday in 20
theaters in lower Manhattan, when the third annual New York
International Fringe Festival opens a run through Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment, including free live street performances,
workshops and more, starts at 3 p.m. daily and runs until midnight.
Among the attractions are new plays by Clive Barker and Janet
Anderson, a one-woman show by Marga Gomez, a drama directed by
Austin Pendleton and an avant-garde musical by Tom Waits, Robert
Wilson and William S. Burroughs. Information: (212) 420-8877.
</P>
<P>
   The Debutant
</P>
<P>
   Question: Guess who's coming to Tanglewood? Answer: For the
first time, at the age of nearly 100, the Philadelphia Orchestra.
Led by its music director, Wolfgang Sawallisch, the orchestra will
be in the Berkshire Mountains at 8:30 p.m. on Saturday to perform
Dvorak's ``Carnival'' Overture and Schumann's Piano Concerto in A
major, with Leif Ove Andsnes as the soloist.
</P>
<P>
   The road trip is a prelude of sorts to the Philadelphians' 100th
anniversary season, starting next month and including a
whistle-stop tour of the United States. Programming for the season
will exclusively feature music written during the orchestra's
history. Information: (413) 637-5165.
</P>
<P>
   Vanished Civilization
</P>
<P>
   Mayan masterpieces spanning over 3,000 years _ heralded as the
most extensive collection of Mayan art ever presented under one
roof _ are on display at the Antiguo Colegio de San Ildefonso in
Mexico City through Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Mayas'' is drawn from museums and private collections in
the countries where the Mayan civilization flourished from 1800
B.C. to the 16th century A.D. The show includes altars, frescoes,
religious objects, jade masks, alabaster heads, conch jewelry and
mundane items like utensils. Information: 011-525-702-4507.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Time
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The music goes all afternoon and into the night when
Lincoln Center Out of Doors presents the 16th Annual Roots of
American Music Festival on Saturday and Sunday. Performances on the
North Plaza and at the Damrosch Park Band Shell will include
gospel, folk, rockabilly, blues and bluegrass music with performers
and groups like Paul Burlison, Billy and Rocky Burnette, Billy Lee
Riley, Doc Watson, the Original Clara Ward Singers, Cry Cry Cry and
the Prodigals. Information:(212) 875-5108.
</P>
</TEXT>
