<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-HOTEL-FIGHT-AR     08-15 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-HOTEL-FIGHT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEIRS OF CLEARED GERMAN COLLABORATOR SEEK REDRESS IN FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France _ If anybody ought to know how the Hotel
Martinez, the most luxurious palace on the palm-shaded beach
promenade in Cannes, got its name, it is Phillip Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   Emmanuel Martinez, the Italian immigrant and bon vivant who
opened the hotel in 1929, was his grandfather, a hotelier as
renowned in his day as the hotel, which was soon taking in people
like the Duke of Windsor as guests.
</P>
<P>
   But after World War II, Martinez was accused of collaboration
with the Italian and German occupiers of this part of the French
Riviera, and he lost the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was later cleared of consorting with the enemy,
confusion about whether he had sold the hotel to a black marketeer
led the French government to seize it in 1944 and keep it until
1982. Then it was sold to the Taittinger family's Concorde Hotel
Group, which had been managing it, for 55 million francs, about $10
million in today's money.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez never saw a penny of that; he had died in Italy in
1973. But his name still stands, in huge illuminated letters
emblazoned over the seventh floor of his hotel. Now Kenny, a
54-year-old film producer who lives in Barcelona, Spain, is suing
for about half a million dollars' worth of compensation from the
French state for himself and a handful of other surviving Martinez
heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to clear my grandfather's name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of dollars' worth of property seized during the war is
still the subject of public debate in France, but mostly it was
property or money taken from French Jews before they were sent to
Nazi camps by French collaborationist authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Martinez story is about the other side of the history of the
occupation, the people accused of collaborating with the Nazis, and
it has almost as many touches of cynicism and irony as
``Casablanca.'' Kenny says he is ready to write the book if
somebody else will make the movie.
</P>
<P>
   But the only collaborator in the story, as Kenny tells it, was
Michel Skolnikoff, a shadowy immigrant from Russia known as the
``emperor of the black market'' in France during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny's own father was a Canadian who worked as an Allied
intelligence agent in Cannes, where he fell in love with a child
Martinez had fathered by one of his employees while he was managing
a hotel in Nice in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Martinez had this child, Micheline, adopted by his
lifelong mistress, Emma Digard. Kenny's father married Micheline
Digard in Cannes in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   But the war plunged Martinez into financial ruin, and, according
to his grandson, he was forced to turn to the shadowy Skolnikoff
for a large loan, surrendering shares in the hotel as security. In
1944, when the Allies began moving in, Skolnikoff, anxious to get
out of the Riviera ahead of them, insisted on having the loan
repaid and returned the shares _ all but a few, that is, which he
left in a safe deposit box in Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was solely on the basis of the few shares found in the safe
deposit box that the hotel was seized,'' Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Italian and later German occupation authorities had
been using the 435-room Hotel Martinez as their headquarters, Kenny
said, Martinez was also denounced as a collaborator. Though
Resistance leaders and a few Jews he had helped protect from the
Nazis would later help him clear his name after the war, Martinez
fled to Italy for his own safety.
</P>
<P>
   A Committee for Confiscation of Illicit Profits, declaring that
the Hotel Martinez had apparently been under Skolnikoff's control,
had the hotel seized as security for a large criminal fine of 39
million francs, then worth about $8 million. A tribunal found
Martinez guilty, in absentia, of collaboration with the enemy and
sentenced him to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnikoff fled to Spain and died in 1945 during an attempt by
French agents to kidnap him and bring him back to France for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's reputation was rehabilitated by a court in Lyons that
acquitted him on the collaboration charge in 1949, but he could not
prove the hotel had not belonged to Skolnikoff when it was seized,
and went back to Italy empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Down through the decades, various would-be heirs tried to claim
ownership, without success, and the French administration kept
running the hotel, saying it was applying the income toward
interest on the fine.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, after Martinez died, the state began putting money
into the hotel to fix it up, finally selling it at auction to the
Concorde Group in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Kenny said, he and his lawyers got a court in
Aix-en-Provence to evaluate the hotel's worth at 140 million
francs, the equivalent of $23 million now, twice what the Domains
Service, a branch of the Finance Ministry, had sold it for.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Kenny said, Jacques Foccart, then one of
President Jacques Chirac's advisers, observed that the hotel had
been sold ``under hardly orthodox conditions'' and told the service
he hoped justice could eventually be done.
</P>
<P>
   Next year Kenny's mother, a nephew of Martinez and Martinez's
former company in Cannes expect a ruling from an appeals court in
Paris on their claims for $500,000 in damages for the failure of
the Domains Service to obey an earlier court order to provide
accounts for the 37 years it owned the hotel. In the next few
months, Kenny said, they also plan to bring a separate suit to get
the original seizure invalidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Cannes still whisper about how Martinez lost his
hotel because he collaborated during the war,'' Kenny said. ``Even
though he was rehabilitated, he still never got his honor back. You
never really win with the French bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Concorde Hotels proudly tells visitors that Martinez, ``after
running several establishments in London, Monte Carlo and Paris,
decided to build a Cannes palace'' in the 1920s, and Concorde keeps
his name in lights over the hotel. But a spokesman, Hubert David,
said the controversy was ``a delicate matter'' about which he could
not comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
