<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-15 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK DIFFUSES, FOR NOW, CONTROVERSY OVER SABBATH TRANSPORT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Sunday defused
a crisis with a key Orthodox party that had threatened to leave his
governing coalition because a huge turbine part was transported on
the Sabbath, in contravention of religious law.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, negotiators for Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat held another meeting, this time in the Gaza Strip.
And there were growing signs that the two sides were slowing
bridging their gap on their latest land-for-security accord. Talks
are expected to last another week or so before an Arafat-Barak
meeting can conclude the arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   On the religious crisis, Barak told the four ministers in his
government from the Shas Party that he would set up a committee to
study alternatives to Sabbath transport. The ministers said that
satisfied them for now, although if no alternative is found, they
will ask their party's Council of Sages to study the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Five more such turbine parts have yet to make the trip, and the
next one is scheduled to be carried out in a month.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-hour, 50-mile transport of the 250-ton turbine part took
place from Friday night to Saturday morning despite protests from
Shas ministers and other religious leaders. Barak said such
transport of major parts had long taken place over the Sabbath,
when fewer people are on the roads than on a weekday, because at
any other time, the roads would be tied up in major traffic jams
that could threaten public safety.
</P>
<P>
   Shas controls 17 seats in Barak's 75-member governing coalition,
guaranteeing him a majority in the 120-seat parliament. If Shas had
used this as an occasion to leave the government, as its leaders
had threatened, Barak would have been left without a majority.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts pointed out that Barak would probably have
persuaded other parties not now in his government to join, thus
regaining his governing majority. That appeared to be one reason
Shas chose not to carry out its threat now.
</P>
<P>
   Secular Israelis cheered the turbine part as it made its way
down from outside Tel Aviv to an electrical plant in the coastal
city of Ashkelon. The flatbed truck took up the entire road and was
accompanied by scores of policemen.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers devoted pages of triumphant coverage to the move
Sunday and presented it as a victory of ordinary Israelis over a
powerful group that often holds the rest of the country in its
political grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a victory of common sense,'' said Nahum Barnea, a
news commentator in the mass-selling newspaper Yediot Ahronot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the first government of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin
fell when religious coalition partners walked out after officials
permitted F-15 jet fighters to be delivered to the country after
the start of the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   On the talks with the Palestinians over the Wye River memorandum
signed in October, aides to Barak said they were encouraged that
common ground was being found between the two sides. The
Palestinians have been insisting that the original timetable for
withdrawals be respected, while Barak has asked the Palestinians to
accept a delay in the last withdrawal in exchange for other
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   One unidentified Palestinian leader was quoted by the Reuters
news service Sunday as saying the Palestinians may accept a slight
delay ``if it comes within a package deal that insures
implementation of the Wye agreements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MILLS-PROFILE-ART-NYT     08-15 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLS-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHERYL MILLS LOOKS FORWARD TO LIFE AFTER IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cheryl Mills acknowledges that it was hard to turn
down the White House counsel's job, and not simply because she is a
34-year-old African-American woman whose appointment would be a
first for both race and gender.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a matter of loyalty. She joined the Clinton
transition team in 1992, moved to the White House in 1993 as
associate counsel to the president and hung on through seven stormy
years, capped by her powerful defense of the president in his
Senate impeachment trial this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard,'' she says a few days after her decision was
announced and the administration renewed their search for a
replacement for the departed Charles F.C. Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   What did the president say when she told him she would not
accept the job? She sighs, heavily. ``I can't,'' she says, shaking
her head. ``But it made me sad.''
</P>
<P>
   It is time to move on, Ms. Mills says. Time to give someone
else, she adds with a hard little smile, ``the joy that I've had
for so many years.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the air of the returning veteran about the young
lawyer, of someone battle-hardened and proud of it. The screen
saver on her computer reads, ``It's the lioness that hunts ...'' A
small sign above her desk declares, ``Don't Go There.'' The walls
are dominated by huge posters of Michael Jordan, at his most
formidable.
</P>
<P>
   Has she put the impeachment battle behind her? If she ended up
at a dinner party with Rep. Henry Hyde, the conservative Illinois
Republican who managed the case against the president, could she
make small talk?
</P>
<P>
   She grimaces and looks up at the ceiling, all the careful
lawyer-speak eluding her for a moment. Then it clicks in. ``I think
that the House managers were obviously committed to their vision
and view of the president's conduct,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that what I've always tried to do is be committed to
not just thoughts about conduct but more the Constitution and what
it would provide, and what our framers would hope we would do in a
moment like this,'' she explains, ``as well as trying to help
people appreciate how difficult the situation was and the choices
people make on a very human level.''
</P>
<P>
   She starts to laugh, and adds, ``And I think that at a dinner
party, assuming we weren't talking about the impeachment, we'd all
be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many departures at the Clinton White House these days,
so many that The Washington Post recently ranked the food at the
going-away parties; the presence of shrimp on the menu was
considered the surest indicator of status. It is probably safe to
say that Cheryl Mills will get shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   She is a classic overachiever, who says she knew by fifth-grade
that she wanted to be a lawyer. ``I know, very bizarre,'' she says.
One of two children in a military family _ her father was a
lieutenant colonel in the Army who retired after 27 years _ Ms.
Mills grew up in Germany, Belgium and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have incredibly positive associations with the military,''
she says. Military communities abroad were ``almost like a little
bit of an experimental environment, in which people really related
well to each other without regard to race, but related to each
other based on nationality,'' she adds. ``In that sense, I grew up
thinking of the world as being, or at least having the capacity to
be, incredibly fair and balanced if given the right environment and
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from the University of Virginia, where she made
Phi Beta Kappa, and from Stanford Law School, where she was elected
to the Law Review. After a brief stint at Hogan &AMP; Hartson, a
Washington law firm, she joined the Clinton transition team and
moved to Little Rock, Ark., where she lived in the same apartment
complex as the president's secretary, Betty Currie, and Carol
Browner, now commissioner of the Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   For seven years Ms. Mills was at the epicenter of the Clinton
scandals and acquired a reputation as extremely tough, extremely
loyal and a leading figure in the give-no-ground camp in the White
House. A fair appraisal? ``I think tough is fair,'' she says. As
for giving no ground, she adds, she merely wanted to make sure that
what information was released was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Davis, who was brought in to help deal with the scandals,
later wrote about the tension between the ``press-political''
operation that he was a part of and the legal side of the White
House. ``In the early days she and I often clashed, sometimes
strenuously, usually over the same issue,'' he wrote of Ms. Mills
in ``Truth to Tell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would want to push out information when the press wanted
it,'' Davis wrote, ``and she would insist on accuracy and
completeness, with what I sometimes felt was an excessive concern
for legal risks.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Davis spoke fondly of his old sparring partner,
saying that as much as they argued, Ms. Mills was the one who
called and checked up on him when he was hospitalized with a bad
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   For all her years in the White House, Ms. Mills' big public
moment came only in January, when she delivered her impassioned
defense of the president, not only against charges of obstruction
of justice, but also against the notion that his conduct betrayed a
profound insensitivity to civil rights for blacks and women. She
dismissed that notion with great disdain. ``I'm not worried about
civil rights, because this president's record on civil rights, on
women's rights, on all of our rights is unimpeachable,'' she
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills says she got hundreds of letters afterward, and even
before the speech got a lot of support inside the White House,
particularly from blacks. ``The day before I went, everyone, but in
particular African-Americans, came by and said, `We know you're
going to do a good job; we know you're going to do us proud.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents were in the Senate gallery that day, and by the end
they were crying. ``In my family, that's a rare occurrence,'' Ms.
Mills says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mills, who was named deputy counsel in 1997, will be the
acting White House counsel until a permanent one is found. She is
vague about her plans, saying only that she is considering ``a
number of different things in the private sector'' and is not
confining herself to law.
</P>
<P>
   The standard explanation for burned-out 30-somethings leaving
high-level jobs in Washington is the desire to ``have a life,'' but
Ms. Mills dislikes that characterization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually think, as unusual as it might sound,'' she says,
``that working in the White House is an extraordinary life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
