<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MO-LIVESTOCK-LAWSUIT-     08-15 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MO-LIVESTOCK-LAWSUIT-ART-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTAL EFFECT OF LIVESTOCK FARMS SPURS ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Okla., Utah)  (ART ADV: Photo of cattle farmer Terry Spence is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONVILLE, Mo. _ With hog manure fouling streams in the rolling
countryside of northern Missouri, the giant pork producer Premium
Standard Farms agreed early this month to pay $25 million to settle
a suit accusing it of violating the state's Clean Water Act.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the hog company, which processes 2 million
pigs a year in six Missouri counties, is the largest environmental
settlement with any hog-producing operation in the United States
and illustrates the tightening restrictions facing the big
producers.
</P>
<P>
   With pigs now being raised in virtual factories, the settlement
by Premium Standard Farms of the suit brought by Missouri Attorney
General Jay Nixon comes as states are starting to monitor livestock
production as they would a smokestack industry.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Kansas, the State Health Department announced
this month that it was requiring farms with more than 10,000
animals to line their waste pits with plastic, a measure designed
to keep manure out of groundwater and prevent it from contaminating
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Several states have declared moratoriums on expansion of giant
hog farms. Dozens of counties around the nation have passed
measures designed to limit or exclude big hog farms. Nebraska has
kept the hog factories out by banning all corporate farming.
</P>
<P>
   There are few issues as contentious in the American countryside
as the corporate hog industry, in which the manure of thousands of
pigs is concentrated in lagoons and then sprayed over fields. The
process can create a terrible odor for miles around. And when
spills occur, the manure seeps into streams and kills fish. Premium
Standard was accused of several spills, including one near here,
that killed fish and threatened groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   While most attention on big hog operations has focused on the
offensive odor, water pollution caused by the manure poses the
biggest threat, environmentalists say. The Sierra Club has labeled
big hog operations as one of the most serious threats to the
nation's environment. The giant hog farms have degraded some 35,000
miles of rivers and streams in 22 states, said Ed Hopkins, a
spokesman for the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hog operations are still classified as agricultural,'' Hopkins
said, ``but they have turned into industrial sites.''
</P>
<P>
   When Premium Standard Farms sprayed animal waste on fields, it
was technically doing the same thing farmers have always done, but
in much larger amounts. In small amounts, in the style of family
farmers, the manure served as fertilizer for crops. The
concentrated manure from the hog factories, on the other hand, is
much too strong for crop fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with the state, Premium Standard Farms must
treat the waste before it is spread on the land, to guard against
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians in Missouri and other states have labeled the
big hog producers, like Premium Standard, as threats to the
environment as well as the rural economy. The big hog producers,
meanwhile, say environmental rules are being used as a weapon to
keep out an emerging industry that does not fit with the rural
tradition of the family farm.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Drabenstott, a vice president at the Federal Reserve Bank
in Kansas City and an expert on the rural economy, said the hog
industry had largely chosen to expand in the West, including the
Oklahoma Panhandle and Utah, which is new territory for growing
hogs. As scrutiny of hog operations intensified, Drabenstott said,
the differences in regulations between states became smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is going to go where it feels welcome,''
Drabenstott said. ``These days, the discussion is not so much
whether we go to Iowa or Missouri _ it's do we stay in the United
States or do we go to Mexico?''
</P>
<P>
   Big hog producers have started raising some pigs in the western
provinces of Canada and are said to be considering doing the same
in Mexico, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tougher regulations come at a time when hog prices have ranged
from poor to catastrophic. The low prices have driven many smaller
farmers out of business and have hurt the big producers, too.
Prices for hogs at meat processors, now about 36 cents a pound,
have rebounded considerably from a low of less than 10 cents a
pound last December.
</P>
<P>
   The rising prices have been fueled, in large part, by
expectations that the economy is improving in Asia, a major
importer of American pork. But even at 35 or 40 cents a pound, most
farmers are barely breaking even, Drabenstott said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Arnott, a spokesman for Premium Standard Farms, said the
state had been justified in ``holding us accountable'' on water
pollution. But Arnott said the debate over large-scale hog
production in the American countryside was often driven by emotion
and nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott said that the increases in technology, along with the
global nature of markets, had forever changed the face of
agriculture. But he said the big-scale hog producers were helping
people survive in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``What everybody is interested in is a quality rural way of
life,'' he said. ``It isn't the same as the old style of
agriculture. But there are a whole lot of people in Northern
Missouri who now are able to live in the country, send their kids
to a rural school and enjoy the neighborly quality of life,''
because of the 2,400 jobs created by the hog producer.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Siemer, a 27-year-old barber, had left his depressed
hometown of nearby Princeton nearly a decade ago, but as economic
conditions improved vastly in the region, he was able to return
home and go into business. His father, who had gone broke in
farming, now drives a truck for Premium Standard Farms.
</P>
<P>
   To the younger Siemer, who goes by the name Ace, a little odor
of hog manure is worth the benefit of jobs. He said the water
pollution was being exaggerated for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a ghost town not long ago,'' Siemer said. ``Now I
look out my door and I see a restaurant, an insurance agency, a gas
station.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the view of Terry Spence, a 52-year-old cattle farmer and
a sharp critic of the big hog factory, the countryside is being
sold down the river. He said the state did not win nearly a large
enough settlement from Premium Standard Farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have grandchildren, and I don't like them to be outside when
this odor gets so bad,'' Spence said. ``This is not the typical
farm smell. Animals have always roamed the land. But when you
compound it like that, it's terrible. It isn't farming. Call it
something else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
