<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Digital Clock Could Disrupt Global Positioning Devices
</P>
<P>
   For unwary users of the global positioning system _ the
government satellite system that guides ships and airplanes, keeps
cellular networks humming and helps surveyors lay out property
lines _ next weekend could be marred by a disorienting flashback.
</P>
<P>
   The system's effectiveness depends in part on a calendar that
boils the passage of time down to the weeks since Jan. 6, 1980,
plus seconds. Sticking to such basics allows the satellites to
communicate quickly, but the system will run out of digital space
for such timekeeping on Saturday. Some confused receivers will stop
working, and others could generate bad data or display 1980 dates.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers Mix Web and Stores
</P>
<P>
   Traditional retailers have spent the last two years watching the
Internet play havoc with their businesses. Now some retailers of
the so-called bricks-and-mortar variety, like Borders Books, are
not only creating Web sites but are integrating their online
operations into their stores. Executives say that by mingling the
virtual and physical environments, they can better serve customers
in both.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Seeks to Repair Network
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom sought to complete repairs to a high-speed data
network that has experienced problems for 10 days, disrupting the
Chicago Board of Trade's trading system and service to thousands of
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Web Service to Provide Anonymity
</P>
<P>
   Privada, a company in San Jose, Calif., plans to introduce a
service Monday, called Web Incognito, that lets users make all of
their Internet activities _ e-mail, online chats, Web browsing and
even purchases _ anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Scrutinizing Papers' Agreements
</P>
<P>
   Many of the original rationales for newspaper joint operating
agreements _ which allow competing papers to share costs and split
revenue while maintaining separate news operations _ were stood on
their heads by the proposed $660 million sale of The San Francisco
Chronicle to Hearst, owner of its archrival, The San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Gets a Makeover
</P>
<P>
   The Brand Integration Group, a division of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
Worldwide, is seeking to raise its profile by doing the same for
its parent. Beginning on Tuesday, the division is introducing the
results of a project to remake the corporate identity of Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather.
</P>
<P>
   $2.5-Billion Bank Deal in Germany
</P>
<P>
   ING Groep plans to buy the 58 percent of BHF-Bank of Germany
that it does not already own for about $2.5 billion in a deal that
could accelerate consolidation in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Book Puzzles Adults
</P>
<P>
   The imaginary characters in Toni Morrison's first book for
children live in a pretty brown box decorated with beanbag chairs
and stocked with pepperoni pizza and Bubble Yum because they are
``kids who can't handle their freedom.'' In focus group research,
some young readers embraced the book, which is scheduled for
publication in September, while adults initially considered it
``weird'' and ``depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   British Airways Threatens Lawsuits
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said that it was considering bringing lawsuits
against several European competitors over incentives to travel
agents and confirmed that it would cut some jobs as it tries to
lower costs by $360 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
