u f BC-FRENCH-BANKS-NYT     08-15 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE FRENCH BANK MERGER AT AN IMPASSE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ After a grueling five-month takeover battle
among three of France's biggest banks, the results of shareholder
votes released on Saturday suggested that all parties had lost and
that efforts to build up a new French national champion in the form
of the world's largest bank had reached a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   French regulators said that the would-be acquirer, Banque
Nationale de Paris, had persuaded a solid majority of the
shareholders at one of its takeover targets, Paribas, to sell it
their shares in a cash-and-stock offer worth about $20 billion. But
it fell well short in the second part of the plan, winning only
31.5 percent of the votes for its $19-billion bid to acquire the
other target, Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
   That constitutes a setback for all three. First, it blocks
Banque Nationale de Paris from creating the world's largest bank,
and it deprives it of the prize it wanted most _ Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
   But the votes seem to have represented an even greater defeat
for executives at Paribas and Societe Generale, who first announced
a friendly, two-way merger _ a deal that would have excluded Banque
Nationale de Paris. That plan is almost certainly dead.
</P>
<P>
   French regulators must now decide whether to let Banque
Nationale de Paris in fact acquire the minority stake in Societe
Generale. If their answer is yes, Banque Nationale would be the
biggest shareholder in its rival and could press it into a
three-way deal after all.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts regard this outcome as unlikely and think that
both plans have been stalemated.
</P>
<P>
   Over the longer term, the protracted struggle is likely to leave
permanent changes in French and even European banking. Never before
had France experienced a hostile takeover on a scale of the one
tried by Banque Nationale de Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The battle also fueled anxieties of France's bankers and
political leaders about losing ground to foreign financial
institutions. That has been a particular concern of Finance
Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the fight is not over yet. If French regulators, led
by the president of the Bank of France, decide this week to let
Banque Nationale de Paris take the 31 percent minority stake in
Societe Generale, Banque Nationale would have an effective veto
over major decisions at Societe Generale and enormous leverage to
continue merger negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement, Banque Nationale de Paris greeted the
outcome of the votes with ``very great satisfaction'' and argued
that it had won ``effective control'' of Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that no other shareholder has, either alone or in
conjunction with someone else, 10 percent of the capital, such a
stake gives effective control of Societe Generale,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts predicted Sunday that the regulators would not
agree, in part because they did not like the idea of a controlling
minority and because Banque Nationale de Paris had received far
less than majority support from shareholders. ``My sense is that
the percentage is low enough that they will turn it down,'' said
John Leonard of Salomon Smith Barney in London.
</P>
<P>
   Societe Generale executives have argued that ``effective
control'' requires a majority of shareholder votes and are expected
to insist that French regulators force Banque Nationale de Paris to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder vote came in an extraordinary battle that is
expected to have reverberations in France for years to come. The
struggle highlighted the growing anxieties among the French bankers
and political leaders about their ability to keep pace with foreign
competition, particularly from the likes of Deutsche Bank of
Germany and UBS AG in Switzerland, which are growing through
mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   It began on Feb. 1, when Societe Generale announced an agreement
to take over Paribas in a stock deal worth about $16 billion at the
time. Though executives at all three big banking companies had
periodically discussed mergers over the previous year, the deal
surprised both French financiers and government leaders.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Banque Nationale de Paris fired back with a
hostile-takeover offer totaling $37 billion for both banks. Societe
Generale and Paribas quickly denounced the bids, and the fight was
on.
</P>
<P>
   The battle pitted members of France's business elite against
each other. The French insurance conglomerate AXA, headed by Claude
Bebear, owned stakes in both Banque Nationale de Paris and Paribas.
When Paribas and Societe Generale announced their original plan for
a merger in February, Bebear said the deal made little sense, and
he threw his support to Banque Nationale when it made its bid in
March.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the argument, Societe Generale marshaled
support from a core group of institutional shareholders, including
AGF, the French insurer owned by Allianz AG of Germany, and CGU PLC
of Britain, an insurance carrier. Late in July, CGU raised its
stake in Societe Generale to 6.9 percent from 3.1 percent and said
it hoped the move would block Banque Nationale's bid.
</P>
<P>
   French politicians strongly favored a merger of some kind and
tried to hammer out a compromise. Jean-Claude Trichet, the
president of France's central bank, pressed the three institutions
into face-to-face negotiations late in June. But after a week, the
talks collapsed and each side continued to promote its own plan.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the divergent outcome of the two shareholder votes
could end up being the worst of all worlds. Paribas is
overwhelmingly an investment bank with businesses in specialized
areas like mortgage financing. It has little in the way of a retail
banking network.
</P>
<P>
   Banque Nationale de Paris has a large retail network, which it
would like to pare down because France has far more competing bank
branches than it needs at the moment. Acquiring Societe Generale
would make it easier to consolidate branches, but acquiring Paribas
would do nothing on that front.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
