<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FORBES16-COX     08-15 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP contenders hope Forbes' liberal spending hurts Bush
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTERSET, Iowa - The single most important money man in the
battle for the Republican presidential nomination is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Because Malcolm S. Forbes left a large fortune _ as much as $1
billion _ when he died in 1990, son Steve can spend a small fortune
on his re-run for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The money makes Forbes the only contender with the financial
ammunition to do something about Gov. George W. Bush's big, early
lead in the polls. It is a fact of fiscal life driving decisions
being made by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It also means the other candidates who survived Saturday's Iowa
straw poll win by Bush are, in effect, running on the money left by
Forbes' dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime Godzilla and King Kong get into a fight, it's always
interesting for bystanders to watch,'' said Ari Fleischer,
spokesman for Elizabeth Dole, who ran third behind Bush and Forbes
in the non-binding straw poll. ``Sometimes they knock each other
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole and other GOP contenders are counting on conservative
Forbes' liberal spending to reel Bush in. It's an effort Forbes is
well down the path on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is what is the big difference between me and a
certain governor from Texas,'' Forbes said, repeating a query from
a man who listened to him speak in Winterset. ``It's a good
question.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, in his low-key staccato, Forbes moved in for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the great mysteries,'' he said, referring to
Bush's positions on major issues. ``Maybe they should do something
on `Discovery.' Where are his positions? You see those puzzles,
`Where's Waldo?' where you try to find Waldo. Maybe you can try
where is his tax plan. Where is the Social Security plan? See if
you can find it. Maybe you have a whole new industry. There's my
entrepreneurial mind going again.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a joke, of sorts. You can tell Forbes is poking fun when
the crooked smile crawls across his generally emotion-free face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put out real principles and policies and I think the
American people are going to demand that,'' he said. ``And those
who don't do it will be able to continue the pursuits they have in
other areas of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a campaign-trail mantra Forbes toted through Iowa last week
in his high-tech bus. And, thanks to the inherited money, Bush is
going to be hearing it for many, many months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, we think it will emerge as a Bush-Forbes race,''
said Forbes adviser Greg Mueller. ``The earlier the better for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes fortune already has dictated decisions for Bush, who
decided early on it was important to raise enough money to be able
to skip federal matching dollars and the spending limits they
bring. Forbes avoided the limits in 1996 by spending $37.5 million
of his own money for a late-starting campaign that had its moments
but eventually lost to Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has succeeded in avoiding the spending limits by collecting
more than $36 million in donations and eschewing the federal money.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Forbes raised $9.5 million, about $6.6 million
of it from his own pocket. He also spent $8.3 million, leaving him
with $1.2 million on hand, compared to Bush's $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the Forbes cash-on-hand figure is misleading. His cash on
hand is limited only by his sizeable personal wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you,'' said Forbes campaign manager Bill Dal Col,
``we will help the governor spend every penny he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes redefined
</P>
<P>
   Like a debutante eager for a second chance at debuting, Forbes
is spending time and money this year to re-tool a first impression.
In 1996 he mounted a television air war based on his flat-tax idea.
Those elements are high priority again this year. But Forbes also
is working to persuade social conservatives he is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   A promise to push for a constitutional amendment banning
abortion is part of the Forbes stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize many Americans do not yet share that goal,'' he
said in Winterset. ``But you do not abandon that goal, put it on
the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a soft dig at Bush, one offered in firmer terms in a radio
ad in which Forbes promises to appoint federal judges who oppose
abortion rights, a promise Bush has declined to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the politicians who are running for president won't
even tell you what kind of judges they will appoint,'' he says on
the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Forbes' family fortune, Bush can count on enduring
more of these kinds of ads. Dole got to listen to them in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't run negative ads,'' Dal Col said. ``We run
comparative ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush remembers those ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996 (Forbes) spent a lot of his own personal money to try
to tear down other candidates,'' Bush said. ``I think there is
going to be a huge backlash in the year 2000 if that were to
happen. But we'll be ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The counter-attack could come along the lines offered by
Michigan Gov. John Engler, a top Bush campaign lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what Steve Forbes would do. He has no record. He
is a complete cipher when it comes to what he would do,'' said
Engler.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes is ready with a high-dollar campaign to show that it
is clear what Bush will do, and it will not be in the best
interests of the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington lobbyists, all the special interests are
rallying around him,'' said Forbes. ``He is clearly the
establishment candidate. That's why the party leadership has
rallied around him and the party money has rallied around him. It
is a contest ultimately between the status quo establishment, where
at most you just make little trimmings around the edges, versus
real, substantive change from an independent outside not beholden
to the lobbyists and special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   On the road
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' effort at repositioning is finding some success. At a
Des Moines, speech, Pam Glazebrook sat down front with 13-year-son
Willie, a home-schooled child sporting an ``Abortion is Mean''
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Glazebrook liked Forbes in 1996, but was not convinced then that
he was as fervently against abortion rights as she is. She is now a
true believer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in gray areas,'' she said of Bush's refusal to
promise to appoint judges and a running mate who share his
anti-abortion rights stance. ``The fact is that (Bush) won't get
behind us with actions. He is willing to support it but he is not
willing to stand up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few tables back, pharmacist Dave Shafman wore his political
feelings on his shirt: ``Christian, American, Heterosexual,
Pro-gun, Conservative. Any questions?''
</P>
<P>
   Shafman is on board with Forbes and down on Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not campaigning,'' he said of the Texas governor. ``He
is just collecting money and not saying anything. If he ends up
being the nominee I will support him, but he is not my first choice
by any stretch of the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, Forbes offers a monotone that sounds like it could
be leading to a homework assignment. Though not devoid of a catchy
line or two (he pitches his call for an end to estate taxes by
proposing ``no taxation without respiration''), Forbes is not
central casting's choice for a late-20th century American political
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I didn't break the screen,'' he told a Des Moines woman
who said she had seen him on TV.
</P>
<P>
   But he is patching together a following that crosses social
class. At his speeches, he's a millionaire preaching a
working-class message. On board his campaign buses, wealthy
businessmen pass the time between stops by comparing notes on their
multi-million-dollar enterprises and private airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm driven by his message,'' said Herman Cain of Omaha,
chairman of Godfather's Pizza. ``And I'm driven by his dedication
and commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Cain met with Bush at the governor's Austin
office. Cain came away more convinced than ever that Forbes is his
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with him just to get acquainted with him and find out
some of his views on some of the issues Steve is talking about,''
said Cain. ``Let's say that I like Steve Forbes much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
