<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A `LUCKY COUNTRY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Of all societies, South Africa cannot be
separated from its past. Not long ago it was a country where people
were tortured and murdered because of their politics. A country
where, because of their race, husbands were systematically
separated from their wives. A country where a small minority,
defined by race, held all economic and political power.
</P>
<P>
   Given that history, it is something of a miracle that South
Africa today is a normal country with social and economic problems.
The problems are large, but they can be debated in freedom. Tyranny
is only a memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a very lucky country,'' Kaizer Nyatsumba, editor of The
Daily News in Durban, wrote in a column the other day. ``We have a
functional and fully stable democracy. ... We have a free press,
opposition parties are free to speak their minds on just about
everything, and we have many outspoken organs of civil society.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Nyatsumba what had led him to write that column. ``You
hear people express concerns about the country,'' he said. ``It's
forgotten that things could have been much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is quite natural for people to think about current
conditions rather than the horrors of the past. They have to live
in the present. And they have to deal with some hard realities.
</P>
<P>
   Education is one of the gravest challenges. The apartheid
government relentlessly denied black children decent schooling. The
legacy of that is too many young people unequipped to deal with the
demands of a modern economy. A new minister of education, Kader
Asmal, has impressed people with his commitment to raise standards.
``He's the best thing to happen to our education in 350 years,'' a
black professional said to me.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment stands at about 30 percent. The hope of lowering
that socially devastating figure rests on economic growth. The
economy has been hit by the falling gold price and repercussions
from the Asian crisis, but inflation has been checked and business
seems reasonably confident.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is a menacing phenomenon. South Africa has the
fastest-growing epidemic in the world, with 1,500 new cases a day.
</P>
<P>
   Crime is a universal concern. One grim story shows the depth of
feeling about it. In Alexandra, a poor black area of Johannesburg,
a man was arrested and charged with multiple rapes. A magistrate
set bail at the equivalent of $1,000. Alexandra residents
contributed about $4 each, a large sum for them, so he could be
bailed _ and murdered. It happened.
</P>
<P>
   But if the problems are profound, so have been South Africa's
achievements in the last 10 years. It has just had its second
democratic, nonracial election _ in peace and with no charges of
corruption in the process. How many countries could make that claim
after so revolutionary a political change?
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to the 1994 election, there were massacres in
black townships and on trains carrying black commuters. Violence
between supporters of the African National Congress and the Inkatha
Freedom Party left thousands dead in this province, KwaZulu/Natal.
``There was the very real possibility of a civil war in this
country,'' Kaizer Nyatsumba said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though there is still occasional political violence in
KwaZulu/Natal, Inkatha and the ANC govern in coalition in the
province. And Inkatha is included in the ANC-dominated national
government.
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of the world, this is a country that functions
highly successfully. The telephones work, expressways connect
cities and suburbs, the indicia of a modern society are all around.
</P>
<P>
   But for visitors who knew the old South Africa, there is
something more important. People of different races mix where they
never could: on beaches, in airline cabin crews, everywhere. And
despite the brutal racism of the old regime, there is a sense of
good will in day-to-day human relations.
</P>
<P>
   It hardly needs to be said that, economically, the gulf between
white and black remains enormous. This is a country of suburbs
reminiscent of Beverly Hills _ and of shantytowns.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges are daunting. But the oppressive weight of a
police state _ something that could be felt almost physically in
the old days _ is entirely gone. It is a land of possibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
