<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-IOWA-POLL-HNS &LR; BUSHGOE     08-15 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER RECONSIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   BUSH GOES BACK HOME AFTER IOWA WIN WHILE (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Flush with a victory in the Republican straw poll
here, Texas Gov. George W. Bush looked ahead Sunday to next year's
primary season and the race for his party's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But the non-binding poll designed raise funds for the state
Republican Party in Iowa has led at least one candidate, Lamar
Alexander, to reconsider the race. Alexander called his sixth-place
finish ``a disappointment'' and said he would decide within the
next few days whether to continue his second run for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a powerful force in this country to elect George W.
Bush,'' Alexander said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next day or two I'll be thinking about that,''
Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has raised a record $37 million for his presidential
campaign, shattered straw poll records when he received 7,418
votes, more than three times the number of votes logged by any
previous winner in the event's 20-year history. He then flew back
to Texas, where he was scheduled relax with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he took a big step toward earning the Republican
nomination,'' Karen Hughes, Bush's campaign spokesman, told a news
conference here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides sought to put the best spin on their win with 31
percent of the vote and to fend off criticism from Republican
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But billionaire magazine publisher Steve Forbes was quick to
point out that more than two-thirds of the voters at the straw poll
cast their ballots for candidates other than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no coronation,'' said Forbes, who portrayed
himself as ``the conservative alternative'' to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has led a chorus of candidates who have complained about
what they say is the favoritism shown Bush by the party leadership
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who spent some $2 million to challenge the Texas
governor here, placed second with 4,921 votes.
</P>
<P>
   He attacked Bush for failing to outline a presidential agenda.
``Money plus no message equals mush,'' is one of Forbes' rhetorical
themes.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mueller, his spokesman, said Forbes' proposals to shore up
Social Security and to improve the healthcare system and schools,
have helped him generate support needed to challenge Bush for the
party's presidential nod.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's front-runner status has made him the target of attacks
from other candidates who remain bunched at the bottom of most
public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the acknowledged front-runner,'' Michigan Gov. John
Engler said of Bush. ``He has everybody shooting at him.'' Engler
supports Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a former president of the Family Research Council,
questioned Bush's commitment to conservative issues and causes.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer placed fourth behind Elizabeth Dole, the former American
Red Cross president, but ahead of TV commentator Pat Buchanan,
radio personality Alan Keyes and former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom were Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., a military hero who called the Iowa straw poll ``a
scam'' because campaigns purchase tickets for those attending and
voting. McCain skipped the event.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle was pummeled in the straw poll, placing eighth. The poor
showing could doom his campaign but he vowed to press on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to New Hampshire,'' Quayle said after he spoke to
those attending the straw poll at Hilton Coliseum at Iowa State
University.
</P>
<P>
   A record 23,000 people participated in the one-day event,
according to state GOP officials.
</P>
<P>
   Although the non-binding straw poll is designed to raise funds
for the party, the hype escalated this year when Bush boasted that
he would win it and win it big.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent roughly $850,000, including the cost of more than
10,000 tickets for potential voters, who were bused to the event
and offered barbecue and entertained with country and western and
Tejano musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spent more than $1 million on television advertising. He
also spent nearly that much on transportation, T-shirts, an
air-conditioned tent and entertainment for his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, the Texas governor's chief political strategist, said
the Bush campaign recruited hundreds of volunteers to generate a
turnout that ``would give us a convincing win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had everybody's fire aimed at us and a million dollars in
advertising aimed at us, and we still came out on top,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we didn't even start campaigning here until June 12, 1999.
Some of these other candidates have been here since June 12,
1909,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said the effort was designed to ``jump-start the
organization'' as it heads toward the Iowa caucuses, which kicks
off the party primary season sixth months from now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
