<HEADER>
A8019 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-ENPRUFMAKKDPLEAS     08-15 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIE BROWN GETS SOME OFFERS HE REFUSES
</HEADLINE>
 EN PRUFMAKKD PLEASE CODE CREDIT/ MANDATORY  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Star Bright, Macy's new promotional crusade (because the
apostrophe in Macy's is a star), includes the propagation of six
 &UR; Annie Leibovitz  &LR; portraits of local celebrities _  &UR; Armistead &LR; 
 &UR; Maupin &LR; ; &UR; Alice Waters &LR;  and her daughter,  &UR; Fanny &LR; ;  &UR; Evelyn &LR; 
 &UR; Cisneros &LR; ; &UR; Michael Tilson Thomas &LR; ;  &UR; Terry McMillan &LR;  and her
husband,  &UR; Jonathan Plummer &LR; ; and  &UR; Willie Brown &LR;  _ dressed in Macy's
clothes.The photos will appear on shopping bags, billboards,
catalogs and giveaway postcards.
</P>
<P>
   The models get to keep the duds, and a $10,000 modeling fee will
be given to a favorite charity of each, with one exception: Brown,
who Macy's says can't take the cash, posed free.
</P>
<P>
   _Upon hearing that Brown wouldn't be able to get the .com domain
name of his dreams _ because the  &UR; Clint Reilly &LR;  campaign had
registered many Brown-related .com names _  &UR; Bob Cullinan &LR;  offered
him free the use of williebrown.to or a whole range of names in the
.to domain, which is licensed to the Kingdom of Tonga. The offer
was refused; campaign-meisters pondered the political Scrabble
tiles, &LR;  and came up with an unregistered .com address.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIANT BEACON BECKONS CRITICISM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   San Franciscans argued over a giant foot statue?  &UR; David Harris &LR; 
forwards a story about Recife, Brazil, where plans for a
30-foot-tall penis-shaped tower with a light on top were greeted
with such acrimony that the mayor threatened to kill a newspaper's
art critic and gossip columnist.
</P>
<P>
   The statue was designed by  &UR; Francisco Brennand &LR; , a ceramicist
known for works hinting at sex. He said, however, that the tower
was supposed to be a beacon to outer space.
</P>
<P>
   After images were shown on TV, &LR;  and the public complained, a
city committee asked the artist to alter his design. He quit on
August 4, smashing another work in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Then the newspaper's gossip columnist and art critic wrote that
the committee's request was due to pressure from the mayor's wife,
who didn't like the work. This so raged the mayor that he went to
the newspaper to confront the writers, in the course of which he
opened his jacket to flash the gun he was carrying.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian Press Association met in Rio to register
disapproval of the threat to freedom of the press. After which,
said Reuters, the city council gave Brennand permission to complete
the work as originally designed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH  &LR;  -  &UR; Ellen Barkin  &LR; told the Calgary Sun she wasn't a fan
of the  &UR; Julia Roberts &LR; - &UR; Susan Sarandon &LR;  movie ``Step Mom,'' which
she said was ``one of the most sexist, anti-female movies I've ever
seen. The husband actually gets his ex-wife to give him her
blessing to marry a younger woman. She gets death. He gets a sexy
young woman and no guilt. Susan tried to call it a woman's movie. I
don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Edwin Heaven &LR; , flying in and out of SFOg (his nickname)
frequently recently, thinks it would be much more fun if the
security guards' detector wands vibrated.
</P>
<P>
   - In line at the Cheeseboard Pizza Collective in Berkeley the
other day,  &UR; L.B. Chapin &LR;  overheard one customer ask another: ``Hey,
by the way, how was your placenta?'' ``Oh, it was good,'' said the
other. ``Was it bloody?'' asked the first. And buon appetito to
you!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASTE NOT, WANT NOT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Those busy Coppolas:  &UR; Roman Coppola &LR; , son of Napa Valley
winemaker/restaurateur/filmmaker /magazine publisher  &UR; Francis Ford &LR; 
and filmmaker/textile expert
 &UR; Eleanor &LR;  and brother of director/actress /clothing designer
 &UR; Sofia &LR; , is one of the creators of Uvavita (which means Grape
Life), a new line of beauty products based on chemicals extracted
from Napa Valley grape seeds. Promotional materials say that Grape
Seed Extract is ``an important nutrient in the quest for anti-aging
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   - On August 20, the QVC will sell 4-foot-tall sycamore saplings
that a company called American Forests has grown from seeds
produced by a tree at Graceland. Spokesman  &UR; Louis DiGiusto &LR;  told
Wireless Flash that fans are likely to buy the saplings, which cost
$32, and turn them into shrines to &UR; Elvis Presley &LR; . The company also
sells trees grown from seeds of trees at Gettysburg, Mount Vernon
and the grave site of  &UR; JFK &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   - Oncologist  &UR; Bernard Lewinsky &LR; , Monica's pa, has hired a
literary agent to help sell a book of his photographs and text on
the healing power of photography, reports the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like a bar, without the drinks or the loud music.
There are even regulars, who get all spiffed up and study the same
paintings every Friday night. I think a museum is a good place to
meet quality people.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &LR;   &LR; Guard at the New York Museum of Modern Art, in Mademoiselle
magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
