<HEADLINE>
TONI MORRISON'S NEW BOOK PUZZLES ADULTS  
 THE NEW YORKER GOES LONG AGAIN  
 PARALLEL LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The imaginary characters in Toni Morrison's first book for
children live in a pretty brown box, decorated with beanbag chairs
and stocked with pepperoni pizza and Bubble Yum.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason Patty and Mickey and Liza Sue inhabit a cozy
carton in ``The Big Box'' is not pretty: They are ``kids who can't
handle their freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an edgy message for a children's book that some young
readers embrace while adults initially considered it ``weird'' and
``depressing'' in focus- group research conducted in June by the
book's publisher, Hyperion, at a school in Port Washington, N.Y.,
on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morrison, winner of the 1993 Nobel Prize for literature and
author of ``Paradise'' and ``Beloved,'' said in a statement to the
publisher that she had written ``a subversive story of adults not
listening to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Her book, which is scheduled for publication in September,
explores the limited world of children who are placed in a big
brown box by doting adults unnerved by their actions. There is
Patty, who talked too much and sang in class, or Mickey, who erred
by sitting on a Honda. The adults return for weekly visits with
presents of ``Barbie and Pepsi and a Princess Phone'' or an
aquarium of plastic fish and a picture of blue sky.
</P>
<P>
   The book is inspired by the experiences of Ms. Morrison's son,
Slade. When he was 9 in the 1960s, Ms. Morrison said, he was hurt
by a teacher's remark that he ``couldn't handle his own freedom.''
Ms. Morrison collected his comments and organized them into a
rhyme, but she had a hard time convincing the adults in publishing
that parents would buy a book describing the plight of children
trapped in an environment where things are more important than
love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told that it was unsalable,'' Ms. Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Disney's Hyperion acquired the book for its new
imprint, Jump at the Sun, which publishes children's literature
exploring African-American culture. It is convinced that Ms.
Morrison's themes will find an audience as it did with a focus
group of fifth-grade students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids really understand what it is to be in a big box,
whether it's their parents punishing them or overscheduling them,''
said Andrea Davis Pinkney, executive editor of Jump at the Sun.
``The parents took it more at face value, but came to realize that
they were doing what Ms. Morrison described in her book: that
adults frequently confine and squelch their children.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft at Length in The New Yorker
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 16 issue of The New Yorker magazine harked back to an
earlier time: the pre-Tina Brown days of the 23,000-word article,
when the magazine was prone to 50,000-word stories about arcane
subjects like zinc mining or the history of corn.
</P>
<P>
   The investigative piece about the antitrust lawsuit against
Microsoft Corp., ``Hard Core,'' by Ken Auletta, was the longest by
far published under David Remnick, the editor who took over from
Ms. Brown last July.
</P>
<P>
   The subject lent itself to a lengthy treatment: arcane antitrust
issues, Byzantine cyberspace maneuvers, the plot's tempestuous
central character, Bill Gates. Indeed, Auletta portrayed Gates, the
chairman of Microsoft, more as an angry adolescent than the
billionaire defendant in one of the century's most important
lawsuits _ a characterization Auletta later put forth in television
and radio interviews as well as in his opus in The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Auletta began to report the story under Ms. Brown in May 1998,
when the Justice Department filed its antitrust suit, but it
expanded under Remnick, who suggested that he devote a full year to
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Remnick said last week that he had not intended to evoke The New
Yorker of old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the longest piece I have run, but it is by no means
an aberration in terms of effort spent, or time, or ambition,''
Remnick said. ``There will be more of this kind of reporting, and
it is expensive. It is expensive in terms of the reporter's time
and resources. And what's great about this piece is that it marries
storytelling and reporting and goes for almost an entire issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Auletta said that Remnick read through the piece, which was
originally 68,000 words, seven or eight times. It was published at
23,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was involved early on in the process,'' Auletta said. ``He
said, `Let's wait and do it right.''' Meanwhile, Auletta _ who
suggested that the trial had irreparably harmed Microsoft's image _
said he had not yet heard from Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not heard a word,'' he said. ``Total silence. Then
again, I'm not really surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Journal Article on Nixon Conjures Deja Vu
</P>
<P>
   A California radiologist, Charles Pfaff, was reading The Wall
Street Journal's editorial page last Monday when he felt a sense of
deja vu. The article he was reading, ``The Day Nixon Said
Goodbye,'' by the former president's confidante, Monica Crowley,
seemed familiar.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. The article paralleled a 1988 piece in Commentary:
``In Praise of Richard Nixon'' by Paul Johnson. Some parts were
repeated almost verbatim.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal said in an editor's note Friday that there were
``striking similarities.'' It added, ``Had we known of the
parallels, we would not have published the article.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wrote of the Nixon administration, ``There was none of
the personal corruption which had marked the rule of Lyndon
Johnson, let alone the gross immoralities and security risks of
John F. Kennedy's White House.'' Ms. Crowley wrote, ``There was
none of the personal corruption that had marked the rule of Lyndon
Johnson or the base immoralities and outrageous security risks of
the Kennedy and Clinton White Houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also wrote, ``In thus rehabilitating himself, Nixon
displayed courage, endurance, persistence, patience, skill and _
there is no other word for it _ magnanimity. The greatness of his
heart is something his enemies never dreamed he possessed, and it
helps explain their misunderstanding of his nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crowley wrote: ``Throughout his self-rehabilitation, Nixon
displayed courage, endurance, patience and skill. But perhaps most
importantly, he showed great magnanimity, a quality that his
enemies never counted on and that helps explain why they so
misunderstood his nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone on Friday afternoon, Ms. Crowley, the
author of ``Nixon Off the Record'' (Random House, 1996) and ``Nixon
in Winter'' (Random House, 1998), agreed that ``there are clear
similarities in the language. I have wracked my brain, and I can
honestly tell you that I have not read'' Johnson's article.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not, nor would I ever, use material from a source
without citing it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her point ``that Nixon always put the country first at critical
junctures'' had, she said, ``been out there a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
