<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PEACEKEEPERS ARE UNEASY IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALISHEVO, Yugoslavia _ As a Russian armored personnel carrier
rumbles slowly through an Albanian village, the children on the
street shout and make mocking V-signs at them, for the Albanians'
victory over the Serbs, Russia's fellow Slavs. The soldiers look
down at them, their faces blank.
</P>
<P>
   Russian peacekeepers in Kosovo, part of the NATO-led
peacekeeping force here, are having an unhappy time. Even in the
rolling hills and woods of central Kosovo, where life is quiet and
security is good, the Russians are being made to feel
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel carrier pulls into a clearing to relieve a unit of
paratroopers manning a checkpoint, who look tired after a sleepless
shift. Several times during the night, prowlers had walked into
trip wires, sending off the warning flares that the Russians had
placed around the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not sleep all night,'' said Senior Lt. Gennady
Kharitonov, of the 106th Paratrooper Division. The paratroopers had
spotted at least one man running off in the night, and the next
morning they surprised another. They found a blanket where he had
been lying in the woods and observing their post.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be a sniper, or a scout _ we don't know what,''
Kharitonov said. Another post in their area had been fired upon,
although it appeared to be just a warning shot, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other peacekeeping unit, the Russians have become
a target of the local Albanians, in whose name they are keeping the
peace. A Russian soldier was shot in the shoulder on Thursday by a
sniper while on guard duty in Robotovo, in eastern Kosovo. The men
in Malishevo have had no casualties yet but are already feeling the
local hostility.
</P>
<P>
   The area they have been allotted in central Kosovo is easy in
one respect: It is populated only by ethnic Albanians, so there is
no continuing ethnic strife, as there is elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Malishevo and the surrounding wooded hills were a center of
activity of the guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army. It
remains a stronghold of guerrilla support, and the local commander
maintains an office in the police station in the center of the
village.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla army appears to run the show here, and its members
are refusing to cooperate with the Russian troops at all. According
to the local guerrilla commander, Habib Paqariz, Russian
mercenaries fought alongside Serbian forces in the area and were
involved in atrocities. Even if the Russian paratroopers had
nothing to do with that, he said, they were of the same nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are here against our wishes, and we will continue
to be against that, but in a peaceful way,'' said a guerrilla
commander in Malishevo, who gave his name only as Mustafa.
</P>
<P>
   So they are ostracizing the Russians. Based in a camp between
the hospital and the school on the southern edge of the village,
the Russian troops are treated almost like outcasts. The local
commanders refuse to meet with them, and even the hospital refused
their assistance, says Lt. Col. Nikolai Greshchnikov, the Russian
liaison officer in Malishevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children shout `Russia kaput!' and more when we drive
through the nearby village,'' Kharitonov said. ``We know it is
because the adults say it at home, and they hear it and repeat
it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Russians know the stories about the mercenaries, and some
say it is true that a unit calling themselves the Czar's Wolves,
probably veterans from the Chechen war, were in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Step by step we are showing them that we are not Russian
mercenaries but people, and representatives of KFOR,'' Greshchnikov
said, using the acronym for the peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are treading carefully around local sensitivities.
They are on their best behavior. In the street a soldier tips his
cap at an old man.
</P>
<P>
   The local Albanians, although unhappy about the presence of
Russian troops, find little concrete to complain about.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beg cigarettes off us,'' complained Zulzim Javoli, a
local trader who drives a Mercedes. ``And they wanted to swap some
diesel for cigarettes.'' Yet Javoli and a cousin conceded that they
brought a truck of produce through the region every day without
problems.
</P>
<P>
   And even the Kosovo Liberation Army finds little to complain
about. The Russians took some chairs and tables from the local
school, says Mustafa, the commander. And they drive too fast, he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, despite a healthy suspicion of the guerrillas, are
giving them an easy ride. Like other troops with NATO, they know
that the fighters are failing to hand in weapons and disarm, as
they are supposed to, yet the Russians are not conducting
aggressive searches. They have confiscated some weapons and
arrested a couple of highway robbers in the last weeks, but little
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go into houses and seize weapons, we would have a big
problem here, and it would not solve the problem of disarmament,''
Greshchnikov says.
</P>
<P>
   Kharitonov adds, ``Nothing is simple here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
