<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-ENGQUIST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLD-MEDAL HURDLER COMPETES DURING TREATMENTS AFTER MASTECTOMY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a summer of improbable sporting comebacks, Lance Armstrong,
the cancer patient turned Tour de France winner, now has company.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Lyudmila Engquist, the Russian turned Swede who won
the gold medal in the 100-meter hurdles in the 1996 Olympic Games
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Like Armstrong, Engquist has had to overcome cancer to compete.
But unlike Armstrong, whose triumph came three years after his
cancer was diagnosed, Engquist did not wait until her chemotherapy
had ended to resume racing _ and excel at it.
</P>
<P>
   She discovered a lump in her right breast in late March and had
a mastectomy on April 21, which happened to be her 35th birthday.
She began chemotherapy treatment in May.
</P>
<P>
   After the fourth of her six scheduled chemotherapy sessions, she
returned to the track for a meet in Stockholm on July 30. With her
doctors' approval, she has postponed the next session until two
days after the world championships, which will begin Saturday in
Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people believe that cancer is the end, but that is not
what I believe anymore,'' Engquist said earlier this month in a
hotel lobby in Monte Carlo, Monaco, several hours before running in
the Golden League meet there.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have done and what I am doing, I understand it's
special. In the world, a lot of people have cancer and a lot of
people have big problems handling it mentally. People don't know
what to do or how to react. If I can help them with this by going
out and doing my sport, then I'm happy to speak out about what has
happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Stockholm, the crowd was thoroughly aware of her
circumstances. Her illness and treatment have generated intense
publicity in Sweden, and as she walked into the Olympic stadium to
compete in her first race in more than a year, there was a standing
ovation that was more a standing roar and tears from many fans and,
soon, from Engquist, too. When her name was announced as she stood
behind the starting blocks, her fellow hurdlers applauded and
Engquist began crying again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, I stopped crying when it came time to run,'' she
said. ``But I lost concentration. For the first time in my life, I
just ran. I didn't think about technique or anything. I just ran.''
</P>
<P>
   She would have been happy just to finish, but she ended up
winning in a time of 12.68 seconds, only 18-hundredths off her best
performance in 1996. When she crossed the finish line, she leaped
into the arms of her husband and manager, Johan, and they shared a
long embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Stockholm was more emotional than my gold medal in
Atlanta,'' she said. ``I don't think anyone has seen something like
that in an athletics meet. It was just beyond belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones, the American sprint star, said, ``I've read that
I'm supposed to be the superwoman, but I think Lyudmila is far more
deserving of the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Engquist ran an even better time last Wednesday at the
Weltklasse meet in Zurich, finishing in 12.66 seconds to take
second place behind Olga Shishigina of Kazakstan (12.55).
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the stands in Stockholm was Dr. Arne Ljungqvist,
the Swedish physician who is a vice president of the International
Amateur Athletic Federation and head of the cancer foundation in
Sweden. Ljungqvist, a longtime friend, was the first person the
Engquists called in a panic after her biopsy results showed
malignancy in late March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed when I saw her running,'' Ljungqvist said. ``That
she won was a total surprise to me and to my colleagues. It was a
great moment, interesting from both a sports and a medical point of
view, because I think it shows that if you are fortunate, a disease
like this and the necessary treatment may not be incompatible with
leading a very active life.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the feats of Engquist and Armstrong were
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``One has to be careful here to make sure that people who cannot
cope so well with their situation should not feel inferior,'' he
said. ``Her physical strength, like Armstrong's physical strength,
were beneficial to them. The stronger you are, the more resistant
you will be to any type of trauma. Highly trained sportsmen are
certainly in better position to cope, but her recovery and comeback
is sensational. I would never have dreamed of her being back on the
top international level this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither would the Engquists when they prepared for chemotherapy
this spring. If all went well with her treatment, their goal was
next year and the Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, my personal doctor was joking that maybe
it's possible to make some competition in September after the
chemotherapy, but it was like joking,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the joke would soon be on the prognosis. Already, the day
after her mastectomy, Engquist had raised eyebrows among the nurses
by doing squats beside her bed.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Do you need some medication? Do you have pain? You must have
pain,''' Engquist said, cheerfully mimicking the nurses. ``I kept
telling them that I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Johan Engquist said: ``When she had the operation, the therapist
and doctor said, `You are welcomed back in six weeks, and then
we'll have a session together with other women, and you will learn
how to lift your arm.' And we just looked at each other and
smiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Engquist said she was using small weights after five days and
was doing clean-and-jerk exercises with weights exceeding 120
pounds after one month. She now wears a prosthetic breast on and
off the track and has continued training throughout chemotherapy,
although her husband said that on the advice of doctors, they had
cut her training to half its customary level to lessen the risk of
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early days of this type of chemotherapy, the normal
cells were difficult to protect,'' Ljungqvist said. ``The drugs
which killed the cancer cells also killed the others and could make
you feel bad physically and mentally. But as time has gone on, we
have learned how to perfect the system. And Engquist's success
sends an interesting message to other people in the same situation
that you can lead a fairly normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Engquist said she began seriously considering competing again in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, it was like perhaps some small competitions, but I
don't like small competitions,'' she said. ``I like big crowds, big
stadiums. It's horrible to just train and train without any
payoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's success had been a source of some comfort to her.
``I don't know much about cycling, but after I started to think
about competing this year, there was a lot in the Swedish
newspapers about Armstrong,'' she said. ``Our situations are not
the same. From what I understand, he started to compete two years
after chemotherapy. I started to compete while it's going on. But
our sports are different, too, and I don't think if I would be a
cyclist, it would be possible to do what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Engquist has landed on her feet in
the wake of considerable adversity. Born and raised in the Soviet
Union and a mother at 18, she won the world hurdles championship in
1991, but in February 1993, after testing positive for steroids,
she was banned from the sport for four years.
</P>
<P>
   She maintained that her estranged husband at the time, Nikolai
Narozhilenko, had planted the steroids in a protein powder
supplement. Narozhilenko admitted as much in a Russian court, where
the ban was lifted.
</P>
<P>
   The International Amateur Athletic Federation, citing its
exceptional circumstances rule, reinstated her in December 1995.
After receiving Swedish citizenship on June 25, 1996, in the wake
of her marriage to Johan Engquist, she became the first Swedish
woman to win an Olympic gold medal in track and field the next
month, by an eyelash in the 110-meter hurdles. Natasha, her
16-year-old daughter from her first marriage, is now a promising
sprinter for Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I've said too often now, maybe this up and down makes my
life a little bit more interesting, a bit different because you
have something to react to and overcome,'' Engquist said. ``I like
to fight. It's my nature, my way of being. It stimulates me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Engquist already refers to her cancer in the past
tense, she acknowledged she had yet to win this fight. ``It's day
by day, hurdle by hurdle,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Engquist will make no predictions for Seville. Her goal is to
reach the final or ``maybe, maybe, maybe'' even win a medal.
</P>
<P>
   In Monaco two weeks ago, in a race featuring the world's top two
hurdlers, Shishigina and Glory Alozie of Nigeria, she had to settle
for fourth place in 12.67 seconds. She did not get the chance to
stand on the podium, but she did not leave Monaco without a prize.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the race, some Swedish fans hurled a bouquet
of flowers onto the track. And as midnight approached and Engquist
answered the last of so many questions from her adopted nation's
news corps in a corridor inside the stadium, she was still
clutching the flowers and the message they came with: ``For us, you
are the best.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
