<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS FROM THE WORLD OF ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGENCY EXECUTIVE SUES HIS EMPLOYERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kassan, president for North American operations at
Western Initiative Media Worldwide in Los Angeles, part of the
Interpublic Group of Cos., has sued Western and Interpublic for
breach of contract and defamation of character, asking for damages
totaling $63.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kassan charged that Interpublic was ``orchestrating a scheme''
to either force him to resign or invent a reason to dismiss him and
to ``ruin his reputation'' with actions that included disseminating
statements that he ``was on an extended leave of absence from
Western because of his role in financial misconduct.'' He is
seeking $50 million in damages through arbitration with the
American Arbitration Association and $13.5 million in a lawsuit
filed in Federal District Court in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Trade publications reported in July that Kassan, who joined
Western in 1994, had suddenly taken a monthlong leave of absence.
Subsequent articles described Interpublic's conducting a financial
audit or internal investigation at Western. But Western later
issued a statement that the leave had ``no connection whatsoever''
to work by Kassan or Western on behalf of clients.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of a news release about the contentions in Kassan's
lawsuits, issued on his behalf, raised eyebrows. It was sent to
reporters late on Friday afternoon _ and many agency executives are
typically absent from their offices on summer Fridays. So it was
not surprising that several telephone calls to executives at
Western and Interpublic in Los Angeles and New York were not
returned. That meant their responses to the charges would appear in
articles after the charges were reported.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE MARKETERS SELECT AGENCIES
</P>
<P>
   Several ``dot com'' advertisers have named agencies to handle
their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Living.com in Austin, Texas, a Web-based home products retailer,
selected two divisions of the Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago as the
first agencies to handle its account, with billings that were
estimated by the trade publication Adweek at $25 million. Burnett
USA will handle branding duties and Starcom Worldwide will handle
media duties. The decision came after a review that had been
narrowed to the Burnett divisions and two other finalists:
McCann-Erickson Southwest in Dallas and Houston, part of the
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising unit of the Interpublic Group
of Cos., and Richards Group in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   AFB Multimedia Inc. in New York named Bozell Kamstra in New
York, part of the Bozell Worldwide unit of True North
Communications, as the first agency to handle the account of
AFBnews.com, a news service devoted to crime, courtroom proceedings
and penology. Billings were estimated at $20 million. The decision
came after a review that had been narrowed to Bozell and two
unidentified finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Storerunner.com in San Diego awarded its branding and marketing
account to three Omnicom Group units, DDB Worldwide in New York,
Interbrand and Porter Novelli. Spending was estimated at $15
million for the rest of the year. The decision came after a
two-week review that had been narrowed to the Omnicom agencies and
undisclosed finalists. The CBS Corp. bought 50 percent of
Storerunner.com in April for $100 million worth of commercial time
on CBS television, radio and online properties over six years.
</P>
<P>
   And Furniture.com in Framingham, Mass., named Bartle Bogle
Hegarty U.S. in New York, the American unit of Bartle Bogle
Hegarty, to handle branding campaigns for the online furniture
retailer. Billings were estimated at more than $5 million. The
decision came after a two-month review; the other participants were
not identified. Bartle Bogle will work with agencies that already
work for Furniture.com, which include Neil Faber Media Inc. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   FINALISTS NAMED FOR INTERNET WORK
</P>
<P>
   Three Internet-related companies in New York have narrowed
reviews on accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Newspage.com named four finalists in a review for its first
branding account, with billings estimated at $10 million to $15
million. They are Chadwick Communications in New York; TFA/Leo
Burnett Technology Group in Boston, part of the Leo Burnett Co.,
and Grey Advertising in New York. In addition, Pro Media Inc. in
Natick, Mass., will compete with those agencies for the off-line
media buying and promotion duties.
</P>
<P>
   Real Media Inc., an Internet marketing company, named four
finalists in a review for its trade account, with billings
estimated at $2 million to $3 million. Real Media and M&AMP;C Saatchi
in New York, which had been hired in September, parted ways over
what were described as creative differences.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists, all based in New York, are: DeVito/Verdi, Hanft
Byrne Raboy &AMP; Partners, Mezzina/Brown and Stein Rogan &AMP; Partners. A
decision is expected by the end of August. Lot 21 in San Francisco
remains the Real Media interactive agency.
</P>
<P>
   And Gfn.com, the Gay Financial Network Inc., which operates a
Web site aimed at gay men and lesbians, named three finalists in a
review to find the first agency to handle its account, with
billings estimated at almost $2 million. Matthew L. Papa, associate
marketing manager at Gfn.com in New York, identified the finalists,
all in New York, as: Interactive8, Mad Dogs and Englishmen and
Prime Access. A decision is expected in a month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTS
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear Tire and Rubber Co.'s European operations, London, to
Leagas Delaney, London, to handle creative duties for its account,
which had been at McCann-Erickson London, part of McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising, a unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos.
Billings were estimated at $20 million. McCann-Erickson London
continues handling media duties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome, Research Triangle Park, N.C., to Robert A.
Becker Inc. Euro RSCG, New York, part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide
unit of Havas Advertising, to handle the account of the drug
company's Serevent Inhalation Aerosol, an asthma treatment.
Capitalized billings were estimated at $7.2 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bcandid, Boulder, Colo., to Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS, New York, part
of the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos., as the
first agency to handle creative duties for the account of the
developer of Internet group-discussion software. Billings were
estimated at $5 million to $10 million. D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP;
Bowles, Los Angeles, part of MacManus Group, handles media duties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey L. Johnson was named to the new post of president for
the Florida operations of West Wayne Inc., Atlanta, responsible for
offices in Miami and Tampa. He had most recently been a consultant;
he previously worked for agencies like Wells BDDP, New York. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dick Emerson was named to the new post of partner at Toth Brand
Imaging, Concord, Mass., and New York, functioning as chief
operating officer. He had been chief operating officer at Arnold
Communications, Boston, part of Snyder Communications. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Oxman was named to the new post of business development
director at Euro RSCG Tatham, Chicago, part of the Euro RSCG
Worldwide unit of Havas Advertising. He had been vice president and
account director at D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles, Troy, Mich.,
part of MacManus Group.
</P>
