<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HISTORY OF SEX' IS LIGHTHEARTED WITHOUT BEING FLIPPANT OR VULGAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you read this column you won't go blind. Really and truly.
</P>
<P>
   But it is about sex, so those who don't like reading about sex,
talking about sex or learning about sex may want to wander
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   For those who stayed, welcome to Sex 101, courtesy of The
History Channel. Yes, indeed. The History Channel, home of ``Great
Ships'' and ``Tales of the Gun,'' finally goes beyond the merely
metaphorical with a five-part series this week called ``The History
of Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone thinking ``why The History Channel?'' right about now
should consider this: At the end of Monday's first episode, airing
at 7 and again at 11, narrator Peter Coyote says soberly, ``Without
sex there would be no history.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it, folks: the perfect justification for a
programming decision. And since this is a History Channel project,
Monday night's installment features a clip of the Japanese attack
on Pearl Harbor. No kidding. And for real history-of-sex buffs,
there's also footage from World War I, with shots of some awfully
big guns.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, even on a channel where war footage isn't so much
symbolic as it is compulsory, the battle scenes are intended to
illustrate the point that American soldiers were exposed to
different cultures and views on sexuality when they went overseas.
The clips are outnumbered, probably a thousand to one, by still
images of erotic art over the five-night run.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't ``Real Sex'' on HBO. Despite the erotica _ the
series is rated TV-14 _ and Monday night's heavy dose of Hugh
Hefner and Helen Gurley Brown, ``The History of Sex'' is not about
titillation, even if the real reason for its existence is to
attract a younger audience than the one customarily drawn to The
History Channel. Scholarly in approach and wide in scope, ``The
History of Sex'' is a laudable attempt to open eyes and minds to
widely disparate takes on human sexuality since the first utterance
of ``not tonight, honey, I have a headache.'' At its best, though,
it is a broad survey of sexual mores and practices through the
ages. Viewers should not expect a probing examination of sex and
its impact on the single planet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in one-hour doses over five August nights, ``The History
of Sex'' is a painless and moderately entertaining way to learn
that, in ancient Mesopotamia, buoyancy could be the deciding factor
in cases of adultery. Couples suspected of doing the deed were
often tied up and thrown in a river. If they floated, they were
innocent; if they drowned, they were guilty. And they probably
didn't do it again.
</P>
<P>
   In other societies, however, there was no stigma attached to
adultery or homosexuality or polygamy, and ``The History of Sex''
deserves praise for issuing no moral pronouncements. For instance,
its reference to one of the first pornographic films in this
country, circa 1915, passes no judgment aside from an allusion to
its randy title (``A Free Ride'') and its creators (a director
identified as A. Wise Guy and a cinematographer named Will B.
Hard).
</P>
<P>
   The series begins Monday night with an installment titled ``The
20th Century,'' hence the appearance of Hefner, Brown and Dr. Ruth
Westheimer to discuss the ``sexual revolution'' and how movies and
the back seats of automobiles contributed to the carnal education
of American society. Tuesday w night, ``From Don Juan to Queen
Victoria'' looks at extremes of sexual behavior, ranging from the
Puritans to the Marquis de Sade, and subsequent installments survey
``The Middle Ages,'' ``The Eastern World'' and _ my favorite _
``Ancient Civilizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lighthearted without being flippant, ``The History of Sex''
bounces from topic to topic like an ancient Chinese husband from
concubine to concubine. (The Confucian book of rites required him
to have sex with each at least once every five days until the
concubines reached the age of 50.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The History of Sex'' would be more enjoyable, or at least less
distracting, if it weren't so obviously an American production hung
up on how explicit it should dare to be. Though there's plenty of
graphic sexual imagery, the viewer is shortchanged many, many times
by prudish editing that crops an image and thus undermines the, uh,
thrust of a particular passage in the script.
</P>
<P>
   Seems odd that a channel so accustomed to showing the ravages of
war can't bring itself to go all the way when it comes to matters
of the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   History of Sex. Five-part series airing at 7 and 11 Monday
through Friday on The History Channel. Parental guideline rating:
TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
