<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-MEMORIAL-ART-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR AFTER BOMB BLAST IN NORTHERN IRELAND, GRIEF PERSISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ A year ago Sunday, shortly after 3
o'clock on a sunny afternoon in this quiet market town in the
Sperrin Mountains, Donna Marie Keyes, her fiance and his
21-month-old niece were shopping for a pair of fancy little shoes
in a store named McElroy's on Market Street, when a policeman
rushed in and told them of a terrorist bomb threat.
</P>
<P>
   They should move down Market Street, away from the courthouse,
he told Ms. Keyes, Gary McGillion and little Breda, who needed
shoes to dress as a flower girl at their wedding a week later.
</P>
<P>
   But the bombers, a splinter group of the Irish Republican Army,
had given police a misleading warning, resulting in hundreds of
shoppers being herded toward, instead of away from, the maroon
Vauxhall Cavalier that held 500 pounds of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Keyes, McGillion and Breda came within a few feet of the
car, the bomb exploded. A shop sign fell on Breda, who was in a
stroller, and killed her; Ms. Keyes and McGillion were sliced by
flying metal and burned over most of their bodies. The explosion
killed 29 people and wounded another 400 _ the deadliest single
bomb attack in 29 years of sectarian warfare in this British
province.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Omagh is a town of lingering grief and trauma.
Many of the injured and their relatives still refuse to come
downtown, fearing another bomb, not wanting to remember images of
the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, several thousand people in this town of about
25,000 did return to Market Street, as the city marked the first
anniversary of the bombing with Catholic and Protestant prayers and
hymns in front of the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel a lot of sadness and sorrow,'' said Ms. Keyes, now 23,
who married McGillion in March. She spent six weeks in a coma and
has a long scar on her forehead. ``But we are lucky,'' she said.
``We have the gift of life. Our hearts are with Breda.''
</P>
<P>
   McGillion, 25, a mechanic and an amateur heavyweight boxer
before his arms and legs were sliced by metal shards, and who still
has a piece of steel in his right ear, said he is unable to go to
his job fixing tractors and earth diggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boxing days are now over,'' he added. He is a coach with
the Omagh boys' boxing club, which is traveling overseas for a
tournament in Yonkers, N.Y., in November.
</P>
<P>
   A director of the club, Joe Byrne, who is also a mainstream
Catholic member of the Northern Ireland Assembly in Belfast, said
Sunday morning: ``As I drove around the town there was a mood of
reflection and sadness. People are subdued today. I went to buy the
newspapers. No one else was in the shop. Normally it would be
crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming majority of republican guerrillas, like the
Real IRA, which acknowledged that it planted the bomb, are Roman
Catholics. So are Ms. Keyes and McGillion; so was Breda; so are 65
percent of the people who live here. Thirty-five percent are
Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Police say privately that, after a year of investigation and the
questioning of 4,000 people, it is unlikely that the bombers will
ever be caught.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA is one of the Catholic paramilitary groups that
opposes the 1998 peace agreement that is supposed to end the
violence. The Catholic dissidents see the agreement as a sellout to
Protestants because it does not provide for a union of British
Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic, to the south.
</P>
<P>
   In the months after the blast, people were encouraged by visits
from President Clinton and Prime Ministers Tony Blair of Britain
and Bertie Ahern of Ireland and many other politicians. Thousands
of people from all over Ireland came here to do their Christmas
shopping and pray for the residents.
</P>
<P>
   Many people thought that maybe the bomb attack at Omagh would be
the last major atrocity of the sectarian fighting, that it would so
horrify ordinary people and political leaders that a permanent
peace would soon follow, with a resolution of disputes between
Catholics and Protestants at the Northern Ireland Assembly in
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not happened. Sporadic paramilitary violence
continues in the province. On Saturday, Catholics protesting
Protestant parades in Londonderry, north of here, threw gasoline
bombs at police and seriously damaged several stores and banks.
</P>
<P>
   As the new violence adds to the tally of those scarred by this
conflict, the people of Omagh are themselves still wounded, still
suffering, physically and psychologically. Scores have been unable
to return to work, still traumatized by what happened to them and
their loved ones. The Bridge, a government-financed trauma center,
says 250 people are still being counseled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a sense of sadness and painful anticipation of
this weekend,'' said the trauma center's director, Michael Duffy,
of Sunday's commemoration. ``All the emotions and the memories are
so vividly resurrected. People have not dealt with their nightmares
and their flashbacks. They still see all the carnage, suffering and
distress of that day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their sense of security is affected,'' Duffy said, adding that
scores of the injured victims and their families could not bear
coming downtown to Market Street, on Sunday or any day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a foreshortened sense of the future,'' he said.
``Many are afraid there will be another bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, Duffy said, have been helped by the center's 20
psychologists, psychiatrists and social workers, who have studied
American analyses of the trauma of Vietnam war veterans. The
patients are also reminded of their own plight when they learn of
the series of fatal shooting incidents in the United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most of the survivors of the Omagh attack, Duffy added,
acknowledge that the news coverage of the bombing and its aftermath
had helped bring in about $10 million in aid. As the anniversary
approached, they gave many interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Two teen-age girls were shown several times on television, one
learning to swim in a pool with one normal leg and the thigh-stump
of the other. Another was shown wearing a plastic mask protecting
her face wounds, still healing. Both have decided to give no more
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media will move on to the next tragedy,'' Duffy said,
without rancor. ``And we have to deal with this ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Business has suffered on Market Street, where 10 stores and
shops, including McElroy's, destroyed by the blast are being
renovated with government money. Patrick Bogues, owner of a jewelry
shop, noted without smiling that his family had moved the business
from Belfast after it had been bombed by German planes in World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas shopping by out-of-towners, he said, ``gave the
town economy a tremendous fillip'' but the momentum could not be
sustained. ``Now people come out of curiosity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of wedding rings were down, he noted, adding, ``But maybe
that's because a lot of people want to be married in the new
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say that they are working hard on the investigation. They
say they have arrested and released about 60 people after
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The only person charged is Colm Murphy, a pub owner in Dundalk,
across the border in County Louth. He was charged in the Dublin
Special Criminal Court with conspiring to carry out an explosion.
But no trial date has been set and he is free on bail and is not
suspected as one of the actual bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, police say it is unlikely they will ever catch the
bombers. Despite the widespread condemnation of the attack, there
has been no help from informers. ``All they have to do is pick up a
phone and tell us that they know something,'' said one officer.
``But they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   At the ceremony Sunday, people waited silently, watching the
courthouse clock as it approached 3:10, the time of the blast. Some
wept. Parents clutched their small children, a few of whom laughed
and shouted, heedless. As the clock reached its mark, a bagpiper
played a mournful song, easily audible at the spot on Market Street
where baby Breda went for new shoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
