<HEADER>
A8051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-STRAW16-COX     08-15 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAW16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush leaves shattered dreams in his wake
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa - The candidate who got here last came in first and
left a Sunday death watch over the presidential dreams of some of
the also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who didn't declare his candidacy until June
12 and spent only nine days campaigning here, won the Iowa GOP
straw poll Saturday and now waits to see if the field will narrow.
</P>
<P>
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander headed home Sunday to
``reconsider my candidacy'' after running sixth and picking up only
6 percent of the straw vote that drew 24,000 participants.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Vice President Dan Quayle, who launched a verbal assault on
Bush at the straw poll, ran eighth, collecting only 3.9 percent.
Quayle played the happy warrior Sunday, heading to campaign stops
in New Hampshire and downplaying his down-ballot finish in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Third-time candidate Pat Buchanan, who ran fifth with 7.3
percent of the straw vote, indicated his days as a Republican may
be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who spent more time campaigning here than any of the
GOP contenders, set up Iowa as a do-or-die effort for himself. He
had the backing of former four-term Gov. Terry Branstad and a
statewide organization.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday he sounded like a candidate planning an exit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a powerful force in this country to nominate George W.
Bush,'' he said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' ``And there is a
powerful force out there, too, I think we saw last night, to have a
contest. But I'm not sure I did well enough last night to be a part
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said he has been unable to penetrate media perception
that Bush is ``the inevitable nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't find a way to overcome that in the country and the
media it doesn't make much sense for me to go ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while some candidates claim Bush does not have the
experience to be president, Alexander noted this curiosity of the
straw-poll results:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little unnerving to stop and think about the fact that
of the first five finishers in the straw poll they have five total
years of experience in elective office. And George Bush has all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the straw poll results, Quayle, already campaigning in
New Hampshire, said nothing happened in Iowa to deter his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go on,'' he said on CBS' ``Face the Nation,'' adding
that, like Bush, he got into the Iowa straw poll race later than
most. ``We are very well positioned now to do very well and
hopefully win the (Iowa) caucuses. That's when the votes really
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, also speaking on ``Face the Nation,'' said he remains
intent on winning the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe I'm the one candidate who disagrees most
profoundly and most extensively with Governor Bush,'' he said. ``I
think we are going to emerge as the conservative challenger to
Bush. It hasn't happened yet.''
</P>
<P>
   During the straw poll, Bush urged Buchanan not to leave the GOP.
Buchanan said he could make no promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going right now down this road,'' he said of seeking the
Republican nomination. ``If the Republican Party moves off in a new
direction, it moves off. I don't know exactly where I'm going to be
in August of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, who did not participate, said Sunday
the event was ``a meaningless, kind of senseless thing.'' He also
said he might not compete in the Iowa caucuses that kick off the
delegate hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to fight on ground that is most favorable to
you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
