<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-SMITH-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DISPELS SOME OF THE MYTHS ABOUT HIRING OLDER WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thing many older workers fear most is being discounted
because of their age, especially when they go to look for new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Although employers insist they don't discriminate, many older
workers would say otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   So which is reality?
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Sabin Forte, the business outreach coordinator for
Bates Technical College in Tacoma, Wash., recently published
results of research looking at employer attitudes toward both older
and younger workers.
</P>
<P>
   The results, published in the March volume of the Journal of
Employment Counseling, are surprising.
</P>
<P>
   In her work with displaced workers, Forte frequently heard older
job seekers complain that no one wanted to interview them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to say to them, other than, `Hang in
there,''' she said. So she and Christine Hansvick, associate
professor of psychology at Pacific Lutheran University in Tacoma,
decided to find out how older workers _ those over age 50 _ were
regarded by potential employers.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption among older workers, backed in part by research
by others, was that younger workers were generally viewed more
favorably than older ones, she said. ``We wanted to test that
hypothesis.''
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing myths were that older workers weren't as quick to
learn, their energy was lower, and they didn't have the computer
skills to keep up with their younger counterparts, she said. ``The
big perception is that they aren't as up to date.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte and Hansvick surveyed more than 300 employers in the
Pacific Northwest, asking them to rate workers under age 49 and
those over age 50 on a range of attributes. The attributes were
attendance, work ethic, stamina, productivity, academic skills,
computer skills, ability to learn new skills quickly, flexibility
and openness to change, ability to get along with co-workers,
willingness to take direction, supervisory skills and appropriate
salary expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The results only partially supported the premise that older
workers are viewed less favorably, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Older workers actually scored better than their younger
colleagues in six of the attributes. They were judged more
favorably on academic skill levels, attendance, ability to get
along with co-workers, work ethics, salary expectations and
supervisory skills.
</P>
<P>
   Younger workers were judged more favorably on computer skills,
ability to learn quickly, energy and flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Employers also indicated they perceived no differences when it
came to willingness to take directions, or productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Job seekers can use that information to help them prepare for
interviews, Forte said. It can help them address the issues that
are likely to be lurking in the back of an interviewer's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a twofold strategy,'' she said. ``You need to capitalize
on the positive attributes, and assuage fears about the
negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   If computer skills are important to the job, for example, the
older worker should state up front that his computer skills are up
to date (assuming they are), rather than assume the interviewer
will know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless they're told otherwise, (a potential employer) may
assume an older worker's skills aren't as current,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Older workers should also pay special attention to first
impressions, she said. Having an outdated haircut and clothes can
reinforce the stereotype that an older worker is resistant to
change.
</P>
<P>
   It's especially important that older workers go into an
interview armed with examples or anecdotes to reinforce any
positive bias the interviewer already has toward older hires. And
they should be prepared to show how they might compensate for
perceived weaknesses, such as having less stamina or less facility
at learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is we do learn a little differently as we get
older, but we also have more experience,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And a willingness to learn goes a long way toward compensating
for some slowing in the grasp of new concepts.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is as the population ages and older workers
increase as a percentage of the labor force, more employers will be
faced with hiring older workers.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is people are working for a longer span of time. The
workplace is changing at an unprecedented rate.
</P>
<P>
   No one has the luxury of kicking back and saying they know it
all.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for all workers _ young and old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
