<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT     08-15 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASANT TEMPER KEEPS WALDEN'S STREAK GOING
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A crucial week for fillies dawned at
Saratoga Race Course Sunday, with Magicalmysterycat primed for
Monday's Adirondack for 2-year-olds and Silverbulletday counting
down to her next appearance Saturday in the Alabama Stakes. And the
week got off to a rousing start when Pleasant Temper won the
Ballston Spa Handicap and sent Elliott Walden back to the winner's
circle as Saratoga's hottest trainer of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Walden had been spending time in the winner's circle lately
greeting such stars as Victory Gallop and Ecton Park, and he made
another visit Sunday to greet Jerry Bailey and Pleasant Temper
after they led all the way and won by nearly three lengths. It was
the second consecutive success for the 5-year-old daughter of Storm
Cat and the fifth in her last seven starts, and she clearly outran
the favored Anguilla, who finished fourth in a field of five.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mare is difficult to train,'' Walden said. ``She's very
high-strung, typical of a Storm Cat. She's settled with age. I
talked with Jerry this morning, and we decided that no plan was the
best plan. Jerry did a great job of nursing her along.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Day, who rode Anguilla, said he was trying to conserve his
mare's energy for the homestretch, but added, ``When I pulled the
trigger and called on her to run, I got no response.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant Temper, who is owned by Mark Stanley, ran the mile and
one-sixteenth in 1:41 4/5, finished 2} lengths in front of Cuanto
Es and paid $5.60 for a $2 bet to win as the second choice to
Anguilla. &QL; 
Giveaway Inspires Record
</P>
<P>
   The giveaway mania reached record levels Sunday at old Saratoga.
Nobody knows how many people actually attended the races, but the
turnstiles clicked 66,194 times for a track record, beating the
previous mark of 61,190 recorded on Aug. 9 last year.
</P>
<P>
   They gave away free T-shirts that day. This time they gave away
drinking steins, and many customers cheerfully paid the $2
grandstand admission or the $4 clubhouse fee two or three times in
order to go back through the turnstiles and receive free mugs.
</P>
<P>
   The track had stockpiled 50,000 steins in anticipation of the
public's response, but it still outran expectations. Even while
long lines were waiting outside the gates, public address
announcements were warning that the house had run out of mugs. But
the turnstiles kept clicking.
</P>
<P>
   STORY MAY END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS
</P>
<P>
   ONE DOWN, TWO TO GO
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's $150,000 Adirondack, which is run at six and a half
furlongs and is the middle race in Saratoga's series of three for
juvenile fillies, Magicalmysterycat will try to repeat her winning
performance July 28 in the Schuylerville. The filly, trained by
D.Wayne Lukas, is the undefeated daughter of Storm Cat who was
purchased last year for $1.1 million. Her next goal if she wins
Monday: a sweep of Saratoga's filly honors in the Spinaway on Sept.
3.
</P>
<P>
   But her life may be complicated by the arrival of Miss
Wineshine, a Texas-bred filly in Bob Baffert's barn and a
stablemate of the undefeated West Coast star Chilukki.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get Miss Wineshine away from Chilukki,'' Baffert
said. ``She's big, she looks like Winning Colors and she's a pretty
awesome filly. And, in my opinion, she's not that far behind
Chilukki at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   A NEW WAGERING FORCE
</P>
<P>
   The 47th annual Round Table conference of the Jockey Club (no
relation to the racing champion of the same name) turned into the
second annual report on the state of the business by the National
Thoroughbred Racing Association, which predictably reported that it
had been doing an excellent job during its 16 months as the
industry's unifying marketing force.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Smith, the commissioner of the NTRA, emphasized the
significance of the Television Games Network, a 24-hour channel
devoted to racing designed to reach a young new audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not an overstatement to say that interactive account
wagering, led by TVG, has an excellent chance of becoming the new
decade's equivalent of simulcasting,'' Smith said, ``both in
producing new distribution for our product and in leading to new
growth in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Boylan, president of TV Guide, in a report titled
``Racing's New Frontier,'' said that the goal of the new channel
was ``to entertain the masses.'' But he emphasized that its success
``depends on states' accepting account wagering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
