<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SIBLEY-HEAVEN-COX     08-15 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-HEAVEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Heaven's golden streets don't entice me half as much as a stand
of pretty trees'
 &HT;    EDITOR'S NOTE: Celestine Sibley wrote the following column for
Christmas Day 1998, shortly after learning that her cancer had
returned.
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A friend for whom I did a slight favor said lightly,
``When you die, you're going to heaven.'' It gave me a bad couple
of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dying is all right if you must, but heaven? I'm not sure about
that, either getting there or liking it.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be secure in your devotion to heaven! She thought I had
blasphemed. I tried to throw her off by singing a few bars from
that old spiritual, ``Evvabody talk about heaven ain't going
there.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no use pursuing the matter. Most of us who went to
Sunday school as children were probably reared with a mental
picture of pearly gates and golden streets, and no self-respecting
ad person nowadays would put that picture in a resort magazine.
</P>
<P>
   What do we want a perfect place to look like? It sounds bizarre
in view of all the troubles we've been having lately, but I happen
to like this world, the one we live in, the one we abuse, the one
we probably don't deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven's golden streets don't entice me half as much as a stand
of pretty trees. Do they have fall color in heaven? Will the sweet
gums there be gold and rose and violet in autumn? Does heaven have
mountain laurel and rhododendron in June? How about mountains and
rushing little creeks and springs of great drinking water?
</P>
<P>
   Since you think of heaven as being ``up yonder,'' what about the
sky? Is it so close to the sky, you can't get a perspective on the
silvery clouds piled against a blue heaven? I like almost any sky
mood, blue or gray or buttermilk-spattered. It's wonderful to watch
the change as you drive home from work in the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   That's another thing. Do you work in heaven? I happen to like it
very much, but nothing I read or heard in my childhood mentioned
that there's a daily paper in heaven. Could it be that all of us
saints don't get the news?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of saints, I worry about them. I have known a few
saintly people, and they weren't half as much fun as some who had
slipped from sainthood. A little spice, a little malice ... Is that
allowed? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   I recently read a book about the Roosevelt women, most of whom
were descended from Georgia's Mittie Bulloch of Roswell. Mittie was
almost too good to be true, except out of sympathy for her
Confederate kinsmen, she sneaked blankets from her Yankee husband's
family and smuggled them south. Some of her descendants were good,
as witness Eleanor Roosevelt, who was so caught up in doing for
other people she missed sitting around feeling virtuous. Then there
was Alice Roosevelt Longworth, who was probably assigned to the
gossip mill if she made it into heaven. There are many stories
about her, but one I hadn't heard was that when her grown-up
brother fell down the long staircase in her house, she sat still
and observed, ``I never liked him anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta people I like a lot may not be headed for heaven, but
when the bank teller tells you to have a good Christmas, I think
she means it. Also the kid in the supermarket and the cashier at
the gas station. She doesn't speak English (do they in heaven?),
but she is cheerful and good-humored, and when she says, ``Mucho
merry to you,'' I feel warm and looked after.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't worried about the white sand and the blue water of the
Gulf of Mexico, but they're on my list of things to ask St. Peter
about if I ever get as far as the pearly gate. Train whistles and
boat whistles and dogs and cats and mockingbirds and rainy nights
and snow ... I must ask my friend and if she doesn't have the
inside word, she should be more careful about consigning some of us
to that exalted place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
