</P>
<P>
   Atlanta people I like a lot may not be headed for heaven, but
when the bank teller tells you to have a good Christmas, I think
she means it. Also the kid in the supermarket and the cashier at
the gas station. She doesn't speak English (do they in heaven?),
but she is cheerful and good-humored, and when she says, ``Mucho
merry to you,'' I feel warm and looked after.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't worried about the white sand and the blue water of the
Gulf of Mexico, but they're on my list of things to ask St. Peter
about if I ever get as far as the pearly gate. Train whistles and
boat whistles and dogs and cats and mockingbirds and rainy nights
and snow ... I must ask my friend and if she doesn't have the
inside word, she should be more careful about consigning some of us
to that exalted place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
