</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SIBLEY-APPRE-TAKE2-CO     08-15 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-APPRE-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CELESTINE SIBLEY: An appreciation
 &HT;    (EDS: Take TWO of 2 takes. MOVING TO (a) General news and (l)
Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (continued)
</P>
<P>
   Sibley married Little, a Press-Register copy editor, and they
took jobs in Atlanta, she with the Constitution, he with the
Associated Press. Little bounced from job to job, in Mobile,
Pensacola, Atlanta, Jacksonville, Atlanta again, Orlando, Atlanta
again, St. Petersburg and Columbus. He stayed in hotels, leaving
Sibley and their children here to live on her newspaper salary and
freelance income from magazine articles and books.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley's life never lacked for melodrama, and occasional real
tragedy. Two of her grandchildren died in infancy, one from SIDS,
the other from a fall. The sadness she knew, and her background of
poverty, gave her a heightened concern for ordinary people that,
more than anything else, made her one of the newspaper's most
popular writers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, she helped convince the state Board of Pardons and
Paroles to free convicted killer Floyd Woodward. A onetime con man
wanted in connection with a 1920 slaying, Woodward had gone
straight for years, living in California under an assumed name,
before he was extradited to Georgia and convicted in 1943. At a
hearing, witnesses testified that Woodward had acted in
self-defense. He was freed and Sibley put him on a plane to
California.
</P>
<P>
   Another of her familiar column subjects was Francis Brunton. He
was a hobo who lived under the Spring Street viaduct and rode
through downtown Atlanta on a bicycle, wearing a globe around his
neck and carrying an encyclopedia. Sibley let him use her office as
a mailing address.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley collected such characters, and her columns were peopled
with a Dickensian gallery of eccentrics and castoffs. Readers will
remember:
</P>
<P>
   _ Miss Anna May Smith, whose house was pulled down by kudzu and
who the police picked up on some minor charge. They reported to
Sibley that they discovered $10,000 sewed into her clothing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mrs. Arizona Bell, who sold papers downtown and had once
ridden in Buffalo Bill's circus. Sibley, in her own subversive way,
chose Mrs. Bell as a partner to accompany her to the Metropolitan
Opera.
</P>
<P>
   _ Miss Peavey, who loved well, but not wisely. Sibley described
one of her elderly suitors as having ``not a tooth in his head, but
the light of love in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ted Hagler and Ronald Rolland, aka Ted and Shorty. Panhandlers
and longtime fixtures of the Marietta Street scene, Ted and Shorty
are among the contemporary street people who also populated the
column. ``She's just the sweetest person you could ever hope to
meet,'' said Hagler, 51.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley was loved by readers for profiling the nonfamous in her
columns, but she knew and wrote about the famous as well. In the
early 1950s, the merged Journal-Constitution sent her on annual
trips to Hollywood to write puff pieces, in her words, promoting
upcoming movies. She earned $100 apiece for the articles, which
were published in the Sunday magazine.
</P>
<P>
   On the set of ``Don't Bother to Knock'' in 1952, Sibley asked
Marilyn Monroe, ``How does it feel to be an international
cheesecake success?''
</P>
<P>
   Monroe replied: ``I just believe in doing the best you can with
what you have.''
</P>
<P>
   She never conferred celebrity on herself, however. When she was
covering the 1976 presidential campaign alongside a visiting
reporter with the University of Georgia's student newspaper, the
Red and Black, she insisted that both journalists be given equal
access. ``I talked to everyone in the Carter family because I was
with her,'' said Patricia Templeton, that student reporter, a
longtime friend, and now an Episcopalian minister, who will preside
at Sibley's funeral service.
</P>
<P>
   Years after her first husband died, she again found love, with
Jack Strong, a real estate broker and former reporter for the
Constitution, who was about 12 years her junior. For more than 40
years, they kept company with each other and finally married in
1987. In November of 1988, at age 59, he died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her heroic productivity, Sibley led a vigorous private
life, full of the enthusiasms that she shared with her readers and
many that she did not, in particular her fondness for gossip. ``She
remembered everything, especially grievances,'' quipped her
long-time editor at Harper and Row, now HarperCollins, Lawrence
Ashmead.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the columns don't reveal about her is that she was a very
intelligent, somewhat cynical, salty-talking reporter,'' said her
friend Robert Steed, a partner in the prestigious law firm King and
Spalding, and a onetime-writer of humorous newspaper columns for
The Atlanta Journal. ``She had another sharper side to her. That
was the fun side, that's why these newspaper people and reprobate
lawyers wanted to be in her company.''
</P>
<P>
   She often used her column to offer tribute to friends and other
notable Georgians who had passed away. Said columnist Jim Minter,
former editor of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,``I'd hoped she'd
live long enough to write a column about me when I die; she could
make some pretty (lousy) people look pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley would sometimes reprint letters from her readers that
questioned her ability, her taste and intelligence. She would
usually answer these with modest restraint. Occasionally her
forbearance might sag. An Americus woman wrote to berate her for
being ``leftist'' on women's rights, and for not appreciating Elvis
Presley, Anita Bryant or the television show ``Dallas.'' Answered
Sibley, ``Ah, what a lot of twaddle!''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Emerson, former Newsweek bureau chief and a friend, cited
Sibley as ``the best columnist the Atlanta newspapers have ever
had, better than Bill Arp, better than Lewis Grizzard, better than
Ralph McGill. She also knew more about the informal history of
Atlanta than any other living person, including Franklin Garrett.''
</P>
<P>
   She loved the religious drama ``Heaven Bound,'' performed yearly
at Christmas by the Big Bethel AME Church, and was such a steadfast
champion that she was awarded a pair of paper wings by the
congregation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   She bragged on those wings more than any of the scores of awards
that she received in her career. Those awards included two honorary
doctorates, a commendation from the Legislature as ``state
treasure'' and even a piece of Ga. 140 renamed the Celestine Sibley
Highway, where she was once involved in a brush-up with a red
pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley was only the second woman to receive The Lifetime
Achievement Award from the National Society of Newspaper
Columnists, which they presented to her in June of this year ``with
envy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Sibley received the Shining Light Award from the
Atlanta Gas Light Co., a distinction that she shared with her
mentor, Ralph McGill. The gas company installs a permanent gas
flame in honor of the recipients, and like McGill's, her lamp burns
outside the newspaper offices on Marietta Street. ``I like mine
even better than McGill's, don't you?'' she asked the charmed
audience. In her acceptance speech she joked about drafty old Sweet
Apple, saying ``I'm getting this award because I have the most
energy-inefficient house in Fulton County.''
</P>
<P>
   On that occasion, members of Big Bethel's choir sang her
favorite hymn, ``Steal Away,'' a song about freedom, eternity and
the hand of God. More than two dozen members of the
African-American church made the antiseptic newspaper conference
room ring with the old spiritual. The song felt like a fresh gust
from a rain-soaked breeze, or a news bulletin from a better place,
the kind of news that Sibley brought to her readers day after day.
Hard-nosed reporters and editors rocked back on their heels, and
Sibley beamed, her eyes shining with tears:
</P>
<P>
   My Lord calls me
</P>
<P>
   He calls me by the thunder
</P>
<P>
   The trumpet sounds within my soul
</P>
<P>
   I ain't got long to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   Steal away, steal away
</P>
<P>
   Steal away to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Steal away, steal away home
</P>
<P>
   I ain't got long to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. Tom Bennett contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   END TAKE TWO.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
