<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SIBLEY-APPRE-TAKE1-CO     08-15 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-APPRE-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CELESTINE SIBLEY: An appreciation
 &HT;    (EDS: IN TWO TAKES. Take one of 2. MOVING TO (a) General news
and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Celestine Sibley, the prodigious chronicler of a
half-century of Southern life, is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley captured the rhythm and flavor and language of the region
in more than 10,000 newspaper columns for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, countless news stories written on deadline,
and more than 20 books.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming known as a columnist, Sibley was a masterful
court, crime and political reporter, covering some of the area's
most lurid murder trials and the equally colorful events under the
gold dome of the Georgia Legislature. But she will be best
remembered for her column on the front of the Journal-Constitution
Features section, rich with folksy wit and universal truth.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998 she suffered heart trouble and underwent an
angioplasty. Four days later she doggedly returned to work and
reported the adventure in her typical low-key style: ``So one
night,'' she wrote, ``lacking anything more exciting to do, I had a
heart attack.'' In July 1999, when her doctor informed her that it
was unsafe for her to continue driving her car, she wrote: ``He
smiled gently and said something about it being a hard decision.
And I moved sneakily toward the window, wondering if one little
push would do it. One little lift of a rod, one little push and I'd
be a free woman again.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last few weeks, Sibley, ailing and on pain
medication, got in the car with family members at the wheel and
made a visit to the important places in her life. They drove to
Alford, Fla., where her mother, the redoubtable Muv, lived most of
her adult life. They also stopped at Holley Fla., where Sibley was
born, to pay her respects at her grandfather's grave. And she came
to rest at Dog Island, Fla., near Apalachicola, a largely
undeveloped island where for years she retreated in summers and
winters alone or with members of her extended clan at a cottage
built by her second husband, Jack Strong.
</P>
<P>
   Never willing to take herself too seriously, Sibley made for
good company at the breakfast table during her 55 years as a
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sibley herself, the columns were deceptive in their plain
attire. She dealt in the homely and homespun. She wrote about
washing and starching curtains, digging in the garden, enjoying
spring rain and summer vegetables. These topics she related without
artifice, but with an abiding love of language and a natural
raconteur's ability to spin a yarn.
</P>
<P>
   Her sharing of the small and large moments of her life at her
log cabin home, Sweet Apple, made for an intimate relationship with
her readers, who were forever mailing her packets of seeds,
cuttings from favorite plants, cakes and poems, books and music,
and letters of undying affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you'd go on a book signing with her it was excruciating,
because everybody had a scrapbook full of stuff that they knew she
wanted to see, and she did want to see it,'' said Atlanta mystery
writer Kathy Hogan Trocheck, a personal friend. ``And they'd all
have groceries they'd want to give her. Something about her made
people want to smoke a ham.''
</P>
<P>
   An older Atlanta reader will recall a Sibley of a different
sort, a cop shop reporter who reveled in a good juicy homicide. As
her fictional alter ego, Katharine Kincaid, the newswriting
protagonist of her first novel, ``The Malignant Heart,'' summed it
up, ``Murder is my favorite assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   She viewed the capital trial as the modern-day counterpart to
Shakespeare's theater, and she was skilled at sketching its cast of
characters. Covering the 1948 trial that would become the potboiler
``Murder in Coweta County,'' Sibley located the seemingly prescient
fortune-teller, Mayhayley Lancaster, who would lend those
proceedings their supernatural air.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was absolutely the best court reporter I ever saw,'' said
former Constitution editor Bill Shipp. ``She knew how to bring a
trial to life like nobody I've ever seen before or since.''
</P>
<P>
   She was also a workhorse, said Shipp. ``You'd send her on an
assignment, she'd give you 800 or 1,000 words on the trial, she'd
give you a sidebar on the principal lawyers, then she'd sit down
and write a column.''
</P>
<P>
   Said friend and fellow sage of Southern food John Egerton,
``That woman could write a column while I was trying to figure out
how to set the margins on my typewriter.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of her writing career, Sibley also pursued a more
exhausting job, single-handedly rearing and supporting three
children. She had unreliable help from her alcoholic first husband,
Jim Little, whom she loved dearly but who proved an unfit spouse.
He died at age 45.
</P>
<P>
   With financial help from Little often nonexistent, Sibley took
to freelancing true confession stories for pulpy magazines,
ghost-writing autobiographical tales (with titles such as ``I Sold
My Baby for $300'') about the ne'er-do-wells she met on the beat.
</P>
<P>
   Though such contributions embarrassed her full-time employer
(her editors at the Constitution, where she hired on in 1941,
eventually offered to raise her undersized salary as an inducement
to end her low-rent freelancing) Sibley refrained from exploiting
her subjects. Not even the young woman who sold her own baby was
treated poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley, as agreed, traveled to the girl's mountain home, and
read the story out loud to the girl and her wrinkled mother. She
needed their approval before she could market it to the penny
dreadfuls. While she read the somewhat purple prose, the girl began
to weep, and the mother threw her own apron over her head in shame.
Sibley soldiered on. When at last she finished, the older woman
heaved a great sigh and exclaimed, ``I do swear that's might near
the prettiest story I ever heard tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley was also adept at coaxing quotes from career politicians,
which she proved while covering the Legislature from 1958 until
1978. She helped push the legislators toward much humane
legislation, said former U.S. Rep. James Mackay of Decatur. ``She
was one of the key people that said the jailhouse is not where the
drunk can recover,'' he said. ``She is credited by the Legislature
for almost singlehandedly causing the Georgia Clinic to be created.
Because of the pain she's had in her own family, she is keen to
other people's pain.''
</P>
<P>
   While at the Capitol, Sibley was often sought for counsel by
legislators, who, in 1978, passed a resolution praising her for her
coverage and just this month announced that the press gallery in
the Capitol House chamber will be named in her honor. Her friend
Dorothy Nix, an executive with the Garden Club of Georgia, once
brought a battalion of ladies to the Capitol to lobby for a law to
control billboards. Her colleagues were unimpressed with the
state's political leaders, however. ``They just wanted to catch a
glimpse of Celestine Sibley,'' said Nix. ``To me, Celestine Sibley
is the first lady of Georgia no matter who's in the Governor's
Mansion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley was one of the newspaper's employees closest to Ralph
McGill, the late editor, publisher and Pulitzer Prize-winning
columnist of the Constitution. He doted on her. ``If there is a
queen of our news shop, it is Sister Sibley,'' he once wrote. ``She
can put words down in a manner to excite envy among the rest of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In later years, when McGill's desk was somehow shifted to the
Constitution's basement, Sibley rescued the rolltop and had it
placed in her office.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Broxson Colley was born May 23, 1914, in , Holley,
Fla., near Pensacola. Her father was Henry Colley, her mother
Evelyn Barber of Alford, Fla. Though their union was not a happy
one, Barber and Colley were never legally divorced. Evelyn Barber,
who would later become famous in her daughter's column as ``Muv,''
laughed off suggestions that she was committing bigamy when she
subsequently married Wesley Reeder Sibley, a lumberman in Creola,
Ala., 18 miles north of Mobile. Sibley (who was known as Pap or
Bob) adopted the 7-year-old Celestine as his own.
</P>
<P>
   The young girl grew up among Mobile County's fishermen,
shrimpers and oystermen whom she recalled as ``self-reliant,
independent, masters of the art of make-do.''
</P>
<P>
   But they were people of the Gulf; she was not. ``We were close
in map miles but eons away in time, temperament and mores from the
salt water and even the aristocratic civilization of old Mobile,''
she wrote. ``We were piney woods people who drew our living from
the woods instead of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   At countywide Murphy High in Mobile, Sibley became editor of the
school paper. The Mobile Press-Register called asking whether any
students wanted to work on weekends. She assigned herself, and at
15 began her newspaper career. Her first story was an interview
with a legislator who had introduced a bill to make illegal the
possession and sale of marijuana. She graduated from Murphy High in
1933, and later attended Spring Hill College in Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   She worked as a full-time reporter for the Press-Register in
1933-36, and for the nearby Pensacola News-Journal from 1936 to
1941.
</P>
<P>
   END TAKE 1
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
