<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8071 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN16-COX     08-15 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOM BAXTER'S COLUMN: Past Iowa straw polls led to straw hopes
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Any discussion of the winners and losers in
Saturday's much ballyhooed Iowa straw poll should begin with a
backward glance at some of those who polled well in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm tied Bob Dole in the 1995 contest and went
swiftly nowhere. In 1987, Pat Robertson soundly beat George Bush
the elder, inspiring hopes that were never realized.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Texas Gov. George W. Bush might not take much
consolation in his first-place finish Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's 31 percent showing, although it was the highest
percentage any candidate has ever received in the poll, couldn't
match the exaggerated expectations created by his prodigious
fund-raising performance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush was the big winner of the day. He spent less than
magazine publisher Steve Forbes, campaigned only a few days in
Iowa, didn't advertise on television and finished solidly at the
head of the pack. Second-guessers might wonder if he could have
invested a little more and finished off his rivals early, but that
would have been hard to do with the turnout at Ames _ nearly twice
that of four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters were an unobtrusive lot. Both inside and
outside the arena where the event was held, Forbes' supporters were
more in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes ``spent to win and came in second,'' Bush's spokesTexan,
Karen Hughes, said after the results were announced. For his money,
however, Forbes did well enough to claim success at the end of the
day and push on with his campaign. His strategic priority now is
likely to be winnowing down the field so this becomes a race
between him and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of the day, simply because so much of the smart
money expected her to fall short, was former Red Cross leader
Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether her third-place finish will be
enough to revive her lagging fund-raising effort, but she
demonstrated her potential to get younger women voters more
involved in the process. She seems much more likely now to go the
distance into next year's primaries.
</P>
<P>
   As Dole was expected to underachieve by many who had watched her
on the stump, Gary Bauer, a leading social conservative activist,
was viewed as the candidate who could pull off a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer did not finish third, as some thought he might, but he
accomplished what was most important to his campaign by finishing
ahead of his rival on the right, Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer had his best fund-raising week of the year leading into
the poll, and he also shows every indication of carrying on into
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan fell way short of his 1995 third-place finish, but he
runs the kind of survivalist campaign that will allow him to take a
setback. The big question is whether he'll reconsider his decision
to continue campaigning as a Republican or jump ship.
</P>
<P>
   About former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and former Vice
President Dan Quayle, who finished sixth and eighth, respectively,
there probably aren't any big questions left. The nominating
process for this election is big money and brutally fast, and it
appears to have left both these contenders behind at the starting
gate.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative talk radio host Alan Keyes and Sen. Orrin Hatch of
Utah didn't have big enough expectations to be much affected by
their showing, and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who at least has
established himself as the true nonconformist in this race, bagged
it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of big money, save a space in the winners column for
the Iowa GOP, which grossed more than $600,000 for this one-day
event, in addition to putting on quite a show. Now, on to the
Alabama straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
