<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Monday, Aug. 16 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please
contact Elizabeth Ferry at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   RALLY (Los Angeles) _ Federal, state and local government
officials joined religious leaders Sunday in a rally honoring the
more than 300 heroes who saved lives and provided comfort during
last week's bloody rampage at a Jewish community center and
shooting of a postal worker. Attorney General Janet Reno attended
the ``Unity Rally'' organized by leading Jewish organizations. By
Harrison Sheppard. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CROWD (Los Angeles) _ A look at some of the hundreds of people
who attended the rally. By Phillip Browne. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH (Los Angeles) _ Services were held Sunday at an
Episcopalian church that has formed a strong alliance with the
North San Fernando Valley Jewish Community Center. By Harrison
Sheppard. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   BAGELS (Los Angeles) _ The image of distraught parents waiting
to be reunited with their children at the North Valley Jewish
Community Center, where a gunman wounded five people Tuesday,
struck home for a Santa Clarita mother of a 4-year-old. So Noli
Wiesen, a publicist who operates a marketing business from her
home, got on the phone and began calling Valley businesses, such as
Western Bagel Too in Granada Hills and Brunswick Matador Bowl in
Northridge. By Sherry Joe Crosby. (Will move in the ``a'' national
and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES (Los Angeles) _ Horror continued to prove irresistible at
the nation's multiplexes as the second weekend of ``The Sixth
Sense'' easily led with an impressive $26.1 million amid a robust
weekend overall at the nation's box office, studio sources said
Sunday. The Disney release, originally set for October, has now
taken in an astounding $70 million in 10 days during what is
traditionally a period when moviegoing slacks off. By Dave McNary.
(Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
