<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS SHOWING WEAKNESS AT QUARTERBACK, BEHIND TESTAVERDE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On what promises to be an even more imaginative and explosive
offense than last year, the Jets may have a weak link: quarterback.
Then again, it may simply be a theoretical problem.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback? Vinny Testaverde looked as good against the Green
Bay Packers in Saturday night's preseason opener as he did in his
best performances of last year's Pro Bowl campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the question still remains _ who is his backup? Although
Testaverde has not missed a game because of injury since 1994, most
quarterbacks are not so lucky. In fact, each of the four teams that
competed in the conference championship games last season lost a
starting quarterback to injury at some point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Testaverde had nine consecutive completions (his
last pass was dropped) in leading the Jets to a field goal and
touchdown against the Packers before sitting down with the rest of
the first-string offense. He completed 11 of 13 passes for an
imposing 147 yards, including a 26-yard masterpiece to Eric Green
that the tight end caught with one hand in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ray Lucas took over at quarterback, and in nine drives
could put only two field goals on the board against mostly the
Packers' second team as Green Bay won, 27-16, at Lambeau Field.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Lucas sounded crushed, as if he knew he had
blown his chance as the club's No. 2 quarterback with his erratic
performance. He completed fewer than half his attempts (14 of 32)
for 143 yards. Predictably, he was the Jets' leading rusher with 42
yards on 5 carries. His rushing skills are outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Zolak plays Friday night against the Eagles,'' Lucas
said in assessing his status, ``and then Vinny will get most of the
work the final two games to get ready for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak is the former Patriots' backup who came to the Jets as a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets seemed to have ended last season with a competent
backup quarterback in Glenn Foley. He had started the season as the
first-string quarterback, but then got injured and had played
inconsistently and Testaverde wound up having what he describes as
``my magical season.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, though, reiterated Sunday why Foley no longer is a
Jet: ``I had to trade him _ I can't afford two guys at these
prices. All the teams are doing that.'' Thus, when Foley refused to
renegotiate the multimillion dollar contract he had signed as a
starter, he was traded to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Parcells always was worried about how fragile Foley
was physically, and in the second game of the season, Foley
severely bruised his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   By trading Foley, however, what the Jets may have lost in a
known backup they gained in other areas, in part by having the
money to acquire Green and several other high-priced free agents.
It has been a trade-off that, so far, has worked in the Jets'
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas did not have the luxury of a first-string line and
first-string receivers for most of his appearance, but neither will
Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem you have when you have so many young guys going in
late in the first half is that there's too many things that can go
wrong,'' Parcells said. ``It makes it more difficult to evaluate
the players as individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he will not make it easier for Zolak because, Parcells
said: ``I just can't do that. There are so many players and I have
to look at them. I don't have the luxury to blend these guys. I
can't afford not to play these guys as a group.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Lucas, Parcells said: ``I thought he was a little jumpy
in the pocket, but the protection wasn't good enough for him to
hold the way we want. I think there has to be more consistency
there. I don't really view this player at this position as an
experienced player, but I think he needs to show he has to be more
consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells also, however, cited good performances by four of his
draft picks: guard Randy Thomas, defensive tackle Jason Wiltz,
tackle Ryan Young and linebacker J.J. Syvrud.
</P>
<P>
   The coach was not that happy with his first-team defense, which
yielded a touchdown on the Packers' opening drive.
</P>
<P>
   But the quarterback search continues and it is between two
players, for now. Punter Tom Tupa, Parcells said, will not be
competing for the backup role. For all anyone knows, the backup
might end up being a player who isn't currently a Jet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
