<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS TURN BACK YANKS AS FANS LOOK FORWARD TO STRAWBERRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ricky Ledee heard voices Sunday at Yankee Stadium,
during the Yankees' 5-3 loss to Minnesota. Ledee tried ignoring the
voices, but they persisted, making an eerie sound familiar to Ledee
and just about every other New York baseball fan.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl, the voices called to Ledee, from the stands. Darryl.
</P>
<P>
   Slugger Darryl Strawberry is expected to join the Yankees soon _
maybe within 10 days, maybe two weeks, maybe after Sept. 1 _ and
create a dilemma for the manager Joe Torre, who has seen Ledee
slowly develop into a confident contributor in the last six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees didn't have enough contributions Sunday, all the way
around. They didn't have enough scoring chances against Minnesota's
Brad Radke, the right-hander who scattered nine hits over 7 2/3
innings. The Yankees didn't have enough efficiency from Hideki
Irabu, who had difficulty finishing off hitters with two strikes
and lost a decision for the first time since May 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins jumped ahead, 5-1, against Irabu _ five of their nine
hits came with two strikes _ and in the next three innings, the
Yankees threatened. Scott Brosius struck out with runners at second
and third and two out in the seventh, missing one of Radke's
changeups, and the Yankees didn't score in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did score a run in the next inning and had the
potential tying run at the plate in Chili Davis, who came into the
at-bat ranked first in the majors when hitting the first pitch,
with a .508 batting average. Eddie Guardado, the Minnesota
reliever, threw a first-pitch fastball, Davis blasted it, and the
56,180 fans who packed Yankee Stadium on a Beanie Baby day roared.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis' fly died on the warning track, in center field. Then,
in the ninth, the Yankees pieced together another run and had first
and second and two out, before Paul O'Neill hit into a game-ending
fielder's choice. The Yankees are 71-45, still far ahead of Toronto
and Boston in the American League East and seemingly destined for
the playoffs. ``I like the way we're playing right now,'' said
Torre, speaking generally.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' standing will provide Torre with a margin for error
as he integrates Strawberry into his roster before the postseason
begins. George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, has
demonstrated a personal interest in Strawberry's comeback, so the
question is not whether Strawberry will rejoin the Yankees; it is
when. ``George is driving this train,'' one member of the
organization said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday's game, Strawberry, suspended and then
reinstated following his no contest plea on possession of cocaine
and solicitation charges, is batting .263 with no home runs and
three RBIs in 11 games, numbers that are hardly inspiring. By all
accounts, however, he is swinging the bat well, and moving in the
outfield and bases far better than anyone expected.
</P>
<P>
   Word in the Yankees' organization is that there have been games
when Strawberry's intensity has waned _ particularly in a game
played in Toledo recently _ but Torre shrugged that off Sunday.
Strawberry wants to be in the big leagues, Torre said, and once
Strawberry rejoins the big leagues, he'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   And then Torre will figure out how to get Strawberry enough
playing time to keep his swing honed, and simultaneously, to
maintain Ledee's performance and confidence. Chili Davis is the
Yankees' full-time designated hitter _ although Jim Leyritz may
play against some lefties _ so Strawberry will get much of his
playing time in left field, probably at Ledee's expense.
</P>
<P>
   Including his single and two walks Sunday, Ledee is batting .364
since being called up June 26, including eight hits in 16 at-bats
(.500) with runners in scoring position. ``He's been playing well,
playing good defense, swinging the bat well,'' said Derek Jeter,
the Yankees' shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jorge Posada, the Yankees' catcher: ``He's getting some
playing time and that helps. He knows when there is a right-hander
on the mound, he's going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't necessarily be the case, of course, once Strawberry
arrives. Ledee will get a share of the playing time, and there
likely will be some games when Strawberry starts, gets two or three
or four plate appearances, before giving way to Ledee or Chad
Curtis in the late innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee knows this. He hears the voices. ``It doesn't concern
me,'' said Ledee. ``They love Darryl here, and we love him, too.
Darryl's talked to me about a lot of things, because he's had a lot
of scars, and I really appreciated it. I'm going to keep doing my
job. Whatever happens, it's not my decision. I can't help it. If it
happens, it happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
