 &HT;    BOOKS BY CELESTINE SIBLEY
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1958: ``The Malignant Heart'' (Doubleday). Sibley's literary
debut, a mystery featuring Kate Kincaid, a fictional reporter for
the equally fictional Atlanta Searchlight newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   1963: ``Peachtree Street USA: An Affectionate Portrait of
Atlanta'' (Doubleday).
</P>
<P>
   1964: ``Christmas in Georgia'' (Doubleday, reissued in 1985 and
1991 by Peachtree Publishers). Short stories that originally
appeared in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   1967: ``Dear Store: An Affectionate Portrait of Rich's''
(Doubleday, reissued in 1990 by Peachtree Publishers). A valentine
to the columnist's favorite store.
</P>
<P>
   1967: ``A Place Called Sweet Apple'' (Doubleday, reissued in
1973 and 1985 by Peachtree Publishers). An account of buying and
renovating her beloved pre-Civil War-era log cabin.
</P>
<P>
   1969: ``Especially at Christmas'' (Doubleday, reissued in 1985
by Peachtree Publishers). A yuletide offering featuring various
Atlanta characters.
</P>
<P>
   1970: ``Mothers Are Always Special'' (Doubleday, reissued in
1985 and 1994 by Peachtree Publishers).
</P>
<P>
   1972: ``The Sweet Apple Gardening Book'' (Doubleday, reissued in
1989 by Peachtree Publishers).
</P>
<P>
   1975: ``Day by Day With Celestine Sibley'' (Doubleday). A
calendar-like assortment of inspirational sayings.
</P>
<P>
   1976: ``Small Blessings'' (Doubleday). Written the summer her
mother died, a collection of anecdotes about the good people do.
</P>
<P>
   1978: ``Jincey'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster). An autobiographical novel
about her Alabama childhood.
</P>
<P>
   1980: ``The Magic Realm of Sally Middleton'' (Oxmoor House). She
wrote the text for a friend's book of paintings.
</P>
<P>
   1981: ``Children, My Children'' (Harper &AMP; Row). An
autobiographical novel based on the kidnapping of two of her
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   1982: ``Young 'Uns'' (Harper &AMP; Row). Collection of tales
featuring her children and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   1984: ``For All Seasons'' (Peachtree Publishers). Reflections on
the seasons of the year.
</P>
<P>
   1988: ``Turned Funny'' (Harper &AMP; Row). Her critically acclaimed
memoir, which traces the columnist's life from her childhood in the
Panhandle of Florida to her professional career in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1990: ``Tokens of Myself'' (Longstreet Press). A collection of
her newspaper columns.
</P>
<P>
   1991: ``Ah, Sweet Mystery: A Kate Mulcay Mystery''
(HarperCollins). The return of her sleuth reporter character from
`The Malignant Heart.'
</P>
<P>
   1992: ``Straight as an Arrow: A Kate Mulcay Mystery''
(HarperCollins).
</P>
<P>
   1993: ``Dire Happenings at Scratch Ankle: A Kate Mulcay
Mystery'' (HarperCollins).
</P>
<P>
   1994: ``Touch of the Shepherd: Reflections on the Life of Vernon
S. Broyles, Jr.'' (Bemis Publishing. Currently available at local
book stores). A biography of her old pastor, written at the behest
of the congregation of North Avenue Presbyterian Church, which she
had attended for years.
</P>
<P>
   1995: ``A Plague of Kinfolk: A Kate Mulcay Mystery''
(HarperCollins.)
</P>
<P>
   1997: ``The Celestine Sibley Sampler'' (Peachtree Publishers. A
collection of columns, tributes and highlights from her many books,
assembled by her granddaughter Sibley Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   1997: ``Atlanta's Half Century With Furman Bisher and Celestine
Sibley (Longstreet). Reprints of some of the best work by the
Constitution's longest running columnists.
</P>
<P>
   1997: ``Spider in the Sink: A Kate Mulcay Mystery''
(HarperCollins). Her final book.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SIBLEY-FIRST-COX     08-15 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-FIRST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CELESTINE SIBLEY'S FIRST COLUMN, JULY 24, 1944
 &HT;    EDITOR'S NOTE: Sibley's first column appeared in The Atlanta
Constitution on July 24, 1944. She would write more than 10,000.
Her last published column appeared 55 years later, almost to the
day.
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There you stand in the hall, backed up out of
traffic's way against the uncompromising contours of a radiator,
your eyes fixed on a swinging green door, your nose breathing in
the sweetish, sickening fumes of ether.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly there is a piercing scream back of the green door and
you clutch the sleeve of a nurse who is rustling by, and cry
accusingly: ``Why is he screaming? I thought it didn't hurt! I
thought they put him to sleep!''
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't time to talk, but her eyes above the white gauze mask
are sympathetic. ``He's all right,'' she says. ``They always cry
out when they are going to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   You subside against the radiator again and try to think of
mothers who have sons on battlefronts, torn and bleeding with maybe
no real hospital near and no white-coated doctors and nurses and
anesthetists to make things easier for them. You think maybe you're
thirsty and you walk to the water cooler and then back to the room.
Twenty-seven steps it is. Maybe if you take 'em slow, and smile,
and speak to people on the way, that'll use up another minute and
leave only about 17 or 18 _ unless there are complications ...
</P>
<P>
   The thought sends you scurrying back to your post against the
radiator. Complications. Your hands are cold and damp. Your shoes
squeak loudly when you move. A woman doctor passes, stethoscope
swinging from her neck, and smiles at you, imperturbably cheerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard, waiting,'' she says, and striving for a calm,
unconcerned expression, your eye lights on the comic book he left
in your safekeeping. A precious, new, unread comic book, presented
by a neighbor who pointed out that it was something new in comics,
all about Robin Hood and therefore wholesome and educational.
</P>
<P>
   You turn a few pages and there in blood-red and eerie, midnight
blue is a poor cringing creature begging: ``No, No! Not the
branding iron!'' You shudder, and turn on, and there's the intrepid
Robin Hood crouched on his hands and knees with these words coming
balloonlike out of his mouth: ``But you were not invited to buffet
me. I'll break you in twain.''
</P>
<P>
   That'll take some translating into modern Superman-ese, you
fear, and you put the comic book on the radiator and return your
attention to the swinging green door. It creaked a second ago.
Maybe they're coming out. You study the door fixedly for
interminable seconds, but it was a false alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall in the sun parlor a man is saying, ``Which way is
town from here? You mean that was all of town we saw last night
coming here? Why, I drove through it without any trouble at all.
Atlanta must not be much bigger than Albany.''
</P>
<P>
   You smile at the note of pleased civic pride and go gulp down
some water. Twenty-seven steps there and back ... twenty or thirty
minutes it'd take, they said. Twenty or 30 minutes .. No, No! Not
the branding iron! Complications .. How big is Albany? Not a
serious operation .. 17, 16, 15 steps.
</P>
<P>
   This time the door is opening and you take the remaining steps
in two bounds. Yes, they are bringing him out _ a colored attendant
and a white gowned nurse lugging his limp, 5-year-old body between
them. Behind them you get a glimpse of the forest of sinister
gleaming instruments you sent your child into, alone and
unprotected. A nurse is wheeling a scary-looking machine away and
saying something over her shoulder to another nurse. You strain to
hear the words and as the door swings shut, you catch them: ``Two
pairs of nylons, my dear.''
</P>
<P>
   You scurry after your child, but are met at the door with polite
but firm resistance. He's all right _ but you'd better stay out of
the room a while. Go sit in the sun parlor. I'll call you.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the book your red-headed neighbor around the corner
brought you as you left for the hospital and you disconsolately
pick it up. Ben Ames Williams' new ``Leave Her to Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a bad woman,'' the donor remarked with gentle
malice. ``It ought to cheer you up.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it doesn't look cheerful, but you tackle it manfully until
after the first couple of paragraphs you find your gaze keeps
wandering from the printed page and off down the hall. You put the
book aside and study a woman in a gray silk dress who is leaning
against the radiator down there across from the operating room. She
keeps staring at the door and then you realize she is the woman who
came up on the elevator with you. Had a little boy by the hand _
cute but not as husky looking as yours. You pick up the book and
start walking toward her, balancing yourself carefully to keep your
shoes from squeaking.
</P>
<P>
   You smile cheerfully and say heartily: ``Hard waiting, isn't
it?''
</P>
<P>
   She gives you a distracted look and nods dumbly. You search your
mind for more comforting conversation, but just then the door to
your child's room opens and the nurse is beckoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awake and asking for his mommy,'' she says. ``And we
haven't been sick a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Who hasn't been sick, you feel like retorting grimly, as you
gallop down the hall, but you remember to smile at that poor,
harassed creature back there by the radiator and to say gaily over
the squeak of your shoes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry! It's a very simple operation. They have thousands
of them every summer _ in fact, July is really Tonsillectomy Time
in Georgia!''
</P>
<P>
   You don't know if she appreciated it or not, but you figure that
was a pretty neat alliteration you flung at that woman. All the
same, you decide as you observe our child's weak smile and ease
your shoes off under his bed, you can both be glad you were just
waiting for your son to have tonsils out. Think how much worse
it'll be 15 or 20 years from now when your daughters have babies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
