<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Monday, Augut
16, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES (Seattle) _ Kathleen Kuechenmeister was only 8 years
old when she learned she had diabetes. Now, nearly four decades
later, diabetes is slowly eroding her health. It's destroyed her
kidneys, clouded her eyesight, and damaged nerves throughout her
extremities, making it difficult to walk. But Kuechenmeister, and
266,000 others like her in Washington, have new hope for a cure for
Type 1 diabetes, a debilitating, chronic illness that kills one
American every three minutes. This fall, a consortium of Seattle
institutions plans to resurrect an old idea _ transplanting islet
cells from a donor pancreas into diabetic patients to free them
from a lifetime of insulin injections.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VFW-ANNIVERSARY (REDMOND, Wash.) _ As 30,000 members of the
Veterans of Foreign Wars gather in Kansas City, Mo., this week to
celebrate the 100th anniversary of America's oldest national
veterans organization, local VFW members continue to work out of
the spotlight in a variety of grassroots programs to help other
veterans and citizens.
</P>
<P>
   By Ed Offley. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER-SUES (Seattle) _ The last time Michael McGuffey of
Anacortes, Wash., assaulted his wife Shelley, he held a loaded gun
to her head and cocked it. She knew the next time she'd be dead,
and went to police to try to press charges. Police said they'd
refer the case to prosecutors the next day. They never did. Weeks
later, McGuffey approached Shelley in her car as she drove up to
work, and shot her three times. An appeals court decision last week
allows Shelley's mother to sue the city of Anacortes, Wash., for
her daughter's death, overturning a lower court decision that said
the police weren't required to refer the charges.
</P>
<P>
   By Rebekah Denn. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE (Seattle) _ Ten years since Washington state lawmakers
made it illegal to drive without car insurance, both consumer
advocates and insurance company executives say the law has done
nothing to reduce the number of uninsured drivers on the roads.
WITH SIDEBAR SLUGGED INSURANCE-MOTHER.
