<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALUM-MERGER-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REYNOLDS METALS REJECTS ALCOA'S $5.8 BILLION BID AS INADEQUATE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a special meeting Sunday, the board of the Reynolds Metals
Co. said a $5.8 billion half-cash, half-stock takeover offer by
Alcoa Inc. was inadequate and that Reynolds should explore all
alternatives, including putting itself up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was the first time that Reynolds, which has been
under pressure from shareholder groups to sell itself, had said it
would consider that move.
</P>
<P>
   The statement did not mention a letter the company, based in
Richmond, received Thursday from McCook Metals, which is owned by
the Chicago investment firm Michigan Avenue Partners, saying that
it wanted to buy the company.
</P>
<P>
   But Reynolds would have had a hard time responding to that
letter because McCook, which is led by Michael W. Lynch, who is
also head of Michigan Avenue, did not specify a price. It said only
that McCook would pay more than Alcoa, which has bid $65 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view this as an astute move by the board to remain
independent of Alcoa,'' Lynch said in a telephone interview Sunday,
though he did not clarify McCook's sources of financing. But he
said McCook had financing in place in the event of a successful
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   It was also unclear how McCook would run Reynolds should the
company come up with a winning bid. Despite investors' objections,
the current Reynolds management is said to want to remain in place.
A person close to McCook, however, said the company was more likely
to offer those managers big severance packages instead of retaining
them.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Alcoa, which is based in Pittsburgh, said that
there was nothing in the Reynolds statement ``that surprises me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for Reynolds, which is being advised by Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co., to avoid putting itself up for sale. Shareholders
unhappy with management met in New York last month to discuss their
dissatisfaction with the company. They complained that Jeremiah
Sheehan, the Reynolds chairman and chief executive, was not
actively seeking a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   McCook has sought to become a significant presence in aluminum
since it bought a fabricating plant in McCook, Ill., in 1997.
Earlier this year, it acquired an aluminum rolling mill in
Scottsboro, Ala., but lost out in the bidding for some smelting
operations of the Columbia Falls Aluminum Co. in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Grubman, a partner in Highfields Capital Management,
which owns 4.3 million shares, or 6.7 percent, of Reynolds, said
that if the Reynolds board wanted to sell the company, it should
name a special committee to handle an auction.
</P>
<P>
   As an investor, Grubman said, he was still somewhat skeptical of
management's intentions because in March the company rejected an
earlier bid from Alcoa without disclosing it. ``A special committee
such as that would have one real task: to sell the company,''
Grubman said.
</P>
<P>
   There was some chance a third bidder might surface. There have
been rumors that Rechiney SA of France, Alusuisse Lonza Group AG of
Switzerland and Alcan Aluminium of Canada, which are in a three-way
merger, might make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, shares of Reynolds rose $3, to $69.375, while those
of Alcoa fell $1.25, to $66.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
