<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GATTI-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATTI AND JOHNSTON SAVOR THEIR VICTORIES, PAINFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arturo Gatti made a successful comeback and Stevie Johnston
retained his World Boxing Council lightweight title at the Foxwoods
Resort Casino in Connecticut on Saturday night. Both accomplished
their goals, but it cost them.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti was too distraught to enjoy his victory _ a first-round
technical knockout of Reyes Munoz _ because Munoz (21-4) was taken
from the ring on a stretcher and spent the night in a Norwich
hospital with a concussion. Gatti (30-4) did not come out of his
dressing room for the post-fight news conference at the casino,
which is in Mashantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston (28-1) scored a unanimous 12-round decision over Angel
Manfredy but wound up in the hospital as well, having a cut over
his eye stitched up and undergoing head X-rays, which showed no
broken bones. Manfredy (28-4-1) also went to the hospital, to have
X-rays of his hand. They were negative, but his ego took a
bruising, as he had predicted he would walk away with Johnston's
title.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti's previous three fights _ all losses _ had been bloody
battles. Manfredy stopped him on cuts in the seventh round two
years ago and Gatti lost two decisions in toe-to-toe skirmishes
with Ivan Robinson last year. The Munoz fight was to be a respite
from the ring rigors Gatti had been encountering.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz, who has spent his days making concrete barriers in an
Erie, Pa., factory and his nights training for bouts, seemed to
have a credible record. But it didn't take long to discover he was
completely overmatched against Gatti, who was once the junior
lightweight champion of the International Boxing Federation and was
moving up two weight classes to junior welterweight.
</P>
<P>
   Lou DiBella, HBO/TVKO's senior vice president for programming,
agreed to the bout for HBO's ``Boxing After Dark'' series. ``Did
the kid have a shot against Gatti?'' DiBella asked. ``No. But you
couldn't tell that from looking at the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first round, Gatti caught Munoz with a right to the
back of his head after Munoz tried to duck a punch. As Munoz fell
backward, Gatti caught him near the temple with a left hand. Munoz
fell to the canvas, but wobbled to his feet. His eyes were rolling
as Referee Ed Cotton waved off the fight. Munoz staggered across
the ring to his corner and was placed on his stool. A few seconds
later, Dr. Anthony Alessi, the ringside neurologist, called for a
stretcher. Munoz's mother and wife, also at ringside, wept as he
was removed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Schwartz, the chief ringside physician, said Munoz
was alert and responsive when taken from the ring. A paramedic said
that on the ride to the hospital, Munoz nearly lost consciousness.
He was listed in stable condition at the hospital and given a CAT
scan that was normal. Arthur Henick, a spokesman for Foxwoods, said
Sunday that Munoz's condition had been upgraded to good and that he
was expected to be released from the hospital later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston put on a masterly display of boxing against Manfredy,
who had moved up from junior lightweight (130 pounds) to
lightweight (135 pounds) to challenge for another world title.
Johnston and Manfredy were more evenly matched than Gatti and
Munoz, but Johnston proved that he was slightly quicker by beating
Manfredy to the punch more often. Johnston's left-handed style also
troubled Manfredy. He never seemed to figure it out and it didn't
work in the best interest of his style, which is to attack the
body.
</P>
<P>
   Although he lost, Manfredy, 24, didn't lose much standing in
boxing. He remains one of the top lightweight contenders after
losses to two of the best pound-for-pound fighters in the sport,
Johnston and Floyd Mayweather Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of good fights for him,'' DiBella said.
``You fight a fighter the level of Johnston and lose, it doesn't
end your career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
