<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-S-NYT     08-15 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-S-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE, HIDING IN PLAIN SIGHT, ELUDED INTERNATIONAL DRAGNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (A longer version of this story will move by 9 p.m. ET.) 
(rk) 
(The following article is based on reporting by Katherine E.
Finkelstein, Joseph Kahn and John Tagliabue and was written by
Kahn.) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last three months, Martin R. Frankel, a sometimes clumsy
fugitive who fled the United States with cases of computers and an
entourage of traveling companions, has managed to evade an
international manhunt by some of the world's most sophisticated law
enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, who federal investigators suspect of stealing as much
as $350 million from U.S. insurance companies, spent the first
weeks of summer hiding in plain sight in Rome, strolling along the
Villa Borghese park on brilliant afternoons and sipping espresso in
open-air cafes.
</P>
<P>
   His was not a low-profile exile. According to associates and one
of the women who was with him, he risked exposure by repeatedly
phoning friends in the United States and by relying for help on
people known to have had associations with him in the past. Six
weeks after arriving in Rome, he arranged for another young female
friend to fly from America to join him.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 177-nation Interpol alert, Frankel has lived openly in
Italy and has visited Spain and possibly France, juggling aliases
and bank accounts faster than courts can seize his money.
</P>
<P>
   He is believed to have left Rome in early July, and American
authorities acknowledge that the trail has gone cold. For now, the
financier's hastily arranged but oddly successful flight appears to
be an instance in which the cooperation among the world's national
police forces is more impressive in theory than it is in practice.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the American pursuit of Frankel complained that
European authorities have not helped matters. In Italy, the FBI,
which at one time in early July felt it had a fix on Frankel's
location, waited days to get an arrest warrant issued by local
magistrates. Frankel had moved on. Italian law enforcement
officials declined to comment on the Frankel case.
</P>
<P>
   But while he has kept a step ahead of police, Frankel seems to
have found life on the lam a source of constant complaints. Mona
Kim, an American confidante of Frankel who traveled with him to
Italy, and others who followed his trail, relate a tale of a
spoiled, fearful man with no evident talent for international
intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   The reedy, bespectacled 44-year-old, who often secluded himself
in his Greenwich, Conn., home, spoke no Italian, and could not call
a taxi on his own. A notoriously fussy eater, he told traveling
companions he could not abide pasta and sent them around Rome for
Chinese take-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was terrified that everybody was going to hurt him,'' Ms.
Kim said. ``He needed a lot of comforting and nurturing. He really
just hated the place so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Prone to pitiful mistakes, worthy of ``The Pink Panther's''
Inspector Clouseau, Frankel relied more on good luck than careful
planning to keep him out of trouble. On at least one occasion, he
stumbled into a situation that might have led to his arrest but
bluffed his way to safety. He also almost fell into a trap set by a
British tabloid which may have come close to capturing Frankel on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   National police forces have historically had a difficult time
collaborating on international cases that involve complex financial
dealings. But Frankel's success in avoiding capture in Italy, a
nation with which the United States has an extradition treaty and a
history of cooperation on drug and Mafia cases, is noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities still hope that Frankel might use up his money, make
more mistakes, even turn himself in. But it is also possible that
he will join a long list of fugitive financiers who have
embarrassed the police with their maneuvers abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Vesco, accused of looting $225 million from an investment
fund in 1973, escaped an indictment in the United States for years
before running into new troubles in Cuba. Marc Rich, wanted in the
United States for evading nearly $50 million in taxes, lives openly
in Switzerland, where tax crimes are not grounds for extradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
