<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SIBLEY-DRIVE-COX     08-15 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-DRIVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CELESTINE SIBLEY'S FINAL COLUMN: UNPUBLISHED
 &HT;    EDITOR'S NOTE: This is the last column Sibley wrote. It is
typically optimistic and feisty, and seemed somehow inappropriate
to run last month when word came that her health was rapidly
declining.
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One thing about being deprived of the right to drive
yourself wherever you want to go in your own car is that the
sympathy of the nation is with you. Friends have called me from
faraway Chattanooga, Memphis and that lovely spot Louisville. They
know what terrible thing is happening to you and they sympathize.
It's not as if your house burned down or your teenage granddaughter
ran off with a gangster. It's not even as if the little children in
the family discovered head lice in their bonny locks or your trusty
watchdog started biting the neighbors. But it's bad.
</P>
<P>
   A person should have her own car. She should drive whenever or
wherever she pleases. And no one should tell her nay. But there are
naysayers all over the place and they will come and sit by your
bedside and say things like, ``'Tine, you wouldn't want to run over
a child, now would you?'' Have I ever run over a child? Of course
not.
</P>
<P>
   The annoying thing is that you keep yearning for the old days
when you and your car were inseparable buddies. The first car I
ever had was a lovesome thing that shimmied when we drove it down
Dauphin Street in Mobile. My buddies and I would pile in it and set
out for a little adventure and we'd get about even with Zoghby's
merchandise and it would start shimmying like some intoxicated
dancer. We would all pile out, take hold of fenders and doors and
shake the chassis like our lives depended on it. It invariably
brought the tin lizzie out of whatever held it in clutch and we
would proceed with dignity toward the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was early in my driving experience. I started at
age 14 _ no driver's license in those days _ and I would go until I
got scared of the heavy Mobile traffic or my friends got scared and
ordered me to pull over and park. Heavy Mobile traffic in those
days amounted to about a car or two moving lazily through the
oak-shaded streets at the rate of one every ten minutes.
</P>
<P>
   We knew people who had fancier, faster cars and zipped out
Government Street at high speed. For ourselves we edged over to the
curb on Springhill Avenue and parked by the big St. Joseph's
church, ate our lunch and spent our nickle for a Milky Way and then
looked for something exciting to do. Looking back I am indebted to
that little old car for some of the richest experiences of my life.
</P>
<P>
   If it hadn't been for having wheels of my own and the right to
drive them I never would have spent the day in a Dauphin Street
bawdy house, courtesy of my friend whose aunt ran the
establishment. I don't exactly recommend it as wholesome high
school recreation but still it was interesting. We became friends
with a couple of ``the girls,'' rather attractive young women who
taught us how to pluck our eyebrows and lent us movie magazines.
And after they had received a gentleman caller they ordered up
barbecue for everybody . On the whole, an interesting day.
</P>
<P>
   But the best days my little car provided were at Bates Field,
Mobile's airport. You could park at the edge of the muddy, unpaved
field and watch those glamorous, barn-storming birdmen all day
long. Toward the end of the day, feeling sorry for us penniless
aviation fans, they sometimes offered us free rides over Mobile
bay.
</P>
<P>
   Who else but the owner and driver of a shimmying Ford had it so
lucky? You see, you've just about got to have a car and the right
to drive it.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, my father felt the same about wheels for the kid. I
drove to town to high school and once I hit a pine tree, doing
something serious to the steering gear. He and our mechanic, Percy,
drove a mule wagon over to Creola and hauled my car home, working
on it all night so I could drive it to town the next day. Some
families understand about the great spiritual bond that exists
between people and cars. Some don't. But I think there must be ways
of learning them.
</P>
<P>
   If I can hold out against family and doctors and other benighted
souls like that I 'll check in with you later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
