<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DALAI-LAMA-ART-NYT     08-15 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DALAI-LAMA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
40,000 IN CENTRAL PARK HEAR WORDS OF LOVE FROM THE DALAI LAMA 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(ms) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some called themselves spiritual amateurs, confessing
that their knowledge of his teachings was not particularly deep.
Others were devotees, steeped in the practices of Tibetan Buddhism
and, in some cases, sharing the Dalai Lama's exile from his home
country.
</P>
<P>
   Worshipful or merely curious or somewhere in between, they
gathered by the tens of thousands in Central Park's East Meadow
Sunday for the simplest of reasons: to hear the spiritual leader of
Tibet give a free public lecture on the basics of leading a life of
kindness and happiness.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, which the police estimated at 40,000, was as diverse
as the city itself. But interviews with some of the attendees
suggested a common search.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some really rough times the past few years,'' Diana
Popescu, a 31-year-old stylist, said. ``I needed to hear what he
had to say about altruism, compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Chien, 20, said had come Sunday hoping that she would
find guidance from the Dalai Lama about her future. She wants to go
into finance, she said, ``but spiritually I'm not sure that will
help people.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said that she is Chinese, and had learned about China's
treatment of Tibet only when she came to live in the United States
nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wish I could do something for Tibet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thupten Dadak was one of many Tibetans in the crowd, with many
of the women in colorful traditional dress. Dadak had flown in from
Minnesota, where he sells collectible dolls, to be rejuvenated and
refocused in the presence of his revered spiritual leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to purify my negativities,'' he said. By hearing the
teaching, again, ``I will try my best again to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   After being introduced by the actor Richard Gere, the Dalai Lama
spoke for well over an hour, his image broadcast on a large screen
for those unable to see the stage.
</P>
<P>
   He focused on how to train the mind to achieve inner peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life, when I look back, has not been easy,'' he said,
referring to his years in exile and China's repression of Tibet.
``One thing I learned,'' he said, ``was that compassion, a sense of
caring, thinking about other's welfare, that sort of mental
attitude brings me inner peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as he practiced his mental transformation, he said, every
human being has equal potential to do so _ maybe more. And then he
took the crowd through eight prayers to train the mind. ``I have
nothing to offer you, miracle things _ nothing,'' he said, by way
of saying it would not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed a few central themes, lacing them with jokes and
personal anecdotes: Problems would not be solved by material
things. Anger is destructive. The way to inner peace is
nonviolence, which he said was not just the absence of violence,
but ``the manifestation of compassion.'' But, he said, nonviolence
does not mean that ``we remain indifferent about problems _ we must
fully engage.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed the increasing interconnectedness of all human
beings in a global world, so that ``the destruction of your
neighbor is actually the destruction of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about the great wealth in America, and the great
poverty, and said that the capitalist system should be used to make
money _ and the socialist system to help the poor benefit from the
profits.
</P>
<P>
   He encouraged society to embrace those _ whether criminals or
persons with AIDS _ that it had cast out.
</P>
<P>
   He said inner spiritual development was not necessarily linked
to religious faith and he encouraged the crowd to weave the
practice into their own religious traditions. Mark Nason, a
40-year-old engineering manager, was doing just that: he had just
come from Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral. The Dalai Lama, he said,
is ``closest thing to Gandhi here on earth,'' and so it seemed
perfectly natural for a practicing Irish Catholic to trek uptown to
see perhaps the world's most famous Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real New York experience,'' Nason said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama occasionally used a translator _ ``As I am
getting older, my English is also getting older,'' he said. Still,
some in the audience said they could not understand everything he
said. Others, at the back of the crowd, said they could not hear
him clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Dorota Wnuk, 44, an interior designer from Manhattan, complained
that his talk was geared too much to those who know too little. ``I
wasn't very happy with the speech,'' she said. ``I would expect
less introductory matter, something more in depth.''
</P>
<P>
   But more people at the park seemed to take away something of
what they had come in search of, and they praised the Dalai Lama
for being down-to-earth, for not elevating himself above those he
addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Saltzman, 50, a computer-system designer, said she did not
hear everything he had to say; she was watching two children. But,
she said, ``It made me think about not getting so caught up in
who's right and who's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   If, she added, ``I can remember that by tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
