<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8098 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CLINTONS-HOUSEHUNTING     08-15 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-HOUSEHUNTING-R-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST FAMILY GOES HOUSE-HUNTING, AND MEETS SOME PROSPECTIVE
NEIGHBORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Refiling to correct spelling of Mike in byline. No other
change.)   (ART ADV: A photo of one of the houses the Clintons visited and a
photo of the Clintons in a crowd are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ President Clinton, his wife, his daughter
and his mother-in-law piled into the family Air Force C-20 Sunday
morning and went house-hunting in Westchester County, where they
made five stops and paused to schmooze with some of their
prospective neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton prepares to leave public life and Hillary Rodham
Clinton gears up for an effort to join it, the family swept through
the wealthy New York City suburbs with about as much casualness as
one can muster when accompanied by a black sedan, two sport-utility
vehicles, three police cruisers and four mini-vans.
</P>
<P>
   They even stopped for (most) stop signs.
</P>
<P>
   Two aides trundled off the plane with heavy coolers, apparently
packed to ensure that the Clintons could concentrate on the task at
hand instead of having to search for a drive-through. And they were
pretty diligent: The first family had planned to stay for less than
four hours, but wound up riding around for more than six.
</P>
<P>
   They announced no decision. Aides have said the president and
Mrs. Clinton definitely plan to move to Westchester, although they
may rent instead of buying. The couple were accompanied by Chelsea
and Mrs. Clinton's mother, Dorothy Rodham, for a trip that was
labeled ``private time'' by the White House, but which was taken at
government expense.
</P>
<P>
   Before the White House, the Clintons had been living in the
Governor's Mansion in Arkansas, and have no home to return to when
he leaves office in 2001. And if Mrs. Clinton is to run for senate
next year, she must establish a residence in New York by election
day.
</P>
<P>
   At one stop, according to witnesses, Clinton wandered out the
kitchen door to kibbitz with friends of the homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Manhattan or the Hamptons, where such an exercise
might be greeted with pointed indifference, crowds waited for hours
outside two of the houses, and several curious people made U-turns
to see what the commotion was about. While many people complained
about the intrusion, they still stood and gawked.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest throng gathered outside a four-story house that is
swathed in pale-pink stucco and shaded by a weeping-willow tree,
with a marble foyer and a pool out back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill's in there checking the kitchen, maybe flushing a toilet,
looking for leaks,'' said Steven M. Green, 55, a hand surgeon who
lives a block away.
</P>
<P>
   A baby shower across the street broke up as the revelers spilled
outside, where they were greeted by Secret Service agents wielding
magnetic wands. The honoree, Suzanne Stauffer, 35, said gamely,
``This was supposed to be a surprise shower, and I'm sure
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The excursion took the Clintons down winding roads loaded with
country clubs and tree-shrouded estates with fountains in front.
Even though the houses were mostly seven-figure offerings on
private roads or behind iron gates, several homeowners said they
believed the first family would improve property values if they
moved in.
</P>
<P>
   The first family finished the day in Edgemont, at a $1.7 million
hilltop house on a corkscrew of a major street known to locals as
``Suicide Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   A local resident, Jon Cramer, 44, said he doubted that Mrs.
Clinton would prevail if she decides to run for the Senate, where
she most likely would face New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she'll move in, lose the election, move out and leave
the imprimatur on the neighborhood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Mitchell, who lives two blocks from the Edgemont house,
was one of many who said they believed the hoopla would die down in
a hurry. ``We have a number of celebrities around here _ I'm
constantly bumping into David Hartman,'' she said. ``After a
fashion, it would become everyday.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Plenty of people fretted about the traffic, but Anna Dekker, 47,
said, ``I don't think I'm going to run into them in C-Town,''
referring to a local grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Glassman, 27, a computer consultant who lives near the
Edgemont house and was wearing a T-shirt from the Black Dog on
Martha's Vineyard _ where the Clintons have vacationed _ said he
saw political overtones to the search. ``They want to look like
they're doing what the average Joe would do,'' he said. ``It is
kind of cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The first stop was in the village of Rye Brook, where the
Clintons disappeared down a long drive at a house labeled
``Brokenwood.'' A house with a swing set is next door, modest
split-levels across the street. A woman in a black Mercedes station
wagon rolled down her window and asked what was up. When reporters
and aides hesitated briefly, she said with irritation, ``I live
right here. What's going on?'' No one said a word, but suddenly a
light dawned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me,'' she said, looking stricken. ``President
Clinton! Come on! Oh, come on.'' She zoomed away.
</P>
<P>
   Next up was Pound Ridge, which was remote enough to make
cellular-phone use problematic for the Clintons' entourage. Their
third stop was at a home in Mamaroneck, but reporters were
prevented from seeing the house.
</P>
<P>
   After that, they headed for New Rochelle. William O'Shaughnessy,
a local broadcast executive, said the interior of the house they
saw is heavy on velvet and velour. ``In Arkansas, this is a
mansion,'' he said. ``Here, it's a substantial manor house.''
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Myrna Root, who has been inside many times,
described the architectural style as ``Mediterranean, with a hint
of Tudor.''
</P>
<P>
   An owner of the house, Vic Vuksanaj, said the Clintons ``liked
everything they saw. They haven't decided anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the traffic jam, Phil Papa, 33, said, ``This is a
reality check about what would happen if you had a former president
in your neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   But the objections seemed to melt when, in their only contact
with the public Sunday, the president and Mrs. Clinton came outside
and signed autographs for neighbors, who had been corralled behind
a candy-striped rope. Clinton wore a yellow Oxford shirt, a blue
blazer, brown slacks and brown shoes, while Mrs. Clinton had on a
dark suit. Mrs. Clinton accepted a kiss from a man in the crowd who
said she would be a great senator.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea Clinton had ducked into the silver Suburban with five
antennas that was ferrying the family. The crowd cheered for her
and, as if answering a curtain call, she emerged and grinned as she
shook hands. Clinton patted his daughter on the back, and rubbed
his wife's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Burrell, 38, said she would love to have Mrs. Clinton as
a neighbor. ``She seems very normal,'' Ms. Burrell said as the
motorcade fired its engines. ``Very normal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
