<SLUG> BC-REGIS-QA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enough about Kathie Lee . . . Regis looks like a million bucks
 &HT;    TV PREVIEW
 &HT;    ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''
 &HT;    Starts at 8:30 tonight on ABC. Airs every night, except Aug. 23,
for two weeks ending Aug. 29. To be a contestant, call
1-900-933-9391.
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regis Philbin, considered by many the better half of ABC's
popular morning shmoozefest ``Live With Regis and Kathie Lee,'' is
confident that Americans will watch his new, two-week prime-time
game show for one simple reason: They love money.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the hit British show with the same name, ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire?'' has a classic format: Reasonably smart people
answer multiple choice questions on different topics. The more
questions they answer correctly, the more money they make, leading
up to the $1 million jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of twists: Contestants can consult the studio
audience or make a phone call to a friend if they get stuck on a
question.
</P>
<P>
   We spoke to Philbin about the show ... and a few other things:
</P>
<P>
   Q.Why are you doing this show now?
</P>
<P>
   A: For a long time people have been approaching me about
reviving old shows like ``What's My Line,'' but I didn't want to do
an old show. Then along comes this thing with high technology and a
million-dollar payoff, and it was something new.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Will this be better than dealing with Kathie Lee every
morning?
</P>
<P>
   A: This will be a little easier than dealing with Kathie Lee,
because she's so unpredictable. I'll miss doing the ad libs with
her, though.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The British have a reputation for bad teeth. What about your
contestants?
</P>
<P>
   A: noticed that too when I went over there to see the show. I
don't know. ... whoever comes in the door can sit there and go for
the million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The British set looks like the Starship Enterprise. Will you
have the same set?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, we will. But I feel like I'm blasting off to the moon on
that set. I don't know if we need all those lights and stuff. It's
futuristic as hell, but you get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you just doing this for the cash?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wish I owned a piece of the show, but I'm just a working
stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How would you do if you were a contestant?
</P>
<P>
   A: You don't have to be a physics professor to score big on this
show. The British contestants were just plain folks, and some of
them came in their overalls. But I took the preliminary test and I
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is doing this show just a subtle way of telling Kathie Lee
``it's over''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Enough with Kathie Lee already! (Laughing.) We're going to be
on for at least two more years. I consider myself a lucky guy,
because no matter what happens with this new show, I'll still be
able to go on every morning and talk about whatever I want to for
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You look pretty fit. How much do you bench?
</P>
<P>
   A: Thank you. I do about 180 pounds about 10 times, and I weigh
158 pounds. Pretty good, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
