<HEADER>
A8104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-TRIP-LYLE-NYT     08-15 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TRIP-LYLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL TO THE BULLPEN BRINGS A MANAGER: LYLE ENJOYS RETURN TO
BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 16 seasons in the major leagues, three World Series
championships and the Cy Young Award, the former Yankee pitcher
Sparky Lyle thought he had accomplished about everything in
professional baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But one aspect of the game had eluded him since he retired after
the 1982 season with 238 saves; Lyle had never managed a team at
any level. Although he was not actively pursuing a managerial
position, Lyle, 54, wanted to keep his options open and was willing
to listen if a good opportunity presented itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Atlantic League, an independent baseball
alliance, was formed in 1997. One of the six teams was based in
Somerset County, N.J., reasonably close to Lyle's home in Dubois,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Kalafer, a co-owner of the Somerset franchise, was
looking for a manager and asked several people in baseball for
references. One of the people Kalafer approached was the
Philadelphia Phillies' third base coach, John Vukovich, a good
friend of Lyle's.
</P>
<P>
   ``John gave him my name,'' Lyle said. Kalafer got in touch with
Lyle, they talked and Kalafer offered him the job. ``I thought it
was a great opportunity,'' Lyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Lyle had not participated in any form of organized
baseball since 1982 (he said he spent most of his time playing
golf), he had to brush up on game strategy and the rule book.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle knew that the players he was managing were either trying to
get back to the major leagues after several unproductive seasons,
had suffered a serious injury and were working their way back, or
simply did not possess the talent to reach the next level.
</P>
<P>
   During the Atlantic League's inaugural season in 1998, the
Patriots went 19-31 in the first half and 21-29 in the second half
and finished a combined 40-60, 24 games behind the team with the
best overall record, Bridgeport. That season was a learning
experience both for the players and for Lyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easier to manage at this level than at Class A because
these guys have experience,'' Lyle said. ``For example, in the low
minors you would have to deal with young kids coming directly from
high school and college. They would first have to be acclimated to
the rigors of professional baseball. These guys already have
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Somerset's players are pitchers Dwayne Henry, who has a
14-15 record in 11 major league seasons, mostly with Texas; John
Briscoe, who appeared in 100 games and compiled a 5-5 record and
two saves for the Oakland Athletics over six seasons, and Ricardo
Jordan, who went 1-2 with the Mets in 1997 and is 5-4 over all in
the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Somerset struggled to a 24-36 record in the first half of this
season, which was expanded from 100 games over all to 120. But in
the second half, the Patriots have bounced back, posting a
league-best record of 20-11.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots do not know a lot about Lyle's playing days because
many of them were very young or, in some cases, not even born when
he was in his prime. Lyle does not mind that; he prefers to be
known as the Somerset manager rather than the former Yankee
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle said he was not actively looking for another job, but that
does not mean he would not consider an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to talk to me about a job at the major league
level, I would be very happy to listen because I think I am
qualified,'' Lyle said. ``But that is not why I took the Somerset
job. I am very happy managing Somerset.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
