<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP THE SERMON AND PASS THE SALT: A LITTLE WORKS JUST FINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visitors to Washington state's Hurricane Ridge in August will
often notice there are more than cars parked in the visitors' lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, isn't that cute,'' a vacationer from Pismo Beach will
exclaim. ``The mama, papa and baby deer are all coming down to see
the tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a second look. The deer are not much interested in the
pudgy people in checkered shorts. They are licking the asphalt.
More specifically, the deer are trying to suck up the antifreeze
spilled from overheated radiators.
</P>
<P>
   Parking lots located at the apex of mountain roads or passes
seem to be appeasing the same primal lust as salt licks.
</P>
<P>
   So far, I haven't been spotted on hands and knees in the parking
lot at Stevens (CQ) Pass, except possibly for the occasional game
of craps.
</P>
<P>
   But, like the mama, papa and baby deer, I lust for salt.
</P>
<P>
   Anchovies, chipped beef, green olives, smoked salmon, salted
peanuts, dill pickles and prosciutto ham all occupy prominent
places on my shopping lists.
</P>
<P>
   Don't give me that scornful glance. Some people are salt
sensitive and must eliminate or reduce the seasoning to avoid high
blood pressure. But studies have indicated this describes only
about 10 percent of the population. And no evidence I have seen
suggests that excess salt will raise the blood pressure of the
other 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   I usually cook with my right hand gripping a wooden spoon. My
left arm is often twisted behind my back by my wife, Alice, who
gives it a painful jerk whenever I try to put excess salt in
recipes we test for this column.
</P>
<P>
   That's reasonable. After all, there is a salt cellar on every
table for individual partialities.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, there may not be a salt cellar on every
table. There are a couple of restaurants I have visited where salt
and pepper shakers have been banished from sight and reach.
Apparently, they are as objectionable to the chef and servers as
second-day socks substituting for napkins.
</P>
<P>
   This practice is nothing more than pretentious preaching on the
part of people who should know better.
</P>
<P>
   What the chef is telling his customers is, ``You don't know
what's good. I know what's good. Shut up and eat your food.''
</P>
<P>
   This is perhaps the proper attitude for somebody running a penal
colony. It should not be adopted by those who hope to survive in
the restaurant industry. The customer is still ``always right,''
even if he or she sprinkles some salt on the Pasta Puttanesca.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you probably won't need any salt with this dish
because it contains a can of anchovies. And, after all, you always
cook your pasta in salted water, don't you?
</P>
<P>
   Pasta Puttanesca
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 can (about 10 fillets) anchovies
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons capers, drained
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon marjoram
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper if needed
</P>
<P>
   Red pepper flakes to taste
</P>
<P>
   14-ounce can chopped black olives
</P>
<P>
   In a blender combine the garlic, anchovy fillets, tomatoes,
capers, marjoram, red pepper flakes and olive oil. Blend, then add
more oil from the anchovy can if you want a stronger taste. When
pureed, pour into a pan, add the olives and simmer 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This should be enough sauce for four portions of tubed pasta
like penne.
</P>
<P>
   Anchovies are also essential in this goop that I like to spread
on triangles of Boboli pizza crust before shoving them briefly
under a broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Red Pepper Spread
</P>
<P>
   17-ounce jar roasted red peppers, drained
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces chopped black olives
</P>
<P>
   4 anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One and one-half teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   Dice the peppers and anchovy fillets. Mix with the olives,
parsley, olive oil and lemon juice. Add salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Did you ever stop and consider that the great Northwest might
still be a wilderness if Lewis and Clark had not assigned three
members of their party to a task that confronted them near what is
now Seaside, Ore.? They kept the fire burning under five pots of
sea water 24 hours a day between Jan. 2 and Feb. 20, 1806. These
efforts produced the four bushels of salt the explorers felt they
needed to make the return trip back to Thomas Jefferson's front
door.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't for salt, Washington and Oregon would still be
listed as ``uncharted territories'' on world maps.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to your waiter and his big-shot chef.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
