<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATORS-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gators welcome underdog status
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ When Steve Spurrier arrived as head coach in
1990, Florida had never won an SEC championship. By the end of the
1996 season, the Gators had five conference titles plus a national
title. As a result, Florida fans and players began to think of the
SEC championship as a given, the natural birthright that comes with
just being a Gator.
</P>
<P>
   No more. For the past two years Florida has been on the outside
looking in while Tennessee won a pair of SEC championships. Last
season, the Volunteers added insult to injury by also winning the
national title. This year, Tennessee is a near-unanimous pick to
win its third straight SEC title.
</P>
<P>
   While Tennessee has been drawing almost universal praise,
Florida's program made the headlines recently for a less-positive
reason when it was revealed that four players from the 1998 team
had accepted money from an agent, a violation of NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the past two years have been a humbling experience
for the Gators, who once seemed destined to rule the SEC as long as
Spurrier was calling the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has brought us back to reality, that's for sure,'' said
linebacker Keith Kelsey. ``We now know this thing isn't given to
you. You have to work for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach agrees. Spurrier agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody knows that the last two years we haven't
achieved what we're capable of,'' said Spurrier, set to begin his
10th season at Florida. ``And this year we're not going to be
favorites like we have in the past. But maybe that will be good for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier stops short of saying that his last two teams had
become complacent about winning. After all, both won 10 games,
finished in the Top 10 and played in a New Year's Day bowl.
Florida's only losses last season were to Tennessee (20-17, OT) and
Florida State (23-12), the two teams that played in the Fiesta Bowl
for the national championship. Those games were on the road and the
Gators had opportunities to win both. Florida was good, just not
good enough.
</P>
<P>
   But Spurrier does concede that somewhere along the way, Florida
lost its edge after the 1996 national championship season. There is
a strong feeling in Gainesville that the 1998 defense underachieved
for a group so talented. Ultimately, it could be that the defense
was too talented to stay hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost convinced that when a player achieves a lot in
college, they are almost ready to go ahead and move on to the pros
or wherever they want to go,'' said Spurrier. ``The defense played
well, but we just didn't dominate the way we thought we would.''
</P>
<P>
   So Spurrier is not particularly concerned that nine members from
that defense are gone and a 10th, defensive back Rod Graddy, was
kicked off the team last week for violating team rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have excellent players here, they just haven't had a chance
to play much,'' he said. ``I think we're going to surprise some
people with the way our defense plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense will be explosive. Quarterback Doug Johnson, who
spent the summer in Gainesville working out instead of playing pro
baseball, is expected to have a huge year. Still, Florida will
enter the 1999 season in an unaccustomed position _ that of
underdog. Spurrier, for one, seems to like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a group of players who are a little closer than the
last few years,'' said Spurrier. ``I think our fans are going to
enjoy watching them.''
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Location: Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment: 42,000.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Steve Spurrier, 113-31-2 overall, 93-17-1 in nine seasons
at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Nickname: Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium: Ben Hill Griffin (83,000).
</P>
<P>
   Record: 545-340-40.
</P>
<P>
   SEC titles: 5.
</P>
<P>
   1998 record: 10-2, 7-1 SEC (2nd Eastern); beat Syracuse 31-10 in
Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: Sept. 4 vs. Western Michigan; Sept. 11 vs. Central
Florida; Sept. 18 vs. Tennessee; Sept. 25 at Kentucky; Oct. 2 vs.
Alabama; Oct. 9 at LSU; Oct. 16 at Auburn; Oct. 30 vs. Georgia
(Jacksonville); Nov. 6 vs. Vanderbilt; Nov. 13 at South Carolina;
Nov. 20 vs. Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
