<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon rolls to 5 in row on road
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Maybe they ought to remove Winston Cup
races from these funky road courses, as stock car purists suggest;
no one but Jeff Gordon can win them, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon won his fifth straight road course race Sunday at Watkins
Glen International and his third in a row at this ancient track.
</P>
<P>
   He led four times for 55 of the 90 laps in the Frontier at the
Glen, including the last 20. He beat the surprising Ron Fellows,
driving a Chevrolet owned by Cup driver Joe Nemechek, by .763
seconds to win $119,860.
</P>
<P>
   Pole-sitter Rusty Wallace was a distant third and points leader
Dale Jarrett finished fourth. Jarrett holds a 300-point lead over
Mark Martin, the last NASCAR driver other than Gordon to win a road
race (Sears Point in June 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett is 482 points ahead of the fifth-place Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   But he was way behind him Sunday at the Glen. Gordon, starting
from the No. 3 spot, was practically flawless over the 220.5 miles.
He led laps 2-20, 32-33, 45-55 and the decisive final 20.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up track position to Wallace a third of the way into the
race was no big problem to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was based on common sense,'' Gordon said, explaining that
another car had dropped oil on the track at the time. ``You see
something shiny and wet on the race track, it's not worth it. Rusty
was pushing me really hard at that time and it just wasn't worth it
for me to push that hard when I see fluid on the track, all the way
around for two laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was going to be a caution. I just didn't know
when. He was willing to take that chance so I said, `hey, go
ahead.' My car was really good. I didn't want to give up the lead,
but I said it just wasn't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a bit more effort to hold off Fellows, who has much
experience on this track in the Trans-Am series. A caution with
five laps to go, when Johnny Benson slammed a wall, bunched things
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get a good restart,'' Gordon said. ``In some
areas, Ron was better than I was. Coming off the _ I don't know,
you've got me confused with the turns here. Some are saying 7, some
are saying 11. I count seven, so I would call that (turn) 5, the
carousel up there. He was stronger than I was off that turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if he got close to me in that area, he could make a
pass. If he made a pass on me, it was going to be very tough for me
to get back by him, even though my overall lap times were a little
bit faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Fellows seemed willing to accept the compliments but
he felt second-place was bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure tomorrow I'll feel better with second place,'' said
Fellows, who led laps 56-58. ``I wanted to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted in the last frantic laps he was awestruck just
being behind Gordon and headed for the checkered flag. ``I was
thinking `how can I get around him,' '' Fellows said, ``and I was
also thinking, `man, this is pretty unbelievable. Me, running
behind Jeff Gordon.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The only other time I thought about (who I was racing) was
early, when I passed Dale Earnhardt. I thought that was pretty
cool. He may have been weaving just to let me go, but I gave a wave
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   He was willing to admit that finishing second in a Winston Cup
race was his biggest racing accomplishment. ``I hope it's my
biggest payday,'' Fellows said. It probably is: second place paid
$67,270.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's the absolute best Cup driver on road courses,
Gordon can appreciate where he's come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard for me to go back just three or four years ago
when a good race for me was if I stayed on the race track and
didn't miss a shift,'' Gordon said. ``Or I should say didn't miss
five shifts.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory continued a hit-and-miss season for Gordon. It was
his fifth win of the season, his 14th top 10 finish in 21 races and
moves him into 12th place on the all-time winner's list with 47. He
leads Cup drivers this year in wins, road wins and money earned
($4,289,101). But because five DNFs will probably cost him the
championship, many see it as an off year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the perception of other people, not us,'' Gordon said.
``We know that every season isn't going to be a season like we had
last year. At the end of the year, if we're not the champion, we're
going to feel like we didn't accomplish our goals. At the same
time, it's hard to took at this season so far and say it's been a
disaster. It just hasn't been as good as last year.''
</P>
<P>
   TOP 5
</P>
<P>
   1. Jeff Gordon, Chevrolet
</P>
<P>
   2. Ron Fellows, Chevrolet
</P>
<P>
   3. Rusty Wallace, Ford
</P>
<P>
   4. Dale Jarrett, Ford
</P>
<P>
   5. Jerry Nadeau, Ford
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
