<HEADLINE>
A YOUTH LEAGUE'S TICKET TO THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES_ Northridge resident and longtime youth-sports coach
Don Rann isn't sure why a free Web site he supports called
SportsCombine.com _ a vehicle to help youth leagues, athletic
directors, coaches and league administrators make their jobs easier
and more fun _ hasn't been embraced in this part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back East, it's big, but here it's been a tough sell,''
admitted Rann, the site's California state coordinator. ``Maybe
because it takes some extra volunteer work. But there's a terrific
opportunity out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Based in Fairfax, Va., the site provides teams with a place to
build their own Web pages, maintain and update stats, post
schedules and network with other leagues and coaches. And because
it allows leagues to accept advertising, it can be a cutting-edge
source of generating more fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Rann, a retiree coaching a midget-division Pop Warner team in
Chatsworth, can be contacted via e-mail at yourstatsaol.com.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Youth Sports Network site (ysn.com), another source for
helping with sign-ups for PONY baseball (www.pony.org) and Pop
Warner football leagues, will produce Saturday's noon telecast of
the PONY World Series from its headquarters in Washington, Pa.,
that is shown on Fox Sports Net. The tournament for 13- and
14-year-olds, which began Aug. 6, can also be followed at the site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8120 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-L-2ND     08-15 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-L-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: passion for astrology. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The decision to depart was abrupt _ only about $2 million of the
$10 million in diamonds had arrived by that time _ but Frankel
determined that it was an astrologically auspicious day for travel.
</P>
<P>
   He did not travel light. People present at his home that day
said it took until mid-afternoon to stuff two Tahoe sport utility
vehicles and a BMW sedan with more than a dozen pieces of luggage,
including personal computers, which Frankel decided to take with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Problems cropped up immediately. The private jet that a local
aviation company was supposed to to send pick him up at Westchester
County Airport, north of New York City, never showed up. Frankel
and Ms. Kim worked the phones to arrange a replacement. When it
arrived, Frankel spent several hours haggling with the pilots over
a flight plan, eventually settling on a stop in Spain on the way to
Rome's Ciampino Airport.
</P>
<P>
   During the flight, Frankel appeared nervous, Ms. Kim said,
chatting with the pilots in the cockpit while his two female
companions watched videos in the main cabin. The moment they landed
in Spain to refuel, Frankel hopped out to make phone calls from the
airport phone. When he returned, his face was ghostly. The diamonds
he had hoped would pay for his life in exile were missing.
</P>
<P>
   While he was over the Atlantic, several members of Frankel's
staff had clashed over who would take possession of the gems, which
were delivered by private jet to Teterboro Airport in New Jersey
from Los Angeles. There are differing accounts of what happened to
about $8 million in diamonds, with several people recounting car
chases and accusing one of Frankel's own security officers of
theft, a charge the security officer's lawyer denies. The diamonds'
whereabouts remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that just two days after he took off from
Westchester, the FBI entered the case and investigators quickly
learned from Frankel's driver that he had left the country.
Interpol was alerted, and the hunt was on.
</P>
<P>
   But it took federal authorities several weeks to assemble enough
evidence to obtain from an American judge the sealed arrest warrant
that would allow them to seek Frankel's apprehension and
extradition from a foreign country. And though several of Frankel's
workers said they knew of his plans to go to Italy, there is no
indication that the FBI began tracking him there until late June.
</P>
<P>
   Rome was not an obvious choice for a fugitive. Notes that
Frankel left behind in Greenwich suggested that he had researched
places where the United States has trouble extraditing people,
including Brazil and Israel. Italy is not among them.
</P>
<P>
   But Frankel had one thing in Italy that he may not have had
elsewhere: friends. Fausto Fausti, a retired Italian air force
officer and aviation consultant, and his son Alfredo, a law
student, had played a shadowy role in Frankel's insurance dealings,
including efforts to persuade Catholic charities in Italy to
participate in his purchases of American insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship appears to have involved money. American
authorities have tracked wire transfers from accounts controlled by
Frankel to Fausti, including one made shortly before Frankel's
departure from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Frankel arrived in Rome, the Faustis were host,
tour guide and booking agent, finding the fugitives places to live
and helping them when they got into trouble, said Ms. Kim and other
associates. The Faustis did not return repeated phone calls. Their
New York lawyer, Paul A. Goldberger, also failed to respond to a
reporter's queries.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop in Rome was an apartment the Faustis arranged for
Frankel in a working-class neighborhood, not far from the Hotel
Dover. But lodging became an immediate and nagging concern for
Frankel, who had lived in a nearly $4 million home on four acres in
one of American's toniest suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   When he inspected his new quarters, with its sparse furniture
and miniscule kitchen, he pronounced it ``a dump.'' There was no
telephone or television. And when the Faustis were not around, no
one in the party spoke Italian. All three struggled to memorize
enough Italian phrases to be able to tell a cab driver where they
lived. Frankel also complained about calculating prices in lire,
the Italian currency, a scrip famous for its lofty denominations.
</P>
<P>
   In his first weeks on the run, Frankel appeared to have few
worries that the Italians or Americans would track him down. Though
they did little touring, Frankel and his entourage did not hide.
Because they had no phone at the apartment, Frankel bought stacks
of phone cards and wandered the city in search of public phones.
Often, Ms. Kim and Ms. Ju sat languidly for hours in outdoor cafes
while Frankel called business associates around the world.
</P>
<P>
   They had easy access to cash. Ms. Kim said she opened an account
in her own name at the Banca Popolare di Brescia in the nearby
Piazza Giuseppe Verdi. In one trans-Atlantic phone call in late
May, Frankel arranged for his diamond dealer to deposit a $450,000
sales-tax refund in that account, which Ms. Kim then drew on for
living expenses.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
