<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8121 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-L-3RD     08-15 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-L-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 
UNDATED: living expenses.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the weeks passed, with still no signs of media attention or
heat from law enforcement, Frankel felt secure enough to find
plusher accommodations. Scouring English-language guide books, he
found a small hotel in an upscale district near the elegant Villa
Borghese park and museum. Frankel rented a suite, and promptly
demanded hard-back chairs to replace the ultra-modern benches in
the room, which he found uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel choice seemed risky from the start. Ms. Kim noticed
that it was near the embassy district and not far from the
well-guarded Israeli mission. ``It had surveillance up the
ying-yang,'' Ms. Kim recalled. Sure enough, at midnight on May 25,
their sense of security was shattered by a knock on the door.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kim, sitting in the living room with Ms. Ju while Frankel
slept, opened the door. The hotel owner demanded to see their
passports, said Ms. Kim. He said that the Israeli Embassy had
contacted the local police chief, who in turn had contacted him.
The problem was that the Frankel party, using an assumed name, had
checked in to the hotel without presenting their passports, a
breach of protocol and security. (Officials in the Israel Embassy
said they recalled no such incident.)
</P>
<P>
   Near panic ensued. Leaving the manager in the hall, Ms. Kim woke
up Frankel. He ordered her not to show the passports. Ms. Kim
returned to the door with an improvised story: that because she
could not figure out how to work the safe in the room, she had
placed their passports in the safe deposit box of a nearby bank and
could not retrieve them until the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Frankel burst out of his bedroom and yelled at the
owner: ``Do you have any idea what time it is? I paid good money
for this villa. You have no right to come here at this hour.'' He
told the owner to return at 10 a.m. to see their passports.
</P>
<P>
   The ruse worked. Stammering apologies, the embarrassed owner
invited them to lunch the next day. He even spent 20 minutes
showing them how to work the safe. At dawn, with the help of a
bellhop, they loaded their suitcases into several cabs and escaped
to the Faustis, who arranged a new place of refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Home for the next five weeks was a pale green apartment building
on Via Asmara in Trieste, an upper middle-class section of Rome.
Here, in an apartment owned by a person Ms. Kim describes as a
Fausti friend, Frankel had more of the comforts of home. But
Frankel was growing fearful for his safety.
</P>
<P>
   At a neighborhood cafe that offered access to the Internet,
Frankel began scanning Web sites to keep up on the news. In early
June, his once buoyant optimism that he could fade anonymously into
well-heeled exile ended when he saw the first wire-service
references to an FBI investigation into his business.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, newspapers were carrying detailed accounts of an
international insurance fraud. One article about him in the Toledo
Blade, his Toledo, Ohio, hometown newspaper, caused him particular
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking of family members who would read the article, Frankel
curled up on the apartment sofa. ``My poor mother,'' he lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's use of aliases and his practice of scattering his
assets prevented the police from locking up all his bank accounts
even by mid-August. But by the end of May, the FBI began to win
court seizure orders on some of his accounts. And he began to get
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the Faustis, he converted some cash into gold,
said one person involved in Frankel's dealings. It was not a
brilliant tactic for a man on the run: The gold bars were too heavy
to move, forcing him to summon help when he needed to change his
address.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-June, Frankel also began to explore safer options for
exile. He sought advice from a Rome-based lawyer, Pierre Fortin.
Fortin did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel also took a trip to Milan, where he consulted with an
extradition expert, people familiar with his travels said. He even
met a friend of the son of Moammar Gadhafi, the Libyan leader, to
ask for protection from that historically anti-American government,
though no deal was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his fears, he kept an open line to his friends. Ms. Ju
began to tire of life on the run in mid-June and insisted on
returning home. Frankel, afraid of being alone, began phoning other
friends back in the United States. At least three former employees
of Frankel received calls from him during this period. It's not
known whether the FBI was monitoring their telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel found at least one new recruit: Cynthia Allison, a
former staff member, flew to Italy to join him, several people
said. On June 26, after Ms. Allison's arrival, Ms. Kim also
returned home. One person close to the investigation said Frankel
gave her a $20,000 parting gift, though Ms. Kim's lawyer, Keith
Rubenstein, declined to comment on that matter. Ms. Allison is
believed to be with Frankel to this day.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Frankel has come to capture in his time abroad might
have been a sting operation. But it was arranged by a British
tabloid, The Express, not by the police.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, The Express solicited the help of Thomas J.
Corbally, an elderly American business consultant and private
detective who was instrumental in Frankel's dealings. Corbally, who
in June and July was living in a luxury hotel in London and putting
off an FBI demand for an interview, has said that he is a friend of
Fausti.
</P>
<P>
   The Express reported that through London intermediaries it made
contact with Frankel, agreeing to lease him a private jet that
would fly him to northern Cyprus, a country considered a safe haven
for fugitives. Although some details of the newspaper account
appear to be inaccurate, several people involved said they believed
the outlines of it to be true. Corbally and his lawyer declined to
return phone calls in recent weeks. But people close to Corbally
said they believe that he did play a role in the newspaper sting.
</P>
<P>
   Had Frankel boarded the plane as arranged, The Express said that
it would have delivered him to the police. But the plan fell
through. Frankel phoned a day before the scheduled departure to
postpone. His reason: He had studied astrological charts and
divined that the stars were not properly aligned for travel that
day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
