<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR NOTEBOOK: Dream run ends for rookie Said
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ For nearly half of the race's 90 laps,
Boris Said was playing out a rookie's dream at Watkins Glen
International.
</P>
<P>
   Starting second after a glorious qualifying run in the No. 14
Ford co-owned by Ernie Irvan, Said was proving he belonged up among
the front-runners in the Frontier at the Glen.
</P>
<P>
   He led laps 21-29, only losing track position when he pitted on
lap 31. Then the engine failed on lap 48 and he retired for the
day, placing next-to-last in the 43-car field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my wife's birthday and I wanted to give her a special
present, but, sorry, Karen,'' Said said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun leading, and it was a lot of fun running
with Jeff Gordon,'' he said. ``I know why that guy's fast now. He's
so smooth. He's an awesome driver. It was fun being out there with
those guys.
</P>
<P>
   Said, a regular road-course and occasional truck-series driver,
is the first driver to lead a lap in his first Winston Cup race
since Kenny Irwin did it at Richmond in September 1997. Said was
the 38th different driver to lead a lap this season.
</P>
<P>
   And he finished just behind his boss, Irvan, whose engine also
failed in the No. 36 Pontiac after 60 laps. But the rookie said
he'll be in Michigan next weekend, even if he's not in a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm Ernie's spiritual advisor for the Busch car,'' Said
said. ``So I've got to go out there, light incense and chant and
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   A sorry 600th
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt called his 600th consecutive start ``pretty
sorry'' and said ``it isn't one I want to remember.'' He started
14th in the Frontier at the Glen and finished 20th, but what
happened in between made the day even more forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   On lap 16, he bumped into teammate Mike Skinner and dented both
cars. And on the last lap, he went deep into the last corner to
avoid Darrell Waltrip and ended up against the wall, showering the
track with pieces of the Styrofoam padding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into the back of Skinner,'' Earnhardt said. ``That ain't
too hard to do here.'' Skinner's explanation was just as sketchy.
``We were just racing real hard and got turned around down there,''
Skinner said. ``I don't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Just racing
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nemechek and Bill Elliott got into a last-lap accident on
the way to the finish line and Nemechek was not too happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove my car in way too deep (into the last turn) and here
comes Bill Elliott and I knew there was no way he was going to make
it,'' Nemechek said. ``I still had to go around the corner or else
get penalized. When he runs into my back tire, it's kind of stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame. We were running eighth and ended up 38th or
something (actually, 30th). I'm still kind of hot right now, but
I'll cool down. We'll be friends again tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's explanation: ``We were just racing. I got inside of
Joe and we got together, hard enough that I had to finish with a
flat left-front tire. We went from ninth to 20th, but that's just
last-lap racing sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
