<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8123 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-ASSESS     08-15 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA VOTE EXPOSES WILD CARD FOR BUSH JUGGERNAUT: STEVE FORBES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to fix last sentence, `seven out of every 10
participants,' sted `seven of the 10.') 
 (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush did not merely want to
place first in the straw poll here on Saturday of Republican
presidential contenders. He wanted, as one of his advisers put it
Sunday, ``to absolutely smash everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why even members of the governor's high command were
personally, and frantically, prodding people to cast their ballots
in the final minutes of voting.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was decisive but hardly a rout. Bush won with 31
percent, and his aides boasted that he amassed 7,418 of the 23,685
votes cast, three times more than any victor in the event's
two-decade history. But his two closest competitors _ Steve Forbes,
who drew 21 percent, and Elizabeth Dole, with 14 percent _ also
turned out more people than any past winner. And seven out of every
10 participants voted for someone other than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The voting here at Iowa State University did not alter the basic
story line of the Republican presidential race: Bush is still the
towering front-runner. Yet while Bush entered the competition here
only two months ago, the results underscored that his course to the
nomination may be turbulent. And they suggested that he will face
forceful, and perhaps damaging, challenges in the crucial
nominating caucuses here in six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are candidates who will be strong and competitive in
January and February,'' Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's advisers were most unsettled by Forbes, the
multimillionaire magazine publisher who has lavished his fortune on
the presidential race and spent far more money on the straw poll
than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   There was never any doubt that Forbes' wealth would give him the
opportunity to spar with Bush throughout the primaries. That, in
fact, is what drove Bush to join Forbes in rejecting federal
matching funds so he is not encumbered by spending limits. But
Forbes demonstrated on Saturday that he knows how to convert his
money into an organization that is adroit at turning people out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely wanted to do better,'' said a Bush adviser who
spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``But there was one thing we
couldn't control: How many votes Mr. Forbes could buy.'' The
adviser went on, ``We have a wild card in this race: Steve Forbes.
The danger is, he could come in and carpet bomb and force us to
spend five, six or seven million dollars just to win the Iowa
caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   While the straw poll was designed as a fund-raiser for the state
Republican Party, and the candidates' paid the $25 entry fee for
participants, it was also an organizational test that will affect
the candidates' fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Because Gary Bauer, the former head of the Family Research
Council, finished fourth place, ahead of conservative commentator
Pat Buchanan, Bauer is portraying himself as the standard bearer of
religious conservatives. Buchanan has hinted that he might consider
bolting the Republicans to try for the nomination of the Reform
Party.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the straw poll, Buchanan said that Bush was so far
ahead in the polls that the governor's campaign felt the ``need to
blow them all out and end it right here.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush fell short of that goal, the outcome does significantly
diminish the fortunes of former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and
former Vice President Dan Quayle. Alexander, who had devoted more
time to campaigning in Iowa than any other candidate, is expected
to suspend his campaign, perhaps as soon as Monday. He ranked sixth
place, with 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a powerful force in this country to nominate George W.
Bush,'' Alexander said Sunday on the NBC News program ``Meet the
Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, already stumping in New Hampshire on Sunday, insisted he
would soldier on, despite being humiliated with an eighth place
finish of 3.9 percent, behind Alan Keyes, a radio host.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, who entered the presidential contest
last month, placed ninth, followed by Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
who did not campaign here and scoffed at the straw poll as ``a sham
and a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the outcome was not as convincing as other, earlier
gauges of his success: a war chest that is 10 times that of his
nearest competitors and polls showing him swamping his rivals. And
in his first side-by-side performance with his rivals in the hall
here on Saturday, Bush did not electrify the crowd _ certainly not
enough to convince people to abandon other contenders in droves.
</P>
<P>
   The hope in the Bush camp is that Republicans will ultimately
stick with him because he looks like a winner and appears to have
the strongest chance to defeat the Democrats in a general election.
He enjoys deep institutional support of money and endorsements and
there is no obvious alternative. Bush's supporters are buoyed by
the fact that the second-, third-, fourth- and fifth-place
finishers have never been elected to public office.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Gov. John Engler, who was here on behalf of Bush, said
of Forbes' inheritance: ``His fund-raising is easy. All he has to
do is have a meeting of the brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   But, turning serious, he adding, ``He's dangerous because he has
money. He's less dangerous because he has no electoral record.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes made the case that his showing on Saturday proves
that he is electable. ``Money plus no message equals mush,'' he
said. ``Voters want real substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the former president of the American Red Cross, benefited
from drawing women and young people to the events, what she called
``an invisible army.'' But Bush's advisers insisted that they
preferred that Dole placed third rather than, say, Bauer. They
expressed concern that if a favorite of religious conservatives was
catapulted to the top tier _ as happened with Buchanan in the New
Hampshire primary in 1996 _ that candidate could prove nettlesome
for months.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign that is probably eyeing Dole the closest is
McCain's. His advisers said Dole could complicate their plan to
emerge as a logical alternative to Bush because she competes for
some of the same support. Making her pitch Sunday, Dole noted that
she spent far less here than the first- and second-place finishers.
</P>
<P>
   The hope among her followers, and the other candidates, is that
Forbes' wealth will alienate voters. As Forbes addressed the hall
Saturday night, several strategists for other candidates looked on
with delight. He had financed a costly balloon drop when he reached
the lectern. But rival camps immediately began popping the
balloons. The noise drowned out most of Forbes' speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
