<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SIBLEY-OBIT-COX     08-15 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-OBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beloved Atlanta Journal-Constitution columnist Celestine Sibley
dies of cancer
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS and SIDEBARS
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Celestine Sibley, whose column ran in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution for 55 years, died early Sunday morning at her
summer retreat on Dog Island, Fla. She was 85. She had undergone
surgery for breast cancer in 1995 and suffered a heart attack in
1998. She learned that her cancer had returned late last year.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best loved and most prolific writers in the history
of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Sibley captured everyday life
in the changing South in more than 10,000 columns since 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celestine was one of the true giants,'' said Georgia Gov. Roy
Barnes. ``She had one of the biggest hearts of any person that I
ever knew. She knew the secrets on all of us in the General
Assembly, and we were comfortable that she knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Ashmead, Sibley's editor at Harper Collins, said, ``A
light's gone out in Atlanta and Georgia and all over the South,
where people read her and loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Ashmead, ``I'm sort of glad she died on Dog Island, the
place she and Jack (her late husband Jack Strong) loved the most of
all the places they had.''
</P>
<P>
   Born near Pensacola, Fla., Sibley was reared in the turpentine
country north of Mobile, Ala. She came to work at The Atlanta
Constitution in 1941. Though best known for the columns that she
wrote from 1944 until shortly before her death, she was a star
court reporter and also covered politics and the Georgia
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   She almost single-handedly brought up three children while
holding down a full-time job, freelancing magazine articles and
writing 25 books. Her honors and awards were many. In June she
became only the second woman ever to receive the Lifetime
Achievement Award from the National Society of Newspaper
Columnists.
</P>
<P>
   According to her daughter Mary Vance, Sibley was alert when she
died around 5:30 Sunday morning. In her last moments she asked
whether they might return to Sweet Apple one last time, explaining
that, ``There are a couple of things I wanted to do in the
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Patricia Templeton, associate rector of St Timothy's
Episcopal Church in Signal Mountain, Tennessee, said, ``She
approached her death the way she lived her life: With courage and
grace and stubbornness.'' Templeton is to officiate at a memorial
service for her longtime friend. Plans for that service were to be
announced later today.
</P>
<P>
   Templeton served as an intern at The Atlanta Constitution in
1976, before she turned to the ministry, and still keeps a clipping
of a Sibley column from that summer. In the column, Sibley writes
of a fierce love of newspapering, saying ``I can honestly say that
there has been nothing in my life so painful and saddening that it
wasn't eased a little bit as I walked toward my job in a newspaper
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Martin, editor of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, said
Sunday, ``Those of us who were fortunate to work with her will miss
her laughter, her wisdom and her example. Her column was Celestine
herself _ an oasis, where you could share a quiet moment, recover
your perspective, and leave refreshed, ready to journey on. It's
hard to imagine the paper without her.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cumming of Carrollton used Sibley's columns when he taught
journalism at West Georgia College, and cherished a friendship that
began in 1957 when he began reporting for Newsweek's Southern
bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always thought of her in heroic terms,'' said Cumming.
``She had all the strength of the Statue of Liberty, only with a
sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley and former governor Zell Miller were friends from the
years when she covered the state legislature and he was a young
lawmaker. ``I always looked upon her as a wise aunt, who would
encourage you with warmth and gentleness,'' said Miller. ``She
taught us how to face our later years: With dignity, with humor,
and occasionally a little bit of irritability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved her very much,'' said Miller, ``and, gosh, I'm going
to miss her, but so will thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include her son, James W. Little V of Alford, Fla.;
two daughters, Susan Sibley Little Bazemore of Des Moines (formerly
of Omaha) and Mary Everitt Little-Vance of Roswell; eight
grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, the family asks that contributions be sent
to the library of their choice or to Trees Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
