<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SIBLEY-REACT-COX     08-15 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-REACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remembering Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We sang when she got her Atlanta Gas Light `Shining Light
Award' (in 1997) at the newspaper. Afterward, she cornered me and
made me promise that the choir would sing at her funeral. She told
me she wanted us to sing spirituals, especially her favorite,
`Steal Away.' I told her, `Of course we will.' Her response to me
was, `Oh, I believe I'll go home and die tonight!'
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY COLEMAN,
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta attorney and long-time member of the Big Bethel AME
Church ``Heaven Bound'' choir
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day for Georgia. She was a great neighbor and a
great friend for over 30 years. If she got busy up there at Sweet
Apple, she just wouldn't bother to answer the phone. When the folks
at the newspaper really needed to talk to her, they'd call the
store and ask if I could go up and tell her. And when I got there,
nine out of ten times, she'd have something for me to do!''
</P>
<P>
   LARRY CHADWICK
</P>
<P>
   Sibley neighbor and owner of Chadwick's Store in North Fulton
County
</P>
<P>
   ``Her book-signings were a love feast between her and her
readers. Over the 23 years she signed at our store, I saw readers
bring her homemade jams and jellies and pictures, everything. She
took the time to talk to each and every person in that line, no
matter how long it took. People would stand in line for two or
three hours and not care one bit. ``
</P>
<P>
   LYN DEARDORFF
</P>
<P>
   Co-owner of The Final Touch Gallery &AMP; Books in Decatur
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started collecting her books, I was working at the
First National Bank on Marietta Street, right down from the paper.
Her first book, `The Malignant Heart' had eluded me for years. When
I finally found a copy in 1981, I called her up and asked if she
would sign it for me. I remember her saying, `Sure honey, come on
over.' This was in the days before security and all that. I walked
into her office to find a mound of papers that looked like a
mini-Stone Mountain. I called out her name and this head popped up
from the pile of papers. That's when I saw the piece of marble with
`Bless This Mess' on it. She inscribed my book with `Noel, you are
a wonder! Imagine the trouble and pain you went through trying to
get this one! With grateful appreciation and love, Celestine
Sibley.''
</P>
<P>
   NOEL BRISCOE
</P>
<P>
   Reader
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always helping people. After she wrote those columns
about me, she actually helped me get some of my back pay from the
V.A. When my dog Bobo was alive, she would show up to visit and
give him some biscuits and she'd always give us a few dollars too.
She was a noble and gracious lady. She never used that column of
hers to say a bad word about anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   TED HAGLER
</P>
<P>
   One of Celestine Sibley's many street friends and the subject of
a series of columns on the homeless
</P>
<P>
   ``She wrote about homey and simple and obvious subjects
sometimes, but she hit all the chords and could break your heart
and make you cry.''
</P>
<P>
   BILL EMERSON
</P>
<P>
   Former Newsweek bureau chief and a close friend
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember at her last book-signing this past spring, she
stayed about 90 minutes longer than she was scheduled. As things
were wrapping up and we were standing there talking, one last
customer approached with a book. Given all the time she had spent
already, I wasn't going to ask her to sign anything else. The woman
eventually put the book down and began to walk out. Celestine
turned to me and said, `We just lost her! She's getting away. Run
and go get her !' .''
</P>
<P>
   MARIE MEALOR
</P>
<P>
   She arranged Sibley's final booksigning on May 8, 1999
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the third generation in my family to read her columns. My
grandmother read her everyday religiously. She always clipped her
articles on roses, canning tomatoes and baking cakes. My mother
would clip out her columns and post them on the bulletin board in
the kitchen and that's how us kids first started reading Celestine.
She was as close to being a member of our family as she could be
without actually being related.''
</P>
<P>
   BYRON CONLEY
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta interior designer and reader
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved cooking for her. She always requested my blue cheese
chicken at her book-signings. At one signing, she teased me about
the dessert I'd made. It was an evening when I was running behind.
Everybody else thought it was this incredibly elaborate masterpiece
but she pulled me aside in the back and said, `Those are just ice
cream balls rolled in cocoa, aren't they?' and winked at me. You
couldn't put anything over on her. Last year, I was working at a
French restaurant, around the corner from where she was signing
books. I brought her some Silver Queen creamed corn from the
restaurant. I remember apologizing to her because I had put leeks
in the dish to make it a little more French.''
</P>
<P>
   JIM CASSELL
</P>
<P>
   He prepared dishes for Sibley's book-signings.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has loved the people in all walks of life in Georgia, and
she has received that love back, and it's not easy to be loved if
you're a newspaper person.''
</P>
<P>
   FORMER U.S. REP. JAMES MACKAY (Decatur, Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A long-time friend
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Richard L. Eldredge and Bo Emerson
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
