<HEADER>
A8146 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-15 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Consumer Price Index for July could add to interest-rate jitters  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those jittery about further interest-rate boosts by the Federal
Reserve are likely to have their anxiety heightened by the July
reading of the {Consumer Price Index,} which will be reported
Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The consensus call is for a rise of 0.3 percent in the general
price level as measured by the index. An increase that large would
be even more shocking because the index has remained unchanged for
the past two months. This lull has been used as a talking point by
those lobbying Fed policy-makers in hopes of heading off another
rate increase. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mitigating factor, if the consensus is accurate, will be
only a modest increase in the core rate, which excludes the
volatile food and energy components from the inflation measure. &QL; 
Tuesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest numbers on {industrial production} and {plant
capacity in use} are forecast to show a reasonably healthy
manufacturing sector, but certainly not one in danger of creating
inflationary bottlenecks. Most analysts expect factory output to
have expanded 0.3 percent while the amount of productive capacity
in use remained unchanged at 80.3 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - The July rate of {housing starts} is likely to reflect the
industry's modest slowdown, which is generally attributed to rising
mortgage rates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - The Treasury has scheduled {an auction of 52-week bills.} &QL; 
Thursday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another huge {international trade deficit} is being projected
for June, but it's not expected to surpass May's record $21.3
billion shortfall. Most analysts look for $20.5 billion worth of
red ink. If the experts are on target it would bring the second
quarter's trade deficit to more than $60 billion. Although some
observers will put a negative spin on this development, the
burgeoning shortfalls are due more to U.S. economic health combined
with efforts by U.S. trading partners to revive their ailing
economies. &QL; 
Friday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest {Treasury report} is expected to show a budget
deficit for July, but not enough to jeopardize expectations for a
three-digit budget surplus for fiscal 1999, which ends Sept. 30.
June's $53.6 billion in black ink brought the surplus for the first
three quarters of the fiscal year to $94 billion. The July
shortfall is expected to pare $20 billion to $25 billion from the
accumulated surplus. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
