<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8148 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-CLINTON-VFW-KAN &LR;      08-15 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VFW-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Clinton to deliver first speech to VFW convention  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Having successfully concluded a conflict with
Yugoslavia, President Clinton comes to Kansas City today to mark
the 100th anniversary of the Veterans of Foreign Wars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His first appearance before a full convention of the VFW _ he
spoke to a smaller legislative conference of the group in 1995 _
has been greeted with scattered protests by some veterans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the first chief executive to emerge from the Vietnam
War generation, has been criticized by some as a draft-dodger who
has diminished the office of commander-in-chief. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the VFW administration, as it does with every president
every year, invited Clinton. And officials from the organization
said they expect his speech to be well-attended. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's usually a somewhat bigger audience when the president
is speaking,'' said Bill Smith, the VFW's director of
communications and public affairs. ``We certainly would hope that
he would address veterans health care, long-term nursing care and
national security.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to deliver the speech at 11 a.m. at Bartle
Hall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 people are expected to come to Kansas City in the
course of the convention. The organization's members number about
1.9 million, and some 10,000 delegates and members are expected to
attend the convention. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the opening session today, which is closed to the
public but will be aired on C-Span later in the day, typically
draws 5,000 to 8,000 members. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the president has not spoken at previous
VFW conventions because of scheduling conflicts. Presidential
attendance at the largest meeting of the country's second-largest
veterans organization has been sporadic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon, a Navy veteran, attended in 1973. Jimmy Carter, a
Navy veteran, never showed. Ronald Reagan, an Army veteran, spoke
to the VFW convention during his Defense Department buildup in 1983
and 1984. George Bush, a former Navy pilot and VFW member,
addressed the convention four times _ twice as vice president and
twice while president. Vice President Al Gore, a Vietnam Army
veteran and VFW member, came in 1996. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The president thought it was important to recognize the 100th
anniversary of this important organization,'' said Elizabeth Newman
of the White House press office. ``President Clinton feels it's
very important to recognize people who have sacrificed for their
country.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, the president visited Whiteman Air Force
Base to thank the nation's military personnel for their successful
campaign with NATO against Yugoslavia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although he was of draft age during the Vietnam War, Clinton was
never called to service. ``I didn't want to be drafted,'' he said
during his 1992 campaign. ``I tried to get out of it.'' Criticism
of his efforts to avoid the draft nearly derailed his efforts to
become president, but he has denied acting dishonestly to dodge the
draft. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith said about 150 complaints about Clinton's appearance have
come to VFW offices in Kansas City by telephone, fax and e-mail in
the past month. None, he said, preceded VFW commander-in-chief
Thomas Pouliot's invitation to the president. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Kenny Rogers concert and patriotic VFW rally is scheduled for
5:30 tonight. Sen. John McCain, a presidential candidate who was a
prisoner of war during the Vietnam War, is scheduled to speak to
the veterans on Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The headquarters of the organization have been at Broadway and
34th Street in Kansas City since 1930, but the VFW hasn't brought
its annual convention to Kansas City since 1931. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8150 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CLINTON-VFW-KAN &LR;      08-15 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VFW-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Clinton to deliver first speech to VFW convention  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
