<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8151 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-2TAKES-NYT     08-15 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS TAKES SECOND MAJOR TITLE BY STROKE OVER WORLD'S NO. 1
TEEN-AGER 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ The century's last major was one of the best. It
was won by the world's No. 1 player, who was pursued by the world's
No. 1 teen &UR; - &LR; ager _ two electrifying talents combining for a
fantastic finish that could be the first chapter of a great
rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Faltering on the back nine, yet keeping his composure when it
counted the most, Tiger Woods won his second major at the age of
23, prevailing by one stroke over Sergio Garcia of Spain to win the
PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Woods shot an even par 72 Sunday to finish 11-under par for the
tournament (277), one stroke better than Garcia (278), who shot a
71, and almost won his first major at the age of 19. Stewart Cink
and Jay Haas finished tied for third at 8- under par, while Nick
Price faded after a sizzling front nine to finish fifth (7-under
par).
</P>
<P>
   But the battle between Woods and Garcia was riveting until the
final hole, a glimpse of golf's future, as two magnetic
personalities captivated the gallery of 45,000 at Medinah Country
Club, with fans cheered and sighed with every swing in momentum.
</P>
<P>
   It was magnificent theater, as Garcia hit incredible recovery
shots, while Woods went forward with determination, his game face
on, his eye on the ultimate prize. Since winning the 1997 Masters
by a record-setting 12 strokes, Woods has contended in other
majors, but something, or someone, always kept him from winning.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Woods sensed that this was the right time and the right
golf course, and while he was severely tested, he passed in the
end. After his tournament-clinching tap-in at No. 18 fell in the
hole, Woods' knees buckled and he sighed in relief, finally able to
exhale.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia thrilled the gallery, But Woods left with the glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get No. 2 is definitely a relief,'' said Woods, referring
to his second major championship, which brought with it a winner's
check worth $630,000. ``I've been trying. I've given myself
chances. I've come close. Sometimes you just need a little bit of
luck to go your way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played well, but I also had a few lucky breaks go my way.
Sergio played a wonderful round of golf and he needs to be
commended, not only for the way he played, but the way he conducted
himself. He was emotional. He was fiery. He was trying. He never
dogged it. It was wonderful to see.''
</P>
<P>
   For Garcia, it was his biggest coming-out party yet on the world
stage, as he became the youngest runner-up in PGA Championship
history, and almost won a major before anyone had a right to
expect. But for Garcia, this was only a beginning. His second-place
finish clinched his spot on the European Ryder Cup team, and it
also clinched his PGA Tour card for next year, if he decides to
play in the United States instead of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The fans at Medinah fell in love with Garcia, chanting ``Sergio,
Sergio'' on the back nine, and cheering for him more loudly than
they cheered for Woods.
</P>
<P>
   With Garcia, what's not to love? Since turning professional
after being low amateur at the Masters in April, Garcia has already
won the Murphy's Irish Open, while finishing second at Loch Lomond,
and third at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   He plays daringly, he connects with the crowd and his golf game
isn't bad either. He ended the day not demoralized, but uplifted,
looking forward to other majors, and to other encounters with
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds were amazing,'' said Garcia, who will never forget
his first PGA Championship. ``I said when I turned pro that I
wanted to be the No. 1 golfer in the world. So I knew I was going
to be a rival for Tiger. But I said I always wanted to be a rival
being friends, like we did today. Nineteen years old and months
since I turned pro, you can't ask for any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods certainly wouldn't ask for any more, as he saw a
comfortable lead all but disappear on the back nine. He started the
day tied with Mike Weir, a 29-year-old Canadian, who collapsed
Sunday and shot an 80 to finish tied for 10th.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Early on, everything went Woods' way. He played with poise and
precision, making birdies on four of the first seven holes, and
when he left the 11th green after another birdie, he was at
15-under par, five strokes ahead of Garcia, who was one group
ahead, and five strokes ahead of Price, who was two groups ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But faster than you could sense trouble for Woods, it came. He
three &UR; - &LR; putted for bogey at No. 12, and when he arrived at the
difficult par &UR; - &LR; 3, 219-yard No. 12, he arrived at the tee box just
in time to hear the crowd roar as Garcia made an 18-foot putt for
birdie, putting him at 11-under par, only three strokes back.
Garcia looked back at Woods, hoping to send a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he recognized me,'' said Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum was changing, and maybe Woods felt it. His 6-iron
tee shot at No. 13 sailed over the green and into the deep rough,
leaving him with a difficult downhill chip, and Woods didn't hit a
good one. The ball rolled down the hill, past the pin, and into the
front rough, leaving him with another scary chip. Woods chipped 10
feet past the pin, then missed the putt coming back and settle for
a double-bogey as the crowd groaned. Suddenly, Woods was at
12-under par, holding just a one-stroke lead. The game was on.
</P>
<P>
   And Woods quickly sensed that many in the crowd were pulling for
Garcia. ``I could tell the crowds were changing when some guy
yelled out, `Thousand dollars you don't slice it in the water on
No. 17,''' said Woods. ``They were saying some pretty tough things.
You had to block it out and execute your golf shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia made a costly bogey on No. 15, hitting his tee shot into
the right rough. His next shot was a great one, a low liner with a
7-iron from beneath a tree that he shaped left to right and onto
the back of the green. But Garcia was left with a difficult
downhill chip, then me missed his eight-foot par attempt coming
back and settled for a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   However, Garcia's most memorable shot of the tournament came on
the next hole, when he saved par at No. 16. He hit another tee shot
into the right rough, and the ball nestled six inches from the
trunk of a tree, resting between two roots. From where Garcia
stood, 189 yards from the hole, he couldn't see the flag, but he
had a glimpse of the left side of the green. The safe play would
have been to hit a wedge into the fairway. But Garcia rarely opts
for safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine out of 10 guys on the PGA Tour would have pitched into
the fairway without even thinking,'' said Jerry Higginbotham, who
spent years caddying for Mark O'Meara, before joining Garcia
earlier this year. ``I started to tell him to pitch out, but I've
seen this kid pull off so many things, I figured I'd let him go
ahead. I can't tell you how impossible that shot was. But he did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia took a 6-iron, closed his eyes on the downswing, but
somehow hit the ball squarely. It sailed toward the left rough,
made a sharp right turn, and flew toward the green. Garcia started
running up the hill like Carl Lewis, racing toward the green to see
if he had executed his miracle shot. He had. The ball rolled onto
the green, about 50 feet from the hole, and the gallery around the
16th green shook the ground. Garcia held his heart and bent over,
then resumed his walk to the green, where he two-parted to save par
and remain two strokes back.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, he was only a stroke behind, after Woods didn't
get up and down from the right bunker. But the tournament was
decided on then next two holes. Garcia had a chance to tie on the
par 3, 206-yard No. 17, but he missed a 15-foot birdie attempt that
broke left right away and never really had a chance. Then Woods
made a tremendous par save at No. 17, when his tee shot went long
into the rough, but he hit a delicate chip shot to eight feet, then
made one of the biggest putts of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Trust your stroke and bury it,''' said Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia wasn't done, making one last threat to tie at the
par-4 finishing hole, hitting a strong approach shot about 15 feet
below the hole. Garcia glanced back at the scoreboard and saw that
Woods was still only stroke ahead. But the putt that would have
tied rolled right of the hole, as Garcia hung his head.
</P>
<P>
   All Woods needed now at No. 18 was a par, and he got it, hitting
his approach shot to 20 feet, hitting a lag putt one foot short,
then tapping in for victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was Woods' fifth victory this year, his fourth in America,
the 11th PGA Tour victory of his career. He is No. 1 on the tour's
leader money list this year, and he can probably start writing his
Player of the Year award speech.
</P>
<P>
   At age 23, Jack Nicklaus had won three majors on his way to
winning 18. Woods has two, and this one, he will never forget,
because a player four years younger gave him everything he wanted.
Yet, when it was over, Woods was where he wants to be _ sitting on
to of the golf world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
