<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8164 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-STRAWPOLL-DOLE-KAN &LR;      08-15 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAWPOLL-DOLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE RE-EMERGES AS STRONG PRESIDENTIAL CONTENDER AFTER STRAW POLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ The pundits' old conventional wisdom on
Elizabeth Dole's campaign: a disappointment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new: definitely back in the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a third-place finish in Saturday's Iowa straw poll, Dole
re-established herself as a top-tier Republican presidential
contender who is prepared to go the distance against front-runner
George W. Bush, the Texas governor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dole's allowed to say that she's still in this race,'' said
Rich Galen, a former Newt Gingrich ally who is not affiliated with
any candidate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole garnered 14 percent of the vote, less than half of Bush's
31 percent. The former Labor Secretary and president of the
American Red Cross pointed out, however, that she spent only a
fraction of the money that Bush and second-place finisher Steve
Forbes poured into the race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Dole didn't populate her straw poll tent with big-name
entertainers and sports stars as other campaigns did to attract
votes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Dole, her low-budget performance was a smashing triumph, and
she proclaimed it as such Sunday at a noon rally at her Iowa
campaign headquarters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we have a great victory last night?'' she asked a roaring
crowd. ``Fabulous.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole's re-emergence after weeks of doubt about her fledgling
effort was just one significant development in the straw poll's
wake. Disappointed by his sixth-place finish, former Tennessee Gov.
Lamar Alexander appeared ready to pack it in. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to sit down ... and reconsider my candidacy,''
Alexander said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate suffering the poor-finish blues was former
Vice President Dan Quayle, who came in eighth, with 4 percent. But
he said he wasn't quitting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I'm the only one who can put together the Reagan
coalition,'' he said on CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Quayle's rivals, religious conservative Gary Bauer, who
finished fourth with 9 percent, can now argue he should be the
right wing's rallying point, analysts said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-place finisher Pat Buchanan was disappointed. He continued
to flirt with the idea of abandoning the GOP to run on the Reform
Party ticket. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magazine publisher Steve Forbes, meantime, made the case that he
should be the choice of the party's right wing as a result of his
second-place, 21 percent showing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm emerging as the conservative alternative,'' said
Forbes, who spent an estimated $1 million or more on the straw
poll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared to solidify his front-runner standing. On Sunday,
aides pointed out that Bush entered the race only weeks ago and
despite flush coffers, did not spend any money advertising on radio
or television before Saturday's vote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this the Iowa way,'' meaning that Bush developed a
strong grass-roots network, spokeswoman Karen Hughes said on ``Meet
the Press.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Dole may get the biggest boost of any candidate from the
nonscientific, nonbinding straw poll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the event, some reports portrayed Dole
as something of a letdown, disorganized and unprepared to
capitalize on the crush of early attention her candidacy received. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, no assistants were on hand to collect names or
donations in February when Dole attracted more than 2,000 Iowans to
an Ames speech, an eye-popping total for an early campaign event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And her fund-raising total of just $3.5 million paled in
comparison to Bush's $36.3 million through the end of June. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, however, those disappointments had faded. Asked at
headquarters how she would capitalize on her showing, Dole didn't
hesitate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Just continuing to work hard,'' she told reporters. ``To me,
that's it. You put in the hard work, you build a great team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As if to demonstrate her commitment, Dole spent painstaking
minutes autographing a pair of T-shirts stretched taut across the
back of a young supporter. She signed posters and at one point, she
took on the task of signing a baseball, which she described as no
easy task. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But she plowed ahead, slowly inscribing each letter of her name
while appearing undaunted by how long she was taking and how many
people still waited to greet her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a slow writer,'' Dole said, adding to her reputation as a
perfectionist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole also fed criticism, as Bush has, that she refuses to take
stands on contentious issues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Sunday morning news shows, Dole declined to answer
questions on whether she believed in evolution or the creationist
view of how the world developed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person of strong faith,'' Dole responded, refusing to
elaborate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She also would not say what steps she would take to stop the
flow of illegal drugs from Mexico. ``I'm going to leave open my
options at this point.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   None of that appeared to matter to her jubilant supporters
Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think everyone sees her as someone to be reckoned
with now,'' said Aimee Sullivan, 24, of Springfield, Ill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Her campaign is re-energized,'' declared Cindy Wycoff of Sioux
City, Iowa, whose daughter works for Dole. But Wycoff acknowledged
that she wasn't sure Dole could get past Bush. ``It'll be hard,''
she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll demonstrated that Dole could transform curious
onlookers excited about the prospect of the nation's first woman
president into loyal supporters, said Steve Roberts, Dole's
honorary campaign chairman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, 1987 and 1995, the eventual GOP nominee was among the
top three straw poll finishers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the pundits take my candidacy seriously now,'' Dole
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990815.0200 </DOCNO>
