<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8171 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE-COX     08-15 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods takes PGA
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Advantage, Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop, The Country Club, Brookline, Mass., for the Ryder Cup
matches in September.
</P>
<P>
   This was only Round One Sunday under an azure sky at Medinah
Country Club. There will be at least a hundred or so more such
confrontations over the next 20 years. By the time Tiger Woods and
Sergio Garcia stop flailing against each other in major golf
championships around the globe, enough hardware and cold cash will
have been distributed to construct a row of Las Vegas casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the old man of 23, bested the 19-year-old Spaniard Sunday
in the 81st PGA Championship in a final-round drama that evolved
sufficiently to place television executives into near-ecstasy.
David Duval-Woods? Forget it. Short of Arnold and Jack dipping
their tootsies into a Fountain of Youth and re-appearing on the
scene in a flood of polyester, it could get no better than this.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't really over until Woods gutted in a 8-foot par
putt at the 17th after hitting into the gunch and Garcia's 15-foot
birdie putt at the 18th stayed out of the hole. Winning his second
major championship 28 months after shocking the world at the 1997
Masters, Woods won by a stroke, at 11-under-par 277 on a closing
even-par 72. Garcia, with a 71, finished at 10-under 278.
</P>
<P>
   Three strokes back came Stewart Cink, who started the day two
shots back but could not find any putting success during a 73 and
finished at 8-under 280. Falling four shots short was two-time
champion Nick Price, who crashed with a double-bogey at the 16th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot more pressure here,'' Woods said, comparing the
Masters and his second professional major. ``If I had lost that
nine-shot lead, I probably would have killed myself. . . It's hard
to compare the two (majors) because they're two completely
different situations. One was for the (Masters) record and had more
of a social impact than this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the back nine Sunday, Woods, who started the day
tied Canada's Mike Weir at 11-under, put the excitement back in the
afternoon. Ahead of Garcia by five shots through 11 holes, Woods
suddenly was up by only one. After Garcia birdied the 13th,
igniting a crowd that jumped on him as the favorite, he pumped his
fist and gave a glance back to Woods on the teebox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to know I was still there and to show him that he
had to finish well to win,'' Garcia said. ``It wasn't a bad thing.
I did it with good feelings, not hoping he would make a
triple-bogey of something. I was kind of telling him, `If you want
to win, you have to play well.'''
</P>
<P>
   Woods didn't triple-bogey, but almost. While the Medinah crowd,
loosening up through the Budweiser effect, threw insults toward him
and playing partner Mike Weir, Woods flew over the 13th green with
a 6-iron chipped back long and eventually missed a bogey putt from
eight feet. The lead had been whittled to one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   After Garcia bogeyed the 15th, he parred the 16th with an
off-balance, face-wide-open shot from the base of a large tree that
found the green with a shot right out of Seve Ballesteros'
scrapbook. Woods then bogeyed the 16th, overestimating the wind on
a 186-yard, uphill 8-iron and finding the bunker, and the lead was
back to one again.
</P>
<P>
   At the 17th, Woods basically put an overlapping grip on the
Wanamaker Trophy. After missing the green of the 206-yard par-3 and
finding the high grass, Woods chipped delicately to eight feet,
then firmly struck a left-edge putt and sank it for par. A slow
pump of his fist sensed a job almost done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just inside the left edge,'' Woods said. ``I said,
`Just go ahead and just trust your stroke and bury it.' I said,
`Keep nice and steady and let the blade release,' and it released
perfectly. I looked up and the ball was going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Two putts at the 18th and Woods had his second major -- a fifth
of you count the three U.S. Amateurs. But golf had the making of
the rivalry it so much wishes to follow. In the matador-like
Garcia, who Sunday was running up the fairway to see his ball land
and leaping in the air, Woods has fiery competition that hasn't
been there during TV's attempt to channel Woods against Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Sergio played a wonderful round of golf,'' Woods said.
``He did what he needed to do, and he needs to be commended for not
only the way he played, but the way he conducted himself. He was
emotional, yes, but he was fiery. He was trying. He never dogged
it, and it was wonderful to see.''''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I turned pro, I wanted to be the No. 1 golfer in the
world,'' said Garcia, ``so I knew I would be a rival for Tiger. ..
. I'm a little unhappy I didn't win, but inside of me I feel like I
won. Being 19 years old, you can't ask for anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
