<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY GENERAL TO CHALLENGE $5 BILLION MERGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly on Monday will
formally appeal the approval of two electric and gas utility
mergers totaling nearly $5 billion and affecting 2 million Eastern
Massachusetts customers, contending Governor Paul Cellucci's
administration betrayed consumers' interests in backing the deals.
</P>
<P>
   Under a procedure last used in 1984, officials said Sunday,
Reilly will challenge the state Department of Telecommunications
and Energy's approval of new rate plans supporting the Boston
Edison-Commonwealth Energy merger and the acquisition of Colonial
Gas by the parent company of Boston Gas.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, utility regulators appointed by Cellucci have
been criticized by consumer and business groups for allowing the
utilities to charge customers for hundreds of millions of dollars'
worth of ``acquisition premiums'' being paid to shareholders and
investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 40 years, for example, the 1.3 million customers
of Edison and ComEnergy will be charged for about $500 million _
and by Reilly's estimates closer to $1 billion _ worth of
merger-related costs. That includes the value of cash and stock
being distributed to the companies' shareholders in excess of what
the companies were worth before they agreed to merge.
</P>
<P>
   In connection with their mergers, Edison and ComEnergy have
agreed to freeze rates for four years. Colonial would cut the
cost-of-gas part of the bill by 2.2 percent immediately, and freeze
the other part of the bill _ the cost of distributing gas _ for 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with all four utilities say that consumers, over time,
will save far more on monthly bills than the acquisition premiums
will cost them, and will also get better service.
</P>
<P>
   But officials Sunday said Reilly thinks current rates are too
high and should be cut, not merely frozen, and consumers should get
stronger guarantees of receiving savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't fault Edison or Boston Gas for doing what they can
for their shareholders, but the DTE is charged with protecting the
ratepayers,'' a person close to Reilly, who asked for anonymity,
said Sunday. ``We don't think they did that in these cases. We
think we are the last hope for protecting ratepayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly will appeal the rate rulings to the DTE and also, Monday
or later this week, to the Supreme Judicial Court, which handles
conflicts between state agencies. The last attorney general to use
this appeal process was Francis X. Bellotti in a 1984 Fitchburg Gas
&AMP; Electric case, Reilly aides said.
</P>
<P>
   DTE chairwoman Janet Gail Besser has defended the agency's
handling of acquisition premiums, saying she is confident that both
combinations will produce, in the long run, lower costs and better
service for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies won't receive the acquisition premium unless
savings from the merger equal or exceed it,'' Besser said, adding
that in the future ``it's a good possibility there will be some
justification for lowering rates.''
</P>
<P>
   L. Carl Gustin, senior vice president of Edison parent BEC
Energy, said state regulators ``recognized, and there was
sufficient evidence to recognize, that the savings will
significantly outweigh the costs over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Edison and ComEnergy officials expect the $4.4 billion merger of
their holding companies into a new company called NStar will close
within a month. Gustin said the 1.3 million Eastern Massachusetts
customers served by the utilities will pay $3.5 billion less on
their bills over the next 40 years than they would if the companies
did not merge.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Edison-ComEnergy combination and the $495 million
acquisition of Colonial Gas by Boston Gas parent Eastern
Enterprises involve holding-company combinations, which are not
subject to state approval. However, the deals do involve, and
regulators last month approved, new rate schedules for Colonial,
ComEnergy, and Edison.
</P>
<P>
   While Reilly challenges the new rate plans, consumers would
continue to pay current rates, and it appears unlikely that
Reilly's action would derail or delay the mergers.
</P>
<P>
   The fight will not affect the planned 5 percent electric rate
reduction mandated to take effect Sept. 1 under last year's
industry restructuring law.
</P>
<P>
   Taking on the utility mergers could help Reilly, a former
Middlesex district attorney who has emphasized his crime-fighter
role, address charges made by his 1998 primary-election foe, former
state senator Lois G. Pines, that Reilly would fall short on the
consumer-protection aspect of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Groups as diverse as Associated Industries of Massachusetts, the
state's biggest business lobby, and the Massachusetts Public
Interest Research Group, a Ralph Nader-established consumer group,
have opposed the Edison-ComEnergy merger and have considered their
own suits to block it.
</P>
<P>
   MassPIRG energy program director Rob Sargent praised Reilly,
saying: ``Somebody needs to send a message to the electric
utilities that they have been getting exactly what they wanted for
too long, and somebody needs to step in and let them know the time
has come for the consumer to take priority. People are getting fed
up with the greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the nation, regulators have long struggled with how to
handle utility mergers. Many believe that unless shareholders can
get some benefit, mergers _ even those that ultimately save
consumers money and improve service _ will never be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, including Kentucky and Maryland, have required that
utility shareholders split savings 50-50 with consumers. Other
states _ including until recently Massachusetts _ have forbidden
merging utilities to charge costs to customers, a stance that
largely thwarted utility combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Gustin said Edison and ComEnergy customers will get far more
than half the savings from meshing the companies, because under the
rate order ``all the net savings are intended to flow to customers
and not be shared with shareholders after the costs are
recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Besser said Massachusetts law ``doesn't really have a good
mechanism'' for mandating as a precondition that merger savings be
passed on to consumers. But she said, ``We do think customers can
be protected under the procedures we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
