<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DOUBT CAST ON RUSSIAN CLAIMS IN DAGESTAN FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to make inserts for clarification in 19th graf of 1st take,
bgng Nobody knows..., and 8th graf of 2nd take, bgng Amid the... No
other changes.)  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Trying to reassure an anxious nation that it was not
being drawn into a Chechnya-like quagmire, Russian commanders
insisted Sunday that Islamic militants dug into remote mountain
strongholds in the southern republic of Dagestan were already on
the verge of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of fighting, commanders said Russian warplanes,
helicopters and artillery had begun to decimate the rebels. Now,
they insisted, Russian troops were ferreting out the die-hards to
destroy Shamil Basayev, the Chechen commander of the insurgents,
and his band of rebels once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about a total liquidation of the militants,''
Gen. Anatoly Kvashnin, the chief of the Russian general staff,
boldly declared.
</P>
<P>
   But some of Russia's most knowledegable military specialists are
skeptical that a victory can be delivered within the two weeks the
commanders have promised _ if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Dagestan, they say, may not be another Chechnya _ a bloody
two-year war that killed tens of thousands, humiliated the
once-proud Russian military and led to the de facto independence of
that republic.
</P>
<P>
   But it does present similar traps, they warn, like being lured
into a heavy-handed and widening military campaign that risks
alienating the local population. Even in this early stage, the
conflict has become an unwelcome challenge to a Russian military
left demoralized by the Chechen war and which sought to restore
some of its lost luster this summer by racing to Kosovo ahead of
NATO peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian military has learned nothing from Chechnya and is
totally unprepared for this war,'' said Pavel Felgenhauer, a
military analyst with the newspaper Segodnya. ``It can't be done
with airpower alone and the troops are not good enough to take the
ground. Shamil Basayev still has the initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Chechnya, there are several important political factors
in the Russians' favor this time. The local authorities in
Dagestan, as well as a multitude of ethnic groups, are so far
backing the campaign against the militants, who say they want to
set up a new Islamic state. Nor do the rebels have the support of
the Chechen government in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of sheer firepower, the rebels are heavily outgunned
and have not been able to infiltrate Dagestan's major towns and
cities, a telling development for those who recall how the Chechen
rebels turned Grozny into an urban killing zone for Russian armored
columns.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians of all stripes in Moscow also seem to back the
military campaign, including sharp critics of the Chechen war like
Grigory Yavlinsky, the leader of the Yabloko party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is radically different from what occurred in Chechnya,''
Yavlinsky said Sunday. ``That was a war by separatists who had 95
percent of the population behind them. This is aggression by
Islamic extremists against Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   But the insurgents do have some things going for them. They know
the mountain terrain and are familiar with Russian air and ground
tactics from the Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   They are also counting on confusion among the hodge-podge of
paratroop, Interior Ministry and police units that constitutes the
Russian force in Dagestan _ a problem that bedeviled the Russian
military during the Chechen conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders insist they have streamlined their command
structure in Dagestan and have vowed to produce a victory within
the next two weeks. If so, they have accomplished a miraculous
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he was ousted as prime minister on Aug. 9, Sergei
Stepashin complained that no one was really in charge of the
situation in Dagestan because Russian commanders were reluctant to
put their reputations on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who remember 1994 and 1995 are afraid to take
responsibility,'' Stepashin said, referring to the disastrous
Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   Lodged between the oil-rich Caspian Sea and the mountains of the
North Caucuses, Dagestan has only about 2 million people, drawn
from more than 30 ethnic groups. While Russia's economic crisis has
weakened Moscow's authority there, the Dagestan authorities want to
remain part of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting began when Basayev and Khattab, a Jordanian-born
militant who joined up with the Chechen leader during the Chechen
war, led hundreds of Islamic militants across the border and
proclaimed that they would establish a new Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows for sure how many fighters are involved, but the
Russian Interior Ministry has estimated that there are 1,200
militants, one-third of whom have remained in reserve in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has declined to say how many troops it has
in Dagestan, but experts estimate they number several thousand,
several hundred of which are directly involved in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   While Russian commanders insist they have enough combat-hardened
troops, several thousand of Russia's best paratroopers are not
available for the fight. They are on peacekeeping missions in
Bosnia-Herzogovina and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Russian officials say that 14 Russian soldiers and more
than 200 guerrillas have been killed in the fighting in Dagestan.
The rebels deny they have suffered such heavy losses and say they
have killed far more Russian troops, including three Russian
prisoners who were allegedly shot when they tried to escape.
</P>
<P>
   This is a conflict, however, that involves politics as much as
body counts. If the Russians level Dagestan villages and
settlements in their hunt for the rebels, they risk turning the
local population against them.
</P>
<P>
   Large-scale bombing raids or even a ground assault against rebel
bases in Chechnya might deprive the militants of their havens near
Dagestan. But they could also incite more Chechens to join the
militants. In fact, some analysts think Basayev's strategy is to
lure the Russians to do precisely that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you escalate you are giving the enemy an advantage,'' said
Dimitri Trenin, a former lieutenant colonel in the Russian military
and the deputy director of the Moscow office of the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of mounting an all-out offensive, Trenin said, the
Russian military should try to contain the rebels in Dagestan by
conducting a diplomatic effort to cut off their foreign sources of
financial support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military force alone will not yield the results Russia is
looking for,'' he said. ``There is no quick-fix policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is not how the Russian military is talking. On Sunday,
Col. Gen. Anatoly Kornukov, the commander of the Russian air force,
told the Russian news agency Interfax that the Islamic militants
would soon be defeated by a punishing offensive involving the
``full-scale'' use of airpower.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the bravado on both sides, the conflict still
appears to be in the early stages. Responding to the incursion by
the militants, the Russian military has poured troops into Botlikh,
a town near the Chechen border which is surrounded by
rebel-infested hills. And for several days Russian troops have been
fighting to take the high ground.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Russian Interior Ministry in Dagestan
asserted that the Russians had killed another 21 rebels on Sunday
and that only four of the 32 villages in the Botlikh region were
now controlled by the militants.
</P>
<P>
   Dagestani authorities, for their part, announced Sunday that
Dagestani villagers had foiled a column of 60 militants led by
Basayev's brother by carrying out a daring ambush that involved
rolling boulders onto the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels said they would respond to the Russian attacks with a
new offensive. And even the Russians conceded that the militants
were continuing to send reinforcements from Chechen territory.
</P>
<P>
   As the fighting intensified, Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov
warned the Russians not to carry out attacks against targets in
Chechnya and decreed a monthlong state of emergency, which calls
for a 10 p.m. curfew and the mobilization of veterans of the
Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   Russian planes struck a rebel base on Friday near the Chechen
town of Kenkhi, located near the border with Dagestan. But the
Russians have not announced any bombing attacks against Chechen
targets since then.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have also insisted that they are not planning a
land invasion of Chechnya despite Gen. Kvashnin's vow to wipe out
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the swirl of allegations and countercharges, it has not
always been clear how Russian forces have been used. Last week, two
Soviet-made warplanes zoomed over Georgia, which borders Chechnya,
and dropped Soviet-made cluster bombs on a Georgian village.
</P>
<P>
   After initially denying that any air attack took place, Russian
authorities conceded that there had been a bombing raid but stopped
short of acknowledging that Russian aircraft were involved. And
Russia's air force chief made no mention of the incident on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely satisfied with the Air Force's operation
against the militants,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
