<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SNAPSHOP-SFCHRON &LR;      08-15 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAPSHOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
Startup Mixes Net Shops, Communities
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Dan Fost
</P>
<P>
   A new service from a small San Francisco software company aims
to add virtual stores to the virtual communities that are sprouting
online.
</P>
<P>
   Snapshop.com, a Web service from the eight-person Haight Street
firm Media in Motion, is being tested on Delphi Forums, where 2
million members talk about everything from Honda motorcycles to
polymer clay in 80,000 active forums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about marrying commerce with community. The
problem is, everything today is pretty intrusive,'' said Jim
Leightheiser director of product management for Delphi Forums in
Cambridge, Mass. Delphi is testing Snapshop and plans to make it
available to all of its forum hosts at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   By intrusive, Leightheiser means irritating ads for minivans or
microwaves that pop up in forums where the topics are macrame or
cable modems. Instead, Snapshop enables a forum's host to control
what is offered in the store.
</P>
<P>
   If someone in, say, a mountain biking forum talks about a great
new tire, the host could offer that tire for sale.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Media In Motion has struck deals with scores of
vendors supplying a range of products to Internet users, and it
plans to add more as quirky new forums come online.
</P>
<P>
   It offers 3 million products from a wide range of companies,
including Black and Decker, Broderbund, Cuisinart, Fisher Price,
Fruit of the Loom, Maytag, Merriam-Webster, Nine West, Rawlings,
Samsonite, Serta Mattress, Timberland, Toshiba and Wrangler. The
main challenge Snapshop needs to overcome is the pitfall of trying
to sell a product to people who are online to talk, not shop.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SNAPSHOP (1057 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Good conversation isn't necessarily the same thing as wanting
to go shopping for something,'' said Howard Rheingold of Mill
Valley, the author of ``Virtual Community.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Pillitteri, president of Media In Motion, said that if
people ``think the forum is being commercialized, they'll speak
up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's a trusted environment, it makes sense to enable
people to make purchases,'' Pillitteri said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rich, who is host of a Delphi forum on Honda Shadow
motorcycles, said Snapshop is welcome as long as it's a service to
his group's 5,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you own a motorcycle, you can never stop spending enough
money in things to bolt onto it,'' said Rich, 55, an investment
manager in Dallas. He hopes Snapshop will enable members to band
together and receive group discounts from merchandisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in making any money from this,'' Rich said.
``I want vendors to offer substantial discounts. Snapshop has a way
that I can take whatever commission I'd earn and turn it into
discounts for the members. That's what I plan to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like an online forum can have the feel of a coffee shop
discussion, a recommendation to buy something from someone you've
met online can have the same weight as from a real-life neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this new world of networked retail, there's a lot of
referrals that are going to happen,'' said Bruce Katz, chief
executive of Well Engaged, a Sausalito firm that plans to use
Snapshop in a large online discussion site it now is developing. It
might also offer Snapshop to companies who use Well Engaged
software to create their own online communities, such as E-Trade,
CBS Sportsline and Forbes. Katz also is an investor in Snapshop,
and the largest investor in Delphi.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of SNAPSHOP (1057 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``We're looking at a whole new world of distributed retailing,''
Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   Blaine Mathieu, senior analyst specializing in e-commerce at the
San Jose research firm Dataquest, said Snapshop has a good idea in
bringing the wares of many merchants into one ``universal shopping
basket.'' That way, customers don't have to click once on a book
from one source, and again to buy a fishing pole from another
source.
</P>
<P>
   That should appeal to online communities who don't like sending
their customers off to other sites like Amazon.com or eToys.
</P>
<P>
   Inktomi, a San Mateo firm, provides a similar service to major
sites such as Yahoo, Mathieu said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
