<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIONBANK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
Union Bank Plans To Reduce Ranks By 1,400 People
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Union Bank of California, the second-largest bank headquartered in
the Golden State, will disclose a plan today to fire about 1,400
employees _ 15 percent of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the San Francisco bank said the cutback will affect
virtually all its business units, although some will feel the
effects more than others.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly two-thirds of the job cuts will be in Southern
California, where most Union employees work, while between 100 and
200 positions are likely to be lost in the Bay Area. The job cuts
are part of an 18-month program, dubbed ``Mission Excel,'' to
streamline bank operations and boost pretax profits by $225 million
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors who bought Union's stock in a public
offering last year demanded a cost-cutting campaign designed to
bring the bank's staffing and efficiency levels to industry
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, which is 64 percent owned by Japan's Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi, is carrying out the program despite record
revenue and profits. In the three months that ended in June, Union
earned $114.7 million, up 11 percent from the comparable period the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we can do even better,'' said spokesman Stephen
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of California bank jobs have disappeared in the 1990s
as a result of cost-cutting drives and mergers involving longtime
institutions such as Bank of America and Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something other banks have already done,'' said Joseph
Morford, a San Francisco analyst with the brokerage firm Dain
Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
   Although Union never offered the lifetime job guarantees that
until recently were normal in Japan, the bank developed a
reputation as a benevolent employer that was slow to eliminate
unnecessary or redundant positions.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, which has $32 billion in assets and 241 branches in
California, took its current form four years ago when Japan's Bank
of Tokyo combined with Mitsubishi Bank and the two merged their
California units, the old Union Bank and Bank of California.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of UNIONBAN (76562 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The two banks avoided the slash-and-burn tactics American banks
usually follow when they merge. Relatively few positions were
eliminated, and those cuts largely took place through attrition.
What changed things was Union's 1998 sale of stock to U.S.
investors, a deal intended to raise cash for the Japanese parent
bank, then struggling amid that country's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure from investors gave the bank's American managers the
ammunition they needed to persuade Chief Executive Officer Takahiro
Moriguchi and wary officials of the parent company to give the
go-ahead for an ambitious cost-cutting and revenue-generating plan.
The bank then promised investors that it would cut its overhead to
about 55 cents for each dollar of revenue it takes in, down from
the current level of more than 60 cents for each dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of this greater focus on shareholder value which
they are hoping to translate into a higher stock price,'' Morford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $225 million in higher profits the program is trying to
produce, officials said about $135 million will come from shrinking
the workforce and other initiatives to pare costs. An additional
$90 million will come from higher revenue generated mainly by
raising fees charged to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Union will set aside $85 million in the current fiscal quarter
to cover the costs of the program, including $70 million for
severance.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who lose their jobs will receive as much as three
weeks' pay for every year of service with a minimum of four weeks
and a maximum of one year's salary, depending on their rank. The
bank will notify staff members who are losing their jobs by the end
of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and company insiders have warned that a deep
cost-cutting program could jeopardize Union's high level of
personal service, something that has been a competitive advantage
for the bank as Bank of America and Wells Fargo cut back branch
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer service is something they are going to have to be
very careful about,'' said Morford.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of UNIONBAN (76562 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The bank insists that it is taking pains to preserve high service
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``By changing the way we do business, we can do things more
efficiently without sacrificing our ability to provide customer
service,'' said Johnson, the bank spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said job cuts are taking place mainly in administrative
and back-office operations, especially those that perform
overlapping functions. For example, private banking service for
wealthy customers, currently a separate operation, will be combined
with a separate program for customers who keep large balances with
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will close some of its 20 processing and call centers,
but will not identify which ones until later, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Partially offsetting its cost cuts, Union plans to spend more on
Internet operations, telecommunications and branch-level computer
systems. No branches will be closed through the program, but they
will lose one or two staff members each. Johnson said service
levels will not suffer because the bank will move administrative
tasks out of the branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We answer 5.7 million calls a year in the branches,'' Johnson
said. ``We will push people to use our tele-services and computer
services instead.''
</P>
<P>
   To plan Mission Excel, Union hired a consulting firm experienced
with in-bank cost-cutting programs and assigned dozens of top
managers to work on the project full time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
