<SLUG> BC-PHONENET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
Soon, You'll Surf the Web From Your Cell Phone
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
On September 20, consumers will get their first peek at the next
hot thing in cell phones _ Web access.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS plans to unveil the first mass-market Web phones next
month, allowing users to surf the Net, send and receive e-mail and
trade stocks _ all from the same size handset we now use to make a
cell phone call.
</P>
<P>
   While Sprint is the first to market, a slew of carriers plans to
introduce wireless Web phones over the next year as companies look
for ways to attract more cell phone users. Most of the phones will
allow customers to get e-mail, browse the Web and order products
online.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has teamed up with Yahoo, which created a wireless Web
portal that allows users to tap into a portion of the World Wide
Web. The Yahoo portal also provides personalized content for cell
phones, so users can get updates on sports scores, news and stocks
sent directly to their handsets.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's wireless Web service works with a minibrowser that
accesses Web content formatted specifically for a cell phone
handset. Because the screens on cell phones are so small, the Web
browsing is limited mainly to text and to sites that have created
specialized ``minibrowser'' pages. The minibrowser technology was
developed by Redwood City's Phone.com.
</P>
<P>
   The forthcoming Palm VII personal organizer uses a similar
approach to Web access. Although few Web pages have adapted their
content for the small format, Sprint said more sites will be
available during the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who spend at least $29.99 a month on Sprint PCS phone
service can add Web access for $9.99 a month. The company has
higher-usage plans with up to 1,200 voice and data minutes for
about $180 per month.
</P>
<P>
   To access the Web, customers with older cell phones will need to
get a new model. All Sprint PCS phones can get text-message updates
from Yahoo, but the Web access is available only on Sprint PCS
models launched in 1999 and beyond. The company is introducing four
new wireless Web phones, including a ``Smartphone'' by NeoPoint of
San Diego. The NeoPoint phone integrates a personal digital
assistant with a phone and Web access. That model _ Sprint PCS
NP1000 _ is expected to sell for about $400 and will be available
in September. The other phones start at $100.
</P>
<P>
   With its latest offering, Sprint also is trying to tap into a
cadre of mobile workers by giving them a way to wirelessly connect
their laptop to the Internet. The company plans to sell kits _
ranging from about $30 to about $200 _ that lets customers plug
their cell phone into a laptop and get wireless Web access.
</P>
<P>
   The phones access the Web at about 14.4 kilobits per second _
about the speed of an older dial-up modem. But Sprint officials
downplayed the speed, saying the convenience of having integrated
phone and Web access makes the product a quick solution for people
on the go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get off the airplane, go to your gate, log on and
check your e-mail and your corporate intranet from your laptop,''
said Charles Levine, chief sales and marketing officer for Sprint
PCS. Or you can get your e-mail and check whether your next flight
is on time directly from your handset, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who track wireless technology said that while wireless
Web products are likely to mature over the next few years, the
Sprint offering is a significant first move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important evolutionary step,'' said Andrew
Cole, head of the wireless practice at Renaissance Worldwide, a
consulting firm. ``Unlike some of the technology that has come
before, Sprint has a robust network that's very powerful. And the
company has realized that if you can make it simple and price it
well, you'll have a winning product.''
</P>
<P>
   However, mobile customers should not expect wireless Web phones
to take the place of traditional Internet surfing anytime soon,
Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very suitable for short messages, but clearly, it's
not good for cruising the Internet,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``it's a positive first beginning both for
Sprint and consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
