<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINEINVEST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
Buy Like Buffett Without Berkshire
<TEXT>
<P>
   By HARRY DOMASH
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A lot of us wish that we could invest like Warren Buffet _ and
for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett and his partners acquired control of Berkshire Hathaway,
then a textile company, in 1965. Since then, Buffet transformed
Berkshire into a conglomerate and, in effect, a closed-end mutual
fund, by acquiring a variety of businesses outright and purchasing
stock in other publicly traded companies.
</P>
<P>
   A $10,000 investment in Berkshire in 1965 would be worth about
$49 million today.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, anyone who hears about Buffett's investment success
wants to get in on the action. Berkshire Class A shares are going
for about $63,000, and the newer Class B stock is around $2,000.
Besides representing less ownership, the Class B shares have
limited voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fantastic track record, some investors don't see
Berkshire shares as a good deal today. They worry that Buffett's
reputation has created tremendous demand for Berkshire stock,
driving the share price to a hefty premium compared with the value
of the holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Berkshire Hathaway itself has become heavily
dependent on the insurance business (about 70 percent of revenues)
and that the near-term outlook for the industry is clouded.
</P>
<P>
   For these investors, it makes more sense just to buy the same
publicly traded stocks Berkshire owns, thereby avoiding the
questions surrounding Berkshire itself.
</P>
<P>
   You could get a handle on Berkshire's holdings by reading its
annual reports and by carefully following the news.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could go online to Today's Value Investor
( &LR; www.tvinvestor.com &LR; ), run by Timothy Vick, a self-described
disciple of Warren Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   Click on Buffett Watch to see TVI's best estimate of Berkshire's
holdings. Berkshire doesn't issue a press release every time it
buys or sells a stock, so the information, gleaned mostly from
annual reports, can be months old.
</P>
<P>
   Because Buffett is a long-term investor, usually holding a stock
for many years, the lack of timeliness isn't a major concern. The
site's primary purpose is selling subscriptions to TVI's
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire's largest holdings include Coca-Cola, Gillette, Wells
Fargo Bank and Walt Disney. Some say these stocks have had their
day and likely will underperform the market in the future, and
because Buffett rarely sells, he is stuck with these companies.
Others fret that because Buffett avoids medical and technology
companies, he is missing the best future investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   These investors figure that it's better to do what Buffett would
do if he were just starting out today than to copy his existing
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett makes no secret of his stock-selection approach. His
``Chairman's Letter'' accompanies each Berkshire annual report.
Taken together, these letters describe his stock-picking
philosophy. You can download the letters going back to 1977 from
the Berkshire Hathaway site ( &LR; www.berkshirehathaway.com &LR; ).
Buffett's stock-picking style combines elements of both value and
growth investing.
</P>
<P>
   Green Mountain Asset Management Corp.'s Web site ( &LR; www. &LR; 
 &LR; stockresearch.com &LR; ) uses an investment philosophy ``quite similar
to that of Warren Buffett,'' according to information on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Bose, a registered investment adviser with more than
20 years of experience, does the analysis and makes
recommendations. Bose has a list of current recommendations, but
new stocks are added only occasionally. For instance, he added
Pfizer on August 7, but that was only the second addition since
Aug. 18, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Current Buy section includes a summary for each stock.
Clicking on the company name brings up additional analysis. Access
to the site is free.
</P>
<P>
   Another more active site is the Investment Mill
( &LR; www.investmentmill.com &LR; ) run by Gerald Oney, Jeffrey Fry and
Steve Lilley. They're all research analysts, with about 25 years of
combined experience. They are ``long-term, value oriented,'' but
like Buffett, they don't limit themselves to value stocks. They say
they will write ``positive notes about growth or even momentum
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, they're adding new stocks on an irregular basis.
They've added one company so far in August and three last month,
but prior to that, they hadn't added anything since April.
</P>
<P>
   Their research reports don't have a rigid report format; each
one focuses on factors the analyst views as important for that
company. Sometimes it's the operating statements and balance sheet
items, other times it's an analysis of the company's technology.
The reports are top quality, among the best I've seen on the Web.
The reports are free, but they plan to start charging within the
next two or three months.
</P>
<P>
   You also can search out your own Warren Buffett stocks using the
free search tool available at Market Player
( &LR; www.marketplayer.com &LR; ). Market Player's stock screening tools are
more sophisticated than most found on the Web. Learning to use them
takes some time, but fortunately, Market Player provides sample
screens to get you started.
</P>
<P>
   One of these samples specifically is designed to search out
stocks meeting Buffett's criteria, looking for reasonably priced
companies with stable earnings growth, good profitability ratios
and a strong balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Select Sample Screens on Market Player's home page and then
click on Try It Out, next to Warren Buffett Stable Growth Screen to
run the search. I got a list of 58 companies when I ran it last
week. You can refine the search if you want to take the time to
learn the screening tools.
</P>
<P>
   As with any screening system, you'll get best results by
considering the stock list as investment candidates to be
researched further.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in more information on Buffett and his
investing style, check out Warren Buffet Links ( &LR; buffett.8m.com &LR; ).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
