<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURA BELTS THIRD SLAM AND ROGERS ENDS METS' COMPLETE-GAME FAMINE
AT 139 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Robin Ventura comes to the plate with the
bases loaded, people are beginning to expect a grand slam. He
fulfilled those expectations Sunday, as he helped power the Mets to
a 12-5 pounding of the San Francisco Giants at 3Com Park with his
third grand slam of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He shared the spotlight with Kenny Rogers (2-0), who gave the
Mets their first complete game of the season after they had gone
139 games _ going back to Al Leiter's complete-game victory last
Sept. 4 _ without one. The major league record is 140, set set by
the Anaheim Angels this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other starters staged a little battle cry and gave him a
pep talk when he came in after the eighth,'' manager Bobby
Valentine said of Rogers. ``Then they came over to me and said he
was going out there. He was kind of cruising. I didn't see any
reason to use anybody else out there and he said he felt fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incentive to finish the game but it wasn't my
objective,'' Rogers said. ``When they scored all the runs in the
fifth and sixth, I knew I was going to stay in there until I had to
come out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I was just saying, `Three more outs. Let's get the
complete game.' There has been so much talk about this. We take
pride in the fact we're a good rotation and that was kind of a
negative number. But you get one, and you don't have to deal with
the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers gave up 12 hits, struck out eight and walked none. He
pitched three complete games for Oakland before being traded to the
Mets on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   The 13th grand slam of Ventura's major league career tied him
with his former teammate, Harold Baines, for the most grand slams
among active players and moved Ventura into a tie for tenth on the
career list. Lou Gehrig hit 23 grand slams during his Hall of Fame
career, the most by any player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea why I keep hitting them and I don't really care
to think about it,'' said Ventura, who hit grand slams earlier this
season in both games of a doubleheader sweep of the Milwaukee
Brewers, May 20, at Shea Stadium. ``I just think about hitting the
ball and if it goes out great. But I don't think you can think it's
a normal at-bat. You have to pretend it is, though. Because if you
go out thinking you're going to hit a home run in that situation,
you'll probably ground out to second.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura has not done that very often every base full. The
32-year-old third baseman is 7 for 13 (.538) with the three homers
and 21 runs batted in, in his first season with the Mets. For his
career, Ventura is 43 for 122 (.352) with the bases full with the
13 homers and a whopping 143 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's gotten to that point, where you expect
him to hit a grand slam every time,'' said Mike Piazza, who worked
Hernandez for a full-count walk to load the bases for Ventura.
``But he's definitely the guy we want to see up there in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and the bases loaded in the fifth inning, and the
Mets trailing by 3-2, Ventura drilled a 1-0 fastball from Livan
Hernandez over the right-field fence for his latest grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets (72-47) also received home runs from Mike Piazza and
Edgardo Alfonzo in a 16-hit attack.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it is almost impossible to explain Ventura's uncanny
success.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine gave it a shot, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because he understands the pitcher is in trouble in that
situation,'' Valentine said. ``And from what we've seen, he seeks a
good pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't everybody? Well, no, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first pitch wasn't and he took it,'' Valentine said.
``Some guys get a little anxious there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, he seems to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to make it a normal at-bat,'' Ventura said. ``I try
and block it out and do the same things I always do at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, that has meant driving in runs in bunches. Ventura
leads the team with 97 RBIs and he is quickly closing in on his
career-best of 105. That was in 1996 with the Chicago White Sox,
when Ventura hit a career-best 34 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's homer was his team leading 27th. And it was more
special than most. Ventura's family and four children were among
the 70-odd guests he had at the park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
