r f BC-REDHAT-SFCHRON &LR;      08-15 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDHAT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  Red Hat Using Its Head
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
How can a business succeed when potential customers can always get
its primary product for free?
</P>
<P>
   That question clearly didn't deter investors in Red Hat Inc.
last week. The Durham, N.C., company's main business is selling the
Linux operating system, which anyone can download at no charge from
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But when Red Hat made its initial public offering last week,
intense demand drove its share price up more than 500 percent in
three days _ from an opening price of $14 to a Friday close of
$85.25.
</P>
<P>
   That adds up to a market capitalization of almost $5.7 billion _
for an outfit that only has 140 employees and recorded sales of
just $10.8 million in the fiscal year that ended February 28.
</P>
<P>
   Is this just a reappearance of the same manic enthusiasm that
drove so many dubious Internet IPOs into the stratosphere earlier
this year? Will Red Hat also plummet back to earth in the coming
weeks? Perhaps. But Wall Street seems to believe that the company's
business plan makes more sense than a casual observer might
realize.
</P>
<P>
   The argument revolves around an ongoing transition in Red Hat's
business model _ from one that depends mainly on software sales to
one based primarily on its Web portal and on its growing service
and support programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, nearly all of the company's &LR;   &LR; revenues came from
sales of Red Hat Linux, a retail package that includes the Linux
``kernel'' _ the core code that coordinates a computer's operations
_ and more than 400 pieces of related software on CD-ROM discs,
plus a printed manual.
</P>
<P>
   Users could find the same software and thousands of pages of
help files on the Web, or simply copy it _ legally, under the terms
of the ``open source'' license under which Linux is distributed _
from a friend.
</P>
<P>
   A fair number of users, however, evidently are willing to pay
for the convenience of getting all the necessary software on CD-ROM
discs and documentation in printed form. In fact, according to
International Data Corp., sales of Linux last year accounted for
more than 17 percent of new operating-system licenses on machines
used as servers, the muscular computers that power corporate
networks and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat is only one of about half a dozen companies selling such
packages (known in Linux lingo as ``distributions''), but the
five-year-old North Carolina company is the clear leader. According
to IDC analyst Dan Kusnetzky., it currently accounts for about 44
percent of paid Linux licenses worldwide, compared with a mere 11.5
percent for the runner-up, a German company named Suse.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  With interest in Linux burgeoning, the product alone might be
enough to make Red Hat profitable soon. Last year, it lost only
$130,000 _ practically nothing by the standards of the Internet
age.
</P>
<P>
   And IDC's Kusnetzky believes that there's ample room for the
company to increase sales, particularly by packaging the OS with
other open-source software targeted at particular market segments _
schools, Internet service providers, medical offices and so on.
Just last week, Red Hat announced a release tailored to e-commerce
operations.
</P>
<P>
   But no one really thinks that software sales alone justify Red
Hat's enormous valuation. The key to its future, as it explained in
the prospectus and ``road show'' meetings with analysts and
institutional investors that preceded its IPO, is a plan to parlay
its position in software into several derivative businesses.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is to make its Web site,  &LR; www.redhat.com, &LR;  into a
full-featured portal for Linux developers and users. In March,
according to the prospectus, the site attracted 265,000 unique
visitors. Linux's continuing popularity and the publicity the
company garnered last week undoubtedly mean increasing traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat aims to turn that into new revenues by selling ads on
its site and negotiating deals that give it a cut when users jump
from the site to make purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The second prong in Red Hat's plan _ one that likely will prove
more important over the long run _ is to beef up its consulting,
training and support programs.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat already has agreements to provide such services to a
slew of other companies that recently have jumped on the Linux
bandwagon, including such giants as Compaq, Dell and IBM. In June,
Red Hat rolled out a new program under which it will offer on-site
services to corporate customers, provided by more than 350 Linux
experts based at 20 offices across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the company announced a deal under which Global
Knowledge, the world's largest provider of training for
information-technology professionals, will offer Red Hat's training
and certification programs.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, the company unveiled yet another program under
which it will offer training and support for developers creating
Linux-based software for corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat won't have this field to itself _ the opportunity is too
lucrative. Last week, for example, IBM's Global Services unit
announced a wide-ranging service program to provide support and
services for businesses using Linux. And other companies with long
experience and established reputations in computing support and
services are sure to follow Big Blue's example.
</P>
<P>
   What Red Hat has going for it is its intimate knowledge of Linux
and the Linux developer community, which even corporate behemoths
like IBM can't match. It also has made its name into the best-known
brand in the emerging Linux market place.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those advantages make it a $5 billion company, only time
will tell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
