<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
Portals Are Climbing the Corporate Ladder
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; By Tom Stein
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
The World Wide Web, as most everyone knows, is a complex and often
confounding beast. So along came ``portal'' sites like Yahoo, Lycos
and Excite to act as a one-stop gateway to the billions of pages of
Internet content. In the process, these sites have become their own
little virtual communities where people gathered before leaping
onto the vastness of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many companies need to get their internal Web sites
organized in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, employees at large companies have used
internal Web sites, called intranets, to post information about
goings-on within the company. For example, the marketing department
might put up information about new hires while manufacturing would
post hundreds of pages about new production techniques. Literally
every employee could become a Web publisher. The end result was
that relevant information got buried deep within the intranet,
which itself became a wild and untamed beast.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the notion of ``corporate portals'' _ centralized home
pages organized to put all of a company's internal information at
its employees' fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate portals also let employees access data that exists
within a host of other applications on company servers, such as
e-mail, spreadsheets and word-processing documents. What's more,
the portals can link to the outside world. They can pull weather
reports, stock updates and breaking news off the Internet and
deliver it in a personalized manner directly to the employee's
desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Scient Corp., a San Francisco Internet consulting firm, has
spent millions of dollars in the past year building its corporate
portal, called the Scient Zone. To ensure that the investment
doesn't go to waste _ and that employees actually spend time in the
Zone rather than on Yahoo _ the company has added a series of fun
features to its portal.
</P>
<P>
   The home page has a weekly list of employees who are celebrating
a birthday, for instance. The site also features links to
employee-written reviews of local eating spots and watering holes.
There's even an area called, ``Hey, you stole my chair,'' where
people at the fast-growing and furniture-poor company accuse
co-workers of, you guessed it, stealing one another's chairs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PORTAL16 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Scient has 10 full-time staff members dedicated to enhancing and
monitoring the Scient Zone. They make sure that whatever content
employees post is easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   Portals can be tailored to meet the needs of a wide range of
workers, from secretaries to chief executives. Salespeople, for
instance, can personalize their portals to include the latest news
and developments about their customers and competitors. A CEO could
choose to see up-to-the minute business data, such as that week's
sales-per-region figures. This data could be garnered externally
from the Web or internally from the company's database and business
software applications.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, corporate portals allow employees to do their
jobs better, according to industry experts. For instance, some
portals sport templates that show new employees how to write a
proposal, conduct an interview with clients or create a PowerPoint
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America is starting to see the light. According to a
recent Gartner Group report, 80 percent of companies on the leading
edge of technology usage will implement a corporate portal by the
year 2000. More than half of the Fortune 300 companies are working
on _ or already have _ a corporate portal. And by 2003, a majority
of all businesses will manage a portal. Major companies such as
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., Wells Fargo, Boeing and even the U.S. Postal
Service have embraced corporate portal technology.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, most companies build their portals from scratch. But
a host of vendors with names like Plumtree, Glyphica, Viador and
Epicentric are popping up to provide the technology in a single,
off-the-shelf package. They sell software to create the sites as
well as do a lot of the integration work to link together disparate
applications and data. Analysts estimate that there are about 15 to
20 such vendors in existence today, with many more sure to follow.
After all, a report by investment firm Merrill Lynch pegged the
market for portal vendors at $100 million, with projections for
double-digit growth during the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Hadley Reynolds, an analyst with the Delphi Group, said more
companies will adopt corporate portals because the technology makes
a lot of sense. The portal is the first place employees go to post
messages and exchange ideas in organized chat rooms, he said,
predicting that eventually all work will be done within the
confines of the portal.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of PORTAL16 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Today, we work in these highly fragmented and disconnected
software environments where we have to jump from one application to
another and one screen to another just to find a document or
retrieve a single piece of information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the portal becomes the central repository for all
information and applications, enabling employees to work in one
centralized spot, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for a corporate portal to be successful, it must be a place
where employees really want to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret to success for a corporate portal is to have
sophisticated data integration, an intuitive user interface,
engaging content and easy navigation,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   Scient works hard to keep its content engaging. A key part of
the Scient Zone is a link called Office Locator. It basically is a
map of the entire 400-person office. When you click on a particular
desk, you see a picture of the person who sits there, as well as
his or her resume, phone and e-mail information, current projects
and even more personal information such as favorite foods. The
office locator is effective particularly at a startup like Scient,
where new people are joining all the time and employees are eager
to get to know one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may think we're wasting our time, but it's
essential to integrate this cultural stuff with the more critical
features for actually doing the job,'' said Doug Kalish, who heads
up development efforts for the Scient Zone. ``The Zone has to be
the first place we go for anything and everything. It is the mother
of our business. It's the place where people live all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the San Francisco brokerage firm, began
building its so-called SchWEB portal two years ago. ``Before that,
it was a grassroots things with people publishing their own Web
content, but that soon became too unwieldy,'' said Bob Lee, a vice
president at Schwab. ``We formalized things with the creation of
the SchWEB,and now it really enhances the way people do their
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the SchWEB features industry news articles, a corporate
white-pages directory, stock updates, the latest information about
Schwab employees and locations, and links to the company's external
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The portal also has self-service features that allow workers to
sign up for the company's 401(k) plan, fill out expense reports,
order office supplies and report a change of address online.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said employees now spend an average of two hours a day
working directly on the SchWEB.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of loyalty, will we soon see companies sell
banner ads across their portals a la Yahoo and other commercial
sites? ``We are starting to get inquiries from companies who are
potentially looking at advertising revenue to offset the cost of
setting up a corporate portal,'' said Oliver Muoto, a co-founder of
portal software vendor Epicentric Inc. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of PORTAL16 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Doug Kalish, for one, could envision a series of rotating banners
with such corporate messages as ``Click here for an important
announcement from our CEO'' or ``This is the last day to sign up
for the 401(k) plan.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's not so keen on, say, a big, splashy ad from
1-800-Flowers racing the portal. ``I'm not sure our employees would
be real comfortable with that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of PORTAL16 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
