r s BC-GLF-PGA-ESTES-TEX     08-15 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-ESTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTES ISN'T COUNTING ON RYDER CUP BERTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Bob Estes stepped to the 16th tee box Sunday
with a berth on the U.S. Ryder Cup team if he could limit himself
to one bogey on the closing holes. Two bogeys later, the University
of Texas product found himself rationalizing the spot that got away
at Medinah Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was expecting me to make the team, anyway,'' said
Estes, who fired a closing 69 in the PGA Championship and missed
becoming a Ryder Cup rookie by a single stroke. ``I knew where I
stood, in terms of the Ryder Cup. But I don't think it affected the
way I played those holes. Those holes had given me trouble all
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Estes' consecutive bogeys dropped him to 6 under par for the
tournament and into a tie for sixth at the PGA, the final
tournament where players earn points in the 1999 Ryder Cup
standings. If Estes had finished at 7 under, he would have joined
Nick Price in a two-way tie for fifth and leapfrogged Jeff Maggert
for the 10th and final automatic berth on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Austin resident must wait and see if U.S. captain Ben
Crenshaw, a fellow Longhorn and Austin resident, will select him
today as one of two at-large choices for the team that will compete
Sept. 24-26 in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Ryder Cup bubble-riders, Estes turned in the most
impressive showing at the PGA. He moved from 15th to 11th in the
final Ryder Cup standings with 611.25 points _ 13.75 fewer than
Maggert, a Texas A&AMP;M product who lives in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this season, Estes has cracked the top 10 in major
championships. In addition to finishing sixth at the PGA, he was
fourth at the Masters. But he has only one career victory (1994
Texas Open) and no experience in international team competition.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Estes said he expects to be bypassed in favor of
two more experienced players who rank below him in the Ryder Cup
standings when Crenshaw announces his at-large picks. Most
speculation has centered around Tom Lehman (No. 12), a two-time
Ryder Cup participant, and Fred Couples (No. 17), a five-time Cup
competitor, as Crenshaw's probable at-large picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I even have a chance,'' Estes said. ``I don't
have the experience of Couples and Lehman.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples, an at-large pick in 1997, openly lobbied for a spot
Sunday after shooting a closing 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I be disappointed if I'm not picked? Sure,'' said
Couples, who spoke with Crenshaw after his round. ``I feel like I
hit a lot of good shots this week. What I have going for me is
experience, and sometimes you can't keep relying on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, in the estimation of peers, is a lock. Fort Worth
resident Mark Brooks said Lehman should be ``a slam dunk'' choice
as an at-large pick. But he said he would pick Estes over Couples,
if put in Crenshaw's position.
</P>
<P>
   What will Crenshaw do?
</P>
<P>
   ``One pick is probably fairly obvious, and one will probably
keep me up all night,'' Crenshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, by all accounts, figures to be the obvious choice.
Estes, by his calculations, probably blew his best chance by
hitting consecutive tee shots into the trees at No. 16 and into a
bunker at No. 17. Both set up pivotal bogeys. Neither, said Estes,
will haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it my best shot,'' he said. ``That's all you can do.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
