<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-VT-PLANE-CRASH-BOS &LR;      08-15 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VT-PLANE-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
  
 FAMILY OF 3 KILLED IN PLANE CRASH
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL VASQUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Signs of trouble came just eight minutes after the small plane
belonging to a Pennsylvania family lifted off Saturday at
Morrisville Airport in Vermont. The aircraft's emergency beacon
went off and the plane was not heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, authorities confirmed the worst: The family of three,
including an 11-year-old boy, were killed after their Cessna 210
crashed into the Putnam State Forest near the Worcester Mountain
Ridgeline in northern Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Lehman, 43, his wife, Joanne, 48, their son, Nathan, and
pet golden retriever, died in the plane crash about 10 miles from
the Morrisville Airport as the family headed home to Mechanicsburg,
Pa., police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the plane burst into flames upon impact'' said
Vermont State Police Sergeant Bruce Melendy, in a statement
released Sunday. The Vermont State Police was one of several
agencies that began searching for the family after the Cessna's
emergency beacon went off at 1:08 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On their flight, the Lehmans said they intended to land at
Capital City Airport in their hometown. The Lehmans took off just
after 1 p.m. and about five minutes later Dennis Lehman, who was
piloting the craft, radioed a request to climb to 6,000 feet over
Boston, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, the plane's beacon went off. A Federal
Aviation Administration official at the Knapp Airport in Berlin,
Vt., tracked the plane's signal for about 10 minutes _ but the
family never made contact again, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Local rescue workers, including firefighters and police,
unsuccessfully searched the highways and roads near Morrisville on
Saturday. Meanwhile, the Civil Air Patrol and Vermont National
Guard searched by plane until midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Then about 1:20 p.m. Sunday searchers using dogs found pieces of
the black, gold and white plane in the Putnam State Forest area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
