<P>
   (NYT16) RAYNE, La. -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- CAJUN-CONGRESS-2, 8-15 --
The Babineaux-Granger family reunion. The gathering brings together
the descendants of families expelled in the 1750s by the British
government from the land they called Acadie. The first Congress was
held in Canada in 1994 and drew nearly 225,000 people, including
some 3,000 from Louisiana. (Lee Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LAFAYETTE, La. -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- CAJUN-CONGRESS-1,
8-15 -- Minus Granger, center, with two of his distant relatives,
Pierre Granger, 60, left, a cardiologist from Quebec, and Collete
LeGac, 49, from Belle-Isle en Mer, France, at his home in
Lafayette. Granger's relatives traveled from all over the United
States and from Canada and France to take part in the second
Congres Mondial Acadien (World Acadian Congress), a bilingual
cultural celebration designed to restore some pride and unity to a
beleaguered people ripped apart nearly 250 years ago. (Lee
Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) GREEN CITY, Mo. -- Aug. 15, 1999 --
MO-LIVESTOCK-LAWSUIT-3, 8-15 -- Jason Siemer, a 27-year-old barber,
left his depressed hometown of Princeton, Mo., nearly a decade ago,
but as economic conditions improved in the region, he was able to
return home and go into business. His father, who had gone broke in
farming, now drives a truck for Premium Standard Farms, a giant
pork producer. With hog manure fouling streams in the rolling
countryside of northern Missouri, Premium Standard Farms has agreed
to pay $25 million to settle a suit accusing it of violating the
state's Clean Water Act. (Rodney White/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- PENTAGON-NOVEL, 8-15 --
``Once an Eagle,'' a cult classic that has worked its way over a
generation into the mindset and lexicon of the American military,
is back in print. When it was first published in 1968, the epic
story of an Army officer as honorable as Robin Hood pitted against
a fellow officer as self-serving as Prince John became an
improbable best seller during the upheaval of those times, its 800
pages tracing the story of the U.S. Army from World War I to the
early years of Vietnam. The book eventually sold millions of
copies. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) GREEN CITY, Mo. -- Aug. 15, 1999 --
MO-LIVESTOCK-LAWSUIT-2, 8-15 -- More than 1,000 hogs can be housed
in each of the barns by the manure lagoon at the Premium Standard
Farms operation near Green City, Mo. With hog manure fouling
streams in the rolling countryside of northern Missouri, the giant
pork producer Premium Standard Farms agreed early this month to pay
$25 million to settle a suit accusing it of violating the state's
Clean Water Act. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
