<P>
   (NYT4) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Aug. 15, 1999 --
SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERTS, 8-15 -- Bruce Springsteen performing the last
of his record-setting 15 sold-out concerts at the Continental
Airlines Arena in East Rutherford. The popularity of Springsteen's
recent performances comes at an interesting time. In 1985 he was at
the height of his ``Born in the U.S.A.''-era popularity; today,
less than a month away from his 50th birthday, most of his recent
releases have been archival. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CHICAGO -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- POETRY-SLAM-3, 8-15 -- A
poetry team from Albuquerque, New Mexico at the kick-off event of
the National Poetry Slam contest. The rise of slam poetry has both
shared in and pushed along a general explosion in the interest of
poetry nationwide, determinable by a number of measures. (Steve
Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHICAGO -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- POETRY-SLAM-2, 8-15 -- Roger
Bonair-Agard from New York, winner of the 1999 National Poetry Slam
contest's individual title. As poetry in general has surged in
popularity in the United States, this offshoot from the traditions
of the art has emerged as a way for passionate people -- mostly,
but not entirely, young and representing a wide ethnic and racial
range -- to air their voices and for an evidently eager audience to
hear and embrace them. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHICAGO -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- POETRY-SLAM-1, 8-15 -- Marc
Smith, founder of the poetry slam competitions, at this year's
National Poetry Slam contest at the Chicago Theater. A weird and
lively amalgam of performance art, hip-hop concert and, with its
randomly selected judges holding up numerical score cards from the
audience, Olympic figure skating, it's a form that is still
disdained by many. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
