<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 08/15/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) EDGEMONT, N.Y. -- Aug. 15, 1999 --
CLINTON-HOUSEHUNTING-2, 8-15 -- A $1.7 million hilltop house on a
corkscrew of a major street known to locals as ``Suicide Hill,'' is
one of the houses President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, are
looking at in the New York region. As Clinton prepares to leave
public life and Mrs. Clinton gears up for an effort to join it, the
family swept through the wealthy New York City suburbs on Sunday
with about as much casualness as one can muster when accompanied by
a black sedan, two sport-utility vehicles, three police cruisers
and four mini-vans. (Richard L. Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. -- Aug. 15, 1999 --
CLINTON-HOUSEHUNTING-1, 8-15 -- President Clinton and his wife,
Hillary, pause to schmooze with some of their prospective neighbors
in New Rochelle. As Clinton prepares to leave public life and Mrs.
Clinton gears up for an effort to join it, the family swept through
the wealthy New York City suburbs on Sunday with about as much
casualness as one can muster when accompanied by a black sedan, two
sport-utility vehicles, three police cruisers and four mini-vans.
(Richard L. Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) RAYNE, La. -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- CAJUN-CONGRESS-2, 8-15 --
The Babineaux-Granger family reunion. The gathering brings together
the descendants of families expelled in the 1750s by the British
government from the land they called Acadie. The first Congress was
held in Canada in 1994 and drew nearly 225,000 people, including
some 3,000 from Louisiana. (Lee Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LAFAYETTE, La. -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- CAJUN-CONGRESS-1,
8-15 -- Minus Granger, center, with two of his distant relatives,
Pierre Granger, 60, left, a cardiologist from Quebec, and Collete
LeGac, 49, from Belle-Isle en Mer, France, at his home in
Lafayette. Granger's relatives traveled from all over the United
States and from Canada and France to take part in the second
Congres Mondial Acadien (World Acadian Congress), a bilingual
cultural celebration designed to restore some pride and unity to a
beleaguered people ripped apart nearly 250 years ago. (Lee
Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) GREEN CITY, Mo. -- Aug. 15, 1999 --
MO-LIVESTOCK-LAWSUIT-3, 8-15 -- Jason Siemer, a 27-year-old barber,
left his depressed hometown of Princeton, Mo., nearly a decade ago,
but as economic conditions improved in the region, he was able to
return home and go into business. His father, who had gone broke in
farming, now drives a truck for Premium Standard Farms, a giant
pork producer. With hog manure fouling streams in the rolling
countryside of northern Missouri, Premium Standard Farms has agreed
to pay $25 million to settle a suit accusing it of violating the
state's Clean Water Act. (Rodney White/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- PENTAGON-NOVEL, 8-15 --
``Once an Eagle,'' a cult classic that has worked its way over a
generation into the mindset and lexicon of the American military,
is back in print. When it was first published in 1968, the epic
story of an Army officer as honorable as Robin Hood pitted against
a fellow officer as self-serving as Prince John became an
improbable best seller during the upheaval of those times, its 800
pages tracing the story of the U.S. Army from World War I to the
early years of Vietnam. The book eventually sold millions of
copies. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) GREEN CITY, Mo. -- Aug. 15, 1999 --
MO-LIVESTOCK-LAWSUIT-2, 8-15 -- More than 1,000 hogs can be housed
in each of the barns by the manure lagoon at the Premium Standard
Farms operation near Green City, Mo. With hog manure fouling
streams in the rolling countryside of northern Missouri, the giant
pork producer Premium Standard Farms agreed early this month to pay
$25 million to settle a suit accusing it of violating the state's
Clean Water Act. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- NY-INDIAN-PARADE-FLOATER,
8-15 -- Young participants get ready to enjoy the 19th annual New
York Indian Day Parade on Sunday. (Frances Roberts/New York Times
photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- DALAI-LAMA-3, 8-15 -- A
young girl checks out some Buddhist monks in Central Park's East
Meadow on Sunday, as the Dalai Lama spoke to a crowd, which the
police estimated at 40,000, as diverse as the city itself. The
Dalai Lama stressed a few central themes, lacing them with jokes
and personal anecdotes but mainly focused on how to train the mind
to achieve inner peace. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- DALAI-LAMA-2, 8-15 -- The
Dalai Lama spoke for well over an hour to tens of thousands who
gathered in Central Park's East Meadow Sunday, his image broadcast
on a large screen for those unable to see the stage. The crowd,
which the police estimated at 40,000, was as diverse as the city
itself. The Dalai Lama stressed a few central themes, lacing them
with jokes and personal anecdotes but mainly focused on how to
train the mind to achieve inner peace. (James Estrin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- DALAI-LAMA-1, 8-15 -- The
Dalai Lama, speaking to tens of thousands who gathered in Central
Park's East Meadow on Sunday. The crowd, which the police estimated
at 40,000, was as diverse as the city itself and came to hear the
spiritual leader of Tibet give a free public lecture on the basics
of leading a life of kindness and happiness. (Edward Keating/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- E-COMMERCE-COLUMN, 8-15 --
Shawn Melvin, a college student, searches for books online at a
Borders bookstore in Manhattan. As customers become technically
savvier, traditional retailers are now creating Web sites of their
own and integrating their Internet operations into their physical
stores. Executives say that by mingling the virtual and physical
retail environments, they can better serve customers in both.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNIONVILLE, Mo. -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- MO-LIVESTOCK-LAWSUIT,
8-15 --Terry Spence, a 52-year-old cattle farmer and a sharp critic
of the big hog factory. With hog manure fouling streams in the
rolling countryside of northern Missouri, the giant pork producer
Premium Standard Farms agreed early this month to pay $25 million
to settle a suit accusing it of violating the state's Clean Water
Act. ``The state did not win nearly a large enough settlement from
Premium Standard Farms,'' says Spence. (Rodney White/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- MILLS-PROFILE, 8-15 --
Cheryl Mills, 34, deputy White House counsel, who recently turned
down the White House counsel's job, is vague about her plans,
saying only that she is considering ``a number of different things
in the private sector'' and is not confining herself to law. For
seven years Ms. Mills was at the epicenter of the Clinton scandals
and acquired a reputation as extremely tough, extremely loyal and a
leading figure in the give-no-ground camp in the White House. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Aug. 15, 1999 --
SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERTS, 8-15 -- Bruce Springsteen performing the last
of his record-setting 15 sold-out concerts at the Continental
Airlines Arena in East Rutherford. The popularity of Springsteen's
recent performances comes at an interesting time. In 1985 he was at
the height of his ``Born in the U.S.A.''-era popularity; today,
less than a month away from his 50th birthday, most of his recent
releases have been archival. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CHICAGO -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- POETRY-SLAM-3, 8-15 -- A
poetry team from Albuquerque, New Mexico at the kick-off event of
the National Poetry Slam contest. The rise of slam poetry has both
shared in and pushed along a general explosion in the interest of
poetry nationwide, determinable by a number of measures. (Steve
Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHICAGO -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- POETRY-SLAM-2, 8-15 -- Roger
Bonair-Agard from New York, winner of the 1999 National Poetry Slam
contest's individual title. As poetry in general has surged in
popularity in the United States, this offshoot from the traditions
of the art has emerged as a way for passionate people -- mostly,
but not entirely, young and representing a wide ethnic and racial
range -- to air their voices and for an evidently eager audience to
hear and embrace them. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHICAGO -- Aug. 15, 1999 -- POETRY-SLAM-1, 8-15 -- Marc
Smith, founder of the poetry slam competitions, at this year's
National Poetry Slam contest at the Chicago Theater. A weird and
lively amalgam of performance art, hip-hop concert and, with its
randomly selected judges holding up numerical score cards from the
audience, Olympic figure skating, it's a form that is still
disdained by many. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
