<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SIBLEY-OBIT-1STLEDE-C     08-15 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-OBIT-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Southern spirit, a worldy wit: Saying goodbye to Celestine
Sibley
 &HT;    (EDS: UPDATES to include new information on her cancer; Adds
additional info with reactions. MOVING TO (a) General news and (l)
Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Celestine Sibley, whose column ran in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution newspapers for 55 years, died early Sunday
morning at her beachside retreat on Dog Island, Fla. She was 85.
</P>
<P>
   She had undergone surgery for breast cancer in 1995 and suffered
a heart attack in 1998. She learned late last year that her cancer
had returned. This time it spread to her brain and bones.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-loved and most prolific writers in the history
of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Sibley captured everyday life
in the changing South in more than 10,000 columns since 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celestine was one of the true giants,'' said Georgia Gov. Roy
Barnes. ``She had one of the biggest hearts of any person that I
ever knew. She knew the secrets on all of us in the General
Assembly, and we were comfortable that she knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Ashmead, Sibley's book editor at Harper Collins, said,
``A light's gone out in Atlanta and Georgia and all over the South,
where people read her and loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Ashmead, ``I'm sort of glad she died on Dog Island, the
place she and Jack (her late husband Jack Strong) loved the most of
all the places they had.''
</P>
<P>
   Born near Pensacola, Fla., Sibley was reared in the turpentine
country north of Mobile, Ala. She came to work at The Atlanta
Constitution in 1941. Though best known for the columns she wrote
from 1944 until shortly before her death, she was a star court
reporter and also covered politics and the Georgia Legislature. She
raised three children while holding down a full-time job,
free-lancing magazine articles and writing 25 books.
</P>
<P>
   According to her daughter Mary Vance, Sibley was alert just
before she died around 5:30 Sunday morning. In her last moments she
asked whether they might return to her Sweet Apple cabin in
Roswell, Ga., one last time, explaining that, ``There are a couple
of things I wanted to do in the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Sibley's wishes were observed, due to a personality that
remained forceful to the end. Sibley underwent chemotherapy after a
mastectomy in 1995. When cancer recurred in 1998, she announced,
``with equanimity and some dignity,'' that she would endure no more
chemotherapy, said her oncologist Dr. Martin York. ``Through it
all, she had this remarkable independence and sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Patricia Templeton, associate rector of St. Timothy's
Episcopal Church in Signal Mountain, Tennessee, said, ``She
approached her death the way she lived her life: With courage and
grace and stubbornness.'' Templeton is to officiate at a memorial
service for her longtime friend. Plans for that service were to be
announced later today.
</P>
<P>
   Templeton served as an intern at The Atlanta Constitution in
1976, before she turned to the ministry, and still keeps a clipping
of a Sibley column from that summer. In the column, Sibley writes
of a fierce love of newspapering, saying, ``I can honestly say that
there has been nothing in my life so painful and saddening that it
wasn't eased a little bit as I walked toward my job in a newspaper
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Martin, editor of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, said
Sunday, ``Those of us who were fortunate to work with her will miss
her laughter, her wisdom and her example. Her column was Celestine
herself _ an oasis, where you could share a quiet moment, recover
your perspective, and leave refreshed, ready to journey on. It's
hard to imagine the paper without her.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cumming of Carrollton, Ga., used Sibley's columns when he
taught at West Georgia College, and cherished a friendship that
began in 1957 when he was at Newsweek's Southern bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always thought of her in heroic terms,'' Cumming said.
``She had all the strength of the Statue of Liberty, only with a
sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley and former Georgia Gov. Zell Miller were friends from the
years when she covered the Legislature and he was a young lawmaker.
``I always looked upon her as a wise aunt, who would encourage you
with warmth and gentleness,'' Miller said. ``She taught us how to
face our later years: With dignity, with humor, and occasionally a
little bit of irritability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved her very much,'' said Miller, ``and, gosh, I'm going
to miss her, but so will thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include her son, James W. Little V of Alford, Fla.;
two daughters, Susan Sibley Little Bazemore of Des Moines, Iowa
(formerly of Omaha, Neb.), and Mary Everitt Little-Vance of
Roswell; eight grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, the family asks that contributions be sent
to the library of their choice or to Trees Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
