<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8199 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-PGA-NOTES-TEX     08-15 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERGIO GARCIA BECOMES A FAN FAVORITE DOWN STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ By finishing first at the PGA Championship,
Tiger Woods regained the No. 1 spot in the world golf rankings. But
he was clearly No. 2 Sunday in the hearts of fans at Medinah
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia, the Spanish teen-ager who finished as the
runner-up to Woods, received the lion's share of the cheers at
Medinah. Woods, in fact, was jeered on multiple occasions.
</P>
<P>
   At various points, Woods and playing partner Mike Weir were
urged to ``choke'' by onlookers. Woods was encouraged to hit tee
shots into the water at Nos. 13 and 17, a pair of water-lined par-3
holes. As Woods lined up a birdie putt at No. 18, several different
fans hollered ``Three-putt!,'' an occurrence that would have forced
Woods into a playoff with Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the things they said weren't too kind,'' Woods said,
adding that none of the marks were racial slurs. ``Fans obviously
were rooting for Sergio, as well they should. Some of the things
they did to Mike and I, I don't think was fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, on the other hand, said he ``felt like I was an
American'' during the closing holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds were amazing. I have no words to say what that did
for me,'' said Garcia, 19, who became the obvious rooting favorite
after closing Woods' five-shot lead to one with a birdie at No. 13.
``I almost couldn't hear by the end of the round.'' JOBE MISSES BIG
PAYDAY
</P>
<P>
   A disappointing final round (75) dropped Southlake resident
Brandt Jobe into a tie for 16th place at Medinah, decreasing a
potential six-digit paycheck to $48,600. Jobe, who competes on the
Japanese Tour, seeks to finish in the top 125 on the PGA Tour
season money list so that he can play full time in the United
States next season.
</P>
<P>
   His earnings at Medinah boost Jobe's season total to $168,600,
putting him within striking distance of the $300,000 he estimates
he will need to earn a PGA Tour card for 2000. But Jobe, who
entered the final round in ninth place, had hoped for more at
Medinah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed. I played better than my score would
indicate,'' said Jobe, who took a double-bogey from a plugged lie
at No. 12 and also bogeyed the par-5 14th to backtrack to 1 under
for the tournament. ``When I needed one bounce to happen, it never
happened for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the problem for Jobe will be adding to his earnings figure
after August.
</P>
<P>
   A nonmember of the tour, he has been given sponsor's exemptions
into events the next two weeks (Sprint International, Reno-Tahoe
Open). After that, he is at the mercy of tournament organizers to
play in additional PGA Tour events. That is why a letter will be in
the mail soon to organizers of the Westin Texas Open, played Sept.
23-26 in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell them I'm a local now. Maybe that will help,'' said
Jobe, who moved from Denver to Southlake during the summer. ``The
way I'm going, maybe one more good finish will give me my card.''
PUTTER DESERTS BROOKS
</P>
<P>
   A balky putter kept Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks from making
a final-round charge at the PGA. Brooks, who finished at 1 under,
needed 33 putts Sunday _ five more than his average during the
first three rounds. Brooks closed with a 74 and finished in a tie
for 16th, his best showing at a major since winning the 1996 PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Medinah, Brooks had missed the cut in six of his
past 11 majors, with a best finish of 38th at the 1999 Masters.
Despite the putting problems, he remained upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I played well. I just couldn't get the speed down,''
said Brooks, who had two three-putts Sunday. ``The greens were a
little faster than they'd been the rest of the week.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Weir, Tiger Woods' playing partner, on problems
experienced during Sunday's closing 80: ``There was nothing with
the gallery or Tiger. It was just me. I just wasn't sharp, all the
way around.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Woods (23 years, 8 months, 16 days) became the fifth-youngest
winner in PGA history. Garcia, 19, is the youngest runner-up in
tournament history. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
