<HEADER>
A8204 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-TEX     08-15 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LONGHORNS PREPARING FOR POST-RICKY ERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While plotting a suitable encore to a season
that produced a Cotton Bowl victory, a Heisman Trophy winner and
thousands of delirious Texas fans, Mack Brown has located a
comforting starting point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' he said. ``By Wednesday, we'd already sold
45,500 season tickets, and that breaks the old record (39,000) by a
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just so encouraging. What last year did for us was it
put us back in the national spotlight and allowed us to walk with a
swagger again. What this does is it sends a message that even
though Ricky Williams is gone, people still care about Texas
football.''
</P>
<P>
   They might find certain aspects of it unfamiliar for awhile.
Along with Williams _ who rushed for 2,124 yards and finished his
career as the most prolific runner (6,279 yards) in NCAA Division
I-A history _ graduation removed premier receiver Wane McGarity and
four immense starters in the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' Brown said, ``We will be more inclined to spread
the field and take what the defense gives us. Ricky allowed us to
be stubborn. This year, we will not be stubborn. Other than that,
not much changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with a few questions, there are two aspects of the offense
about which the coaching staff is certain: (a) Major Applewhite is
the starting quarterback, never mind what you have heard about
incoming freshman Chris Simms, and (b) Williams will be replaced by
junior Hodges Mitchell and redshirt freshman Victor Ike.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the latter situation, offensive coordinator Greg Davis
said he feels comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hodges will be our starter, but Victor is definitely going to
play,'' he said. ``We'll be fine, because they're both very
talented. In fact, Hodges is _ careful how you print this _ better
than Ricky was in some aspects of the receiving game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the thing with Ricky is, it's probably bigger with the
media than it is with us. He's gone. And the thing about sports is,
when they're gone, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who has set a goal of 1,000 yards for himself, said he
feels OK, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't think Ricky will ever be ``gone'','' he said.
``Those are the biggest shoes in the country to fill, but I don't
feel pressure because of it. For me, pressure comes from what I
expect of myself. He's the greatest back I've ever been around, and
I learned some things: The main thing he taught me is, you've got
to run hard at those linebackers, and it's no time to be mincing
steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who in his time has coached Gary Kubiak, Kevin Murray,
Barry Lunney and Rocky Zeier, calls Simms _ national offensive
player of the year in ``USA Today'' _ ``The best freshman
quarterback I've seen in 27 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, he isn't as good as Applewhite, who threw for
2,453 yards and 18 touchdowns as a redshirt freshman while guiding
the Longhorns to a 9-3 year capped by a 38-11 victory over
Mississippi State in the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both looking good, but Major has really picked up his
game,'' Davis said. ``Frankly, I like the fact that Chris wants to
be the starter _ and that Major doesn't want him to be the
starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the two are getting along well, Applewhite said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself the starter, but he's a teammate, and it's
part of my job to help him if I can and answer any questions he
has,'' Applewhite said. ``So far, most of his questions have been
like, `Where's the nearest drug store?''' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
