<HEADLINE>
AFTER TOURNAMENT, WILLIAMS MAKES IMPORTANT STOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Serena Williams has a long-term plan
to be ranked No. 1. Her short-term plan, however, is more simple:
``The first stop will be the jewelry store,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After Williams won the Acura Classic 6-1, 6-4 against Julie
Halard-Decugis, the 17-year-old talked about jewelry. As her
winnings moved to $580,015 this year, fifth highest on the WTA
Tour, she can afford trinkets in Mr. T proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Williams talked about a nearby jewelry store in Manhattan Beach
all week and has her eye on a necklace with many gems, including
garnet, amethyst, topaz and blue topaz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really different design,'' Williams said. ``It goes all
the way around and looks like a bracelet.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who wears a gold necklace and bracelet on the court,
probably won't wear the necklace in a match. But considering her
desire for it, she might be wearing it soon, as a college freshman.
</P>
<P>
   __ Finalists jump: Both Williams and Halard-Decugis will jump in
the WTA Tour rankings to be released today. Williams will move from
11th to ninth; Halard-Decugis from 16th to 11th. Both rankings are
the highest in their respective careers.
</P>
<P>
   Halard-Decugis, 28, said she is playing the best tennis of her
13-year pro career. She returned to the tour in 1998 after a
variety of injuries kept her out for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``During all that time, I did a lot of physical training,''
Halard-Decugis said of the layoff. ``I'm enjoying the tour much
more. I'm having more fun on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Williams drives away:Williams received $80,000 for her
victory, and Halard-Decugis got $40,000 in the $520,000 tournament.
As a bonus, Williams also received a an Acura TL.
</P>
<P>
   __ Attendance booms:The tournament set an attendance record with
53,713 for the week. The finals and semifinals were sold out,
filling the 5,324-seat stadium.
</P>
<P>
   __ TV time travels:The final was broadcast on NBC, after a
one-hour tape delay. The final ceremonies also were broadcast,
which caused an awkward silence. Officials waited for a commercial
break to end without saying a word to the crowd, before presenting
the players with their awards.
</P>
<P>
   __ Neiland/Sanchez-Vicario win:In the anti-climactic doubles
final, Larisa Neiland and Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario beat No. 3 Lisa
Raymond/Rennae Stubbs 6-2, 6-7 (4-7), 6-0. Neiland and
Sanchez-Vicario aren't exactly known for their doubles. They are
ranked 17th and 19th, respectively. Martina Hingis and Natasha
Zvereva are the top-ranked doubles players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
