<HEADLINE>
2 PLAYERS REMAIN TO BE NAMED TO U.S. RYDER CUP TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ The top 10 players on the U.S. Ryder Cup team
are set, leaving Ben Crenshaw to announce his two captains picks on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw will almost surely name Tom Lehman, who finished 12th
in the points race, with one of the two captain's pick. The second
pick will be more difficult, although Fred Couples, a Ryder Cup
veteran who finished 17th in the points race, is probably the
favorite. Bob Estes, Steve Stricker, Steve Pate, John Huston, and
Chris Perry will also receive consideration.
</P>
<P>
   he 10 players who clinched spots through Sunday's PGA
Championship are Tiger Woods., David Duval, Payne Stewart, Davis
Love 3rd, Mark O'Meara, Hal Sutton, Justin Leonard, Jim Furyk, Phil
Mickelson, and Jeff Maggert.
</P>
<P>
   Couples was hoping for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never told anyone I didn't want to be on the team,'' said
Couples. ``That's something everyone wants to make. I'm sure
everyone is hoping for a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his chances to be chosen, Pate said, ``Very
unlikely, but not out of the question. ``I haven't talked to Ben.
It's not my place. But I would love it. It's the first chance I've
had to do this in eight years, and who knows how often your chances
come along. I'm sure I'm being considered, but so are a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   DUVAL SLIPS FROM TOP RANKING
</P>
<P>
   David Duval lost his No. 1 world ranking to Tiger Woods
following Sunday's outcome, and Duval will have to wait another
year to win his first major championship after finishing tied for
10th place, 3-under par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play as well as I would have liked,'' said Duval. ``I
hit the ball pretty well. I putted poorly and failed to get the
ball in the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   SINGH DISAPPOINTED
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh, the defending PGA Champion, was never in
contention, and he finished at 5-over par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' said Singh. ``I thought I was going
to play a little better. The one consolation is that I got to play
the weekend. The way I started off Thursday, I thought I was going
to struggle to make the cut. I'm disappointed that I didn't contend
for the title.''
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE-BOGEY COSTS PRICE
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price got to within three strokes of Tiger Woods, but a
costly double-bogey at No. 16 forced him to settle for fifth place
at 7-under par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to have to have a mistake free round to
have a chance,'' said Price. ``I just made too many bogeys this
week, to many mistakes. My game is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 42, Price has remained one of the game's most consistent
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing for the older guys is the question of
whether or not you have the desire,'' said Price. ``It's hard to
look at the suitcase every week. I'm trying not to play too much so
that I don't lose my desire.''
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA MAKES THE RYDER TEAM
</P>
<P>
   Mark James, the European Ryder Cup captain, doesn't have to
worry about picking Sergio Garcia now that he has made the team on
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is obviously a huge talent,'' said James of Garcia.
``The way he has played over in the States is incredible. To play
these tournaments at his age so maturely is quite unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question for James, who must decide on his two captain's
picks on Aug. 24, is whether to select Nick Faldo, who has
struggled for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick knows that to be considered, he has to show some form,''
said James. ``I would love to have form from Faldo, from Ian
Woosnam, and from Seve Ballesteros. If they're not going to be
there, they're not going to be there. There comes a time when
everyone has to move over, and if it's that year, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
