<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-IRABU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRABU LOSES CONTROL OF HIS SPLITTER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hideki Irabu raised his hand to imitate how he held
the ball, jutting the heel of his palm forward a bit, spreading his
fingers just so, struggling Sunday to explain the ephemeral feeling
he was supposed to have when he throws his splitter.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu spent his start against the Minnesota Twins in search of
that feeling, abandoning the routine of throwing a little of
everything when warming up between innings, instead throwing
splitter after splitter trying to find his range. The splitter
requires a lighter touch, and when Irabu's is working, he throws it
in the low to mid-80s. Sunday, he was higher up on the radar gun
and Irabu allowed five runs on nine hits in 6 1/3 innings in the
5-3 loss to the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   It was Irabu's first loss since May 25, a span during which he
recorded eight victories in 13 starts. But of more concern was
Irabu's loss of control of one of his favored pitches. Until last
week, Irabu had been, after David Cone, the most consistent starter
the Yankees have had in a season in which Roger Clemens has
curiously been un-Clemenslike. But Joe Torre said Irabu had not had
the splitter for the last few starts _ including his last one, when
he was bombed by Oakland, leaving after just four innings in which
he gave up eight hits and six runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is something to worry about, it's the feeling,''
Irabu said. ``That's what I need to worry about. I have confidence
in it. It's a matter of feeling, how you feel when you throw it.
It's the meaning and intent with which you throw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu's search for meaning was fruitless Sunday. With the
splitter staying up in the zone, he had trouble putting batters
away. Of the nine hits he surrendered, five of them came when he
had two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, with the score tied, 1-1, Irabu gave up a
leadoff double to Ron Coomer. Corey Koskie's groundout moved Coomer
to third and Terry Steinbach, with an 0-2 count and the infield
pulled in, hit a squibber under a diving Tino Martinez to give the
Twins a 2-1 lead. The next hitter, Denny Hocking was also in the
hole, 0-2, before hitting a single. Both hits came off splitters.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning, with two on and one out, Marty Cordova
hit an 0-2 fastball into left-center that scored two runs and sent
Irabu to the shower. Irabu got ahead in the count by starting his
fastball low and trying to go up in the zone. It worked twice. But
on what he hoped would be the third strike, the ball hung over the
middle of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no command, and it wasn't breaking,'' Torre said of the
splitter. ``He was leaving it up in the strike zone. The last two
or three starts it's been that way. He was able to get ahead in the
count today _ that was the frustrating part of it. He made too many
mistakes with the two-strike pitch. Those are the ones that
shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu seemed unfazed afterward, perhaps because he has rebounded
from a disastrous spring training in which he was the target of an
insult from George Steinbrenner to have a surprisingly strong
season.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu did not pitch in the post-season last year because,
after getting off to a good start _ he went 9-3, with a 2.86 ERA in
his first 17 starts of 1998 _ he faltered in his last 11, going 4-6
with a 5.91 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he was 9-3 with a 4.07 ERA before Sunday's game and
has now been hit hard in his last two starts. Irabu admitted Sunday
he had hoped to protect his no-loss streak but there was little
regret and certainly no panic in his voice. There was only
befuddlement and a commitment to continue with the things that had
helped him start the streak in the first place. The playoffs, he
said, he would worry about late in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than being satisfied, I want to be consistent,'' Irabu
said. ``I want to keep working on my conditioning. I have about 10
more starts left and I just have to do well in those starts. I have
some things I need to work on and solve in the next 10 starts.
Until I work on those things, I can't worry about anything else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
