<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOAIZA DISPLAYS ACE FORM, LEADS RANGERS PAST WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Esteban Loaiza is technically the Rangers' fifth
starter. Sunday, he did a fine impression of a staff ace.
</P>
<P>
   Riding to the rescue of his reeling teammates, Loaiza put a stop
to the Rangers' four-game losing streak with eight scoreless
innings and beat the Chicago White Sox, 10-0, at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza threw 126 pitches, which kept manager Johnny Oates from
sending him out for the ninth inning and getting his second career
shutout. But Dan Kolb held the White Sox scoreless in the ninth to
give the Rangers their fifth shutout this season.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Loaiza's performance allowed the Rangers to
maintain their 41/2 game lead in the American League West because
the Oakland Athletics completed a three-game sweep of the Toronto
Blue Jays with a 9-5 victory at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers open a four-game series against the Cleveland
Indians tonight and weren't too thrilled about the possibility of
taking a five-game losing streak to Jacobs Field. Loaiza helped the
Rangers avoid that, not to mention 16 hits from the offense,
including two home runs from both Rusty Greer and Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for us to come out and play well today,''
Greer said. ``We haven't been playing bad baseball but we haven't
played winning baseball, either. Cleveland is a tough place to
play, so we needed to come out of here with a win. But it all
starts with pitching, and Esteban pitched a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory also left Loaiza 5-0 with a 2.97 earned-run average
in his past six games, including five starts. After being banished
to the bullpen and missing much of the first half with a broken
hand, Loaiza is finally pitching the way the Rangers expected when
they acquired him July 17 last year for second baseman Warren
Morris and pitcher Todd Van Poppel.
</P>
<P>
   With Morris competing for National League rookie of the year,
the trade was starting to look like a Pirates swindle until this
latest surge by Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consistency he's giving us, that's what you want,'' Oates
said. ``I'd much rather have consistently average than a no-hitter
one game and getting knocked out the next. That gets you 50
percent, and 50 percent is not going to win you anything. He's
given us a chance to win five games.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza was not only good Sunday, but he was smart and tough. But
perhaps a near-brush with death will do that. His day almost ended
prematurely in the first inning when Frank Thomas ripped a line
drive straight back at Loaiza's skull. But Loaiza, with an
impressive survival instincts, got his glove up and made the catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucky I caught it, or I'd probably be in the hospital,''
Loaiza said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he stayed around and held the White Sox to five hits
and a walk over eight innings. The White Sox did threaten by
getting runners to second base with one out in each of the third
through sixth innings. But Loaiza, mixing in off-speed pitches with
his fastball, held the White Sox to a collective 0-for-8 with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to go hard, hit my spots and throw strikes,''
Loaiza said. ``When I was a reliever, I threw hard all the time.
Now I'm mixing my pitches. That's what's working for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza finished strong, retiring the last nine hitters he faced.
But Oates keeps his starters on a relatively strict 120-pitch limit
and called on Kolb for the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I wanted to finish,'' Loaiza said. ``But Johnny said 120
pitches, it's time to get ready for my next start. I can't say much
but I really wanted to go back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   What he did was plenty for a struggling team. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
