<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   During a recent lunch at the Stage Delicatessen, I was served by
a waitress who called me ``Sweetie,'' ``Love'' and ``Bubeleh'' as
she glided among the tables.
</P>
<P>
   She seemed highly unflappable until, for some reason, something
irritated her. She scurried past me, running her fingers through
her hair and loudly exclaiming:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oy!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oy vay!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oy caramba!''
</P>
<P>
   New York multiculturalism at its finest.
</P>
<P>
   _ NAT LEHRMAN
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Taking the subway during a recent morning rush hour on my way to
work on 35th Street, I had nothing to hold on to other than the
bodies of people in front of and behind me. A woman frowned at me
as we bumped into each other. To demonstrate my vulnerable
position, I stretched my arm straight up into the air, holding onto
an invisible pole.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my surprise when a passenger behind me firmly clutched
my hand and held it in his until we safely arrived at 34th Street.
As I was making my exit I thanked him. He said it was his pleasure.
We parted. It was so crowded I never did see his face.
</P>
<P>
   _ HARRIET BAILER
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Presslaff was walking along Lexington Avenue on a Sunday
afternoon when she came to a trendy dog-and-cat boutique. An
elegant woman was looking at the posted store hours. Her terrier
alternated between looking at her and at the door, but seemed to be
firmly planted at the shop. As Ms. Presslaff passed, she heard the
woman explain the situation to her dog. ``I'm sorry, Henry,'' she
said. ``There's nothing I can do about it. They're closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Horse-and-carriage gathering place at 59th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Participants: Phyllis Canter and her 5-year-old grandson, Kyle
Canter.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle: ``How come these horses are there?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Canter: ``That's the way people used to travel a long time
ago when there were no cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle: ``Were there houses here then?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Canter: ``Yes, there were farmhouses and dirt roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle: ``Were there buildings then?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Canter: ``I guess you could call them buildings. They were
really houses and barns.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle: ``So they rode their horse from their house to another
one?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Canter: ``That's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle: ``So then they could ride their horses into
Bloomingdale's?''
</P>
<P>
   PHONIC RHETORIC
</P>
<P>
   In Des Moines you don't hear either ``s.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the French derivation, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   But, although slightly slurred,
</P>
<P>
   In Des Plaines they're both heard;
</P>
<P>
   This is phonic irrationalness.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT J. BAGBY
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those sweltering 90-degree days when Diana Binder
noticed this handwritten sign posted above the sermon announcement
board of a church on East 22nd Street: ``Smile! We know of a hotter
place.'' She obeyed instructions.
</P>
<P>
   TAXI DRIVER
</P>
<P>
   Yellow zephyr in the dark night,
</P>
<P>
   speeds onward to subsidize
</P>
<P>
   the worker's meager existence;
</P>
<P>
   imprisons a scorched spirit
</P>
<P>
   and reduces earned hopefulness
</P>
<P>
   to a short break for spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   as he dines in still solitude
</P>
<P>
   at a greasy-spoon dive;
</P>
<P>
   soon to be locked behind the wheel
</P>
<P>
   for hours, while the brain plays games
</P>
<P>
   with bold dreams that disappear,
</P>
<P>
   when the red-light blinks back to green.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVIDSON GARRETT
</P>
<P>
   During the recent hot weather, Joe Hecht, unwilling to button
his shirt until absolutely necessary, took to walking to his office
on 45th Street with his tie untied, just draped loosely around his
collar.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, arriving at his office, he realized that the Perry
Ellis blue-striped tie he had had on that day had fallen off while
he was walking. He reluctantly left his cool building to retrace
his steps. There, at the corner of 43rd Street and Ninth Avenue,
was the missing tie. A good Samaritan had not only hung it on a
pole but even tied it like a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Nine-year-old Ian Engoron prefers taxicabs to other means of
transportation. His father, Arthur, recently complained about this
preference and received a short but definitive explanation: ``It's
not my fault. You and Mom got married. You had me. And this is how
I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Engoron's comment: ``Five will get you 10 he follows my
footsteps into the legal profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the items included in John Gabrielson's Saturday morning
dry-cleaning drop-off were some wool place mats that he and his
wife, Marie, had bought abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The woman behind the counter eyed them somewhat suspiciously.
When Gabrielson told her what they were, she replied, ``You don't
clean place mats _ you wash them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Gabrielson said. ``They need to be dry-cleaned. They're
wool. They come from Wales.''
</P>
<P>
   A look of consternation crept over the young woman's face. ``I
didn't know you could get wool from whales,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Annette I. Minkalis had heard that the duck crossing on Shore
Road in Port Washington was a daily occurrence, but she recently
witnessed it firsthand. About 15 ducks were crossing, making their
way from Baxter Pond to Manhasset Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars came to a halt as the single-file line of ducks waddled
across,'' she reported. ``These were ducks with attitude _ they had
the right of way. No one in the cars seemed upset as they waited.
No one honked. There were even smiles. As the last duck crossed, it
flapped its large wings as if saying to the others in front,
``Let's move along, we've held up traffic long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Her conclusion: ``I'll never again think New Yorkers are so
rushed that they won't suspend their own hurried pace _ and
actually enjoy the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL PARK IN SUMMER IS
</P>
<P>
   lunchtime, lying under a locust tree,
</P>
<P>
   spying a butterfly land on a leaf
</P>
<P>
   and fold its wings as if to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, what pleasant company to keep!
</P>
<P>
   _ TOM FURLONG
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Tenace got on an M104 bus late one night and couldn't
believe her eyes. One of the few passengers was sitting with what
Ms. Tenace described as a ``really large'' chest of drawers near
her at the back door. ``A wood chest with at least four or five
drawers,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The bus zoomed down Broadway and when it arrived at 43rd Street,
the driver came back and lowered the chest to the street on the
mechanism used for wheelchairs. According to the conversation that
ensued, the woman had apparently told the driver she couldn't
afford to transport the chest any other way and he took pity on
her. But as he lowered the chest, his good-Samaritan instinct was
strained. ``Never again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Ms. Tenace saw as the bus drove off was the woman
standing on the street with her chest, apparently waiting for a
friend, or another good Samaritan, to help out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
