<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT-TEX </SLUG>
 
JARRETT FINISHES FOURTH, PADS LEAD (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Dale Jarrett checked another race off the
1999 NASCAR Winston Cup schedule Sunday, and added 26 points to his
championship lead.
</P>
<P>
   A guy could get used to that formula, all the way to his first
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett added to his points lead for the ninth consecutive race,
when he finished a career-best fourth in the Frontier at The Glen.
Jarrett, who began the season's 21st race at Watkins Glen
International with a 274-point lead over Mark Martin, extended his
advantage to a season-high 300 points heading into the Pepsi 400 at
Michigan Speedway on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For those with short memories, Jarrett buried the field en route
to victory in the Kmart 400 at Michigan Speedway on June 13. He is
scheduled to enter the same No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit
Taurus he won with at Michigan and at the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we had to do,'' said Jarrett, who tied his
career-best finish on a road course, originally set at Sears Point
Raceway in May 1997. Jarrett failed to earn five points for leading
a lap and never seriously challenged winner Jeff Gordon, runner-up
Ron Fellows or third-place Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some work to do on the road courses,'' Jarrett said.
``We'll just move along. We got what we could, and we'll be
extremely happy with that.'' STEWART SCRAMBLES TO SIXTH
</P>
<P>
   Rookie points leader Tony Stewart's first race at The Glen
featured a botched pit stop and another miscue by the driver. But
Stewart rallied for a sixth-place finish, his 13th top-10 result of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's first pit stop led to a stop-and-go penalty after he
exited with his gas refueling can connected to the car's nozzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a major setback, having to go from sixth to the tail of
the field because of a fuel can getting stuck,'' said Stewart,
driver of the No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart later overcooked his entry into the inner loop turns,
forcing him into a complete stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably gave up 14 or 15 spots right there,'' Stewart said.
``We're making gains on our pit stops. We've still got room to
improve yet, and I've got room to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we finish in the top 10 it feels good. But we made it
all too tough on ourselves to do that. We should have had a lot
easier day, and then maybe we could have concentrated more on
running in the top five.'' EARNHARDT HITS 600
</P>
<P>
   Seven-time Cup champion Dale Earnhardt hit 600 consecutive
career starts Sunday, and at least two other cars.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt and Richard Childress Racing teammate Mike Skinner
spun after making contact in Turn 1 of the 11-turn layout to
effectively drop both out of contention on Lap 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into the back of Skinner,'' said Earnhardt, driver of
the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``That
ain't too hard to do here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the final lap, Earnhardt tangled with Darrell Waltrip and
smashed into the huge styrofoam blocks lining the Armco barrier.
Earnhardt managed to finish in 20th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 600th start was pretty sorry,'' said Earnhardt, who
joined Terry Labonte as only the second driver to make 600
consecutive Cup starts. ``It isn't one I want to remember.'' LAST
LAPS
</P>
<P>
   _ Drivers Ted Christopher (31st), Dave Murry (39th) and Boris
Said (42nd) completed their first career Cup races at The Glen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Boris Said led laps 21-29. The last driver to lead a lap in
his first career Cup race was Kenny Irwin Jr. at Richmond in
September 1997. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Jerry Nadeau led laps 59-67, the first time in his 56-race Cup
career that he has led an event..MDBU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
