<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-GORDON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON EXTENDS ROAD-COURSE STREAK WITH WIN AT THE GLEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Jeff Gordon may not rule all he surveys in
NASCAR-land these days. His designs on a third consecutive Winston
Cup championship remain barely mathematically alive.
</P>
<P>
   But on NASCAR's two road courses, Gordon still rocks. He has
since the summer of 1997, when Gordon began a streak of consecutive
road-course victories that reached a NASCAR Winston Cup record five
after Sunday's Frontier at The Glen.
</P>
<P>
   His record run of three consecutive road-course poles snapped by
Rusty Wallace on Friday, Gordon regeared and retained his magic
line around Watkins Glen International's repaved and repaired
2.45-mile, 11-turn layout. Gordon led a race-high 55 of 90 laps
while repelling the challenges of Wallace and road-racing hired gun
Ron Fellows to notch his series-leading fifth victory of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the reigning and three-time Cup champion, scored the
first road-course victory of his career here in August 1997. Since
then he has swept the two events run at Sears Point Raceway in
Sonoma, Calif., and two at WGI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it. It blows me away,'' said Gordon, who
finished 0.736 seconds ahead of Canadian native Fellows. ``What
we've done on road courses lately has shocked me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard for me to go back three or four years ago and
think about a good (road) race for me was just if I stayed on the
racetrack and didn't miss a shift. Or, I should say, I didn't miss
five shifts. Now it's just trying to get the most out of the car
and be smooth and not be too aggressive. I was pretty proud. I
didn't miss a shift all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon knew that whatever chance Fellows had of winning his
first Cup race boiled down to a restart after the day's seventh
caution flag flew on laps 87-88.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some areas, Ron was better than I was,'' said Gordon, driver
of the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``I
knew if he got close to me in the carousel turn, he could make a
pass. If he made a pass on me, it was going to be very tough to get
back by him. It was very important to not only get a good restart,
but drive hard into Turn 1 and get through the first couple of
corners and get some distance between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellows said Gordon _ buried in fifth in the points chase _
coyly initiated that process moments before the restart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to take a run at him at the green,'' said Fellows,
driver of the No. 87 Bully Hill Vineyards Chevy. ``He saw me, he
jumped on the brakes, I jumped on the brakes _ and he took off.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellows, driving a car owned by Cup regular Joe Nemechek,
nevertheless closed a super season that saw him win the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck event here June 26 and finish second in the
companion Busch Grand National race the next afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second place to Jeff Gordon is not that bad,'' said Fellows,
who is developing the Chevrolet Corvette C-5 that will be raced in
the 24 Hours of LeMans in June. ``I'm sure I'll be happier
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, the record-setting polesitter, settled for third. It
was his 11th top-10 result of 1999. Wallace also earned his third
consecutive top-four finish at WGI and his ninth top-10 in 14 races
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon just really had a great car today,'' said Wallace,
driver of the No. 2 Miller Lite Ford Taurus. ``He's really got
something figured out on road courses.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points-leader Dale Jarrett placed fourth, a
career-best at WGI. Jarrett, driver of the No. 88 Quality Care
Service/Ford Credit Taurus, extended his lead over Mark Martin by
26 points to 300. It is the largest spread of a season that on the
road courses, at least, has seen Gordon rock. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
