<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CATCHER DREAMS OF MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Texas Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez, after becoming
the first catcher in major-league history to hit 20 home runs and
steal 20 bases in the same season, dreams of an even greater honor
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The American League's Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look for the MVP, some guys have some great numbers,''
Rodriguez said. ``But if I keep playing hard and do what I'm doing,
it's possible. That's one of my dreams, to win the award.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said his chances of winning will be much better if he
finishes the season with 100 runs scored and 100 runs batted in. He
would be the first catcher to do so since Kansas City's Darrell
Porter in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to have that,'' Rodriguez said. ``I think my
only chance to get MVP is if I make those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez helped his cause Sunday by going 3-for-6 with a
double, two home runs, three runs scored and three RBI. He now has
81 runs scored and 82 RBI. CATCHER STEALS
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez is the 13th catcher in major-league history to
steal at least 20 bases in a season. The list: Player, team/Year/SB
John Wathan, Royals/1982/36 Ray Schalk, White Sox/1916/30 John
Wathan, Royals/1983/28 Jason Kendall, Pirates/1998/26 John Stearns,
Mets/1978/25 Ray Schalk, White Sox/1914/24 Johnny Kling,
Cubs/1902/23 Johnny Kling, Cubs/1903/23 Jason Kendall,
Pirates/1999/22 Benito Santiago, Padres/1987/21 Craig Biggio,
Astros/1989/21 Red Dooin, Phillies/1908/20 Ivan Rodriguez,
Rangers/1999/20
TOUGH STRETCH
</P>
<P>
   With the Oakland Athletics charging, the Rangers enter one of
the most difficult stretches of their schedule. Their next 13 games
consist of four games at the Cleveland Indians, a six-game
homestand against the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees and
three games in Toronto against the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 10-16 against those four teams this year.
However, the Rangers are one of the few teams that have had some
success at Jacobs Field. They're 13-12 at the Indians' home park
since it opened in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough stretch, but I think we can handle it,'' first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro said.
GREER HOBBLED BUT HOT
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer is bothered by his strained left ankle but continues
to play, and it hasn't affected his hitting. Greer went 9-for-18
during the White Sox series with four home runs and seven RBI. He
hit two home runs Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this series I felt comfortable at the plate,''
Greer said. ``But for the last few weeks, I've been getting on base
and I'm continuing with the same feeling. Fortunately, some balls
fell in.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, fell in the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hit enough home runs to know the difference,'' Greer
said. ``I'm up there swinging the bat and hoping it falls in the
hole. If it falls over the fence, that's even better.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Rafael Palmeiro walked twice Sunday but has only one hit in
his past 19 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Todd Zeile tied a career high with four hits Sunday, the
eighth time he has done it, including three this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rangers starters are 25-12 with a 4.42 earned-run average over
their past 54 games. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
