<HEADLINE>
RICHARD UP FOR THE TASK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC cornerback Kris Richard is wearing Brian
Kelly's number and replacing Daylon McCutcheon. Other than that,
there isn't much pressure on the sophomore who hasn't started a
college football game.
</P>
<P>
   If one player has a question mark heading into the season, it's
Richard, who has the task of following McCutcheon, a mainstay for
USC's defense the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's added pressure. A lot of people have big expectations on
me replacing a guy who was All-Pac-10,'' Richard said. ``I think
I'm the man for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe early on teams will come at me. I believe it's going
to be a learning season. It's not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard also hasn't shied away from wearing No. 42, which was
worn by Kelly, not to mention Ronnie Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want to wear it. I want to wear it because it's a
personal challenge,'' Richard said. ``I don't see it as a burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Richard's inexperience, some believe true freshman Darrell
Rideaux of Long Beach Poly will eventually start at his cornerback
spot. Rideaux is projected as a nickel back as training camp opens
and isn't ready to ponder starting just two days into camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in a position to complement (the secondary),''
Rideaux said. ``I look at myself as a student. My role has not been
determined. I'm not there yet. I believe I'm on my way.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Poll position: USC coach Paul Hackett didn't agree with the
first Associated Press poll, which had USC ranked 19th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little overzealous at this point,'' Hackett
said. ``A little ambitious. Could we be that high (later in the
season)? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   One player who disagreed with Hackett was quarterback Carson
Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a little underrated,'' Palmer said. ``And
hopefully we'll surprise some people.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ochs injured: Fullback Brennan Ochs, projected to be a
starter, sprained his ankle and will be out at least two days. Chad
Pierson moves into the No. 1 spot, but there is a chance Jabari
Jackson and Frank Strong could also play fullback.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest questions when we start (practicing in
pads) is where are we at the fullback position?'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Simmons slowed: Starting cornerback Antuan Simmons had cramps
for the second straight day and missed most of Sunday's two
practices.
</P>
<P>
   __ Watch that swing: USC free safety Ife Ohalete lost his cool
during a scuffle with tight end Pat Swanson. Ohalete took a punch
at Swanson and hit him in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very fortunate he didn't break something,'' Hackett
said. ``Boys will be boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, I was a fired-up coach, and I'd jump in the
middle of those things,'' Hackett said. ``But I got hit in the head
once.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett planned to lecture the team about practice-field fights
Sunday night, to avoid any preseason injuries.
</P>
<P>
   __ Morning off: Freshmen Steve Stevenson, Kareem Kelly, Lucais
MacKay, Chris Prosser and Omar Nazel missed the morning practice
for academic-counseling sessions.
</P>
<P>
   __ By the numbers: For the second day in a row, a field crew
botched painting the field at UC Irvine. The 20-yard line said
``02'' and the 30 was ``03.'' The mistakes were eventually
corrected.
</P>
</TEXT>
