<SLUG> BC-NY-PEE-WEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEE WEE REESE MOURNED AS ONE OF BROOKLYN'S OWN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the bar at VFW Post 1380 in Brooklyn, a
yellow-brick box a few blocks from Prospect Park, Bill Reilly and
Jack Farrell were arguing Sunday about an old neighbor who excelled
on the baseball field.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, he was like a vacuum cleaner,'' said Farrell, 81, a
retired heating engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with you,'' said Reilly, 72, a retired cargo
weigher. ``He gave the team stability, but he wasn't a Marty
Marion,'' the St. Louis Cardinals' gracefully rangy shortstop.
``What he was was the essence of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor, of course, was Pee Wee Reese, who captained the
great Brooklyn Dodgers teams of the '40s and '50s from a spot
somewhere between second and third base, thereby anchoring not just
an infield or a team but a whole borough.
</P>
<P>
   Reese's death on Saturday at the age of 81 of lung cancer
afforded Brooklynites of a certain age yet another opportunity to
revisit the days when a ballplayer meant something to a town. Like
Joe DiMaggio, Reese was remembered for leading his team with class
and dignity, but unlike DiMaggio, Reese was a king who lived among
his subjects, in a little brick duplex in Bay Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in those days,'' Reilly said as he pointedly ignored the
Yankees-Twins game on TV behind him, ``the Dodgers were a community
team. You have to understand, nobody made any money, so you lived
in the neighborhood. You had Reese and Snider living in Bay Ridge,
hanging out in the same gin mill. You know what it's like now? It's
like going to the movies. Who cares!''
</P>
<P>
   Reese may be best remembered as the Dodger who did the most to
ease Jackie Robinson across the color barrier, and Reilly was
annoyed that Reese ``became known as a humanitarian, and it
overshadowed his baseball prowess.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sunday, no one was remembering a diving backhand stab or a
clutch run batted in. They were remembering that Pee Wee was the
Dodgers, and the Dodgers were Brooklyn, and now Pee Wee, who long
ago moved on with the Dodgers to sunnier climes, was dead, and that
was it.
</P>
<P>
   Outside 9712 Barwell Terrace, the aforementioned little brick
duplex, James Millar was kicking himself all over again for having
given away Reese's autograph to a family who moved into Reese's
house, only to see them move later to Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I said today,'' said Millar, 58, a flagman for
New York City Transit, ``son of a gun, I gave that thing away. Does
anybody know where ballplayers live today?'' he asked. ``Nobody
does. They live on their three-quarter of an acre in what's the
name of that place over the GWB.'' He was referring to New Jersey
towns across from the George Washington Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Samara, who grew up on 97th Street, vividly recalled
seeing Carl Erskine, the pitcher, pick up Reese in his car on his
way to Ebbets Field. ``I'd say hello, but I liked to not bother
them too much,'' he said. ``I'd try to respect their privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the VFW, Farrell and Reilly seemed to be coming to an
agreement. ``We lost a guy who loved to play baseball, and perhaps
had more moral fiber to his character than any of those so-called
multimillionaires you have today,'' Farrell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pee Wee was Pee Wee,'' his friend replied. ``He was a good
guy, a decent human being. But the point is this: in all of your
life, have you ever heard a bad word about Pee Wee?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Farrell said solemnly. ``Never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
