A8341 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     08-15 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB PICTURE LOOKING FUZZY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eight months after it began, UCLA's quarterback
quagmire remains exactly that. Coach Bob Toledo's April optimism _
that a starter would emerge to direct an offense loaded with
playmakers _ has dissolved into August reality.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks before the season opener, Toledo's talking platoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing two is a real possibility,'' he said. ``I don't like
playing two, but we might start that way and see how they respond.
I'm not ready to go with one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior Drew Bennett is the front-runner based on experience and
would start if the season began today. But Toledo and offensive
coordinator/quarterbacks coach Al Borges will give Bennett's
competitors (sophomore Scott McEwan and freshmen Ryan McCann and
Cory Paus) plenty of opportunities this week.
</P>
<P>
   Borges has rigged the practice schedule to ensure that each
quarterback gets ample time with the No. 1 offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a checklist of plays that each guy will run several
times,'' Borges said. ``We want to evaluate each guy against
multiple scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes a scrimmage Saturday afternoon. Afterward, Toledo
and Borges will select two quarterbacks to compete for the starting
job. It's the only option, since they can't prepare four
quarterbacks for game conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all throwing the same amount of passes (this week),
and in the scrimmage situation we'll try to let them all go with
the first team,'' Toledo said. ``But I told them this isn't an
intramural team. Everybody doesn't get an equal chance. By Sunday,
I'd like to have two.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Helping hand: McEwan, a Thousand Oaks native, injected some
zing into his passes after several summer workouts with Clay
Richardson, a former college coach who tutors quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the season, coach Borges teaches us the philosophical
points and how to read defenses,'' McEwan said. ``But he isn't
allowed to coach us in the summer (because of NCAA rules) and I
needed someone to work on my throwing mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson advised McEwan to throw off his back foot and drop
his release point a few inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hardest I've ever thrown,'' McEwan said.
</P>
<P>
   __ On losing Losman: Toledo on freshman quarterback J.P.
Losman's decision to transfer after participating in spring
practice:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed he left. He didn't give it a chance here. He
expected too much too soon. Fifteen days? So he'll go to Tulane and
redshirt and he'll be a long way (from home).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Zamano update: Former linebacker Anselmo Zamano's recovery
from a devastating knee injury is nothing less than amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago at Michigan, Zamano tore every ligament in his
right knee and almost lost his lower leg because of a severed
artery. Now, after numerous surgeries and hundreds of hours of
rehabilitation, Zamano, a Fontana resident, can run full speed and
move laterally. But a return to football remains at least a year
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had arthroscopic surgery this summer to clean some things
up and it looks good in there,'' said Geoff Schaadt, UCLA's
director of athletic training. ``But he's not ready for this
season. He might have a chance next spring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
