<HEADER>
A8344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-N     08-15 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: IOWA SPINS A POLITICAL STRAW POLL INTO GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ The Republican Party held a presidential straw poll
in Iowa on Saturday and to tell the truth, it was fantastic. If the
state fair over in Des Moines drew more people, it was probably
only because the Republicans could not match a sculpture of the
Last Supper made entirely out of butter.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the state fair had Little Richard in the music hall, but
the Republicans had Vic Damone in the Orrin Hatch tent! The fair
had dozens of food stands, but it could not conceivably have had as
many people doling out barbecue sandwiches as George W. Bush had.
</P>
<P>
   Under the straw poll rules, residents had to personally show up
at the state university campus to vote, so the candidates went
crazy looking for ways to entice them. Participants could get
T-shirts in nine different colors, each with a different
politician's name. One elderly woman claimed that she attended the
straw poll every four years solely to replenish her supply of dust
cloths.
</P>
<P>
   And it was all free! American politics hasn't seen this many
giveaways since the reformers put an end to drink-buying on
Election Day. Free chicken from Orrin Hatch and free ice cream from
Alan Keyes. Balloon hats from Elizabeth Dole and potholders from
Pat Buchanan. Over here, the swing dance band, over there, the face
painters.
</P>
<P>
   Diners at the Buchanan tent took away complimentary bottles of
barbecue sauce. Dan Quayle's organizers, in a telling sign, tried
to win over the undecided with bundles of raw corn. Steve Forbes
set up a whole little amusement park, behind a giant arch of
balloons, surrounded by a long, snaking line of Forbesians waiting
for their lunch. Children climbed a mountain made of foam rubber
and raced around a huge inflated dinosaur while Debbie Boone sang
``Bibbidi-Bobbidi-Boo'' and a clown on stilts tottered around
yelling ``Hello, America!''
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the entire Forbes effort was overspending. He was
the only Republican in the history of the Iowa straw poll who paid
to have his tent air-conditioned, and as soon as it opened for
business, the temperature dropped into the '70s. His organizers
bought more balloons to fall from the ceiling during his speech
than the eight other competitors combined, and all you could hear
was the sound of people popping them when they hit the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spent a million dollars, maybe two, to win the hearts of
the Iowans. In the end that got him just under 5,000 votes and 21
percent of the total _ 10 percentage points less than George W.
Bush, and about 1,500 ballots more than Elizabeth Dole, whose staff
bragged that she won the contest for lowest per-voter expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   It all turned out pretty much as anticipated, although you would
have to be pretty cruel to have predicted that Lamar Alexander
would only get 1,428 votes. Given the amount of time Alexander has
spent here over the last four years, he must have been rejected
even by people who had him over for dinner and let him spend the
weekend in their guest room.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle finished eighth, with 916 votes, behind Keyes, a
black candidate who claims the federal income tax is the equivalent
of slavery. All the candidates trotted their families on stage
during the final speechathon, but only Quayle forced his wife and
the kids to stand there through his entire address. ``I trust your
judgment,'' he told the Iowans. That was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The memorable thing about the Iowa straw poll was not the fact
that George Bush won it, but the spectacle of so many average
people actually enjoying themselves at a political event. The state
Republican Party may have meant to hold a cheesy self-promotion
under the guise of testing the electorate's temperature, but the
desperation of the candidates and the enthusiasm of the volunteers
turned it into something different, a family entertainment that
actually managed to make the presidential campaign temporarily
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll drew almost 24,000 voters _ not to mention their
children, friends and ineligible onlookers. It was almost twice
what the organizers were expecting, and the fire marshals were
eventually forced to close the doors to the auditorium and turn
away regular citizens who wanted to listen to the speeches.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, Americans ran their elections like this, with
parades and picnics and fireworks, and contests to see which
candidates' supporters could raise the tallest pole or roll the
biggest ball from one town to the next. People voted like crazy
back then, and everybody loved politics. Maybe the wheel is
turning. Maybe democracy, like Las Vegas, needs to reinvent itself
as wholesome family fun to attract a new audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first time at one of these,'' said Vickie
Setterberg, a program assistant at Iowa State University who was
expressing her support for Elizabeth Dole by pumping air into
balloons that were then twisted to resemble dachshunds or funny
hats.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the party organizations' idea of how to involve
newcomers in the political process is to permit them to collect
signatures on candidates' petitions, and perhaps appear as
witnesses during one of the ensuing court fights over who gets to
stay on the ballot. Personally, I would rather make balloon dogs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
