<SLUG> BC-EDIT-POLICE-DNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEFECTS IN THE DNA LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 16:
</P>
<P>
   The potential value of DNA evidence as an identification tool in
criminal cases is vast. New York state wants to tap that potential,
but its new law expanding the collection of DNA samples from
convicted felons is deficient. Among other things, Gov. Pataki and
legislative leaders failed to address the legitimate privacy
concerns that creating an extensive DNA data bank inevitably
raises.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, starting Dec. 1, anyone convicted of one of a
long list of felonies will have a DNA profile entered into a state
database for use in solving crimes and aiding prosecutions. The law
permits DNA to be collected either from a blood sample or by taking
cells from the inside of the mouth with a cotton swab _ not an
unreasonable intrusion. The state already collects fingerprints,
and has begun taking blood samples from people convicted of sex
crimes and a few other violent offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to match DNA profiles against evidence from unsolved
cases will give police a powerful new crime-fighting tool, though
some police officials are pushing to go further and take DNA
samples from suspects as soon as they are arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The new law is silent, however, on a grave civil liberties
question. What happens to the left-over DNA sample containing
highly personal medical data and other information once a felon's
individualized digital pattern is filed on computer?
</P>
<P>
   A computerized fragment of a person's DNA that does not reveal
intimate medical details is all the state needs for criminal
identification. The law says that samples can be used only for
forensic identification, but unless the left-over blood or saliva
samples are destroyed, it is conceivable that they could lead to
invasions of privacy and other abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The law's silence on that point invites the state's forensic
science commission, which regulates DNA labs, to provide an answer.
Otherwise, the Legislature will be obliged to make sure that
samples taken for the purpose of making a high-tech fingerprint do
not get retained for potential abuse later on.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond privacy, there are major practical questions. The law
calls for collecting DNA samples from everyone now in prison, on
parole, or on probation for one of the crimes on the list _ about
100,000 people. But it earmarks no money to accomplish this
daunting feat. The state's criminal justice coordinator, Katherine
Lapp, hopes to find money in the current budget to get the system
running.
</P>
<P>
   But that still leaves two other unmet needs. No money has been
provided to build up existing lab capacity. Nor is there money to
teach police detectives how to identify and properly handle DNA
samples at crime scenes. Unless these gaps are filled, the state
will be unable to realize DNA's crime-fighting potential no matter
how big a database it builds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
